<HTML><!-- Head Tag -->
<HEAD><TITLE>Utility Restructuring Coalition Press Release</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><B><BLINK>PRESS RELEASE</BLINK></B></CENTER><P>

                       <CENTER>September 6, 1995</CENTER>
                    

<DT><B>Contacts:</B><BR>
<DD>Clean Water Action, Craig Johnson 612-623-3666
<DD>Cooperative Power, John Warren 612-949-1501
<DD>EnergyCENTS Coalition, Pam Marshall 612-872-3293
<DD>Izaak Walton League of America Midwest Office, Bill Grant 612-922-1608
<DD>Minnesotans for an Energy-Efficient Economy, Michael Noble 612-872-3282
<DD>Minnesota Municipal Utility Association, Jack Kegel 
612-682-4104 
<DD>Minnesota Rural Electric Association, Mark Glaess 612-424-1020<P>

<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR>      
         
                                    
 <CENTER><B>UNLIKELY ALLIANCE FORMED TO PROTECT PUBLIC INTEREST IN DEBATE
 OVER ELECTRIC UTILITY INDUSTRY RESTRUCTURING</B></CENTER>
                                    
     A broad alliance of Minnesota electric cooperatives, 
municipal utilities, low-income energy advocates and clean 
energy advocates announced today that they will be working 
together in the debate over restructuring of the electric 
utility industry.  These groups, often opponents on many energy 
issues, have joined together to ensure that the future of the 
electric industry is shaped with the public interest firmly in 
mind.<P>



     The seven groups in the alliance represent several million 
Minnesotans statewide.  They have prepared a joint statement to 
be filed with the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission, laying 
out public interest criteria on which any decision on electric 
industry restructuring should be based.  The principles include 
maintaining such public interest objectives as safety, 
reliability and customer service standards; protection of 
residential ratepayers and low- and fixed- income customers; 
stewardship of the environment through cost-effective 
conservation and renewables; and continued regulatory oversight 
such as integrated resource planning.<P>



     "The electric utilities in Minnesota are in an enviable 
position, with low rates, excellent reliability, strong 
financial health and sound environmental practices," said Mark 
Glaess, general manager of the Minnesota Rural Electric 
Association. "The proposals by some large utilities and large 
industrial customers to move toward retail competition and 
deregulation should not be allowed to jeopardize this position 
or to place residential and small business customers at risk of 
paying more and having fewer choices."<P>



     The debate before Minnesota's Public Utilities Commission 
mirrors discussions going on around the country about how 
utilities should be structured and allowed to compete for 
customers.  As in deregulation discussions in other industries, 
the largest utilities who are in a position to dominate markets 
favor a system that frees them from such requirements as 
service territories and the obligation to serve certain 
customers.  Smaller utilities, environmentalists, and 
low-income advocates want to ensure that the public interest 
obligations that are current state policy are maintained.<P>



     Pam Marshall, director of the EnergyCENTS coalition, noted 
that, "Industries that provide energy for basic human survival, 
such as heating and cooling, ought to be overseen by a body 
whose duty it is to maintain those services for everyone and to 
ensure against the public harm that energy tragedies can 
cause."<P>



     "People want low rates and reliable electric service that 
doesn't harm the environment," said Michael Noble of 
Minnesotans for an Energy-Efficient Economy, "Clean, renewable 
energy is in the public interest and these radical proposals to 
restructure the electric industry promise to undermine 
Minnesota's progress toward a sustainable energy future."<P>



     "We support open and robust competition at the wholesale 
level, which is now in the process of developing," said Jack 
Kegel, executive director of the Minnesota Municipal Utility 
Association.  "We should wait and see how this competition 
shakes out before jumping into retail competition, which may 
simply allow large customers to get better rates at the expense 
of small customers."<P>



     "The question that Minnesotans must answer, " added Bill 
Grant of the Izaak Walton League, "is how to restructure 
electric utility regulation to obtain the benefits of greater 
competition while strengthening our fundamental commitment to 
environmental protection."<P>



     "These principles are motherhood and apple pie," said 
Craig Johnson of Clean Water Action Alliance, "which is why 
such a large and diverse alliance has been formed."<P>

<!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="http://www.me3.org/projects/dereg/12prcpls.html">Joint Statement of Public Interest Principles on <BR>
Electric Utility Industry Restructuring.</A>                          

<P>
