<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --></head><body><H2>STATE OF MINNESOTA<p>
<p>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</H2><p>
<p>
<p>
<B>In the Matter of an Investigation into			Docket E-999/CI-95-135<p>
Structural and Regulatory Issues<p>
in the Electric Utility Industry</B><p>
<p>
<p>
Reply Comments of <p>
<p>
<H3>IZAAK  WALTON LEAGUE OF AMERICA (MIDWEST OFFICE)</H3><p>
<p>
and<p>
<p>
<H3>MINNESOTANS  FOR AN ENERGY-EFFICIENT ECONOMY (A COALITION)</H3><p>
<p>
<I>January 18, 1996</I> <p>
<p>
<p>
The IWLA and ME3 are pleased to submit these comments on the PUC's suggested
guidelines for the restructuring and re-regulation of Minnesota's electric
industry. With only a few reservations, noted below, IWLA and ME3 find the
direction of the draft principles to be an encouraging start for the
restructuring of electric industry regulation. Creating principles to guide the
discussion and establishing a step-wise approach to electric industry
restructuring and re-regulation is a sensible approach. IWLA and ME3 also agree
with most of the content and tone of the proposed guidelines. The draft
principles lay a solid foundation for evaluating where restructuring will lead
us before we set out on that journey, and acknowledge the role that renewable
and DSM resources should play in the future electric industry. <p>
<p>
IWLA and ME3 do, however, offer suggestions to clarify the intent of some
principles, and raise some issues that may need to be considered when applying
the principles. First, while the principles address the key issues when
evaluating and proceeding with <p>
regulatory restructuring, IWLA and ME3  perceive that many of the principles
focus on how to bring about retail competition. IWLA and ME3 believe that a
step-wise approach to restructuring requires the Commission to evaluate the
potential benefits of direct retail access against the risks and costs of that
form of regulatory restructuring. Retail competition is not the inevitable
result of industry and regulatory restructuring, and the Commission should
proceed down that path only subsequent to an explicit decision that retail
competition is the preferable structure. <p>
<p>
The Commission should consider, therefore, additional principles that clearly
identify the standards by which restructuring options will be evaluated. Rather
than assuming retail competition to be at the end of the restructuring process,
the Commission should examine the myriad of alternatives with the following in
mind: <p>
<p>
  <!-- List Tag -->
<UL>
<LI> the costs and risks posed by the restructuring alternative;

<LI>   the potential benefits of the restructuring alternative;  and

<LI>   the match between statutory goals of regulation and the benefits offered by
the         
   restructuring alternative.<p>
</UL>
<p>
Second, industry and regulatory restructuring offer an opportunity to better
accomodate the unique benefits of renewable resources and DSM in the electric
industry's investment decisions. Whether restructuring leads to retail
competition or another alternative to the existing regulatory structure, IWLA
and ME3 believe that the current state policy of using all renewable energy
options in the public interest must  be incorporated. Restructuring should lead
to enhanced ability to meet public policy goals, rather than changing public
policy goals. <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b><i>Proposed Principles</i></b><p>
<b><i></i></b><p>
1. 	<B>A deliberate, step-wise approach to restructuring.</B>  IWLA and ME3
strongly endorse 	the Commission's commitment to incremental or marginal
movement toward 	restructuring and re-regulation. In particular, IWLA and ME3
support the 	Commission's recognition that robust wholesale competition must
necessarily 	precede retail restructuring. IWLA and ME3 do, however, caution
the 	Commission to proceed toward retail competition only after determining
that 	doing so is consistent with the statutory principles and goals
surrounding electric 	service and regulation. <p>
<p>
2. <B>The benefits of competition should be available to all customer
classes.</B>  IWLA and ME3 	strongly endorse this principle, and presume that
benefits should not only be 	available but must be <u>realized</u> by all
customer classes. The Commission should 	also: 1) be attentive to the magnitude
of the risk associated with restructuring 	relative to the potential benefits
of competition; and, 2) ensure that the potential 	benefits of competition are
commensurate with the risks of restructuring. Finally, 	while the benefits of
competition may be available to all customer classes, the 	costs of such
competition may make some customers worse off. The Commission 	should commit
that any regulatory change designed to encourage efficient 	provision of
electric service will make all customer classes better off than they are 	under
existing forms of regulation.<p>
<p>
3.<B>Competitively neutral laws and regulation.</B>  IWLA and ME3 believe that
the intent of 	this principle needs to be more clearly stated. Competitors for
the same service 	should be subject to identical regulation. Essential
components of electric service,<p>
	and the risks associated with the provision of electric service, should be
borne by 	all competitors with no opportunity for bypass. The Commission must
recognize, 	however, that electric service providers sometimes provide
different services (the 	"products" are not direct substitutes) and different
service may warrant different 	laws or regulation.<p>
<p>
4. 	<B>Equitable and efficient unbundling of generation, transmission and
distribution rates and 	services.</B>  IWLA and ME3 believe that unbundling at
the wholesale level is a 	necessary precondition for robust wholesale
competition. IWLA and ME3  also 	support  the PUC's condition of robust
competition at the wholesale level as a 	precondition to retail restructuring.
A step-wise approach to retail restructuring, 	however, does not  begin with
unbundling of retail rates; retail unbundling is the 	final step to one
restructuring scenario (retail competition) rather than a principle 	from which
the Commission might explore regulatory restructuring. Moving into 	retail
unbundling presupposes that the potential benefits of retail competition
outweigh its risks, a presupposition at odds with the step-wise approach to
electric industry restructuring.<p>
<p>
	To stimulate increased wholesale competition the Commission might investigate
whether electric utilities should divest natural gas distribution functions
from 	parent or affiliated companies. <p>
<p>
5. 	<B>Obligation to provide distribution service.</B>  Most visions of a
restructured electric 	industry require the distribution function to remain a
monopoly. The 	Commission must, however, address the uncertain distinctions
between 	generation, transmission, and distribution functions in the grid. DSM
serves 	generation, transmission, and distribution functions, as do some supply
technologies such as photovoltaics, fuel cells, battery or other storage, and
distributed generation. The neat distinctions often drawn between generation,
transmission, and distribution carry a theoretical elegance, but may have
little to	 	do with reality.<p>
<p>
	As the Commission considers the ongoing monopoly/common carrier role of the
distribution function, the Commission must be aware of the "split incentive"
that 	may be created if distribution is unbundled from transmission and
generation. 	DSM, for instance,  that is cost-effective for a utility providing
bundled service 	(taking advantage of both T&amp;D and generation benefits of
DSM) may not  be 	cost-effective when evaluated solely as a generation
resource. T&amp;D  benefits of 	DSM typically account for between 10 and 30
percent of total avoided costs. 	Photovoltaic and storage resources may be
similarly disadvantaged if the 	incentive to invest in them is split between
unbundled services in a vertically 	disconnected industry.<p>
<p>
	The Commission might consider the model of DSM investment by Minnesota gas
distribution companies to address the split incentive problems and
operationalize DSM and renewable mandates. <p>
<p>
6. 	<B>Universal energy service</B>. IWLA and ME3 strongly support the
continued emphasis 	on universal service. The Commission should remain open to
creative methods 	of ensuring universal service, and should investigate methods
of ensuring 	universal service without relying on universal service
assessments.<p>
<p>
7. 	A<B>ttention to the needs of residential consumers.</B> IWLA and ME3
endorse the 	Commission's concern with addressing the unique aspects of
providing a basic 	necessity to residential consumers and low-income consumers
in particular. 	IWLA and ME3 wish to point out, however, that this principle
addresses only 	one of a number of restructuring scenarios - retail
competition. Since a cautious 	and step-wise approach to restructuring only
considers retail competition at the 	end of the process (or not at all, if the
potential benefits do not warrant the risks), 	IWLA and ME3 believe that this
principle should be modified to address a 	broader range of potential
restructuring scenarios. <p>
<p>
8. 	<B>Public participation.</B>  IWLA and ME3 applaud and endorse the
Commission's 	commitment to public participation in the restructuring process.
The		 	Commission needs to extend this principle beyond the decision-making
processes that lead to restructuring, however, and commit to public
participation 	and public scrutiny in any resulting structure. Public
participation is not only 	necessary in forming the new industry structure; it
is equally important as part of 	the output. Integrated Resource Planning (IRP)
is one example of how public	 	participation is incorporated into the existing
regulatory structure. A modified 	IRP process to allow public participation in
both transitional and ultimate 	industry structure will continue to ensure that
public goals are valued in the 	planning process and statutory goals are
attained. <p>
<p>
	As the Commission has noted in the past in its support of intervenor
compensation legislation, providing a means of funding public participation
increases the number and quality of public voices in the regulatory process.
The 	Commission should extend the principle of public participation to ensure
both 	the opportunity for public participation in the new regulatory structure
and the 	maintenance of public participation. <p>
<p>
9. 	<B>Performance standards. </B> IWLA and ME3 support the concept of
developing 	customer-based performance standards. Such standards are of
particular value as 	utilities cut costs to competitively position themselves
for potential retail 	competition, and in light of the industry's own
restructuring (the rash of mergers 	and consequent shedding and reorganizing of
staff).<p>
<p>
	Given the Commission's previous commitment (principle #5) to retaining a
distribution monopoly, IWLA and ME3 must note that most reliability problems,
including outages and power quality problems, stem from failure or overloading
of distribution system elements. Outage, power quality, and safety risks can
often be mitigated by investment in DSM, some renewable supply options, and
appropriate cogeneration. Such investments are historically not considered as
within the province of distribution planning, nor have they been part of a
meaningful risk diversification strategy for reliability concerns. Such
benefits 	may never be realized if the incentive to invest in DSM, renewables,
or 	cogeneration is split among different companies in a vertically
disintegrated 	industry. <p>
<p>
	Substantial research by EPRI and other utilities demonstrates the value of
both 	targeted DSM and appropriate renewable investment for transmission and
distribution planning. The most cost-effective utility investment to meet
performance standards will likely include investment in appropriate DSM,
renewables, and cogeneration, if the generation benefits of such resources are
also included in resource planning. <p>
<p>
10. <B> 	Fair and immediate treatment of transition costs.</B> IWLA and ME3
support reasonable 	sharing of costs, but are concerned that several principles
regarding transition 	costs should precede the treatment of such costs. First,
the Commission should 	consider transition costs in evaluating the potential
benefits of retail competition 	against the risks and costs posed by retail
competition. Transition costs or 	stranded investment is likely to be an issue
only in one restructuring scenario. As 	with several previous principles, IWLA
and ME3 note that retail competition is 	one of a number of restructuring
scenarios, that should only come about at the 	end of the Commission's
step-wise movement toward a restructured industry.<p>
<p>
	Second, IWLA and ME3 believe that the driving principle should be to first
identify reasonable transition costs, if any. The parties entering a
competitive 	market have substantial economic incentive to claim all uneconomic
investment 	as "stranded." More importantly to IWLA and ME3, however, is the
prospect that 	"stranded" investment may become a viable asset soon after being
written off as 	stranded. Coal and nuclear plants may be written off, at the
expense of 	ratepayers, only to resurface and displace other less polluting
resources. 	Generating plant that is "stranded" should be retired, not sold at
bargain 	basement prices to a subsidiary. <p>
<p>
	Finally, while sharing of transition costs is in theory equitable, IWLA and
ME3 	believe that any stranded costs must be assigned to departing customers so
that 	other customers are not forced to pay for not choosing to escape the
utility's 	embedded costs.<p>
<p>
11.	<B>Environmental improvement.</B> IWLA and ME3 strongly endorse the
Commission's 	commitment to improving environmental quality as part of
regulatory 	restructuring. IWLA and ME3 believe that such a commitment should
not, 	however, be limited to a "transition to a retail competitive market."
Retail 	competition is one possible endpoint for a regulatory restructuring
effort. If, 	however, the Commission determines that retail competition is not
warranted, 	IWLA and ME3 believe that the restructuring process should still
incorporate the 	improvement or retirement of generating plant with
environmental liabilities, 	and the development of clean and renewable
resources. <p>
<p>
12.  	<B>State participation in transmission planning.</B>  IWLA and ME3 concur
that 	Minnesota's interests and concerns with transmission planning warrant
participation and advocacy by state agencies. It must also be noted, however,
that the rash of proposed mergers are threatening the viability of most
regulatory authority in regard to transmission planning. Given that the
industry 	may soon be regional even in regard to intra-state retail
transmission planning, 	IWLA and ME3 recommend that the Commission consider
what regional forms 	of regulation might be available in which to advocate for
Minnesota's 	environment and the cost and reliability of Minnesota's retail
electric services.<p>
<p>
13. 	<B>Diverse portfolio of energy resources</B>.  IWLA and ME3 wholeheartedly
support the 	Commission's commitment to fuel and energy diversity, and the
research and 	development of new generation and delivery methods. IWLA and ME3
recommend, however, that the Commission commit to building in structural
mechanisms to make the commitment to state support for diversity a reality in a
restructured industry. The Commission should ensure that the restructured
regulatory processes achieve fuel diversity, incorporate U.S.  climate change
goals voluntarily agreed to by major Minnesota utilities, actively address
environmental degradation such as mercury  bio-accumulation, and mitigate
environmental  and economic risks to ratepayeers.  In its response to the
Lignite 	Energy Council's appeal of the Commission's Interim Externality
Values, the 	Commission supported the effort to "help focus attention on
alternative resource 	options that would allow utilities to avoid environmental
and economic risks 	associated with this emission (carbon diozide)."<p>
<p>
14. 	<B>A competitive state economy.</B>  IWLA and ME3 endorse the
Commission's 	commitment to promoting the state's economy and fostering
cost-effective in-	state energy resources. <p>
<p>
15.<B> Streamlined regulation</B>.  IWLA and ME3 are concerned that decreased
regulatory	 	oversight is a siren call. Little evidence supports the contention
that regulatory 	change leads to less regulation or oversight. The vast body of
anti-trust law and 	enormous regulatory bodies associated with other industries
operating in a 	"competitive" environment testify to the likelihood that
regulatory and industry 	restructuring changes regulation, but does not
"streamline" it. The competitive 	market provides incentives for efficiency,
but also provides incentives to 	predatory price, shift costs onto captive
market share, shift environmental risk to 	the public sector or to externalize
environmental costs altogether, enhance the 	value of existing investment (such
as coal and nuclear power plants) at the 	expense of new investment, and
leverage the mobility of capital against the 	immobility of labor. <p>
<p>
	The Commission should commit to an appropriate level of oversight, and should
evaluate the new regulatory costs of different restructuring scenarios when
determining whether the potential benefits of a restructured industry are
worthy 	of the potential risk and costs. <p>
<p>
<p>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>


