<HEAD><TITLE>Restructuring the Electric Industry</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 


<H2><P ALIGN=CENTER>Restructuring the Electric Industry<p>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>December 1995</P></H2><p>
<p>
<H3>Summary</H3> <p>
<p>
Over the past few year, competition at the wholesale level of the electric
industry has been increasing throughout the country, due primarily to
technological advances and to changes in federal laws and regulations.  Both
nationally and in Minnesota, state legislators and regulators are feeling
pressure from large industrial electricity customers and non-utility
electricity generators to restructure the electric industry to allow
competition at the retail level.<p>
<p>
This report analyzes and assesses the need for restructuring the electric
industry in Minnesota.<p>
<p>
<H4>1.  <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct1.html">The Traditional Rationale for Regulation</A></H4><p>
<p>
The first chapter informs readers, perhaps unfamiliar with the issue, about the
traditional rationale for regulation.  It describes the structure of the
electric industry in Minnesota and the regulatory compact it presently operates
under.  The provision of electricity services has traditionally been considered
to exhibit the characteristics of a "natural monopoly."  In theory, a natural
monopoly exists in a market if one service provider in the market can serve
customers more efficiently than many competing service providers.  IN markets
exhibiting the characteristics of a natural monopoly, government intervention
in the form of regulation over a single firm is considered necessary to provide
the market discipline that competition cannot provide.<p>
<p>
However, some in the electric industry argue that the generation sector of
industry no longer exhibits the characteristics of a natural monopoly, thus
continued regulation of this sector may no longer be necessary.  As the
underlying economic rationale is perceived to be eroding, the calls for
deregulation and increased competition increase.<p>
<p>
<H4>2.  <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct2.html">The Regulatory Context for Competition in the Electric Industry</A></H4><p>
<p>
The second chapter discusses the regulatory context for competition and the
steps that both the U.S. Congress and Minnesota have taken to encourage
wholesale competition.  For example, in Minnesota, regulators and the
legislature have introduces competition into the state's regulatory structure
by encouraging generation by non-utilities; authorizing utilities to offer
competitive rates to retain customers; and instituting competitive bidding for
new generation capacity.  Currently, both the Minnesota Public Utilities
Commission and the Minnesota Department of Public Service are looking into
potential models for restructuring the electric industry, among other issues.<p>
<p>
<p>
<H4>3.  <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct3.html">A Discussion of Issues and Options</A></H4><p>
<p>
The third chapter discusses issues and options concerned with restructuring the
electric industry.  The issues defined and then briefly discussed are market
structure, stranded costs, obligation to serve, long-range planning, stranded
benefits, and unbundling.  The options that the Minnesota Legislature can
consider are then described with a set of pros and cons following each option.
The legislature can do nothing; it can provide a list of principles to guide
the agencies and the industry in restructuring the electric  energy system in
Minnesota;  or it can encourage wholesale competition in the region, either
directly or by instructing the MPUC to initiate an investigation into the
benefits of expanding the use of competitive bidding.  Finally, the legislature
could create an organized statewide generation pool, as well as a kind of
"stock exchange" for electricity; or it could allow at least some customers to
choose their electricity vendor (retail wheeling) instead of requiring them to
purchase power from the utility in their service area.<p>
<p>
<p>
<H4>4.  <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct4.html">Performance-Based Regulation</A></H4><p>
<p>
The final chapter discusses replacing traditional cost-based regulation with
performance-based regulation, an idea of great interest to many engaged in the
restructuring debate.  Proponents of performance-based regulation argue that
cost-based regulation results in inefficiently operated utilities and inflated
prices to customers.  Performance-based regulation refers to a variety of
regulatory approaches that attempt to provide or enhance incentives for
utilities to operate more efficiently.<p>
<p>
However, others argue that a move to performance-based regulation, if such a
move is accompanied by a decrease in oversight of the utility by regulators,
could lead to severe abuses by utilities, such as a decline in quality of
service or inflated returns to the utility.<p>
<p><BR>
This report provides a <b><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restructglos.html">Glossary</A></b> in the end that defines all the terms
used throughout the chapters. <p>
<BR>
<P><BR>
This report is prepared by <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:mbull@teal.house.leg.state.mn.us">Mike Bull</A>, Legislative Analyst in the <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.house.leg.state.mn.us/hrd/hrd.htm">House Research
Department</A>, 612-296-8961.  This publication can be made available in alternative
formats upon request.  Please call Karin Johnson, (612) 296-5038 (voice); (612)
296-9896 or 1-800-657-3550 (TDD).<p>

<HR>
