<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>ME3 Position on Retail Wheeling-October 15, 1996</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>ME3 Position on Retail Wheeling<BR>
October 15, 1996 </H2>	
<!-- Font Tag --><B><FONT SIZE=4>W</FONT></B>e oppose radical restructuring of the electricity industry as proposed by advocates of "retail wheeling". Instead, we seek environmental improvement and economic development through energy efficiency and renewable energy. <P>

Retail wheeling would increase pollution, reduce reliability, shift costs to small consumers, and eliminate energy efficiency and renewable energy progress. Retail wheeling masquerades as "customer choice", but customer choice is meaningless in an industry controlled by monopolies and oligopolies. Winners will be lawyers, lobbyists and middlemen, and the losers will be most customers and the environment. Instead of retail wheeling, our proposals improve wholesale competition while increasing opportunities for renewables. Minnesota has made great progress towards a sustainable energy future. We need to keep moving forward, instead of returning to a past that ignored energy efficiency and renewable power. Minnesota needs to "cap" pollution emissions as it "capped" nuclear waste in 1994. Now is the time to move to the technologies of the future. <P>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Moving From Polluting Energy To Sustainable Energy</H2>

<B>Capping Pollution Levels and Cleaning Up Old Coal Plants</B><BR>
The oldest coal plants are the most polluting. They are exempt from the pollution standards for new plants, giving them an economic advantage over cleaner sources. To eliminate the unfair advantage for old coal plants operating in our communities, Minnesota should establish a total maximum level of allowable power plant emissions , and require that old plants meet the same pollution standards as new ones.<P>

<B>Continuously Increasing Renewable Power</B><BR>
To achieve environmental benefits and economic development in Minnesota, we support a policy requiring that a steadily increasing percentage of all our electricity come from sources of renewable power.<P>

<B>Energy Efficiency Programs</B><BR>
Current Minnesota law requires minimal utility investments in energy efficiency. This requirement must be a permanent commitment. Control of energy-saving programs must be independent of owners of electricity generation, to avoid conflicting interests.<P>

<B>Green" Pricing</B> <BR>
"Green pricing" (the idea that willing rate-payers should pay more for clean electricity) may help get innovative renewable pilot projects underway, but cannot replace a comprehensive policy aimed at creating strong renewables markets with multiple competitors. Everyone benefits, so everyone should participate in progress toward sustainable energy.<P>

<BR>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Consumer Protection & Cost-Shifting</H2>

<B>Prevent Unregulated Monopolies</B><BR>
No competitor should be allowed to gain market power in electricity markets. Market power means monopoly prices. Domination of the market can be used to block new sources such as renewables from reaching customers.<P>

<B>Public Bail-Out of Utilities</B><BR>
No public bailout of utilities' bad investment decisions should be approved. Any calculation of so-called "stranded costs" must be offset by the increased value of power plants which become more economic as a result of regulatory changes.<P>

<B>Nuclear Power</B><BR>
Nuclear power poses enormous financial and environmental risks which are already largely borne by the public. The public has a right to know the full extent of these liabilities (such as the terms of the Westinghouse/NSP lawsuit settlement). Restructuring of the industry must not be used to further shift nuclear liabilities from private interests to the public. Minnesota's plan to gradually phase out nuclear power, as agreed to by lawmakers in 1994, is the right start. <P>

<B>Equity</B><BR>
Low-income Minnesotans are at risk of loss of service and higher cost. Equity and universal access in electric service are bedrock principles. Shifting of costs of service from industrial users to low-income communities must not be tolerated.<P>

<B>Legal Separation of Generation and Distribution Ownership</B><BR>
To prevent unfair control and manipulation of the system by the biggest utility, ownership of electricity generation assets must be legally separated from the ownership of the distribution system serving end users. To reduce the potential of gaming and unfair competition, there should be no affiliation of ownership interests between these two sectors.<P>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Regulatory Reform</H2>
<B>Fair Prices Ð Full Cost</B><BR>
Improved rate flexibility for utilities and their industrial customers makes sense, but only if small residential and commercial customers can be guaranteed long-term rate caps. Otherwise, industrial costs will inevitably be shifted to small users. The full environmental cost of our electricity choices should be reflected in the price.<P>

<B>Public Participation in Planning</B> <BR>
Sensible reform requires improved efficiency and effectiveness of resource planning, certificate of need, and siting functions, but new processes must include meaningful public participation, including compensation for public interest intervenors.<P>

<HR>
Return to the <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/">Sustainable Minnesota Home Page</A>

</BODY> 
