</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Restructuring Position Paper:  Stranded Costs</title></head><!-- Body Tag --><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><H2>STRANDEDCOSTS:  A "BIGGER <BR>RIPOFF THAN THE S&amp;Ls"?</H2>Prepared for ME3 by Martha J. Hewett, Center for Energy and Environment, April, 1996<p><H3>What are "stranded costs"?</H3>In the policy debate about deregulation of the electric utility industry, therehas been a great deal of discussion about compensation of utility shareholdersfor  "stranded assets."  In this discussion, stranded assets are described asthe capital costs (depreciation and return on investment) for a generatingplant that cannot be fully recovered in a competitive market, because therevenue at the market price is less than total operating cost, including thecost of capital.  <p>The major driving force for deregulation of the electric utility industry is toreduce electricity prices.  Large industrial customers want to be able to buypower from any supplier precisely because the competitive market price will beless than the rate of return required to pay the full cost of power supplied bytheir current utilities.  The question is, who will pay for the utilities'resulting "stranded costs"?<p>The options are:<p><UL><LI>to write off these capital costs, that is, to make shareholders take theloss;<p><LI>to minimize the loss by improving the efficiency of utilities as businessentities, thereby reducing their overall operating costs;<LI>to redistribute these costs onto captive customers (i.e., residential andsmall commercial customers) who will not be able to buy power from competitivesuppliers until many years after large customers can do so;<LI>to distribute costs over all customers, through exit fees, transmission ordistribution surcharges, or other mechanisms;<LI>to distribute costs over all customers by delaying the transition to retailcompetition, to allow more time for capital recovery;<LI>to redistribute some of these costs onto the public sector throughnationalization of particularly uneconomic assets.</UL><p>Many utilities are claiming that because of the historical "regulatory compact"between shareholders and regulators, shareholders are owed full recovery ofthese costs and should not be required to accept any losses.  Large customersdo not want to pay stranded costs because it will delay the lower rates theywant from competition.  In the negotiation among Goliaths, captive customerscould be left holding a very large bag.<p>CEE believes that some utilities intend to use the "stranded cost" argument toshift large paper losses to ratepayers and shift problematic nuclear facilitiesto the public sector, while retaining for themselves the windfall profits fromlow cost plants that are the mirror image of "stranded costs."  In a fullycompetitive market, the true value of "stranded costs" in Minnesota would benegligible or even negative:  if anything, Minnesota utilities would owe moneyto ratepayers for the unexpected increase in value of assets, paid for byratepayers, that will arise from competition with expensive suppliers inmarkets like Chicago.  <p>Minnesota legislators and regulators have an obligation to the citizens ofMinnesota to assure that an unnecessary "stranded cost" bailout does not goforward.  Minnesota should say "NO" to recovery of stranded costs, and "NO" tothe portrayal of stranded costs as a legitimate bargaining chip in thederegulation process.<p><H3>The claim that the "regulatory compact" justifies shifting all so-called"stranded costs" to ratepayers doesn't hold water.</H3>Economist Robert Michaels points out that in the 220 years since Adam Smith,economists have never before invented the concept of stranded investment orproposed policies to deal with it.  In market-based economies, the shareholderseat the losses from bad business decisions.  Alfred Kahn (1994), former chairof the New York PSC, points out that "economic efficiency would be best servedby ignoring sunk costs and freeing utility companies to reduce their rates tomarginal costs to the extent necessary to meet competition."  Allowing recoveryof stranded costs would give the greatest reward to those utilities which madethe worst business decisions.<p>Many utilities claim that they are different, and that because of thehistorical "regulatory compact" between shareholders and regulators,shareholders are owed full recovery of these costs.  Because this claimprovides the entire rationale for recovery of stranded costs, it is importantto scrutinize it thoughtfully.<p>One of the common arguments is that because utilities have had an obligation toserve, all costs for capacity that they built to meet that obligation should befully recovered.  However, in a fully competitive market, simply owningcapacity does not create stranded costs; only owning capacity that costs morethan the market price creates stranded costs.  Therefore, recovery of strandedcosts in a fully competitive market should require utilities to show that "theservice obligation...forced the utility to use higher cost plants than it wouldotherwise have installed."  (Michaels 1994).  <p>One case where this might appear to be true on the face of things is wherespecific costs were incurred on orders by regulators.  The examples mostcommonly used in arguing for recovery of these costs are the high pricedpurchased power contracts that utilities in California and New York wereordered to sign with qualifying facilities under PURPA, based on regulators'overestimates of long run avoided costs.  Utilities have generally claimed thatsince they were forced to sign these contracts, they should be compensated forthem completely.  They calculate their stranded costs based on the assumptionthat without regulatory intervention,  they would have developed "an optimalsystem based on perfect foresight."  However, as Peter Bradford, former chairof the New York PSC and the Maine PUC points out, "their actual record duringthese years belies any assumption of perfect foresight in a world withoutPURPA... At best, the utilities were forecasting a future kW and kWh value10-15 percent below the [states'] adopted long-run avoided cost... Indeed,utilities trying to justify completing problem nuclear units were drivento...adopt figures at least as high as the states'. [Therefore], the utility'sown build or buy decisions would still have caused at least 75 percent of theactual...problem."  Likewise, utilities were forecasting load growth andcalling on regulators to approve construction of plants which, had they beenapproved, would be facing stranding today.<p>Another frequent argument is that stranded costs should be fully recoveredbecause regulators determined at the time that they were prudently incurred.But as Bradford says, "the proposition that regulators, as society'srepresentatives, have blessed as `prudent' every dollar of investment notspecifically disallowed, and must therefore assure full recovery of this moneyas part of a transition to competition..." is silly and naive.  Utilityregulation has a long history nationwide of either being grossly underfunded toconduct a thoroughgoing review of all utility investment, or being largelycontrolled by cozy relationships with the utilities.  It is ridiculous to claimthat utilities have been relying on prudency review to determine whetherparticular generation investments were a wise business decision.  <p>An additional argument commonly used for recovery of stranded costs is thatutility shareholders have accepted low returns based on low risk, and wouldhave invested their money elsewhere without this low risk, so they are owed thereturns.  This argument is wrong on two counts.  First, a study by staff of theNational Association of Regulatory Utility Commissioners shows that returns toelectric utility investors over the past 25 years have been as high as orhigher than those to other industrial investors.  "This makes it hard to arguethat electric utility investors have not been adequately compensated"(Bradford 1995).  Second, the prospect of competition has not in fact taken theutility industry by surprise.  It has been discussed in trade publications forthe last decade.  And significant regulatory disallowances occurred even in the1970s, so, as Bradford says, "Not a single dollar invested (or left ininvestment) in an electric utility after 1980 came in justifiable ignorance ofthe possibility that it might not be recovered."<p>In summary, the argument that the regulatory compact justifies shifting allstranded costs to ratepayers doesn't hold water.  In a fully competitiveenvironment, utilites could at the very most claim compensation only for caseswhere they were forced to use higher cost plants than they can documentthat they would have chosen without regulatory oversight.  Even in this case,they cannot reasonably claim compensation for investments made after 1980, whendisallowances served notice on the investment community that utilities were nolonger a risk-free investment.  As Michaels says, "no other industry can tapwidows and orphans to undo $300 billion of retrospective mistakes."<p><H3>Utilities will use stranded costs as a business opportunity to shift aslarge paper losses as possible to someone else.</H3>Assuming for the moment that "stranded costs" are valid in concept, theiractual dollar value for a particular plant would be equal to the differencebetween the net present value of total future costs (including capital costsand uncertain future operating costs) and the net present value of total futurerevenues at competitive market prices.  Since these future costs and revenuesare unknowable, the valuation of stranded costs is a "shot in the dark at amoving target"  (Cearley and McKinzie 1995).  This creates an irresistableincentive for utilities to distort the valuation in their favor.<p>Any ratepayer who listens to the numbers thrown around in the stranded costdebate will realize that it's time to check his wallet.  The magnitude ofstranded cost estimates is on the order of $130 billion (Moody's, cited byIvins 1996) to $550 billion (ICF Kaiser, cited by Ivins 1996).  The latternumber, by the way, is bigger than the $500 billion bailout of the savings andloan industry.  Like the S&amp;L bailout, the so-called recovery of so-calledstranded costs has the potential to transfer enormous wealth from averagecitizens to a select group of individuals.  There is no question that manyinvestor-owned utilities will attempt to use stranded costs to rake in as muchmoney as possible.  As Dave Penn of the American Public Power Association hassaid, the IOUs need to "get real."  The total investment in the electricindustry is only $600 billion, the market value $250 to $300 billion, and thedepreciated book value only $175 to $190 billion (Penn, quoted by Maize 1994,and Black 1994).  Before getting out their checkbooks, ratepayers should askhow almost the entire value of the generating base in the country can suddenlybecome "stranded."<p>Utility applications to FERC for recovery of stranded investments and utilitycomments in response to a Public Utility Commission of Texas study of strandedcosts demonstrate that utilities intend to claim the entire lost revenue fromdeparting customers as stranded costs (Michaels 1994, Matlock 1995).  Thisimplies the dubious proposition that 100% of the capital value of the assetsserving these customers is unrecoverable.  Lost revenues have absolutely nonecessary relationship to stranded costs.<p>Minnesota legislators and regulators should view utility estimates of strandedcosts in the light of the utilities' obvious self-interest in inflating them.<p><H3>Utilities are strangely silent on the subject of the "stranded benefits"that will provide them with windfall profits.</H3>The transition to a competitive market creates "stranded benefits" as well as"stranded costs."  Stranded costs occur when revenues at the competitive marketprice cannot cover total costs (operating costs and capital costs).  In exactlythe same manner, stranded benefits occur when revenues at the competitivemarket price exceed total costs.  Utilities claim that in the former case,ratepayers should reimburse shareholders, but they have failed to mention thelatter case, leaving it to others to point out that stranded benefits cangenerate huge windfall profits for the utilities.  Many utilities own fullydepreciated generating plants that can generate power at total costs well belowthe market price, plants that were paid for with ratepayers' money.  There isabsolutely no conceptual distinction between stranded costs and strandedbenefits, only a different algebraic sign that affects whether the wealth flowsfrom ratepayers to shareholders or the reverse.  "Customers should becompensated for their lost benefits, just as investors should be compensatedfor their stranded costs.  If regulators allow a utility to recover strandedcosts only and do not consider the potential stranded benefits, then, ineffect, the utility is allowed to receive the protection of regulation as wellas the benefits of the free market.  Customers, on the other hand, pay thecosts of the regulated asset when the costs are high and never receive thebenefits of the lower price when the asset becomes fully depreciated.  Instead,they pay a price equal to the marginal cost of a new asset in a free marketsituation" (Cearley and McKinzie 1995).<p>A report by staff of the Public Utilities Commission of Texas found that thebook value of the nuclear plants owned by four IOUs in Texas was a phenomenal$2700 to $4400/kW, compared with a top-end cost of $750/kW for a brand-newcombined cycle turbine.  Ignoring stranded benefits, the potential strandedcost from these plants could be $11 to $15 billion, which amounts to 45% toover 100% of the total common equity of these utilities.  But the reportconcluded that "These four utilities appear, however, to have enoughundervalued assets (in the form of highly depreciated non-nuclear generation)to largely offset or in some cases completely offset any stranded nuclearinvestment."  The utilities naturally argued that the estimates of strandedbenefits were way too high, and that stranded costs should be based on lostrevenue, anyway (Matlock 1995).<p>Lawyer Bernard Black (1994) describes retail competition as giving utilitiesthe "ability to recover sunk costs from customers, especially small customers,during the transition period; [and the] opportunity... to form unregulatedsubsidiaries that can compete in the service territories of other utilities andkeep any above-market returns from doing so...The utility will do its best toload the sunk costs that it can no longer recover from large customers ontosmall, captive customers."  There is no question that utilities intend to usestranded costs to take ratepayers for a ride.  The question is, will Minnesotalegislators and regulators let them drive?<p>In a fully competitive market, the amount of so-called stranded costs will bevery unevenly distributed throughout the country, with the regions with thehighest electricity prices having the largest stranded assets.  All ofMinnesota's investor-owned utilities have industrial rates in the bottom halfof rates for the nation.  If anything, Minnesota's utilities stand to make akilling selling their low cost power to customers in traditionally high pricedmarkets.  In considering claims of "stranded costs," Minnesota legislators andregulators should be careful not to try to fix in Minnesota something that isonly broken in New York and California.  The Minnesota utilities own numeroushighly depreciated generating plants paid for by ratepayers that will be highlycompetitive in an open market; if anything, they may owe money to ratepayersfor the unexpected windfall profits they will make in a competitive market.<p><H3>Utilities intend to use the stranded cost argument to transfer futureresponsibility for their "safe, cheap, zero-emissions" nuclear facilities tothe public sector.</H3>Anyone who has been involved in energy policy in Minnesota for any length oftime knows that Minnesota utilities claim that nuclear power is safe, that thestorage and ultimate disposal of nuclear wastes will not be a problem, thatnuclear generation has no environmental externalities, and that nuclear poweris a valuable, low cost component of Minnesota's generation mix.<p>Yet there is widespread agreement that the bulk of the "stranded assets" in aderegulated utility industry will be nuclear plants (Sant and Naill 1994, Cohenand Kihm 1994, Kahn 1994).  When Britain privatized its electric powerindustry, it was unable to find buyers for the nuclear plants.  It is widelybelieved that there would be no buyers for nuclear plants if utilities in theU.S. were to attempt to divest them.  "Buyers would...require federal insuranceprotection to guarantee disposal of the plants' nuclear wastes anddecommissioning costs (no private investor is likely to be interested in takingon these risks)."  Proposals to nationalize nuclear power in the U.S. havealready been floated (Kahn 1994).  <p>It is ironic that an industry that has championed nuclear power over vociferousopposition for years, and has claimed that decommissioning and waste disposalare not a big concern and that nuclear power has no external environmentalcosts, is so eager to transfer these costs to the public in a competitiveenvironment.  It is estimated that underaccruals of funds for nucleardecommissioning costs nationwide could easily total $40 to $50 billion (Black1994).  Minnesota legislators should make sure that the costs of nucleardecommissioning and waste disposal in Minnesota are fully paid out of thewindfall profits from competition, not tranferred by slight of hand to thepublic or ratepayers.  "Stranded" nuclear costs would make recent corporatewelfare like the Target Center buyout look like pocket change.<p><H3>Utilities can significantly offset "stranded costs" by improving theeconomic efficiency of their operations.</H3>Roger Sant and Roger Naill, executives with AES, one of the largest independentpower producers in the world, have estimated that the overall cost ofelectricity in the U.S. could be reduced by 5 to 15%, or $15 billion per year,through efficient competitive operation (1994).  Others have estimated thepotential savings at 20 to 40%.  Utilities compensated on the basis ofcost-of-service have had little incentive to find these cost savings.  Undercompetitive pressure, utilities are asking regulators for performance-basedrates that will allow them to cut operating costs and retain some of thesavings for shareholders.  Minnesota legislators and regulators should assurethat any earnings from performance-based rates go first to pay off any claimedstranded costs.<p><H3>Large customers will attempt to bypass "stranded costs" even without retailcompetition.</H3>Nationwide, the largest utility customers are already attempting to use theirpolitical and market power to transfer "stranded costs" to others by securinglower rates for themselves.  One strategy they use is to propose toself-generate, and then accept an offer of flex rates or competitive rates fromtheir utility.  Another strategy to win rate concessions or switch to adifferent supplier is for large customers to attempt to convince a municipalityto form a new municipal utility that includes their plant, or to take advantageof obscure legal provisions to switch suppliers.  These piecemeal strategieshave been used in Minnesota, as well.  They are of particular concern because,if they succeed in idling part of a utility's capacity, they can in fact createreal stranded costs.  Even when utilities have assets that would have totalcosts below the market price in a truly competitive market, if there is nomarket and the capacity is idled, then its costs are indeed stranded.<p>Ron Matlock, a manager at the Public Utility Commission of Texas, describesutilities' reactive or pre-emptive redesign of rates and pricing as thecreation of stranded costs by "Chinese water torture."  Unless regulators arewatchful, the accumulation of competitive rate agreements and pre-emptivecreation of "innovative" rates will shift these stranded costs to captiveratepayers as surely as, if more slowly than, a transfer of stranded costsunder retail competition.<p>Minnesota regulators should review competitive rate proposals and "innovative"rate structures in the context of the overall impact on revenue allocation byclass and on equity of rates between classes and between customers within thecommercial and industrial classes.  Shareholders' should also accept a share ofresponsibility for decreased revenue from large customers.  The wealthtransfers inherent in changing rate designs and pricing are too significant tobe glibly approved on an incremental basis without an explicit policyevaluation of the cumulative impacts.<p><H3>Conclusion</H3>In summary:<p><UL><LI>The "regulatory compact" does not justify shifting all so-called "strandedcosts" to ratepayers.  The amount of "stranded costs" that can be legitimatelyclaimed based on the "regulatory compact" is only a small fraction of theamounts commonly proposed.<p><LI>The dollar value of "stranded costs" depends on many future factors that areunknowable today.  With estimates of "stranded costs" running as high as theentire first cost of utility investments, ratepayers should check theirwallets.  Minnesota legislators and regulators should recognize that theincentives for utilities to claim as large stranded costs as possible areirresistible.<p><LI>Deregulation will create "stranded benefits" as well as "stranded costs."Stranded benefits are conceptually identical to stranded costs, but becausethey imply a flow of money in the opposite direction, from shareholders toratepayers, utilities have neglected to mention them.  Especially in stateswith low electricity costs like Minnesota, it is highly likely that strandedbenefits will exceed stranded costs.  Minnesota legislators should make surethat ratepayers are fully compensated for the windfall profits arising fromgenerating assets that they paid for.  They should resist utility efforts torecover stranded costs for some plants while keeping the windfall profits fromothers, and look at the net value of all generating assets.<p><LI>Nuclear power is widely considered to account for the bulk of strandedassets, based on both the high cost of the plants and the liabilities ofdecommissioning, fuel reprocessing and waste disposal. Minnesota legislatorsshould make sure that the costs of nuclear decommissioning and waste disposalin Minnesota are fully paid out of the windfall profits from competition, nottranferred by slight of hand to the public.<p><LI>Utilities are eager to increase their earnings through performance-basedrates. Improvements in performance will come primarily from eliminating excesscosts that were of little concern to utility executives under cost-based rates.Minnesota legislators and regulators should assure that any earnings fromperformance-based rates go first to pay off any claimed stranded costs.<p><LI>Large customers will attempt to use their political and market power totransfer "stranded costs" to others regardless of the course of deregulation.Minnesota regulators should review competitive rate proposals and "innovative"rate structures in the context of the overall impact on revenue allocation byclass.  Shareholders' should also accept a share of responsibility fordecreased revenue from large customers.  </UL><p>It is widely agreed that most of the real efficiency gains from deregulationcan be achieved through wholesale competition in bulk power production.  In anytransition to retail competition, the legislative and regulatory treatment of"stranded costs" has the potential to transfer enormous amounts of wealthbetween ratepayers and shareholders and between classes of ratepayers.  It isthe prospect of being on the receiving end of these transfers of wealth, andnot true wealth creation through increased productivity, that has sparked theinterest in retail competition.  In light of the intractable complexitiesinvolved in the valuation and allocation of "stranded costs," responsiblepublic policy requires a rational and orderly process to assure that the validclaims of all parties are treated fairly.  Minnesota has one of the lowest costelectric utility systems in the world.  We should not rush to implementinadequately considered fixes to a system that is broken somewhere else, whenit is not in fact broken in Minnesota.  Minnesota legislators and regulatorsshould take the time to craft a responsible public policy on stranded costs.<p>In the case of higher cost renewables utilities should have to prove that therewill be no market for them as higher priced "green" power required underresource procurement plans and that they have net stranded costs after weighingrenewables off against their stranded benefits.<p><H3>References</H3>Black, Bernard, 1994.  "A Proposal for Implementing Retail Competition in theElectricity Industry."  <i>Electricity Journal</i>.  October 1994.<p>Bradford, Peter, 1995.  "A Regulatory Compact Worthy of the Name."<i>Electricity Journal</i>.  November 1995.<p>Cearley, Reed and Lance McKinzie, 1995.  "The Economics of Stranded Investment- A Two-Way Street."  <i>Electricity Journal</i>.  November 1995.<p>Cohen, Armond and Steve Kihm 1994.  "The Political Economy of Retail Wheeling,or How Not to Re-Fight the Last War."  <i>Electricity Journal</i>.  April1994.<p>Ivins, Molly, 1996.  "Utilities Deregulation Would be a Bigger Ripoff than theS&amp;Ls"  <i>Star Tribune Newspaper of the Twin Cities</i>.  March 21, 1996.<p>Kahn, Ed, 1994.  "A Modest Proposal"  Nationalize the U.S. Nuclear Industry toFoster Competition."  <i>Electricity Journal</i>.  June 1994.<p>Kahn, Alfred, 1994.  "Can Regulation and Competition Coexist?  Solutions to theStranded Cost Problem and Other Conundra."  <i>Electricity Journal</i>.October 1994.<p>Matlock, Ronald J. 1995.  "Been There, Done That:  Lessons Learned from aReport on Stranded Investment." <i> Electricity Journal</i>.  November 1995.<p>Michaels, Robert, 1994.  "Unused and Useless:  the Strange Economics ofStranded Investment."  <i>Electricity Journal</i>.  October 1994.<p>Maize, Kennedy P., 1994.  "Stranded Investment-- $300 Billion Anchor, or `TonyaHarding' Issue?" <i> Electricity Journal</i>.  March 1994.<p>Sant, Roger and Roger Naill, 1994.  "Let's Make Electricity GenerationCompetitive."  <i>Electricity Journal</i>.  October 1994.<p><HR>Return to <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/">Sustainable Minnesota Home Page</A></body></html>
