<HEAD>
<TITLE>Request for an Environmental Impact Statement: MN Utility Deregulation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<CENTER><H3>STATE OF MINNESOTA<P>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</H3>
<BR>
In the Matter of an Investigation into Docket E-999/CI-95-135<BR>
Structural and Regulatory Issues <BR>
in the Electric Utility Industry<BR>
</CENTER><P>
<HR>

<CENTER><B>COMMENTS OF MINNESOTANS FOR AN ENERGY EFFICIENT ECONOMY<P>
July 7, 1995</B><P></CENTER>

<H4>D. REQUEST FOR AN ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT STATEMENT</H4>
ME3 will argue herein that conditions in Minnesota do not warrant a radical restructuring or deregulation of the state's electric utility industry. However, other parties may propose and the Commission may consider, some  radical restructuring schemes. ME3 believes that such proposals, now under active consideration in other jurisdictions, would pose grave risks to the state's authority to enforce environmental regulations on generators or to compel development of non-polluting energy efficiency and renewable energy technologies.  <P>
Accordingly, ME3 strongly encourages the Commission to order the preparation of an Environmental Impact Statement (EIS), perhaps in conjunction with the instant investigation, but prior to adoption of any formal rules in this area. Authority for such an order can be found under the state's environmental policy act at Minn. Stat. Chapter 116D, which specifies the need for an EIS in any proposed agency action that might result in adverse environmental impacts. The Commission may wish to consult with the Environmental Quality Board as to the selection of the Responsible Governmental Unity before proceeding.<P>

</BODY>
</HTML>

