<HEAD>
<TITLE>Need for Change: MN Utility Deregulation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<CENTER><H3>STATE OF MINNESOTA<P>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</H3>
<BR>
In the Matter of an Investigation into Docket E-999/CI-95-135<BR>
Structural and Regulatory Issues <BR>
in the Electric Utility Industry<BR>
</CENTER><P>
<HR>

<CENTER><B>COMMENTS OF MINNESOTANS FOR AN ENERGY EFFICIENT ECONOMY<P>
July 7, 1995</B><P></CENTER>

<H4>E.   Need for Change</H4>
<I>1.Is there a need to change the current structure and regulation of Minnesota's electric industry?</I><P>
Many parties to this proceeding will argue that the elimination of the traditional system of monopoly and cost-of-service regulation is inevitable. ME3 is not convinced, however, that the trend towards largely unregulated competition is necessarily in the public interest. While we recognize that the current system has significant flaws which must be remedied, we also believe that unregulated competition poses serious technical and public policy questions that cannot be answered by a generic reference to the ability of "market forces" to provide solutions to the most vexing and complex of issues.<P>
ME3 does not challenge the proposition that the future is likely to bring more rather than less competition to the energy system. ME3 also believes that competition can offer a smart change for the better. At the present time, however, the driving force behind many proposed changes are large industrial customers seeking relief from high energy prices that have resulted from poor capital investment decisions by utilities. Particularly in states where stranded investments are very large, industrial energy prices are often uncompetitive and the pressure for restructuring is great. <P>
None of these conditions exist in Minnesota. The state's industrial rates are comparatively low, some low-income customers are offered discounted rates, and major utilities have comparatively few capital investments which are uneconomic. Minnesota is also poised to take advantage of very significant clean renewable development opportunities. In addition, resource planning which considers the full social costs combined with forecasted growth in demand gives Minnesota an even greater opportunity to diversify its resource portfolio.<P>
Given these conditions, ME3 urges the Commission to proceed cautiously in its efforts to restructure Minnesota's electric energy system. As stated above, it is clear that major elements of the current energy system are in need of significant reform and that Minnesota can benefit from improved competition in wholesale and electric generation. However, while we support reforms which lead to smart competition, we are opposed to radical restructuring driven by the needs and desires of specific companies seeking to gain greater control over particular markets. The profound differences between these two approaches to reform are easily demonstrated:<P>
<B>SMART COMPETITION</B><P>
More competition through bidding and small, diverse, and distributed generators.<P>
Stable, low electricity costs for everyone.<P>
Increased energy conservation through  supply-side and end-use efficiency.<P>
Cleaner, safer, and more diverse energy resources through resource planning and cost analysis that includes environmental costs.<P>
Excellent system reliability for routine and emergency back-up requirements.<P>
More research, demonstration and commercialization for sustainable energy development.<P>
Regulatory institutions and practices capable of articulating and implementing public policy goals and objectives. <P>
<B>RADICAL RESTRUCTURING</B><P>
Opportunity for domination of Midwest electricity by one utility.<P>
Small customers pay more now; everyone pays more later.<P>
Increase excess generation  and /or capacity shortages while conservation programs disappear.<P>
Residential and small commercial customers left to rely on oldest, dirtiest, least efficient and least diverse resource.<P>
Low-income customers left with uncertain access to affordable service.<P>
Reduced reliability because of cost and coordination difficulties.<P>
No one willing to invest in research, development and demonstration of efficiency and renewable technologies.<P>
No regulatory institutions capable of articulating or implementing public policy goals and objectives.<P>
The question that Minnesota must answer is how to restructure utility regulation and the generation, transmission and distribution of energy in a manner which obtains the potential benefits of greater competition while strengthening its commitment to environmental protection and social equity.<P>
<I>2.What are the advantages and disadvantages of various models moving from a more regulated, monopolistic structure to a less regulated (or unregulated) competitive structure? (For example, the advantages and disadvantages of vertically integrated monopoly service providers versus robust wholesale competition versus various forms of retail competition?)</I><P>
Commissions across the country are being asked to deal with a great number and variety of restructuring proposals. Despite this diversity, all of them share a common attribute: uncertainty about the consequences which will flow from their implementation. This is true for both the benefits and the costs of greater competition. Among the issues that must be addressed by any proposal are the following:<P>
(1)  the potential evolution of unregulated monopoly/oligopoly in response to competitive restructuring;<P>
(2)  vertical disintegration and the impact of nuclear power plants on utility competitiveness;<P>
(3)  the stranded investment dilemma;<P>
(4)  the role of long-term integrated resource planning;<P>
(5)  increasing barriers to conservation the diminution of environmental protection;<P>
(6)  obligation to serve and other distributional/equity issues; and<P>
(7)  loss of state jurisdictional authority.<P>
Many of these issues are discussed elsewhere in these Comments. Detailed comments are limited to the problems of market structure, vertical disintegration, and nuclear power plants.<P>
<B>The Evolution of Unregulated Monopoly or Oligopoly</B> <P>
As can be seen in the wholesale market, competition is not guaranteed by merely opening the market to all comers. The rush towards competition presents the possibility for an evolution to a system of unregulated oligopolies or even monopoly, particularly if the retail market is opened to highly competitive forces. Examples of this evolution can be observed even at the earliest stages of a more competitive environment. This is certainly true in the case of Minnesota and Wisconsin where two sizable electric utilities are attempting to merge. How does the merger of two large utilities contribute to greater competition?<P>
<B>Vertical Disintegration </B><P>
By extending competition to the retail level, vertical disintegration likely becomes necessary. Generation, transmission, distribution and energy services must be separated in order to set accurate prices for unbundled services in a competitive market, and to minimize the conflict of interest and potential gaming that would likely occur. In other words, generation companies would not be allowed to own transmission or distribution assets, and so on. This creates the problem of planning for appropriate levels of reliability, since traditional cooperation among vertically integrated utilities would likely not withstand competitive pressures.<P>
Vertical disintegration is particularly difficult in the case of nuclear power plants. To a great extent, those utilities with a high degree of "nuclear exposure" are most likely to be experiencing higher electricity prices. In a restructured environment, these utilities will try to shed such inefficient generating assets. Unfortunately, there are likely to be few buyers for nuclear power plants; even more worrisome, there are likely to be even fewer buyers who are competent to operate such complex technology. The uncertain costs of decommissioning and spent fuel disposal has also proven to be too much of a risk for other countries experimenting with competitive markets, as evidenced by the failure of the United Kingdom to privatize its nuclear industry. <P>
<I>3.What is the best electric industry and regulatory structure for the state of Minnesota?</I><P>
ME3's view of what constitutes the "best" utility and regulatory structure for the State of Minnesota continues to evolve as more and more of the complexities associated with restructuring become clear. As discussed in the preceding two questions, however, we are certain about at least two things. First, we draw a strong distinction between smart competition and radical restructuring. Second, any restructuring plan carries with it both benefits and costs. <P>
Because of the highly tentative nature of many restructuring proposals, ME3 defers comment on the "best electric industry and regulatory structure for the state of Minnesota." We offer instead a number of Principles which we think should guide the Commission in its deliberations about any proposal.<P>
<B>Principles for Any Restructuring of the Electric Industry</B><P>
The test of a good proposal is the extent to which it:<P>
(1)  guarantees universal access to electric service;<P>
(2)  equitably allocates all costs across all classes of ratepayers;<P>
(3)  provides guarantees against market domination by any corporation or utility while simultaneously offering assurance regarding the existence of many sellers, including small-scale  energy producers;<P>
(4)  maintains and strengthens Minnesota's commitment to  environmental protection and to long-range resource planning;<P>
(5)  expands investment in cost-effective conservation and renewable energy;<P>
(6)  provides strong protection against job loss and the erosion of  bargaining power, worker pay and benefit levels.<P>
(7)  ensures affordable or more affordable electric service for all customer classes in both the short- and long-term and offers meaningful choice to those customer classes;<P>
(8)  increases investment in low-income customer assistance and energy efficiency programs<P>
(9)  establishes high standards for customer service, including consumer protection measures;<P>
(10)  informs the general public of potential changes in the electric industry and encourages broad public participation through statewide public hearings;<P>
(11)  maintains safe and reliable service; and<P>
(12)  enhances and improves regulatory practices and assures that states will have the ability to pursue and achieve public policy goals and objectives.<P>
Many of these Principles are discussed in other parts of our Comments. Detailed discussion is provided only for those Principles not elsewhere discussed.<P>
<B>Equitably Allocate All Costs Across All Classes of Ratepayers </B><P>
In a fundamental way, this issue is a driving force in the debate. Residential and small commercial users have benefited from some protection within the present regulatory system. If market power alone determines the pricing of electricity, the rates experienced by small users will inevitably go up as competition accelerates for industrial customers with large and stabilizing loads. It is only fair that classes of low-income residential and government purchasers have equal access to low-cost and/or stable cost power supply.<P>
Equally important, energy markets can only send the correct signals to ratepayers when all costs of energy production including appropriately allocated environmnetal costs that are presently externalized, are included in the price ratepayers pay for electric utility services.<P>
<B>Provide Guarantees Against Market Domination by Any Corporation or Utility While Simultaneously Offering Assurance Regarding the Inclusion of Small-Scale Energy Producers </B><P>
Monopoly, oligopoly and monopsony all confer excessive market power on a few companies. Such power oftentimes leads to a corresponding inefficiency in the pricing of energy. Vigorous but fair competition is welcome in the wholesale market, but for any radical restructuring, wholesale buyers and transmitters must be totally indifferent to who owns the generation of the power they buy (or transmit). Similarly, the distributors of the power must also be indifferent to who owns the generation. <P>
The restructuring discussion in Minnesota must not be driven by the proposed merger of two utilities well-positioned for market domination. In addition, small-scale producers of electricity must have ample opportunity in the market, especially providers capable of generating environmentally-benign electricity having long-term price stability.<P>
<B>Ensure Affordable or More Affordable Electric Service for All Customer Classes in Both the Short- and Long-Term </B><P>
Keeping electricity affordable in the long-term is a primary responsibility of the regulatory system. Any proposed price decrease through efficiency must be demonstrable; short-term rate freezes are no substitute for long-term price stability. If short-term competitive pricing drives the market, many investment decisions will err in favor of energy which is cheap now, but which may pose great risks to the consumer due to future escalation of fuel prices or future changes in environmental regulation. To avoid these imprudent investments, decisions must embody the full social costs of resource options, including the future risk of those costs being internalized in the price of energy.<P>
<B>Enhance and Improve Regulatory Practices While Assuring That States Will Have the Ability to Pursue and Achieve Public Policy Goals and Objectives  </B><P>
Radical restructuring will likely entail a significant reduction in state-level regulation and a parallel increase in the responsibilities of FERC. ME3 questions whether or not the loss of state autonomy, or more precisely, the loss of a state's ability to creatively respond to clearly voiced public policy goals and objectives, is desirable.<P>

</BODY>
</HTML>

