<HEAD>
<TITLE>Specific Issues : MN Utility Deregulation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<CENTER><H3>STATE OF MINNESOTA<P>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</H3>
<BR>
In the Matter of an Investigation into Docket E-999/CI-95-135<BR>
Structural and Regulatory Issues <BR>
in the Electric Utility Industry<BR>
</CENTER><P>
<HR>

<CENTER><B>COMMENTS OF MINNESOTANS FOR AN ENERGY EFFICIENT ECONOMY<P>
July 7, 1995</B><P></CENTER>
<H4>F.  Specific Issues Relating to Structural and Regulatory Change</H4>
<P>
<B>2.Technical Issues</B><P>
<I>a.What impact would electric utility restructuring have on system reliability? How would system reliability be managed?</I><P>
Reliability standards for generation and transmission are currently established by MAPP, an organization composed largely of utilities that voluntarily agree to plan and operate their facilities to meet an agreed upon level of reliability under a range of circumstances. MAPP does not include any independent power producers. There are concerns that increased wholesale competition would have an adverse effect on reliability because IPP's might not build and operate their facilities in a way that is consistent with regional standards. <P>
Retail competition would add several additional elements of uncertainty into the system planning process, including unexpected loss of load to competing suppliers and the extent of competing loads requiring transportation over the existing transmission and distribution system. It could also affect the joint planning and coordination of Minnesota's municipals, cooperatives and investor-owned utilities.<P>
<I>b.Who would be responsible for power quality in a restructured industry?</I><P>
In a more competitive industry, whether wholesale or retail, MAPP will likely no longer be adequate to ensure reliability. With MAPP, the utilities use, own and control access to transmission. In a restructured, or vertically disintegrated, power supply system, opportunities will be created for self dealing and the erection of access barriers to parties not owning or controlling access. <P>
Since 1993, MAPP has been exploring the formation of a Regional Transmission Group (RTG). The RTG would be responsible for transmission pricing, planning and reliability. Under the 1994 recommendation of the MAPP RTG Management Advisory Group, "public utility regulatory and environmental agencies with ratemaking or permitting, siting or similar authority related to transmission in the region would have the right to attend Management Committee and other committee meetings. State agency representatives would not be voting members of the Management Committee or of any other committee in order to protect their agencies' ability to regulate."<P>
 <P>
The question remains whether RTGs can self-regulate (subject to FERC oversight) without detracting from existing state authority, and what role state regulatory and other interested and affected parties will have. While it may be possible for an independent party, such as a Regional Transmission Group, to play a major role in assuring reliability, appropriate public agencies must retain regulatory control over a natural monopoly such as a transmission system.<P>
Even more problematic is how to achieve coordination among vertically disintegrated generators, transmission systems and distribution companies. While RTGs may be able to coordinate the actions of transmission companies, this solves only a small part of the problem. Currently, the integrated utility is able to reasonably gauge the number of new transmission lines they will require given forecasted demand and new generation. How this will be accomplished in a restructured environment, and under whose authority, has yet to be resolved. <P>
<B>3.Long-Range Planning</B><P>
Whatever one's view of the future electric utility industry, there will unquestionably be a need to maintain functions that are presently addressed through Minnesota's Integrated Resource Planning (IRP) process. These necessary functions include the balancing of supply and demand resources, transmission and distribution planning, load forecasting, pricing, reliability, commitments to energy efficiency and renewable energy sources, environmental protection, and public involvement in decisions affecting the public interest. Of particular concern to ME3 are the latter three functions that we feel are crucial to the future sustainability of Minnesota's energy supply. <P>
We are aware of arguments that, in a more competitive industry, utilities will be reluctant to share information to conduct planning that may hurt their competitive positions; and that pressures to reduce costs may cause utilities to substantially reduce commitments to DSM, renewables and environmental quality in whatever planning does take place. Utility inclinations along these lines only serve to increase the importance the Commission should attach to continued oversight in these areas through its IRP process. Of course, much depends on the type and degree of restructuring that actually occurs in Minnesota.<P>
The differences between a fully competitive wholesale market (which ME3 generally supports) and a deregulated market for retail customers (which ME3 fears would be disastrous for ratepayers and the environment) are enormous and require vastly different regulatory responses to maintain an effective IRP process. Without speculating about which outcome is most likely for Minnesota, ME3 offers the following thoughts on long-range planning issues raised in the Commission's order.<P>
<I>a.How would the benefits of resource portfolio management (i.e., the selection and purchasing of a combination of generating resources, purchased power and energy efficiency improvements that minimize the life-cycle cost and environmental impacts of energy services) be delivered in a restructured environment?</I><P>
The Commission's initiative to allow competitive bidding for new generation acquisitions has fundamentally changed the traditional portfolio management function. Instead of considering proposals for utility constructed, owned and operated generating plants, the commission now considers utility RFP's for power to be purchased from third party generators or utility affiliates, then approves contracts after an independently evaluated competitive bidding process has selected a "least cost" vendor. Even so, the commission must still ensure that the RFP balances the various planning concerns (i.e., price, reliability, environmental impacts, and resource diversity, including the state's preference for renewable energy). This process has already begun, and has the potential to ensure that Minnesota ratepayers are able to take advantage of emerging competition in the generation market, while continuing to enjoy the benefits of prudent portfolio management.<P>
More radical restructuring, however, may require more creative regulatory responses. The American Wind Energy Association, for example, has proposed a renewables portfolio standard-a market-based strategy to further the integration of renewables into the market. The AWEA proposal would require, as a condition of doing business in a state, that every power supplier (vertically-integrated utility, distribution-only utility, direct access supplier, or power aggregator) purchase a percentage of its energy needs from renewable resources. The percentage would be determined by the commission after considering Minnesota's current resource diversity, environmental protection and economic development goals, and other factors. Individual requirements could be made tradable so that every power supplier need not become a renewable energy developer and to allow the standard to be met in most flexible and cost-effective manner. Commission involvement would likely be limited to monitoring compliance and facilitating trading.<P>
AWEA's suggested approach is competitively neutral in that it applies to all competitors equally; it eliminates the need for government financing guarantees or utility contracts because the market can be expected to develop workable contracts; it would hedge fuel price and supply risks; it accounts for public goods such as clean air that cannot be captured by consumers; and it provides a predictable market for renewables, which will drive technology costs down rapidly. In addition, because the standard sets a floor rather than a ceiling, it allows power marketers to sell renewable energy to consumers wishing to exceed the standard. ME3 expects that, when faced with increasing competition, utilities will resist any type of obligation that could place them at even a slight disadvantage in short term markets that will not reward environmental benefits or risk mitigation. The portfolio standard, or some similar mechanism, would give the commission assurance that renewables, as well as other preferred resources, will be a valuable commodities in future markets by involving all power suppliers in contributing to a diverse resource portfolio for Minnesota.<P>
<I>b.What efforts, if any, should be made to perform long-term planning and minimize long-run costs, including environmental costs, under a model which includes retail competition?</I><P>
The Commission must maintain, at least during a transitional period, its authority to conduct long-range planning to minimize long-run costs, including environmental costs. Over time, these functions might appropriately be devolved to a regional planning authority, similar to those that already exist in the Pacific northwest and Tennessee Valley. Rather than superseding the commission's authority, a regional planning entity would be able to work with the commission and other state PUCs to more effectively plan generation and transmission investment and siting decisions by inter-state holding companies and small IPP's alike. This would be especially critical in a retail competition environment in which responsibility for region-wide stranded costs, resource diversity and environmental quality might otherwise be vague or nonexistent.<P>
<I>c.How would Research and Development be funded in a restructured industry? How would new technologies be developed, demonstrated and commercialized?</I><P>
An alternative to a renewables portfolio standard is now under discussion in California and New England. Some writers have coined the term "stranded benefits" to describe any utility investment in energy efficiency, renewables R&AMPD, or environmental protection that a utility avoids because it might have the effect of raising the direct cost of electricity. <P>
These writers argue that state regulators need a near-term strategy that can sustain utilities' progress on crucial long-term investments while the restructuring debate proceeds. They propose that cost recovery for such things as energy efficiency, low-income services, and renewables R&AMPD be converted to a non-bypassable, usage-based "system benefits charge" (sometimes referred to as a "wires charge") on electric distribution services. This would create a cost recovery structure capable of accommodating strong performance-based incentives, while maintaining consistency with all plausible restructuring options. Further, it would prevent distribution system users from bypassing their share of contributions to stranded benefits by designating a new electricity provider elsewhere on the grid. In this manner, the commission would retain the authority to assure cost recovery for investments that are crucial to sustaining high quality electric service.<P>
<B>4.Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy</B><P>
<I>a.How should energy efficiency be delivered in a restructured industry?</I><P>
<P>
Energy efficiency programs are currently mandated by a number of laws and regulatory practices. These mandates are justified on the basis of the different planning and payback horizons experienced by customers and utilities. That is, while consumers demand relatively short pay-back periods when they purchase energy-saving equipment, utilities can readily amortize the costs of efficiency measures over a much longer period of time. Energy efficiency measures therefore appear more desirable to utilities than to individual energy consumers. The result of these varying economic perspectives is that utilities have traditionally been seen as the logical vehicle for implementing energy efficiency policies. However, in an era in which the focus is limited to lowering costs experienced by the consumer, there is likely to be little support for energy efficiency. Even now, the mere threat of restructuring is causing utilities around the country to back away from their efficiency commitments, in that they are seen as inefficient when viewed from the very short run perspective that will likely dominate competitive retail markets. <P>
Our review of both the early experiences with more competitive environments and the likely impact that short-term planning will have on energy efficiency programs lead us to the same conclusion: the critical principle to be maintained in any restructured environment is that which was codified in Minnesota state law in 1983 and again in 1993. This law states that when new energy resources are needed renewables and energy efficiency should be used wherever possible. In fact, no non-renewable resource may be permitted unless it is demonstrated that the renewable alternative is not in the public interest. We strongly urge the Commission to continue to move forward with these principles adopted by the Minnesota Legislature. <P>
<I>b.In a restructured industry, what strategies should be used to overcome market barriers to cost-effective energy efficiency and renewable generation?</I><P>
After California, Minnesota leads the nation on implementing renewable energy development. Despite this relative level of development and despite the importance placed on renewables and efficiency by Minnesotans, and the reflection of that support in the actions of Minnesota legislators and regulators, Minnesota remains virtually totally dependent on fossil and nuclear fuels. Without explicit recognition of the local economic benefits and the environmental benefits of renewable energy and efficiency, fossil fuels will dominate our energy resources as they did before Minnesota enacted legislation and regulation to support renewables and efficiency. <P>
While Minnesota state law requires that energy efficiency and renewables have the first priority in resource development, the market will not follow this law on its own. In any restructured environment, strategies such as the inclusion of environmental externality values, set-aside policies, and preferential procurement policies in integrated resource planning will be needed to preserve and enhance our investments in renewable and efficiency-based resources. The rationale behind the tools used today to promote the development of clean reliable energy resources should not be abandoned, and the tools themselves should be improved in any restructuring environment.<P>
The inclusion of externality values will compensate for the inability of markets to effectively internalize the full social costs of energy production and use. Renewable fuels, such as wind, photovoltaics, and biomass, will be more competitive in a planning environment that weighs environmental costs and benefits along with fuel costs, capital, and operations and maintenance. <P>
Portfolio standards for renewables are critical for several reasons. First, they help to prove the cost-competitiveness of renewable technologies, as in the case of wind development projects on the Buffalo Ridge, which are now cheaper than coal and on par with natural gas, even without including external environmental costs. Second, portfolio standards are critical for new technologies specifically of interest and importance to Minnesota, such as biomass technologies. Such technologies need extra help at the commercialization stage, which set-asides can provide.<P>
<B>5.Public Interest Issues</B><P>
<I>a.Should universal service at reasonable rates be a goal in a restructured industry? How should this goal be achieved?</I><P>
ME3's positions on the public interest issues within this section have been developed based on significant input from the Energy CENTS Coalition, which ME3 recognizes an important voice for the energy concerns of low-income Minnesotans. <P>
Under the current system of electric industry regulation, utilities are obligated to serve all residential customers in their assigned territories.  This obligation is perhaps the most fundamental benefit of current regulation; movement away from this principle is likely to be one of the most significant changes in a more competitive industrial structure. Even when paying more than 15% of their income for utility service, low- and fixed-income people at least have the opportunity to purchase electricity. Particularly with recent programs designed to make electric service more affordable, the burden for some households is mitigated somewhat. Without the obligation to serve and affordable rate regulation, however, low- and fixed-income people may either be priced out of the market completely or have difficulty gaining access to service.<P>
The question of universal access is at the heart of this matter since the goals of current regulation and proposed changes seem incompatible. ME3 does not believe that universal service at reasonable rates is a goal of those parties that seek extensive competition in the electric industry. The absence of this goal means that low- and fixed-income people, while retaining the theoretical right to electric service, will not be offered the privilege of obtaining it. Minnesota regulated utilities must offer service regardless of ability to pay, at the very least, under most circumstances during the winter months.<P>
<I>c.How would public policy goals, such as cold-weather shut-off protection, the provision of affordable electric service to low-income customers, community economic development and the creation of a state renewable energy industry, be addressed in a restructured industry?</I><P>
ME3 agrees that restructuring presents a host of critical public policy issues, a great number of which are addressed elsewhere in these Comments. The following comments are directed at what we perceive to be the most important issues not addressed elsewhere.<P>
<B>i. Affordability</B><P>
Current statute allows the Commission to consider ability-to-pay as a factor in setting utility rates. Recent legislation calls for at least two pilot programs designed to assist low-income utility customers by offering utility rate discounts. Minnesota has just recently made significant progress in creating ways to address the problem of unaffordable utility service. In a deregulated electric industry, however, reasonable rate provisions and affordability programs have, at best, an uncertain future and, in the worst case, no future at all. <P>
While affordability is not explicitly addressed in current regulation, there are provisions which promote increased affordability through rate design. Under a deregulated system, neither access nor affordability is guaranteed. In fact, inability to afford the service may prohibit access. In a deregulated electric industry, affordability and access may be the same thing, particularly for low-income people.<P>
<B>ii. Customer Service</B><P>
Especially with unknowns surrounding the question of reliability, adequate levels of customer service are of particular importance. This would be particularly true under a deregulated system which allows for retail wheeling, in that customers who take power from an IPP would have no regulatory body for recourse if reliability is not adequate. Any alternative regulatory plan for the electric industry must therefore contain a customer service index that monitors key factors of customer satisfaction and service reliability, such as meter reading, outage restoration efficiency, call answer time at phone centers, and PUC complaint ratios. <P>
<B>iii. Low-Income Programs<P>
</B>Making utility bills more affordable will result in customer service efficiencies to utility companies, regularity in customer payments and service and the lessening of energy burdens on low-income people. Although not as widespread as they should be, Minnesota has enacted some of the solutions to the problem of unaffordable energy and these issues need to remain important considerations before the Commission. Unfortunately, in those areas of the country in which changes to the electric industry are further along, the prospects for continuing such programs are bleak. Indeed, without regulatory mandates, many of these programs, the primary goal for which was to make energy services more affordable, would never have been created.<P>
<I>d.Given that the generation and transmission of electricity can have adverse impacts on the environment, what is the best way to avoid or mitigate those impacts under a restructured industry?</I><P>
Over the last two decades a number of mechanisms have evolved which work against the traditional supply-side biases historically favored by utility planners. IRP and DSM programs, which put demand-side resources on a par with supply-side investments, have demonstrated their ability to identify cheaper energy resources and to encourage the development of least-cost renewable resources. As a result of the application of these tools Minnesota now finds itself far ahead of the nation in the development of non-polluting and cheap renewable resources. <P>
Unfortunately, these programs are now threatened by the advent of competitive energy systems. The reason for this threat lies in the mistaken presumption on the part of some energy producers that environmentally-sound investments represent a cost that cannot be afforded in a competitive world. Indeed, in those places where competition has either been integrated into the system or is on horizon, investments in DSM and other environmentally-conscious systems has declined. Market advocates dismiss the importance of these early experience with competition, arguing that, over the long haul, consumers will be allowed to make the decision as to whether or not they value "green energy". ME3 does not believe that "market-discipline" is an adequate basis for preserving and enhancing environmental quality. It is well established that significant market barriers exist which prevent energy prices from reflecting their full social costs. Equally significant barriers exist regarding the adoption of energy efficient technologies and practices on the part of both households and businesses. Indeed, it is precisely these barriers which have led Commissions to mandate the adoption of DSM and IRP.<P>
The importance of the Commission maintaining a proactive stance with respect to sound resource planning and environmnetal quality is shown in a recent report issued by the Oak Ridge National Laboratory. This report documents several likely responses on the part of Commissions when faced with increased pressures for deregulation and restructuring. One such scenario is "chaos", or a partially restructured industry where Commissions would only require historically-regulated utilities to comply with existing IRP/DSM and other public policy mandates rather than all new entrants into the energy system. Such a situation will undoubtedly lead to many parties making demands upon Commissions that they exempt all parties from such requirements, including "full-service" companies (i.e., existing utilities). ME3 views any movement in this direction as inviting significant harm for the operation of the electrical system, and in particular, for the maintenance of long-term environmental quality. Rather than retreating from traditional environmental concerns, the Commission should extend all public policy requirements to any entity which seeks to generate, transmit, or distribute energy to customers of any type. <P>
The continued use and refinement of the IRP process is a reasonable first step in assuring environmentally-conscious regulation within the context of a more competitive system. ME3 does not believe that the IRP process and competition are incompatible. Indeed, it is quite likely that more aggressive use of IRP can serve as an effective bridge to smart competition by making information on resources and their selection criteria available to all smaller, less powerful competitors in order that they might win market share. Thus, making IRP a more flexible tool can serve the interests of all parties. An important aspect of IRP's refinement is the competitive bidding process discussed in Section B(2)(c) above. The Commission should expand the scope of the process and reinforce the importance of the environmental criteria included in the selection process. The AWEA proposal discussed in Section B(2)(c) serves as a useful starting point for this effort.<P>
The Commission should also continue its efforts to assure that the full costs of energy of reflected in the price of energy. The Minnesota Legislature has required that the all environmental externalities be incorporated into the resource planning process. Retail competition should, however, not be allowed undermine this expressed public policy goal. In a fully disintegrated system, environmental damage is seldom experienced as a direct cost of doing business. As a result, no individual party has any incentive to include these costs in the price of a unit of electricity. In a system driven by the spot price of electricity, the additional price/cost increment required to account for human health effects, atmospheric damage, or mercury contamination associated with energy production and use is left out of the price signals delivered to the customer. ME3 urges the Commission to explore ways in which all parties in the energy system be accountable for the full costs of generating, transmitting and distributing their product in a more competitive environment.<P>
The ability to continue the successful development of policy tools capable of maintaining and enhancing environmental quality will depend upon the specific outcomes of the restructuring debate. ME3 does not believe that wholesale competition, by and large, threatens the environmental gains of the last two decades. It is our view, however, that the closer reform edges towards radical restructuring, the greater the likelihood for significant environmental harm. In the same vein, we believe that radical restructuring will undermine the State's ability to fashion effective tools in response to public policy goals and objectives.<P>

</BODY>
