<HEAD>
<TITLE>Transition Issues: MN Utility Deregulation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<CENTER><H3>STATE OF MINNESOTA<P>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</H3>
<BR>
In the Matter of an Investigation into Docket E-999/CI-95-135<BR>
Structural and Regulatory Issues <BR>
in the Electric Utility Industry<BR>
</CENTER><P>
<HR>

<CENTER><B>COMMENTS OF MINNESOTANS FOR AN ENERGY EFFICIENT ECONOMY<P>
July 7, 1995</B><P></CENTER>

<H4>G.  Transition Issues </H4>
<P>
<B>1.Role of Regulation</B><P>
<I>a.What should be the role and responsibility of the Commission in managing change in the electric industry?</I><P>
The electric industry is already changing, and has been for the last decade of two. The Commission has addressed these changes (and even initiated some of them) by reviewing the state's goals and desired outcomes, and examining the best method to achieve them. While the pace of change may be accelerating, ME3 believes that the Commission's central role should remain the same: to manage this change in a deliberate and orderly fashion. As we stated at the beginning of these comments, while we are convinced of the need for change, we are not convinced that widespread social benefits will be attained under the proposals for radical restructuring.<P>
<B>2.Treatment of Stranded Costs and Other Transition Costs</B><P>
<I>a.In the move to a more competitive market, what costs in Minnesota are likely to be stranded? What is your estimate of the stranded costs for any or all of Minnesota's utilities?</I><P>
Past investments, power purchase contracts, and public policy-driven programs that made sense in a era of cost-of-service regulation may not be cost-effective in a competitive power market. However, these investments were determined to be prudent by the Public Utilities Commission at the time they were made, and were based upon anticipated customer demand. Although some stranded investments may be created with wholesale competition, it has been estimated that the vast majority of stranded investments occur at the retail level. Stranded investments could include:<P>
1.  Stranded assets, primarily inexpensive power plants and excess capacity;<P>
2.  Stranded liabilities, primarily in power purchase contracts and  deferred income taxes; and<P>
3.  Regulatory assets, whose value is based on regulatory decisions  rather than on market forces, including deferred expenses and  costs for DSM paid for by all customers, special programs for  low-income customers, and support for energy research and   development; and<P>
4.  Fuel contracts and other long term agreements.<P>
The level of stranded costs that will occur in Minnesota will depend on many factors, not the least of which is the form that restructuring ultimately takes. A 1995 Oak Ridge report on Stranded Investments estimates that under a scenario where only industrial customers were allowed to leave the system, stranded costs might exceed 55 percent of Minnesota utility equity.1 <P>
<I>b.What are the legal and economic bases for stranded cost recovery by utilities?</I><P>
The issue of stranded investments is complicated by several fundamental issues. First, how are the value of the stranded assets and/or costs to be calculated? Second, suppose one observes that certain generating assets are less valuable today than last year and that, simultaneously, one or more major customers have left the system during this period. But suppose also that certain exogenous changes have taken place, say a recession. How does one distinguish the effects of these changes relative the decline in the value of the assets? Finally, who is to be responsible for paying for assets that were built due to forecasted system demand in prior periods, particularly when specific demand sectors can be identified (i.e., large industrial customers who might have sought to have nuclear power facilities built in the past and who are now seeking to remove themselves from the burden of these plants)? <P>
 <P>
A Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (NOPR) approved on March 29, 1995 by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) seeks to provide at least a partial answer to these questions. FERC established the principle that utilities are entitled to full recovery of legitimate and verifiable stranded costs at both the state and federal level. FERC stated that utilities may seek recovery through FERC-jurisdictional transmission rates.<P>
FERC also said that state's are expected to deal with any costs stranded due to retail wheeling or direct access programs. However, there is still much uncertainty over the difference between FERC's jurisdiction over transmission in interstate commerce and the state's jurisdiction over local distribution. The line that is drawn will determine what will come under the state's authority to assess stranded costs. We urge that the Commission continue to participate in FERC's rulemaking process in this matter to protect the interest of Minnesotans.<P>
<I>c.Is there an appropriate mechanism to allocate and recover stranded costs? If so, what is it?</I> <P>
Any mechanism chosen for recovery and allocation of stranded costs must be fair to all parties. In addition, no party should be allowed to avoid their share of an investment that they were at least partly responsible for.<P>
Three primary options for dealing with this problem have been discussed. The first is to offset revenue losses from customers leaving the system by raising rates for the remaining customers. This is inequitable, and has the additional problem of setting off the chain reaction of more customers leaving the system. Alternatively, rates could be left unchanged and investors would be forced to absorb the impact. This could seriously compromise the health of the utility before it even had a chance to compete. The third option is to attach a charge to all parties for their share of the recovery of those investments through some service that does not face competition-such as a transmission charge. The most equitable option to all concerned would likely be recovery through a transmission tariff. However, states may lack authority to set and collect transmission fees to pay for stranded investment or other programs.<P>


</BODY>
</HTML>

</DOC>
