<HEAD>
<TITLE>Structure of Benefits:  MN Utility Deregulation Reply</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H3>STATE OF MINNESOTA<P>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</H3>
<BR>
In the Matter of an Investigation into <BR>
Structural and Regulatory Issues <BR>
in the Electric Utility Industry<BR>
Docket E-999/CI-95-135
</CENTER><P>
<HR>

<CENTER><B>REPLY COMMENTS OF MINNESOTANS FOR AN ENERGY EFFICIENT ECONOMY<BR>
and<BR>
IZAAK WALTON LEAGUE OF AMERICA (MIDWEST OFFICE)<P>
September 11, 1995</B><P></CENTER>
<P>

<H3>1.  The "Structure of Benefits" Associated With Radical Restructuring: Big Winners, Big Losers</H3>
The Comments offered in this docket reveal a number of "fault lines" that fundamentally divide the parties to the restructuring debate. Perhaps the most important of these divisions involves the degree of support for radical restructuring and the likelihood of immediate benefit that will be obtained from unregulated markets. While not universal, most commentators supporting the radical reform proposals were those positioned to gain domination over electricity markets, or achieve substantial financial gain.<P>
We argued in our Initial Comments that radical restructuring is being advanced by those parties who, by virtue of their market power, will be able to reap substantial economic benefit in a radically restructured environment. The Comments offered by the parties to this Docket demonstrate the legitimacy of our argument. <P>
The Comments offered by the Large Power Intervenors (LPI) are typical of those parties most likely to reap immediate benefit should radical restructuring occur. LPI first asserts that the "question is not whether Minnesota's electric industry must change . . . (but) how to change"(LPI at 3). Claiming that both utilities and customers "have chafed under the strictures imposed by regulation"(LPI at 3) and citing the advantages brought about by the tentative steps towards wholesale competition, LPI asserts that retail wheeling would also produce similar benefits. Indeed, the LPI sees no need for the State "to wait ... to implement competition at the retail level"(LPI at 7).<P>
The arguments made by LPI are flawed in several respects. First, LPI acknowledges that the present system of regulation has yielded substantial benefits, most notably in the form of reliable service and guaranteed, if relatively high, rates (LPI at 3). Minnesotans for an Energy-Efficient Economy (the ME3 Coalition) and the Izaak Walton League of America, Midwest Office (IWLA) agree that service has been reliable and rates guaranteed. However, the argument that large customers pay high rates in Minnesota is not supported by any facts. LPI seems to be alone in their assertion that rates have been relatively high since it is an almost universally agreed upon point of fact in the Comments that Minnesota's electric rates, including those charged to industrial consumers, are among the lowest in the nation.<P>
Second, LPI asserts that "retail wheeling would involve both benefits and costs. For at least for some consumers (retail wheeling) would mean a choice of suppliers and a range of prices"(LPI at 4). The ME3 Coalition and IWLA agree. However, it is our view that the structure of benefits and costs would follow a predictable pattern: those with market power of the sort possessed by users represented by LPI would realize the benefits of restructuring while those customers without market power would be left to bear the costs of restructuring.<P>
Third, the road to restructuring, according to LPI, the Minnesota Energy Consumers (again representing the largest users of electricity), the American Forest and Paper Association, National Steel Corporation, and Northern States Power involves a retreat from the most important energy policy initiatives of the last two decades. In their zeal for radical restructuring, the Minnesota Energy Consumers (MEC), for instance, assert that "several barriers to competition must be removed in order to achieve a competitive electric industry . . . (including) certificate of need for the construction of new generation; energy efficiency program mandates; renewable generation mandates; and taxes and assessments"(MEC at 5). The ME3 Coalition and the IWLA emphatically reject the assertion that these policy instruments constitute a barrier to the achievement of a socially-efficient energy system. <P>
The supporters of radical restructuring do not, however, limit their proposals for change to policy provisions that have been successful at preventing the construction of unnecessary and polluting generating resources or to regulatory tools designed to bring on-line competitively-priced pollution-free electricity resources. Instead, MEC and others seek to establish a new and radically-narrow framework for Minnesota's energy policy goals. According to MEC, "the goal should not be universal service at reasonable rates. . . Instead the goal should be consumer choice, with varying levels of price and reliability based on that choice." This represent an extreme view of what should be the policy goals governing the electricity industry: nowhere in the Comments is the fault line between public and private interest more clearly articulated. The extension of this logic is quite profound. For instance, would those receiving no service due to an inability to pay be exercising that "consumer choice"? The ME3 Coalition and IWLA do not believe that any responsible body, including the PUC or the Minnesota Legislature should reject the notion that every home should have electricity. <P>
Far from being in the public's interest, radical restructuring will primarily serve the particular interests of large industrial customers, but even for them perhaps only in the short run. In fact, in the long run, the increased demand for electricity will drive up the price for natural gas, resulting in higher prices for everyone. In our view, the decision to discard the fundamental goal of universal service in pursuit of the hypothetical (and oftentimes arguable) benefits of retail competition is near the heart of the debate. In its most severe form, radical restructuring will not only mean that households with high enough incomes will have a cafeteria of electricity options for which there is little consumer demand; it will mean that those without adequate incomes may simply be left to freeze in the dark. <P>
</BODY>
</HTML>

</DOC>
