<HEAD>
<TITLE>Market as A Universal Solution:  MN Utility Deregulation Reply</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H3>STATE OF MINNESOTA<P>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</H3>
<BR>
In the Matter of an Investigation into <BR>
Structural and Regulatory Issues <BR>
in the Electric Utility Industry<BR>
Docket E-999/CI-95-135
</CENTER><P>
<HR>

<CENTER><B>REPLY COMMENTS OF MINNESOTANS FOR AN ENERGY EFFICIENT ECONOMY<BR>
and<BR>
IZAAK WALTON LEAGUE OF AMERICA (MIDWEST OFFICE)<P>
September 11, 1995</B><P></CENTER>
<P>

<H3>2.The Market as A Universal Solution</H3>
<P>
This proposed new "public interest" standard -that customer choice should be the only policy goal-  also substitutes for other existing goals like thoughtful long-range planning and environmental protection. As envisioned by LPI, MEC and others, radical restructuring assumes an unlimited capacity of unfettered markets to achieve the public's interest. According to this argument, regulators can safely ignore, among other things, the environmental consequences of energy production and the problems of assuring sufficient levels of costly research and development. Regulators can also abandon any mandates for Integrated Resource Planning, Demand Side Management, and energy efficiency and renewable energy. Instead, "truly competitive power supply markets" will (1) furnish sufficient incentives for power generators and suppliers to provide the most efficient and reliable power at costs demanded by the market; (2) allow a determination as to whether it is in producer's and consumer's best interests to minimize environmental damage; (3) allow short-term considerations to dictate whether it is in producer's best interests to engage in research and development of emerging clean technologies, such as biomass gasification and photovoltaics; (4) allow consumers to make environmentally sound decisions, again, assuming it in their best economic interests to do so; and (5) allow cost-effective efficiency and renewable resources to enter the market. <P>
The ME3 Coalition and IWLA do not dispute that a competitive market represents one kind of social choice mechanism which is well-suited to achieve certain social goals. However, not only is the range of tasks assigned in this case is truly heroic, it is highly problematic. First, the MEC, LPI and others presume that economic efficiency is the only basis upon which to make critical social judgments. We argue that public interest criteria, including that of universal electric service, environmental protection and resource diversity, represent more sound bases upon which to craft public policies. <P>
<P>
Second, the argument that a competitive market will address significant public interest issues seems to be willfully ignorant of basic principles of economics regarding barriers which inhibit competitive markets from adopting long-run socially-efficient measures. Far from being barriers to competitive markets, mandates and other social policies such as cold-weather shutoff policy or inclusion of environmental costs in resource selection, are responses to structural failures that prevent competitive markets from achieving long-run social efficiency. These principles were enunciated in our Initial Comments and have been even more thoroughly addressed by the Comments of the Attorney General.<P>
Finally, the ME3 Coalition and IWLA question whether or not deregulated energy markets will yield a result that even marginally resembles the kind of competition presumed by many of the parties. "Perfect competition" as an ideal type of market system presumes the existence of many small companies producing similar, price-differentiated products. Yet, early indications are that competition in the energy field will produce oligopoly or perhaps even monopoly. "Merger-mania" is not limited to Minnesota and Wisconsin, but is currently affecting electricity markets in all regions of the country: this summer, proposed mergers were announced between Philadelphia Electric Company and Philadelphia Power and Light; Union Electric and Central Illinois Public Service near St. Louis: and Southwesterrn Public Service Company and Public Service of Colorado. Mega-mergers of regulated monopolies promises to result in bigger and fewer "competitors" rather than diversity and differentiation among many small suppliers of electricity.<P>
</BODY>
</HTML>

