<HEAD>
<TITLE>Loss of Portfolio Diversity:  MN Utility Deregulation Reply</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H3>STATE OF MINNESOTA<P>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</H3>
<BR>
In the Matter of an Investigation into <BR>
Structural and Regulatory Issues <BR>
in the Electric Utility Industry<BR>
Docket E-999/CI-95-135
</CENTER><P>
<HR>

<CENTER><B>REPLY COMMENTS OF MINNESOTANS FOR AN ENERGY EFFICIENT ECONOMY<BR>
and<BR>
IZAAK WALTON LEAGUE OF AMERICA (MIDWEST OFFICE)<P>
September 11, 1995</B><P></CENTER>
<P>

<H3>3.  Loss of Portfolio Diversity Through DSM and Renewables under Radical Restructuring: Why Resource Planning Remains in the Public Interest</H3>
<P>
ME3's initial comments in this docket stressed the critical need to maintain the PUC's integrated resource planning (IRP) process to assure the future sustainability of Minnesota's energy supply. Commentators supporting what the ME3 Coalition and IWLA would describe as "radical restructuring" uniformly endorse the elimination of the current IRP process because, "the market will determine the type, timing and size of generation need based on price signals from the market"(NSP at 24). These proposals are particularly alarming; in their simplicity they overlook the public interest goals achieved through an effective IRP process, none of which are attainable through a singular reliance on competitive markets. <P>
Supporters of radical restructuring have not demonstrated, for example, how the market will act to assure the public that power plants will be built only when needed and using the least environmentally damaging fuels and technologies. Minnesota Energy Consumers suggests instead that "competition cannot exist if the need for additional electric generating facilities is governed by regulatory approval rather than customer demand"(MEC at 9). And NSP contends that, "resource acquisitions would be dictated by customer wishes" carried out by individual (read: large power) customers, or "aggregators." Some may equate the competitive process with the public interest; however, this equation offers no assurance that the public's interest will be served. <P>
 <P>
Indeed, it is unreasonable to expect that the largest buyers and sellers of power in a radically restructured market will attend to any interest other than near-term pricing. NSP suggests that 'aggregators' of power could package a mix of resources to a customer to market DSM and renewables. But why would an aggregator who hopes to stay in business offer such a mix when some of the benefits -such as clean air or mercury-free lakes- flow to society as a whole rather than any individual customer? Why too would an aggregator offer free-of-charge benefits to society when the extra value is unrecognized in the price paid by his customer? Even if the resulting price of a non-fossil fuel package were just one mil per kWh higher in cost than a fossil-fuel alternative, trusting large power customers to select even slightly higher cost power is a dangerous strategy for protecting the state's environment. For example, an industry such as wind energy, which appears capable of providing power over thirty years at 3.0-3.5&CENT/kWh, with negligible external environmental costs, could easily be driven out by the "customer choice" exercised by big industrials, who can find marginally cheaper gas-fired power for the short term. Clearly, loss of public participation and full-cost resource selection through IRP is an abandonment of the public's preferences and interests, in favor of private interests of big buyers and sellers who literally 'make' the market through buying power or market share. It is unfortunate that Minnesota competitors in global markets are focused on near-term costs, when key competitors such as Japan and European Union consistently plan for the long term. <P>
While the ME3 Coalition and IWLA anticipated the clear self-interest of NSP and large consumers, the comments of the Department of Public Service were especially troubling. While the Department seeks to position itself as an honest broker of the policy issues inherent in this debate, it has unfortunately adopted much of the rhetoric of radical deregulation and a commitment to retail wheeling, a stance to our knowledge unmatched by any state energy agency or regulatory commission in the nation.<P>
As the state agency charged with protecting the public's interest in energy, the Department avers that planning and competition are not mutually exclusive. The ME3 Coalition and IWLA agree in principle. However, we are surprised at the extension of this precept to a conclusion which is not sufficiently supported by Department analysis. The Department contends that while any remaining vertically-integrated utilities' plans for new generation should be subject to regulatory review (the Department makes no specific mention of IRP), for all other generators, "long term cost minimization will be market-driven"(DPS at 7). <P>
The Department correctly argues that efficient markets must recognize external environmental costs, but offers no conviction that this sine qua non of a true market can be reasonably implemented as part of restructuring reform. Their first proposal is to employ the allowance-trading scheme now in place to control sulfur dioxide emissions, and extend such a system to other emissions. After three years, the only successful component of the EPA's Acid Rain Program is the nationwide cap on emissions. Allowance trading has failed to materialize as most utilities have shown little interest in trading the marketable permits. Similarly, the Department contends that demand-side management and renewable-energy investments can be left to the market, except for customers of a "host" utility for whom regulators will set DSM investment levels. The ME3 Coalition and the IWLA seriously question NSP's argument that, "(e)nergy efficiency and renewables that are truly cost-effective should be able to compete with other options"(Emphasis added, NSP at 26). DPS's and NSP's facile belief in the power of a competitive market to do good ignores the fact that market failures have always prevented cost-effective DSM and renewables from coming to the market on their own. A competitive market for retail power does not remove these market failures; it exacerbates the failures by taking away regulatory authority to correct them. It is a troubling contradiction that the Department of Public Service fails to recognize market barriers to DSM and renewables in this docket, and yet remain committed to a "societal test" of cost-effectiveness in its review of CIP dockets. Neither does DPS reconcile contradictory views that electricity generators will "bear the full social costs of their actions" with the recommendation to move to full retail competition. DPS does not say how full-cost accounting and the societal test of cost-effectiveness can avoid being undermined in a pure retail market, other than to suggest that "(w)e will need to develop new ways"(DPS at 11).<P>
A market-driven system, for example, will not reverse decades of Federal subsidies to coal, natural gas and nuclear power that keep prices artificially low. A recent study by the Alliance to Save Energy calculated these subsidies to be $36 billion in 1989 alone. Competition, by itself, does not change the split incentives for renters and landlords to invest in energy efficiency, or overcome the high discount rates most consumers apply to energy-efficiency investments. And yet, society's interest is in seeing that energy-efficiency and renewable-energy investments do not disappear simply because competition is introduced in electricity markets. Society continues to prefer clean air to dirty air, lower costs of production to higher costs, and the technical capability to make the transition away from finite fuel resources. But nowhere do the supporters of radical restructuring make plausible arguments for the continuation of the benefits we all enjoy from IRP, DSM and renewables in their restructuring proposals.<P>
While the ME3 Coalition and the IWLA are skeptical of many of the Department's positions, we applaud their suggestion for fundamental changes in the pricing of energy. This is a laudable goal historically supported by the ME3 Coalition and IWLA. We have supported various policy instruments which enable a full-cost accounting of electricity resource options. We welcome the Department's views that internalization of now-externalized costs improve the efficiency of the market. Full internalization of social and environmental costs would be a major first step to correcting the most serious environmental damages of a fully deregulated market.<P>

</BODY>
</HTML>

