<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reforms for Competition in Wholesale Market:  MN Utility Deregulation Reply</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H3>STATE OF MINNESOTA<P>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</H3>
<BR>
In the Matter of an Investigation into <BR>
Structural and Regulatory Issues <BR>
in the Electric Utility Industry<BR>
Docket E-999/CI-95-135
</CENTER><P>
<HR>

<CENTER><B>REPLY COMMENTS OF MINNESOTANS FOR AN ENERGY EFFICIENT ECONOMY<BR>
and<BR>
IZAAK WALTON LEAGUE OF AMERICA (MIDWEST OFFICE)<P>
September 11, 1995</B><P></CENTER>
<P>

<H3>4. Complete Reforms for Competition in Wholesale Market Before Consideration of Retail Competition </H3>
<B><BR>
</B>The various supporters of radical restructuring want to push the state toward competition at the retail level without evaluating whether we have even begun to reap the benefits of emerging competition at the wholesale level. As the Department correctly notes, efforts to capture the benefits of wholesale competition, such as competitive bidding for new generation, should be regarded as "work in progress"(DPS at 2). In contrast, National Steel argues that "the wholesale market is nearly as active as it can get, and retail competition through direct bilateral contracts is required to introduce any significant level of competition into the electric industry"(National Steel at 6). This assertion flies in the face of the preponderant weight of evidence. The activity on the wholesale market, and the diversity of entities using the market is rapidly increasing. The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission's (FERC') Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (NOPR) on open access to the transmission grid is still in the early comment phase. This NOPR is designed to facilitate new wholesale transactions and competition. It is premature to say that the benefits of wholesale competition have been maximized before open access allows the complete and robust competition of multiple wholesale generators. In Minnesota, only NSP has a bidding system in place to access the emerging competitiveness of wholesale power markets.<P>
The Large Power Intervenors note that ". . . wholesale generation markets cannot be truly competitive until all investment and operational risk associated with generation is internalized to the owners of those facilities"(LPI at 8) The ME3 Coalition and IWLA find it curious that retail competition is considered by LPI to be an improvement, given that fewer of the external costs of electricity production will be internalized. Wholesale generation markets should first be made more efficient by internalizing environmental and social costs (including risk) before attempting to fix the much larger problems raised by retail competition. The existing regulatory apparatus, industry structure, and means of distributing benefits can partially internalize social costs and benefits through wholesale competition. The same cannot be said for retail competition.<P>
In addition, the ME3 Coalition and IWLA strongly caution the Commission that the public interest issues we have raised relative to retail competition are not close to being resolved. Yet National Steel points out that if Minnesota is the first state on the block to have retail wheeling, "many electricity intensive industries that depend on low cost power and that have been demanding direct access may consider expansion into Minnesota because of retail electric competition"(National Steel at 4). National's enthusiasm for new industrial development in Minnesota notwithstanding, the state may first want to consider whether enacting retail competition for the purpose of attracting energy-intensive "smokestack industries" is in the state's best interest. Consider that the future growth of the world's economy and the creation of high-paying jobs will be from clean industries, including high-technology, communications, and other high-value-added and information-based industries.<P>
The ME3 Coalition and IWLA believe that competition at the wholesale level has yet to deliver its potential benefits to Minnesota electric consumers. With significant excess capacity remaining in the region it seems likely that it will take years, even with open access transmission, for the remaining low cost power to find its way to consumers. A headlong rush to retail competition will only serve to allow large power customers to push their way to the head of the line for this cheap power. Even National Steel has to admit that, "large industrial customers stand to benefit the most from retail competition"(National Steel at 5). Retail competition is unlikely to fairly distribute costs and benefits of electricity production between customer classes.<P>

</BODY>
</HTML>

