<HEAD>
<TITLE>Retaining Needed Regulatory Capacity:  MN Utility Deregulation Reply</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H3>STATE OF MINNESOTA<P>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</H3>
<BR>
In the Matter of an Investigation into <BR>
Structural and Regulatory Issues <BR>
in the Electric Utility Industry<BR>
Docket E-999/CI-95-135
</CENTER><P>
<HR>

<CENTER><B>REPLY COMMENTS OF MINNESOTANS FOR AN ENERGY EFFICIENT ECONOMY<BR>
and<BR>
IZAAK WALTON LEAGUE OF AMERICA (MIDWEST OFFICE)<P>
September 11, 1995</B><P></CENTER>
<P>

<H3>5.  Retaining Needed Regulatory Capacity to Meet Agreed-upon Policy Goals</H3>
</B><BR>
Given the public interest implications of greater competition in the electric industry, the ME3 Coalition and IWLA have argued that the Commission must retain its regulatory capacity to assure that the public's interests are truly protected. Proponents of radical restructuring argue instead for stripping the Commission of most of its real authority. Minnesota Energy Consumers typifies this position. It suggests that the Commission itself propose legislation this year to repeal statutes related to exclusive service territories, Certificate of Need for construction of new power plants, energy efficiency mandates (i.e. CIP), and renewable generation preferences. (MEC at 5). At the federal level, NSP asks the Commission to support repeal of PURPA (NSP at 15), the very statute that brought competition to wholesale electric markets, and that offers any opportunity to dispersed and renewable generators for finding a market niche. The only thing left within the Commission's jurisdiction would be rate setting at the local distribution level. Other commentators propose the elimination of the Commission's integrated resource planning authority, and the transfer of responsibility for "social programs"(e.g., CIP, cold weather shut-off protection, etc.). to a governmental agency to be named later. In other words, radical restructuring proponents want the Commission stripped of any meaningful ability to protect the public interest.<P>
The ME3 Coalition and IWLA have detailed elsewhere in our initial and reply comments the potential effect on system planning and the environment caused by the elimination of the Commission's IRP process. We have not discussed other difficulties, already experienced in other deregulated industries, that await Minnesota electric consumers. Without state-level IRP and ratemaking authority, the Commission will find it difficult to regulate the activities of existing and yet-to-be-formed multi-state holding companies. While NSP worries only about recovery of stranded costs and disparities in treatment of environmental costs from state to state, the Commission should be worried about how it will enforce a rational approach to capacity planning with a multi-state holding company like NSP's proposed Primergy. Other deregulated industries have also encountered severe problems in maintaining adequate customer service. There is a real danger that all-out efforts to be the lowest cost provider forces companies to sacrifice service maintenance operations first, particularly for those customers without market choice. It is unclear how the Commission's current authority to adjust service quality complaints will be effected by a move to retail competition.<P>

</BODY>
</HTML>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT15-B08-21</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA007-000067-B012-159</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.me3.org:80/projects/dereg/me3rply7.html 198.174.235.57 19970222005052 text/html 8541
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 22 Feb 1997 00:51:13 GMT
