Content-length: 8370
Last-modified: Wed, 16 Oct 1996 20:04:36 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Social and Environmental Costs of Electricity:  MN Utility Deregulation Reply</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H3>STATE OF MINNESOTA<P>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION</H3>
<BR>
In the Matter of an Investigation into <BR>
Structural and Regulatory Issues <BR>
in the Electric Utility Industry<BR>
Docket E-999/CI-95-135
</CENTER><P>
<HR>

<CENTER><B>REPLY COMMENTS OF MINNESOTANS FOR AN ENERGY EFFICIENT ECONOMY<BR>
and<BR>
IZAAK WALTON LEAGUE OF AMERICA (MIDWEST OFFICE)<P>
September 11, 1995</B><P></CENTER>
<P>

<H3>6.  Social and Environmental Costs of Electricity:  Characterization of Costs as Social Programs</H3>
<BR>
A number of commentators, including NSP, National Steel, and the Minnesota Energy Consumers, recommended eliminating "social programs" or "social goals" in the restructuring of electricity regulation. Included in the characterization of "social programs" were renewable-energy development and energy-efficiency investments, low-income affordability goals, and economic development issues. These commentators disingenuously argue that these goals will be met by the market, or more cynically, that government should take on these responsibilities. The above commentators would lead the Commission to believe that traditional regulation seeks merely to impose a variety of social costs upon private parties, i.e.. utilities and large customers and that retail competition is a means to properly readjust the cost structure. <P>
The environmental and social costs associated with public interest goals are not, however, eliminated in a retail competition scenario. The costs are shifted to someone else. In our view, the interest in retail competition is not cost-efficiency, but cost-avoidance. To say that the price of energy should not reflect real but unallocated environmental costs makes no more sense than saying that the price of steel should not reflect environmental protection, or that the price of lumber should not reflect sustainable forestry management. To say that the price of energy should not reflect costs such as lifeline rates for low-income users makes no more sense than saying the price of automobiles should not reflect the costs borne by the auto industry to minimize bad debt. <P>
By characterizing real costs as "social programs", the commentators trivialize important policy goals for the electric industry such as universal access, ensuring fuel and resource diversity, minimizing environmental risks which are potentially catastrophic and/or irreversible, and minimizing bad debt, collections, and reconnection fees. Calling these long-held policy goals "social programs" is an attempt to further externalize real costs from energy prices. Ensuring that our power mix includes efficiency and renewables, and proactively addressing social consequences of affordability through lifeline rates and shutoff moratoriums, recognizes that the real price of energy extends beyond the cost of capital and fuel and labor. <P>
Several parties point to a two-tiered energy supply market as a major concern under a partially-deregulated system. Minnegasco, for instance, hypothesizes that "in a more competitive environment, supply services for both electricity and natural gas will likely be provided by entities who are not subject to current state regulation,"(Minnegasco at 6). According to NSP, unregulated entities will enjoy a major competitive advantage in that they will be free of the cost burdens of "environmental, conservation, and social program(s)"(NSP at 13). Consequently, "(t)he Commission should examine the effect of . . .social programs . . . on the ability of electric utilities to compete with unregulated entities"(Minnesota Energy Consumers at 20). In our view, these recommendations constitute a prelude to total deregulation. Considered alongside MEC's urging the Commission to abandon its most substantive powers and NSP's suggested repeal of major PURPA provisions, the thrust of these proposals is nothing less than the wholesale abandonment of the public interest in the pricing and selling of electricity. Far from being a rationale for retail competition, the presence of a two-tiered energy supply system is an argument against moving to a retail competition environment, since the full costs of energy cannot reasonably be internalized under such a regime. <P>
Parties that characterize environmental and fuel diversity goals as "social programs" also assert that "(e)nvironmental impacts . . . have already been addressed in Minnesota's and the Federal government's environmental regulation laws." Minnesota Energy Consumers (at 18) fails to recognize the inability of the market to adequately address uncertainty. Environmental regulation addresses those risks we understand and have determined to be too high. Environmental regulation does not, however, address the extraordinary uncertainty associated with potentially catastrophic events. The typical response to uncertainty about catastrophic events such as global warming in an unregulated market is, "we don't know what the potential consequence are, but neither do our competitors, so we will ignore it." Only after the catastrophic event are the costs of such a strategy paid. Sustained orderly development of renewable energy capacity is, at a minimum, an effort to mitigate that uncertainty, an uncertainty which poses costs which cannot be effectively transferred to the market. <P>
Many of the parties calling for radical restructuring offer very little guidance on how broader public policy goals, such as the consideration of environmental costs, will be achieved in the absence currently available policy mechanisms. The Department of Public Service for instance, provides a self-contradictory argument on ensuring the continued incorporation of the full costs of energy in resource selection and rate setting. While supporting the existing public policy goals of environmental protection, shutoff protection, universal service, and affordability, DPS recommends moving toward a retail competition environment where existing mechanisms to achieve these goals will be entirely eliminated. At best, DPS makes a cavalier attempt to reconcile these contradictory views, never explaining how providers of generation service will "bear the full social costs of their actions"(DPS at 11) in a competitive retail environment. "We will need to develop new ways . . ." states DPS. Never does DPS adequately enunciate these potential new ways or grapple with the economic and/or policy implications of such mechanisms that require generators to "bear the full costs of their actions." It is especially ironic that DPS recommendations for retail competition likely will sweep away the policy instruments now used to address such social priorities, however inadequately.<P>
Finally, the suggestion made by several parties that "social programs" be shifted to government and funded through general revenues is disingenuous at best. Industrial and utility parties often accuse environmental interests of having the not-in-my-backyard syndrome (NIMBY). In advocating for government to cover social costs associated with energy, these commentators have fallen onto their own NIMBY refrain. "Yes, we need environmental and affordability protections," they say, "but not on my dime!" Self-interest in an unregulated environment will lead parties to try to escape paying legitimate costs associated with their energy consumption. In this era of massive downsizing of governmental programs, where protection of the environment and low-income citizens have been especially targeted for cuts, suggesting that these costs should be covered via new government programs and taxes is fundamentally an admission that the objectives should be eliminated.<P>
The Large Power Intervenors stated that "the risks associated with generation can never be fully allocated to shareholders as long as captive customers remain a ready repository for risk and cost shifting"(LPI at 8). The ME3 Coalition and IWLA suggest a corollary to this axiom: The risks associated with generation can never be properly allocated to the beneficiaries of that generation as long as those large power consumers can successfully shift those risks and costs to the government, regardless of the government's readiness to assume them.<P>

</BODY>
</HTML>

