<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>
<p>

<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Defining Competition"><H3><B>Defining Competition</B></H3></A><p>
<p>
<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Competition refers"><H3><B>Competition refers both to a process and a market structure.</B></H3></A><p>
<p>
Competition as process involves rivalry among firms for customers.  Usually,
this rivalry involves providing better service or a better price.  Competition
as a market structure requires that there be a number of comparable suppliers
in the market, as well as a number of comparable customers. <p>
<p>
By "comparable," economists mean that several suppliers of generally equal size
and market&nbsp;share participate in the market to serve several customers of
equivalent demand characteristics. Otherwise, either a dominant supplier or a
dominant customer can exert market power over the market, meaning the dominant
actor could raise prices without experiencing a decrease in revenues.  As a
result, the benefits of competition could not be realized.  These benefits
include<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI> lower prices (or more technically correct, output prices approximating the marginal aggregate costs of inputs)<p>
<p>
<LI> a more efficient allocation of resources<p>
<p>
<LI>	increased innovation<p>
<p>
<LI> a better quality product or service<p>
</UL>
	<p>
It is important to recognize the distinction between the two uses of the term
"competition."  A market in which ten suppliers compete, but which has a
dominant supplier with 95 percent of the market, is not a competitive market,
even though the multitude of suppliers contend with one another for customers.
Likewise, a market with two or three comparable suppliers, each with equal
market shares, is generally not considered to be a competitive market.<p>
<p>
<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Increased competition "><H3><B>Increased competition in the electric industry could occur at either the
wholesale or retail level of the market, or both.</B></H3></A><p>
<p>
<b><H3>The Wholesale Level</H3></b><p>
<p>
Some competition at the wholesale level exists under the current
regulatory structure.  Utilities may purchase power from wholesale electricity
generators, who may or may not be other utilities, for distribution to retail
customers.  Competition at this level will be further enhanced by open access
to transmission facilities owned by entities who are not parties to the
transaction. As access is increased, wholesale competition will become more
intense.  Some within the industry suggest that opportunities for competition
at this level could be encouraged without unnecessarily disrupting the current
regulatory and industry structure, thereby allowing the benefits of competition
to be realized with minimal disturbance to the status quo.<p>
<p>
<b><H3>The Retail Level</H3></b><p>
<p>
For competition to occur at the retail level, customers must be allowed
the option to choose their electricity supplier, instead of having to purchase
electricity from the utility which has&nbsp;been granted the exclusive service
territory in which the customer is located.  "Retail wheeling" or "direct
access" requires a fundamental shift in the way legislators, regulators,
providers and customers view the electric industry.  Fundamental concepts of
the electric industry in Minnesota, as elsewhere, such as the provision of
universal service and the maintenance of exclusive service territories, may
have to be re-assessed in such an environment.  As a result, changes in
Minnesota's legal and regulatory regime are necessary to implement retail
competition. Proponents of retail competition argue that its benefits cannot be
fully realized unless full retail competition is available.<p>
<p>
Currently, comprehensive competition at the retail level of the market does not
exist in Minnesota or elsewhere.   However, over 35 states are exploring costs
and benefits of retail competition in the electricity market.  Two state
legislatures--New Hampshire and Michigan--have ordered pilot programs to allow
limited retail wheeling.  Michigan, however, will not begin its retail wheeling
experiment until after the year 2000.  Other states, including Connecticut,
Illinois, Maine, New Mexico and New Hampshire, have created task forces to look
into the issue.  The Rhode Island Legislature passed two bills that  would have
allowed limited retail wheeling to occur but the governor vetoed the bills.<p>
<p>
In addition, several state PUCs have opened dockets into restructuring the
electric utility industry.  The Connecticut PUC has issued a draft decision,
finding that "industry restructuring" should precede the authorization of
retail competition.  In California, the PUC&nbsp;has issued two proposals for
comment, one which would encourage competition in the wholesale market, and one
that would allow retail wheeling.  Although the California PUC has issued both
proposals for comment, the commission voted three to one in favor of the
wholesale competition proposal.  The Wisconsin PUC will announce its
preliminary decision regarding restructuring in mid-December, and has brokered
an agreement with the key parties in that state not to seek any legislative
action with regard to restructuring in the 1996 legislative session.<p>
<p>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>
<p>
<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Federal Regulatory"><H3><B>The Federal Regulatory Context for Competition</B></H3></A><p>
<p>
Since 1978, both the federal and Minnesota governments have taken steps to
encourage wholesale competition in the electric industry, both responding to
and creating forces for change in the industry.  This section summarizes
federal measures of the regulatory context for competition.<p>
<p>
<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Public Utilities"><B>Public Utilities Regulatory Precedures Act of 1978</B></A><P>
<P>
Prior to the passage of the Public Utility Regulatory Procedures Act of 1978
(PURPA), the U.S. Supreme Court held that the Federal Power Act did not
authorize the Federal Power Commission, the administrative precursor to the
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC), to order wholesale wheeling, i.e.
access to transmit one's power through the transmission facilities of another
for sale to a third party at wholesale.  <i>Otter Tail Power Co.&nbsp;v. United
States</i>, 410 U.S. 366, 375-76 (1973). <p>
<p>
In 1978, Congress passed PURPA, which, among other things, attempted to address
competition in the wholesale electricity market by adding a new section,
section 211, to the&nbsp;Federal Power Act, and by stimulating the
establishment of a certain class of non-utility generators called "qualified
facilities" (QFs).  An upsurge in the number of other non-utility generators,
known as independent power producers (IPPs), closely followed the proliferation
of QFs in the wholesale market.<p>
<p>
<b>Section 211</b><p>
<p>
Section 211 purportedly gave FERC limited authority to order wholesale
wheeling. However, the FERC later determined that this authority was too
limited to have any effect; only one order was ever issued under this
section.<p>
<p>
<b>Qualifying Facilities</b><p>
<p>
On the other hand, the establishment of QFs had a substantial effect on
wholesale competition.  To qualify for this regulatory status, a non-utility
generator had to either be a cogeneration facility, or a small power producer
using specified energy sources such as biomass, geothermal, solar or wind.<p>
<p>
Once a facility acquired QF status, PURPA provided the QF with a guaranteed
market for its power by requiring the utility in whose territory the QF was
located to purchase the power produced by the QF at no more than the utility's
"avoided cost," i.e., the incremental cost to the utility to purchase or
produce the same amount of electricity.  QFs are also exempt from FERC rate
regulation; the rates and terms of QF contracts with their host utility are
approved by the state regulatory commission.<p>
<p>
In addition to the guaranteed market for their power, QFs were also exempted
from the restrictions of the Public Utility Holding Corporation Act of 1935
(PUHCA). PUHCA requires a holding company (defined as a company that "directly
or indirectly owns, controls, or holds with a power to vote, ten percent or
more of the outstanding voting securities of a public utility) to limit its
holdings to only those entities that are<p>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>consistent with the operation of an integrated public utility system and
reasonably incidental, or economically necessary or appropriate, to the
operation of an integrated public utility system.  15 United States Code 79K.<p></BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
Additionally, entities that are subject to PUHCA must register with the
Securities and&nbsp;Exchange Commission and submit to that commission's
oversight in a number of&nbsp;areas.<p>
<p>
<b>Independent Power Producers</b><p>
<p>
In addition to QFs, other non-utility generators, IPPs (as well as
wholesale power producers affiliated with a utility--APPs or affiliated power
producers), have managed to prosper in the years following the enactment of
PURPA.  Many entities found the size and type of energy requirements for QF
status too restrictive, and decided to forego the guaranteed market of QFs to
test the wholesale market for non-QF power.<p>
<p>
In the 1970s and early 1980s, electric utilities, anticipating a growth in
demand for electricity, built large generation facilities (many of them
nuclear).  They turned out to be unneeded.  Many of these capital investments
were determined by state PUCs to&nbsp;be imprudent investments which then had
to be written off (borne by utility shareholders rather than passed through to
customers).  Large-scale write-offs endangered the solvency of many utilities
and made utility managers industry-wide leery of making such capital
investments in the future.<p>
<p>
As a result of these write-offs, electric utilities that once saw IPPs as
unwanted interlopers now saw them as an opportunity to share the risk of
increasing generationcapacity.  Instead of building expensive facilities,
subject to imprudence determinations by state regulators, the electric
utilities could purchase power from&nbsp;IPPs.  And, unlike QFs, the electric
utility could purchase this power at negotiated rates. <p>
<p>
<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Obstacles"><H3><B>Obstacles to Expansion of Competition</B></H3></A><p>
<p>
The growth in the number of QFs, IPPs and APPs, as well as the establishment of
competitive bidding for generation contracts, helped to erode the effective
monopoly the electric utilities possessed with regard to generation, and
provided additional impetus for competition throughout the industry. <p>
<p>
However, a number of obstacles remained in the way of further expanded
competition at the&nbsp;wholesale level.  One of these obstacles was PUHCA.
Although QF status garnered an exemption from the requirements of PUHCA, other
IPPs expended scarce resources to form intricate organizational structures to
avoid PUHCA's regulatory burden.  These structures are sometimes referred to as
"PUHCA pretzels," with their confusing institutional arrangements created to
avoid triggering the statute.  In addition to using up scarce resources, PUHCA
pretzels also made it more difficult for project proposals to receive
financing.  Lenders did not look with favor on the "fragmented ownership and
separation of ownership from operation control" characteristic of these
organizational structures.<a href="restruct2_fn.html#fn0">[1]</a><p>
<p>
Another obstacle to increased wholesale competition was the lack of
transmission access that IPPs faced when attempting to market their power
outside of the service area of their local utility.  As noted above, although
PURPA professed to give FERC the authority to order such access, this authority
was too restricted to be useful.<p>
<p>
<H3><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Act of 1992">Energy Policy Act of 1992</A></H3><p>
<p>
In 1992, Congress passed the Energy Policy Act (EPAct).  EPAct addressed the
two obstacles referred to above by exempting PUHCA requirements for certain
wholesale generators, and by amending section 211.<p>
<p>
<b>Exempt Wholesale Generators</b><p>
<p>
EPAct exempted another class (other than QFs) of IPPs from PUHCA.
Termed "exempt wholesale generators" (EWGs), an IPP that is engaged exclusively
in the business of owning or operating a facility used for the generation of
electric energy exclusively for sale at wholesale is exempt from the
requirements of PUHCA and the QF PURPA limitations.  15 U.S.C. 79z-5a.  Since
an EWG is not an electric utility company as defined by PUHCA, no part of that
statute applies to EWGs.  EWGs are, however, public utilities for the purposes
of the Federal Power Act, and are therefore subject to "regulation of rates and
charges for sales of electricity or leased capacity, tariff requirements, and
information reporting."<a href="restruct2_fn.html#fn0">[2]</a><p>
<p>
<b>Amended Section 211</b><p>
<p>
EPAct also amended section 211 to allow FERC substantially more
authority to order wholesale transmission access.  Section 211, as amended by
EPAct, authorizes any entity generating electric energy for sale at wholesale
to petition FERC to order a "transmitting utility" to provide wheeling
services.  A transmitting utility is defined as<p>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>any electric utility, qualifying cogeneration facility, qualifying small power
production facility, or Federal power marketing agency which owns or operates
electric transmission facilities which are used for the sale of electric energy
at wholesale.  16&nbsp;U.S.C. 796(23).<p></BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
FERC is authorized to order such services, including the siting and
construction ("enlargement") of transmission capacity necessary to provide the
services requested by the petitioner.<p>
<p>
Under EPAct, FERC is only authorized to order transmission access for those
who&nbsp;petition the commission.  EPAct does not authorize FERC to order
general transmission access.  In addition, FERC is expressly prohibited from
requiring "the transmission of electric energy directly to an ultimate
consumer," i.e., retail wheeling.  16 U.S.C.  824k(h).<p>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="FERC"><H3><B>FERC Actions That Promote Competition</B></H3></A></B>
<p>
FERC has taken a number of actions to encourage competition in the wholesale
market.  These actions include:<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI> authorizing of market-based rates<p>
<p>
<LI> issuing section 211 wheeling orders<p>
<p>
<LI> 	ordering open access transmission tariffs<p>
<p>
<LI> issuing the Open Access NOPR or "MegaNOPR"<p>
</UL>
<p>
<b>Market-Based Rates</b><p>
<p>
Market-based rates are those set by willing buyers of power.  This
method of setting rates may be used instead of the more traditional method, by
regulators pursuant to administrative proceedings with rates based on the costs
of producing the power.  Market-based rates, unlike cost-based rates, allow the
seller of power to retain the difference between the seller's cost of producing
the power and the price the buyer is willing to pay.  Market-based rates foster
the development of competitive bulk markets by allowing electricity generators
to respond quickly to market opportunities.<p>
<p>
FERC approves the use of market-based rates on a case-by-case basis.  FERC has
authorized market-based rates <b>only</b> where the commission determines<p>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>that the seller - electric utilities as well as non-utility generators - either
lacked power to influence price in the relevant market or had mitigated that
power in some fashion.<a href="restruct2_fn.html#fn0">[3]</a><p></BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
Thus, FERC's primary concern when considering each application for market-based
rates has been the power generator's ability to limit access to transmission
facilities, and thus, exert market power over that aspect of the power market.
The ownership or control of transmission facilities, according to FERC, is "the
most likely route to market power in today's electric utility industry . . ."
<i>Citizens Power &amp; Light Corporation</i>, 48 FERC [[paragraph]] 61,210 at
61,777 (1989).   Thus, initially, FERC favored authorizing market-based rates
only for IPPs.  FERC later extended the use of such rates to utilities,
provided the utility adequately mitigated any market power enjoyed by the
utility.<p>
<p>
<b>Section 211 Wheeling Orders</b><p>
<p>
As noted previously, EPAct authorized FERC to issue section 211 orders,
upon application, to&nbsp;require a transmitting utility to allow the use of
the utility's transmission facilities by a competitor.  FERC has utilized this
option as one tool to encourage competition in the bulk power market.  However,
the effectiveness of such orders to encourage competition in the wholesale
power market is reduced because section 211 orders are only applicable between
the utility and the competitor applying for access, and the process for
approving such an application takes time. <p>
<p>
Thus, FERC has found that section 211 orders alone are not adequate to
sufficiently open up the bulk power market to competition.  FERC has determined
that "open access transmission  tariffs" (see below) are preferable, in that
such tariffs have general applicability and result in more efficient and
immediate access than section 211 orders.  Therefore, FERC began to impose the
filing of such tariffs as a condition for the authorization of the use of
market-based rates, or for approval of a merger, consolidation or purchase of
public utilities, when FERC determined that open access to transmission
facilities was necessary to mitigate market&nbsp;power.<p>
<p>
<b>Open Access Transmission Tariffs</b><p>
<p>
Once open access transmission tariffs have been filed with FERC, others
may use the transmission facilities controlled by the power supplier to
transmit their power at the rates listed in the filed tariff.  This opens those
facilities to competitors and eases the transmission barrier power generators
face.<p>
<p>
In the past, open access transmission tariffs have allowed only what is known
as "point to point" service,  which involves "designated points of entry into
and exit from the transmitting utility's system, with a designated amount of
transfer capability at each point."  <i>El Paso Electric Company v.
Southwestern Public Service Company</i>, 68 FERC [[paragraph]] 61,182 at
61,926&nbsp;n.&nbsp;9&nbsp;(1994).<p>
<p>
However, in 1994, FERC held that point to point service was unduly
discriminatory and&nbsp;anticompetitive.  <i>American Electric Power Service
Corporation</i>, 67 FERC [[paragraph]] 61,317. Following that decision, FERC
now requires such open access transmission tariffs to adhere to&nbsp;what FERC
terms a "comparability standard."  This standard states that<p>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>[A]n open access tariff that is not unduly discriminatory or anticompetitive
should offer third&nbsp;parties access on the same or comparable basis, and
under the same or comparable terms and conditions, as the transmission
provider's uses of the system.  AEP, 67 FERC [[paragraph]]&nbsp;61,317 at
61,490.<p></BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
Thus, currently, when FERC sees an opportunity to mitigate market power (thus,
encourage competition), FERC now requires the utility holding market power to
file an open access transmission tariff that allows competitors comparable use
of the utility's transmission facilities as the utility itself experiences.
Often, the comparability standard requires "network service" instead of point
to point service.  Network service is more similar to the access that the
controller or the owner of the transmission facilities enjoys, thus does more
to mitigate market power and encourage competition than does point to point
service.<p>
<p>
<b>The Open Access NOPR or "MegaNOPR"</b><p>
<p>
On March 29, 1995, FERC issued a controversial Notice of Proposed
Rulemaking entitled<p>
<p>
Promoting Wholesale Competition Through Open Access Non-discriminatory
Transmission Services by Public Utilities (Docket No. RM95-8-000) and Recovery
of Stranded Costs by Public Utilities and Transmitting Utilities (Docket No.
RM94-7-001), FERC Statutes and Regulations [[paragraph]] 32,514.<p>
<p>
Called the Mega-NOPR by some, this notice of proposed rulemaking indicated
FERC's intent to require all electric utilities to file non-discriminatory open
access transmission tariffs with the&nbsp;commission.  The Mega-NOPR outlined
FERC's proposal as well as the commission's authority to undertake this
rulemaking.<p>
<p>
Essentially, FERC proposes to require all electric utilities to file
non-discriminatory open access transmission tariffs which provide for both
point to point and network services.  FERC&nbsp;argues that it has the
authority to require such open access as a result of its charge under sections
205 and 206 of the Federal Power Act "to ensure that, with respect to any
transmission in interstate commerce or any sale of electric energy for resale
in interstate commerce by a public utility, no person is subject to any undue
prejudice or disadvantage." <i>Mega-NOPR</i> at 33,053.  FERC explains that<p>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Unless all public utilities are required to provide non-discriminatory open
access transmission, the ability to achieve full wholesale power competition,
and resulting consumer benefits, will&nbsp;be jeopardized.  If utilities are
allowed to discriminate in favor of their own generation resources at the
expense of providing access to others' lower cost generation resources by not
providing open access on fair terms, the transmission grid will be a patchwork
of open access transmission systems, systems with bilaterally negotiated
arrangements, and systems with transmission ordered under section 211.  Under
such a patchwork of transmission systems, sellers will not have access to
transmission on an equal basis, and some sellers will benefit at&nbsp;the
expense of others.  The ultimate loser will be the consumer.  <i>Mega-NOPR</i>
at 33,071.<p></BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
The commission's authority to order industry-wide open access is the subject of
significant dispute and is certain to be the topic of much litigation, if FERC
decides to continue with this&nbsp;rulemaking. <p>
Additionally, public utilities will also be required to "functionally unbundle"
their power and&nbsp;services under this rulemaking.  Traditionally, the cost,
when power is purchased, includes the cost of generating, transmitting, and
distributing the power, as well as the cost of any ancillary services.  These
costs and services are functionally bundled, i.e. the purchaser pays one price
for the suite of services.  To functionally unbundle these costs and services,
the utility has to establish separate prices for generation, transmission,
distribution, and ancillary costs, so that a purchaser can shop around and pay
one entity for generating the power, another to transmit the power.
This&nbsp;is not "corporate unbundling" when utilities would have to establish
separate generation, transmission, and distribution entities, or sell off
assets associated with these functions.  FERC is expressly not requiring
corporate unbundling.  Unbundling is an important issue for state regulators
because it could remove a large amount of rate-setting authority from state
regulatory commissions and give this authority to FERC.<p>
<p>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>
<p>
<H3><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Minnesota Actions"><B>Minnesota Actions That Promote Competition</B></A></H3><p>
<p>
Regulators and the legislature in Minnesota have consistently recognized the
benefits of competition in certain aspects of the electric utility industry and
have taken several steps in&nbsp;recent years to introduce competitive aspects
into the Minnesota regulatory structure.  These include:<p>
<p>
 <!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=square>
<LI>encouraging non-utility generation<p>
<p>
<LI> 	authorizing utilities to offer competitive rates<p>
<p>
<LI> instituting competitive bidding for new generation capacity<p>
</UL>
<p>
<B> <!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Non-Utility Generation">Non-Utility Generation</A></B><p>
<p>
In 1980, the legislature passed a bill implementing several aspects of PURPA
into the state regime.  Minn. Stat. [[section]] 216B.164.  As stated in that
law, <p>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>This section shall at all times be construed in accordance with its intent to
give the maximum possible encouragement to cogeneration and small power</BLOCKQUOTE>
production consistent with protection of the ratepayers and the public.<p>
<p>
The statute details the process by which rates for interconnection and wheeling
of power are&nbsp;set by the MPUC.  In 1981, the legislature provided
additional encouragement to the construction of cogeneration facilities.  Minn.
Stat. [[section]] 216B.166.  These statutes embody early attempts by the state
to encourage, as PURPA did, certain non-utility generators to compete with the
state's utilities.<p>
<p>
<B> <!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Competitive Rates">Competitive Rates</A></B><p>
<p>
In 1990, the legislature enacted legislation allowing certain utilities in
certain cases to lower their rates for large industrial customers.  Minn. Stat.
[[section]] 216B.162.  The statute, passed in order to allow utilities to
respond to potential competition (and thus keep large customers from leaving
the utility's service grid), provides that <p>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>within its own assigned service territory, the utility, at its discretion and
using its best&nbsp;judgment at the time, may offer a competitive rate to a
customer subject to effective&nbsp;competition.<p></BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
Effective competition is defined as "a market situation in which an electric
utility serves a customer that . . .  has the ability to obtain its energy
requirements from an energy supplier" that is not rate regulated by the
commission. <p>
<p>
The commission is required to approve a competitive rate schedule when the
provision of service to a customer or a class of customers is subject to
effective competition, and the schedule applies only to customers requiring
electric service with a connected load of at least 2,000 kilowatts.   The
commission may approve a competitive rate schedule that applies to customers
requiring electric service with a connected load less than 2,000 kilowatts.
The legislature reaffirmed the effectiveness of this statute in the 1995
session, removing a provision that would have automatically repealed the
statute.<p>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Competitive Bidding">Competitive Bidding</A></B><p>
<p>
In 1993, the legislature authorized the MPUC to allow competitive bidding for
generation resources identified as needed by a utility's integrated resource
plan under Minn. Stat. <p>
[[section]] 216B.2422.  Each utility is required to develop a resource plan,
which is:<p>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>a set of resource options that a utility could use to meet the service needs of
its customers over a forecast period, including an explanation of the supply
and demand circumstances under which, and the extent to which, each resource
option would be used to meet those service needs.<p></BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
Subdivision 5 of this section allows a utility to "select resources to meet its
projected energy&nbsp;demand through a bidding process approved or established
by the commission."  The MPUC has ordered Northern States Power Company to
utilize competitive bidding for all new&nbsp;generation acquisitions.  As
discussed more fully in part three of this series, some proponents of wholesale
competition suggest that expanding the use of competitive bidding, together
with certain other measures, will enable the state to extract the full benefits
of wholesale competition.<p>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Current Activities">Current Activities</A></B><p>
<p>
Currently, both the MPUC and the Minnesota Department of Public Service (MDPS)
are looking into the issues of competition in the electric industry, including
potential models for&nbsp;restructuring the industry.  In March 1995, the MPUC
instituted an investigatory docket entitled "In the Matter of an Investigation
into Structural and Regulatory Issues in the Electric Industry."  Docket
E-999/CI-95-135.  The commission is currently receiving comments from
interested parties.  The commission states that it hopes to achieve three main
goals through this investigation:<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag --><OL>
<LI> to examine MPUC policies regarding electric utility regulation<p>
<p>
<LI>	to provide an opportunity for all stakeholders to discuss possible industry changes<p>
<p>
<LI> to inform the commission's position on these restructuring issues<p>
</OL>
<p>
On June 30, 1995, the department issued a "critical issues paper" entitled
"Competition in the&nbsp;Electric Industry: Policies to Serve the Public
Interest."  In this paper, the MDPS stated its position that "introducing
competition in the electric industry is pertinent and desirable."  The
department plans to hold workshops and meetings over the next 18 months, with
the&nbsp;goal&nbsp;of this process being "legislation that has general
consensus from most, if not all, stakeholders . . . "  The department sees this
as an informal process that will complement the&nbsp;MPUC's formal
investigation.<p>
<P><BR>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>
<P>
The third information brief of this series--<b><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct3.html">A Discussion of Issues and
Options</A></b>--provides a brief description of issues the restructuring debate
raises and discusses a number of options available to policymakers.<p>
<p>
Return to <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.mn3.org/">Sustainable Minnesota Homepage</A>
</body></html>
