<html><head><title>Chapter 3</title></head>
<body>
<p>
<H2><P ALIGN=CENTER>Chapter 3<br>
A Discussion of Issues and Options</P></H2>
<p>
Over the past few years, competition at the wholesale level of the electric
industry has been increasing throughout the country, due primarily to
technological advances and to changes in&nbsp;federal laws and regulations.
Both nationally and in Minnesota, state legislators and regulators are feeling
pressure from large industrial electricity customers and non-utility
electricity generators to restructure the electric industry to allow
competition at the retail level.<p>
<p>
This information brief series provides information for analyzing and assessing
the need for restructuring the electric industry in Minnesota.  This brief is
the third in the series.  The others are:<P>  
<b> <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct1.html">The Traditional Rationale for Regulation</A></b><p>
<b> <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct2.html">The Regulatory Context for Competition in the Electric Industry</A></b><p>
<b><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct4.html">Performance-Based Regulation</A></b>.<p>
<p>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>

<p>
<H3><B>Contents</B></H3><p>
<p>
<b>	<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Restructuring Issues">Restructuring Issues</A>	</b><p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Market Structure">Market Structures</A><P>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Stranded Costs">Stranded Costs</A><P>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Obligation to Serve">Obligation to Serve - Provider of Last Resort</A><P>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Long-Range Planning">Long-Range Planning</A><P>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Stranded Benefits">Stranded Benifits - Public Purpose Programs</A><P>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Unbundling">Unbundling - Corporate or Functional</A><P>
</UL>
<p>
<b>	<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Restructuring Options">Restructuring Options</A></b><p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Do Nothing">Do Nothing</A><P>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Guiding Principles">Guiding Principles</A><P>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Wholesale Competition">Wholesale Competition - Voluntary Power Pool</A><P>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Wholesale Competition - Mandatory">Wholesale Competition - Mandatory Power Pool</A><P>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Direct Access">Direct Access</A><P>
</UL>
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>

<p>
<B><H3><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Restructuring Issues">Restructuring Issues</A></H3></B><p>
<p>
<p>
Any consideration of whether and how to restructure or deregulate the
electric industry raises several issues.  This section discusses a few of those
issues.<p>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Market Structure">Market Structure</A></B><p>
<p>
Part two of this series explained how, in order for competitive forces to
effectively provide beneficial competition, the electricity market (or any
deregulated segment) must have a competitive market structure.  The market must
be able to support many comparable sellers competing to serve many comparable
buyers.  If a dominant seller or a dominant buyer emerges in the market and is
able to exert power over the market, the benefits of competition will be
reduced or perhaps negated.  Policymakers should ask what the expected
characteristics of a deregulated electric market will be.  For example:<p>
<p>
 <!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI>will the market have few or several suppliers?  <p>
<LI> what will their respective market shares be?  <p>
<LI> will a single buyer or class of buyers be able to dominate the market?  <p>
<LI> what regulatory or legal protections will exist to constrain the activities of market participants to allow a competitive marketplace to flourish?<p>
</UL>
<p>
If the structure of any deregulated portion of the electricity market cannot
support a competitive marketplace, then utility regulation may be able to
provide the "benefits of competition" in this market better than competition
itself.<p>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Stranded Costs">Stranded Costs</A></B><p>
<p>
Stranded costs, also known as stranded investments or transition costs, refer
to investments in assets and obligations rendered uneconomic in a competitive
market.  These costs may financially burden utilities and hamper their ability
to compete.  The utility will have to either write these investments off as a
loss or pass the costs on to former or current ratepayers in order to compete.
One such cost is investments in generation plants utilities have made in order
to serve the customers in their service territory, but which will not be needed
in a more competitive environment.  An ongoing and heated discussion concerns<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI> the magnitude of these costs <p>
<LI> who should bear these costs if the industry is restructured.<p>
</UL>
<p>
Some argue that these costs in Minnesota should be relatively small, compared
with other states, and that costs should be even smaller if the utilities have
prudently planned for a transition.  Others argue that these costs will be
greater than expected if policymakers allow full retail competition over a
short time period.<p>
<p>
Who should bear these costs?  Some stress that the regulatory compact did not
guarantee utilities a profit, only the opportunity to make a profit.  The
utility and its shareholders were, or should have been, cognizant of the risk
of their investment.  As a result, they should bear the brunt of that risk.
Others, like the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC), argue that these
investments were made in order to serve customers, with the expected
continuation of the current regulatory system.  Therefore, utilities should be
allowed to recover any prudently made investments stranded in the transition to
a restructured industry.<p>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Obligation to Serve">Obligation to Serve - Provider of Last Resort</A></B><p>
<p>
Currently, utilities are required by statute to serve all customers in their
service territory at just and reasonable rates.  In a deregulated industry,
suppliers will naturally prefer to serve consistently high volume customers in
order to maximize profits.  It is unclear who would choose to serve low volume
customers, such as residential or low-income customers, in a competitive
environment.  Electric service is as necessary to these customers as to any.
It will be important to determine whether and how to develop a structure that
will ensure service to all customer classes.<p>
<p>
Some economists are concerned that segmenting customer classes and serving them
separately could increase overall system costs.  The cost advantages for a
natural monopolist due to economies of scale, scope and coordination may be
minimized or negated.  Serving customer classes A and B together, as they have
traditionally been, may result in lower overall system costs compared to
serving A and B separately.<p>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Long-Range Planning">Long-Range Planning</A></B><p>
<p>
The present regulatory regime obligates utilities to plan for energy demand
with time horizons of 15 years or more.  In a more competitive environment,
some analysts suggest that utility planning horizons may shrink to a few years
due to increased emphasis on a quick return from capital investments.   Others
believe the problem will not be as great as some anticipate.  However,
understanding the public policy effects from a lack of long-range planning in
the electric industry will be another key issue.<p>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Stranded Benefits">Stranded Benefits - Public Purpose Programs</A></B><p>
<p>
In addition to stranded costs as a result of the transition to a restructured
industry, many expect there to be stranded benefits as well.  Stranded benefits
refer to public purpose programs that may be a burden to suppliers in a
competitive market.  Such programs include low-income discounts, demand-side
management and conservation, integrated resource and long-range planning,
economic development and research and development of new technologies.  Some
suppliers would prefer that these programs be provided and managed by a
government agency, rather than by utilities.  Policymakers will have to
determine whether and how to continue such programs in a competitive
environment.<p>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Unbundling">Unbundling - Corporate or Functional</A></B><p>
<p>
In order to protect customers from the exercise of residual market power,
policymakers may&nbsp;have to decide whether to require utilities to divest
themselves of their generation, transmission and/or distribution assets, or
whether the functional unbundling that may be required by FERC will suffice.
Unbundling is an important issue for state regulators because it may result in
state regulatory commissions losing a large amount of rate-setting authority to
FERC.<p>
<p>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>
<p><H3><B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Restructuring Options">Restructuring Options</A></B></H3>  <p>
<p>
The Minnesota Legislature has various options for restructuring the
electric industry.  This section lists some advantages and disadvantages of
five general alternatives.<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag --><OL>
<LI> <!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Do Nothing">Do Nothing</A><p>
<LI> <!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Guiding Principles">Establish Guiding Principles for the State's Energy System</A><p>
<LI> <!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Wholesale Competition">Encourage Wholesale Competition - Voluntary Power Pool</A><p>
<LI> <!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Wholesale Competition - Mandatory">Encourage Wholesale Competition - Mandatory Power Pool</A><p>
<LI> <!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Direct Access">Authorize Direct Access</A> (Retail Wheeling)<p>
</OL>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Do Nothing">Do Nothing</A></B><p>
<p>
In this case, doing nothing doesn't mean nothing gets done.  The FERC will be
finalizing and implementing its Open Access Transmission rulemaking (see
MegaNOPR discussion in Part 2).  This rulemaking is expected to have an
enormous impact on the wholesale power market.  In Minnesota, the Minnesota
Department of Public Service (MDPS) will continue its&nbsp;workshop discussions
on restructuring, and the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (MPUC) will
continue its investigation into restructuring.  Both agencies expect to present
their ideas and recommendations to the legislature.<p>
<p>
In addition, the Mid-Continent Area Power Pool (MAPP), the power pool to which
the utilities of Minnesota, some other midwestern states, and a couple of
Canadian provinces belong, will continue a process to create a Regional
Transmission Group (RTG).  RTGs are a new creature in the utility industry.
They are expected to provide regional transmission system planning, pricing and
integration for its members.  Ideally, all participants in the midwest
wholesale power market, those needing transmission capacity, as well as those
who own or control such capacity, will be members of MAPP's RTG.  This will
increase access to transmission, thus increasing wholesale competition.<p>
<p>
Given this level of activity, the legislature may find it useful to monitor the
progress of these entities and await clearer policy options.  In addition,
other states with higher electricity rates and more dissatisfied customers are
moving ahead on restructuring.  Their mistakes and successes could be
instructive.<p>
<p>
<!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=3 CELLPADDING=3 BORDER=2>
<TR><TD><B>Pros</B></TD><TD> <B>Cons</B></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>allows ongoing changes in FERC, and regional policies time to develop and be evaluated</TD><TD><LI>regulatory agencies may need guidance from the legislature </TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>allows the regulatory agencies time to plan;  maximizes their expertise and experience, while minimizing the legislature's relative lack of experience on these technical issues  </TD><TD><LI>if neighboring states move more quickly  than Minnesota and if their efforts are successful, they might draw economic activity away from Minnesota</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>over time, the experience of other states may prove some policy options                                               superior to others for Minnesota's needs</TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Guiding Principles">Guiding Principles</A></B><p>
<p>
The legislature might wish to provide a list of principles to guide the
agencies and the industry in restructuring the electric energy system in
Minnesota.  The legislature could establish policies and a framework for
restructuring, providing guidance as well as time to plan to regulators while
leaving the details of structure to the agencies.  The legislature could then
consider the agency recommendations in subsequent session(s).<p>
<p>
<p>
<!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=3 CELLPADDING=3 BORDER=2>
<TR><TD><B>Pros</B></TD><TD> <B>Cons</B></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>allows ongoing changes in FERC, and regional policies time to develop and be evaluated</TD><TD><LI>care would have to be taken to ensure that the legislative process does not create a contradictory set of principles not helpful to the agencies </TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>provides guidance to agencies, as well as an opportunity to plan</TD><TD><LI>minimizes legislative input into the details of the restructuring</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>maximizes legislative expertise and experience</TD><TD><LI>if neighboring states move more quickly than Minnesota and if their efforts are successful, they might draw economic activity away from Minnesota</TD></TR>
<TR><TD> <LI>over time, the experience of other states may prove some policy options superior to others for Minnesota's needs</TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Wholesale Competition">Wholesale Competition - Voluntary Power Pool</A></B><p>
<p>
This option would involve encouraging wholesale competition in the region,
either directly or by instructing the MPUC to initiate an investigation into
the benefits of expanding the&nbsp;use of competitive bidding, implementing
information technologies such as electronic bulletin boards, and utilizing
real-time cost and transaction information.  The use of such information and
technologies would facilitate the development of the wholesale power market by
minimizing transaction costs.  <p>
<p>
<P>
<!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=3 CELLPADDING=3 BORDER=2>
<TR><TD><B>Pros</B></TD><TD><B> Cons</B></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>may maximize benefits of wholesale competition with minimal disruption to current electricity  structure</TD><TD><LI>would have to work out jurisdictional issues carefully (FERC has exclusive jurisdiction over wholesale power transactions, by and  large) </TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>would be consistent with federal and regional initiatives, as well as current state programs such as integrated resource planning and demand-side management</TD><TD><LI>may require increased reporting requirements in the short term </TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>may provide an institutional framework for competition                                               
in the electricity industry and allow policymakers to better assess the costs                                               
and benefits of retail competition</TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Wholesale Competition - Mandatory">Wholesale Competition - Mandatory Power Pool</A></B><p>
<p>
This option, which the California PUC favors, would create an organized
statewide generation pool, as well as a kind of "stock exchange" for
electricity.  All generation facilities of the pool's members would be placed
under the control of an independent system operator (ISO) that would match bids
to provide electricity with bids to purchase.  The ISO would manage the
dispatch of generation plants, putting the least-cost plants into service first
in order to minimize overall system costs.  Purchasers of electricity would
face an averaged system cost for the period, which would reflect the efforts of
the ISO to minimize costs.  All (or most) power generators in the state would
have to be members of the pool to maximize the economic and reliability
benefits.<p>
<p>

<!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=3 CELLPADDING=3 BORDER=2>
<TR><TD><B>Pros</B></TD><TD><B>Cons</B></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>would extract some benefits of wholesale competition with minimal disruption to current structure</TD><TD><LI>would have to work out jurisdictional issues carefully (FERC has exclusive jurisdiction over wholesale power markets, by and large) </TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>may provide an institutional framework for competition in the electricity industry and allow policymakers to better assess the costs and benefits of retail competition </TD><TD><LI> may not maximize the benefits of   competition, either wholesale or retail </TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>policymakers would have the flexibility to allow some or all customers to buy from the pool, or to restrict purchases to distribution utilities</TD><TD><LI>may be inconsistent with, or  duplicative of, regional initiatives, such as MAPP's RTG development</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD><LI>may  create significant and costly litigation  regarding state jurisdiction, as well as ownership and pricing of assets</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Direct Access">Direct Access</A></B><p>
<p>
This alternative would allow at least some customers to choose their
electricity vendor, instead of requiring them to purchase power from the
utility in whose area the customer is located.  The native utility would
continue to serve those customers who do not choose to exercise this option.
Customers who choose to leave the current utility system would be allowed to
shop around for power that meets their needs in terms of price and reliability.
The option for customer choice could be phased in over time for different
classes of customers to minimize the disruption to the electricity system, or
allow for all customer classes at one time.<p>
<p>

<p>
<!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=3 CELLPADDING=3 BORDER=2>
<TR><TD><B>Pros</B></TD><TD><B>Cons</B></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>may maximize customer choice if a competitive market structure develops</TD><TD><LI>if a competitive market structure does not develop, decreased regulation could increase overall electricity costs and prices</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>increased rivalry for customers could reduce overall electricity prices</TD><TD><LI>may increase total stranded costs, relative  to other options</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><LI>could spur innovation in technology and energy services </TD><TD><LI>public purpose programs would have to be provided by other means, or discontinued</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD><LI>may  cause problems with regard to reliability, power quality, and transmission system integrity</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
The final information brief in this four-part series--<b><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct4.html">Performance-Based
Regulation</A></b>-- provides an explanation of both traditional rate of return
regulation and performance-based regulation.  It lists some advantages and
disadvantages associated with each form of regulation.<p>
<p>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>
