<html><head><title>Chapter 4</title></head>
<body><p>
<p>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Chapter 4<p>
Performance-Based Regulation<p></H3>
<p>
Over the past few years, competition at the wholesale level of the electric
industry has been increasing throughout the country, due primarily to
technological advances and to changes in&nbsp;federal laws and regulations.
Both nationally and in Minnesota, state legislators and regulators are feeling
pressure from large industrial electricity customers and non-utility
electricity generators to restructure the electric industry to allow
competition at the retail level.<p>
<p>
This information brief series provides information for analyzing and assessing
the need for restructuring the electric industry in Minnesota.  This brief is
the fourth in the series.  The others are:  <p>
 <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct1.html">The Traditional Rationale for Regulation</A><p>
 <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct2.html">The Regulatory Context for Competition in the Electric Industry</A><p>
 <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="restruct3.html">A Discussion of Issues and Options</A><p>
<p>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>

<p>
<B><H3>Contents</H3></B><p>
<p>
	<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Traditional">Traditional Cost-Based Regulation</A><p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#From Revenue">From Revenue Requirement to Rates</A><P>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Perceived Disadvantages">Preceived Disadvantages of ROR Regulation</A><p>
</UL>
<b>	<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Performance-Based Regulation">Performance-Based Regulation</A></b><p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Types of PBR Plans">Types of PBR Plans</A><P>
<LI><!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#Basic Components">Basic Components to a PBR Plan</A><P>
</UL>
<P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>

<B><H3><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Traditional">Traditional</A> Cost-Based Regulation</H3></B><p>
  <p>
  <p>
  Many participants in the restructuring debate are calling for
replacing the use of traditional cost-based regulation with "performance-based
regulation<a href="restruct4_fn.html#fn0">[1]</a>" (PBR), either as a primary
restructuring proposal or as a tool to ease the transition to a more
competitive industry.  These participants argue that although regulation is
meant to mimic the disciplining effect of competition, it does not provide the
incentives for a utility to operate at maximum efficiency the way that
competition would.  PBR refers to regulatory efforts to restructure regulation
to provide more incentives to utilities for efficient operation.  <p>
<p>
The aim of cost-based regulation, also known as cost of service regulation or
rate of return regulation (ROR), is to ensure that utilities offer their
services at prices that are based on the cost of the services, rather than on
the value that customers place on those services.  In a monopoly market, absent
regulation, the utility would price its services at whatever the market would
bear, in order to serve the utility's private interest - maximizing profits.
Allowing this practice to go unregulated would result in unreasonably high
prices for electricity.  This would price many customers out of the market, a
violation of the universal service goal that policymakers have set for this
industry, as well as increase the cost of goods and services for which
electricity is an input.  <p>
<p>
In Minnesota, as elsewhere in the U.S., the rates for electricity have
traditionally been calculated using ROR regulation.  The goal of ROR regulation
is to balance "the public need for adequate, efficient, and reasonable service"
against "the need of the public utility for revenue sufficient to enable it to
meet the cost of furnishing the service . . ."  Minn. Stat.
[[section]]&nbsp;216B.16, subd. 6.<p>
<p>
In ROR regulation, a regulatory commission, such as the MPUC, undertakes an
administrative proceeding, known as a rate case.  It has three principal
steps.<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag --><OL>
<LI> determine the revenue requirement, i.e. the cost of providing utility service<p>
<LI> allocate the requirement among customer classes<p>
<LI> translate the allocated revenue requirement into rates.<p>
</OL>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="From Revenue">From Revenue</A> Requirement to Rates</B><p>
<p>
The revenue requirement consists of the utility's expenses (based on a
test-year period) plus the cost of the capital invested and committed to
utility operations.  Minn. Stat. [[section]]&nbsp;216B.16, subd. 6.  The
utility's expenses include <p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI> operating expenses, such as wages and salaries, and maintenance costs<p>
<LI> annual depreciation on capital investments, such as generation facilities<p>
<LI> taxes, such as income and property taxes<p>
</UL>
<p>
In a rate case, these expenses are reviewed by the MPUC and may be "disallowed"
or not&nbsp;recognized as legitimate expenses for the provision of service.  If
the expenses are disallowed, they may not be passed on to customers in rates,
and must either be eliminated from the company's operations or be borne by the
utility's shareholders.<p>
<p>
The next step in estimating the revenue requirement is the determination of the
rate base.  The rate base is the capital upon which the utility is allowed to
receive a rate of return.  In calculating the rate base, the MPUC<p>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>shall give due consideration to evidence of the cost of the property when first
devoted to public use, to prudent acquisition cost to the public less
appropriate depreciation on each, to construction work in progress, to offsets
in the nature of capital provided by sources other than the investors, and to
other expenses of a capital nature.  Minn. Stat. [[section]] 216B.16,
subd.&nbsp;6.<p></BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
Thus, the rate base is a measure of the capital that a utility has committed to
the provision of its services, the vast majority of which is termed "plant in
service."  Plant in service refers to facilities "used and useful" for
rendering electricity service to the public.<p>
<p>
Upon determining the rate base, the MPUC must then calculate the allowable rate
of return on that capital, or as the concept is often stated, the opportunity
cost of the capital committed to utility service.  The opportunity cost of the
capital is measured by the opportunities lost by&nbsp;not investing those funds
in another activity.  Thus, the shareholders of a utility should receive a rate
of return that is equivalent to investments in similar risk categories.  <p>
<p>
Multiplying the allowed rate of return by the rate base results in the required
amount of return on that capital.  This amount added to the utility's expenses
is the total revenue requirement of the utility.  The revenue requirement is
then allocated among the various customer classes (e.g., residential,
commercial and industrial).  A rate is then designed for each customer class
which will allow the utility the opportunity to recover its revenue
requirement.<p>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Perceived Disadvantages">Perceived Disadvantages</A> of ROR Regulation</B><p>
<p>
Proponents of PBR argue that ROR regulation allows the utility and its
shareholders to pass on all of the utility's costs and risks to its ratepayers.
Because the utility has thus minimized the risks that it faces, the utility has
little or no incentive to increase its operating efficiency, or to minimize
expenses.  ROR regulation "fails to penalize efficient producers or reward
efficient ones."<a href="restruct4_fn.html#fn1">[2]</a>  Inefficiently
operating electric utilities cause a drag on the economy, resulting in a
decrease in social welfare and increased costs to ratepayers.  <p>
<p>
However, many people counter this argument by stating that ROR regulation
provides more incentives for efficient operation than its detractors
acknowledge.  For example, the authority of the MPUC to disallow utility
expenses provides an incentive to the utility to be efficient and prudent.  In
addition, the fact that a utility may be involved in a rate case to set its
rates only once every few years creates a "regulatory lag."  Because utility
rates are based on a past estimate of its expenses, the utility has an
incentive to minimize expenses between rate cases, thereby recouping the
difference between its estimated revenue requirements and its actual expenses.
Utilities successful at reducing costs between rate cases may even earn a
return higher than the rate of return set by the MPUC.<p>
<p>
Another perceived disadvantage of ROR regulation is that, because of the fact
that the utility knows its own expenses much better than regulators (a
condition known by economists as "information asymmetry"), the utility may be
able to inflate its estimates of its expenses, or to pad the rate base, thereby
increasing its revenue requirement.  In addition, ROR regulation is criticized
as being overly inflexible, as well as expensive, in that a rate case may
result in significant administrative costs.<p>
<p>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>

<p>
<B> <H3><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Performance-Based Regulation">Performance-Based Regulation</A></H3></B> <p>
  <p>
  Performance-Based Regulation is meant to address the above perceived
disadvantages of ROR regulation.  PBR, also known as incentive regulation,
refers to a variety of regulatory approaches that attempt to provide or enhance
incentives for utilities to achieve desired goals, such as operational
efficiency or conservation targets, by inserting a system of rewards and
penalties into the regulatory structure.  <p>
<p>
Advocates of PBR claim that it reduces or avoids the potential problems of ROR
regulation outlined above, and induces utilities to achieve efficiency gains
that leave both customers and&nbsp;shareholders better off.  Others suggest
that PBR has many potential pitfalls, such as <p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI> the selection of inappropriate performance benchmarks<p>
<LI> the temptation to incorporate too many, or contradictory, societal or regulatory goals, into the PBR plan or<p>
<LI> exacerbating the "information asymmetry" between utilities and regulators.<p>
</UL>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Types of PBR Plans">Types of PBR Plans</A></B><p>
<p>
Types of PBR include flexible regulation, targeted incentive plans, external
performance indexing, price and revenue "caps," among others.<p>
<p>
<b>Flexible Regulation</b><p>
<p>
Flexible regulation refers to regulatory attempts to increase the
flexibility of ROR regulation.  Examples of this type of regulation include<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI> allowing utilities to charge rates within an acceptable range<p>
<LI> allowing utilities to unilaterally flex rates downward<p>
<LI> authorize utilities to negotiate rates with specific customer classes, subject to regulatory approval<p>
</UL>
<p>
<b>Targeted Incentive Plans</b><p>
<p>
Targeted incentive plans seek to improve the effectiveness of ROR
regulation by providing performance incentives for specific, well-defined areas
of utility activity.  Sample activities of a targeted incentive plan might
include<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI> efficient fuel purchases<p>
<LI> increased capacity or investment in infrastructure<p>
<LI> demand-side management or conservation<p>
</UL>
<p>
<b>External Performance Indexing</b><p>
<p>
An external performance indexing plan uses an external benchmark to
measure a utility's performance.  One possible benchmark can be the performance
of other similarly situated utilities.  Examples include<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI> pricing production inputs<p>
<LI> ranking electricity rates<p>
<LI> ranking average customer bills<p>
<LI> measuring quality of service<p>
</UL>
<p>
<b>Price and Revenue Caps</b><p>
<p>
Price caps set an upper limit on the prices of a utility but do not
directly control the profits of the utility.  Revenue caps guarantee a utility
a certain income, but decouple that income from the amount of sales the utility
makes.  Revenue caps are suggested as a way to maximize conservation and
demand-side management goals.<p>
<p>
Both price and revenue caps can be used with external performance indexing to
measure a utility's performance.  Thus, both price and revenue caps can include
specific consideration of quality of service measures or environmental
factors.<p>
<p>
<B><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Basic Components">Basic Components to a PBR Plan</A></B><a href="restruct4_fn.html#fn2">[3]</a><p>
<p>
There are three basic components to a PBR plan.<p>
<p>
<!-- List Tag --><OL>
<LI> an adequate, but not inflated, baseline revenue requirement<p>
<LI> a package of incentives to encourage the utility to operate below this baseline revenue requirement<p>
<LI> a "quality control mechanism to ensure that the utility does not pursue cost savings at the expense of system reliability, safety, customer satisfaction, and other measures of quality."<a href="restruct4_fn.html#fn3">[4]</a><p>
</OL>
<p>
The PBR plan should allow for the baseline revenue requirement to be adjusted
over time for inflation.  In addition, the baseline should be offset by
advances in productivity from new technology and new techniques.  <p>
<p>
A provision to allow customers to share in the savings produced by the plan may
be built into the plan, but the ratio of the sharing between the utility and
its customers should be such that the utility's incentive to maximize these
savings is not impaired. <p>
<p>
The ability of PBR to address the perceived disadvantages of ROR regulation is
currently the subject of intense debate among utilities, regulators and
analysts.  Some argue that PBR can be used as a transition tool, to provide
incentives that will better mimic competitive forces.  Others, however, suggest
that to do PBR correctly, regulators must be provided with more, not less,
information then they currently have access to.  In addition, administrative
oversight, at least for the short term, may need to increase rather than
decrease.  Utilities under PBR would still control the information upon which
their incentives are based, and would still be motivated to maximize profits.
Given these fundamentals, a utility will have reason <p>
<p>
 <!-- List Tag --><UL TYPE=circle>
<LI>to fashion a PBR plan that incorporates too easily achieved benchmarks<p>
<LI> to provide regulators only with information that serves the interest of the
<LI>utility<p>
</UL>
<p>
Policymakers considering a plan to incorporate PBR into the regulatory
structure of the electric industry should determine whether or not the PBR
proposal adequately addresses those concerns.<p>
<p>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>
<P>
Return to <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="www.me3.org">Sustainable Minnesota Homepage</A>
<p>
</body></html>
</DOC>
