<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.5 --><title>THE MINNESOTA ENERGY CODE:PROGRESS, PROMISE AND PITFALLS</title></head><body><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>THE MINNESOTA ENERGY CODE</b><p>
<b>PROGRESS, PROMISE AND PITFALLS</b><p>
<b>__________________________</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>POLICY RECOMMENDATIONS </b><p>
<b>FOR THE SECOND HALF OF THE NINETIES</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b><!-- MailTo Tag -->
<A HREF="MAILTO:me3noble@mtn.org">MICHAEL T. NOBLE</A></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>Sustainable Resources Center</b><p>
<b></b>1916 Second Avenue South<p>
Minneapolis, MN 55403<p>
<p>
March, 1995<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<i>The SUSTAINABLE RESOURCES CENTER works to build vital communities that meet
people's needs today while renewing the environment for future generations. It
accomplishes this through both service work and policy work, focused on energy,
urban land use and community gardening, and community environmental
issues.</i><p>
<i></i><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<i>This project was made possible by a grant from the McKnight
Foundation.</i><p>
<i>Printing of this report was assisted by Minnesotans For An Energy-Efficient
Economy.</i><p>
<p>
<p>
(c) Sustainable Resources Center, 1995<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
As directed by the Minnesota legislature, the Minnesota Energy Code is very
stringent, and buildings which meet the code are very energy-efficient.<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn0">[1]</a> In 1998 the code will be more strict. There
is a growing concern that the standards and requirements of the code may be
outstripping the abilities of designers, builders and mechanical contractors to
meet them, and code officials to enforce them. This paper describes the history
and the derivation of the Minnesota Energy Code, and the building science and
energy-saving logic behind them. It will be evident to the reader that the new
codes will require the combined effort of all stakeholders to achieve
compliance and enforcement of the code. The final section offers policy
recommendations for properly implementing the changes in the energy code and
gaining the maximum benefit of the excellent codes that have been adopted.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>
<a name="RTFToC1">I.
A BRIEF HISTORY OF THE MINNESOTA ENERGY CODE
</a></b><p>
<b></b><p>
Energy codes in Minnesota have a twenty year history. Prior to 1975,
Minnesota's climate dictated that there be some attention paid to energy in new
Minnesota buildings, but there were no building code provisions governing
energy consumption. In 1975, the State legislature required that an energy code
be developed, primarily as a response to the energy crisis of 1973. In its
authorization to Commissioner of the Department of Administration, the
legislature cited a "compelling need for energy conservation."<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn1">[2]</a> The parameters for the energy code were
established, ordering the Commissioner to "adopt rules governing building
design and construction standards regarding heat loss control, illumination and
climate control."<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn2">[3]</a><p>
<p>
The legislature has frequently given guidance to Minnesota codes officials. In
some cases, the directives have been broad policy statements to assist the
overall direction of code-making. In other cases, the legislature has adopted
specific standards or requirements by statute. In the area of broad guiding
policy, the code officials must reconcile the following three directives from
the legislature:<p>
<p>

<UL>
<LI>"To the maximum extent practicable, the rules providing for the energy
portions of the building code shall be based on and conform to model codes
generally accepted throughout the U.S."<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn3">[4]</a><p>
<p>
<LI>The Minnesota Energy Code "must be designed to equal or exceed the most
energy-conserving codes adopted by any other state."<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn4">[5]</a><p>
 <p>
	<LI> "The rules shall be economically feasible in that the resultant savings in
energy procurement shall exceed the cost of the energy conserving requirements
amortized over the life of the building."<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn5">[6]</a><p></UL>


<B>The Early Years</B><p>
<u></u><p>
<u></u>Minnesota's first energy code was effective January 30, 1976, within ten
days of the inauguration of President Jimmy Carter, the last U.S. President for
whom energy conservation was a priority issue. During the early years, the code
was very simple and residential energy standards could generally be met with
six inches of attic insulation, an insulated two-by-four wall and storm
windows. <p>
<p>
<B>
<a name="RTFToC2">The
Middle Years:  Working from the Model Energy Code
</a></B><p>
<u></u><p>
In a second phase of development from 1982 to 1992, the focus was on
integrating Minnesota's needs and the Model Energy Code of the Conference of
American Building Officials (CABO). In 1982, the State legislature moved some
of the authority for the Energy Code from the Department of Administration to
the Minnesota Energy Agency, now the Minnesota Department of Public Service
(MDPS). While MDPS authors the code and provides technical support, the
Building Codes Division is accountable for enforcement, training and and the
mechanical portion of the building code. <p>
<p>
In 1983 the State adopted the Model Energy Code, 1982 edition. Two years later
the code was upgraded to be consistent with the Department of Housing and Urban
Development's (HUD) minimum property standards for residential construction.
This required that wall construction generally shift from 2x4 to 2x6 to
accommodate six-inch fiberglass batts. Attic insulation levels were doubled
from the prior period and foundation walls were insulated as well. <p>
<p>
<B>
<a name="RTFToC3">Beyond
the Model Energy Code
</a></B><p>
<u></u><p>
<u></u>The legislature in 1991 enacted statutes that set high goals for the
energy code for both commercial and residential buildings, including the
provision that the Minnesota Energy Code be as rigorous as any state's. In
commercial buildings, this required higher-efficiency building envelopes,
lighting and heating-ventilating-and-air-conditioning (HVAC) systems. The
American Society of Heating Refrigeration and Air-conditioning Engineers
(ASHRAE) had recently completed work on a rigorous standard for the energy
performance of commercial buildings, Standard 90.1-1989. This was specified in
Minnesota statute as Minnesota's new commercial energy code.<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn6">[7]</a> The federal government followed Minnesota's
lead in the Energy Policy Act of 1992 (EPAct), and required all states to move
their commercial building codes to compliance with ASHRAE  Standard
90.1-1989.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn7">[8]</a><p>
<p>
By September 1992, the Energy Code was amended for commercial buildings to meet
the statutory requirements mandating Standard 90.1-1989 as performance
minimums. In some aspects, Minnesota codes exceeded the ASHRAE standard.<p>
In commercial lighting, the Minnesota legislature went a step further,
requiring that our minimum standards be equivalent to those required in new
Federal buildings.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn8">[9]</a> To our knowledge, no
other state has adopted these very aggressive lighting standards as their
minimum commercial codes. In 1993-94, the Department of Public Service was
supported with a grant from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA) to
assist in the implementation of these rigorous requirements. <p>
<p>
Major changes in 1994 address residential airtightness and air quality issues,
and will be fully explored below. In 1994, a new rule was adopted requiring
that for January 1998, Minnesota's minimum residential energy code will be
equivalent to the best 1% of homes now constructed in Canada -- all Minnesota
new homes then will be built to the Canadian Home Builders Association's (CHBA)
R-2000 standard.<p>
<p>
<b>
<a name="RTFToC4">II.
MINNESOTA'S ENERGY CODE: HOW ENERGY-EFFICIENT IS IT?
</a></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>Minnesota's energy code lags behind the best codes in the world, but is
excellent when compared to other states. Builders in Sweden, for example, built
houses in 1984 to an energy code (ELAK1984) that is stricter than the 1998
Minnesota code. However, Minnesota code-makers have met their statutory charge
to create an energy code as stringent as that of any state, according to a 1995
report of the Alliance to Save Energy (ASE). In its <u>Report Card on State
Residential Energy Building Codes</u>, ASE rated Minnesota A+, along with five
other states.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn9">[10]</a> <p>
<p>
<i>
<a name="RTFToC5">Table
1.  	S tate Enegy Code Grades Issued by the Alliance to Save Energy  (1995)
</a></i><p>


<pre>
   A+     A         A --      B+           B         C+/C        D+/D      F                 
Californ  Georgia   Arkansas  Massachuset  Alaska    Connecticu  Arizona   Alabama,          
ia                            ts                     t                     Colorado          
Florida   Indiana   North     New York     Iowa      District    Idaho     Delaware, Hawaii  
                    Carolina                         of                                      
                                                     Columbia                                
Kentucky  Montana   North     Utah         Maryland  Michigan    Maine     Illinois, Kansas  
                    Dakota                                                                   
Minnesot  New       Tennesse  Washington   New       Nebraska    Nevada    Louisiana,        
a         Mexico    e                      Jersey                          Missisippi        
Oregon    Ohio                Wisconsin    Rhode     New         Vermont   Missouri,         
                                           Island    Hampshire             Oklahoma          
Virginia                      Wyoming      West      Pennsylvan            South Dakota,     
                                           Virginia  ia                    Texas             
                                                     South                                   
                                                     Carolina                                

</pre>
<p>
<B>
<a name="RTFToC6">Minnesota's
Energy Code Compared to Model Energy Code
</a></B><p>
<u></u><p>
<u></u>In 1992 the Energy Policy Act (EPAct) required that each State report to
the Secretary of the U.S Department of Energy (DOE), comparing its State energy
codes for residences with the Council of American Building Officials (CABO)
1993 Model Energy Code. For commercial buildings, the states must certify that
their standards do meet or exceed the Model Energy Code. On October 18, 1994,
in a letter to Christine Ervin, the Assistant Secretary for Conservation and
Renewables at DOE, DPS Commissioner Kris Sanda certified that the Minnesota
Energy Code for residences equals or exceeds the Model Energy Code. For
commercial buildings, Minnesota's standards are more stringent than either the
Model Energy Code, 1993 edition or the Standard 90.1 1989.<p>
<p>
A comparison of the Minnesota Energy Code to the Model Energy Code verifies
that Minnesota standards far exceed the model. Of 36 residential measures
identified for comparison, 25 of the requirements, or 70% were more stringent
in Minnesota. In 9 cases, or 25% of the measures, the codes were equal. In 2
cases, or 5%, the Minnesota code was less stringent. The exceptions were in
foundation wall insulation requirement for northern Minnesota, and pipe
insulation. State code officials felt that insulation of foundations to R-15 in
the northern half of the state was impractical, because it virtually
necessitates an interior application of insulation, and installation of
foundation wall insulation to the outside of foundation may be more effective.
For commercial buildings, 46% of 35 measures (16) were more stringent in
Minnesota than in the Model Energy Code and the remaining 19 were equally as
stringent.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn10">[11]</a> <p>
<B>
<a name="RTFToC7">Minnesota's
Commercial Lighting Codes
</a></B><p>
<u></u><p>
<u></u>The most far-reaching variation between the Minnesota Energy Code for
new commercial buildings and the minimum Federal requirement for all States is
in lighting.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn11">[12]</a> By State statute,
Minnesota has adopted as its code the technical lighting requirements for new
Federal buildings for 1993. These are considerably more stringent than the
lighting requirements of Standard 90.1-1989.<p>
<p>
The requirements are listed as "unit power allowances" -- essentially wattage
budgets for lighting for 125+ different commercial purposes. The power budgets
specify the maximum number of watts that can be used for lighting commercial
space for a specific function. As an example, storage and warehousing in active
use can consume 0.3 watts per square foot, unless the materials stored are fine
rather than bulky. For finer storage, 0.9 watts per square foot is allowable.
<p>
<p>
These rules were in draft form at the time the legislature required their
adoption as code. This forced Minnesota and DOE engineers and analysts to
closely examine the proposed Federal standard, and verify its suitability as a
minimum code. Of 125+ standards, a few were regarded by state lighting experts
as too aggressive. Based on current technology, certain functions in buildings
would not be provided adequate lighting quantity or quality. In particular,
there was concern about standards for classrooms and fast food restaurants.
Based on input from lighting design professionals, standards for classrooms
were corrected in the Minnesota Energy Code, and it is anticipated that DOE
soon will publish revised numbers for the other few standards that are
considered too aggressive.<p>
<p>
The code offers a prescriptive method for compliance, "intended for use with
buildings having simple lighting requirements and where the minimum amount of
calculation and effort to achieve compliance is of primary concern." <a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn12">[13]</a>A more complex performance standard allows
wattage credits for using advanced controls. Such controls include occupancy
sensors, daylight sensors, programmable timing controls or lumen maintenance
controls. For example, daylight sensing controls must be capable of dimming
light fixtures to 50% output, and they must control any light fixture for which
a power credit is taken, and that sheds half of its light in a room that
receives daylight.<p>
<p>
A simple summary of Minnesota's energy code for commercial lighting is that it
represents state-of-the-art energy performance in lighting, and is considerably
more complex than prior standards. Full compliance demands enforcement, as well
as high-level training for designers, contractors and enforcement officials.<p>
<p>
In 1993-1994, the Minnesota Department of Public Service used a Federal grant
from the Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA) to develop, demonstrate and
evaluate the implementation of lighting standards in Minnesota buildings by
providing training. The University of Minnesota provided the training, relying
on the expertise of the Department of Design, Housing and Apparel; the Regional
Daylighting Center; and the Minnesota Building Research Center. The targets of
the training were lighting designers, electrical contractors and building
officials. <p>
<p>
A November 1994 report on the training was submitted to the USEPA by the
Department of Public Service.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn13">[14]</a>  Among
its major findings, the Department concluded that compliance with the lighting
standard would reduce the lighting power requirements for new and remodeled
building by more than 20%. However, the Department also concluded that full
compliance will not occur unless the code is enforced. This finding was based
on surveys of opinions of designers and contractors, and actual practice in
1993. In the first year of the code, it was acknowledged that "there is
substantial compliance even if enforcement is weak."<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn14">[15]</a> About half of new commercial buildings
met the requirements for power budgets, and about a third met the requirements
for lighting controls. The analysis of implementation effectiveness was
conducted by the Minneapolis-based Center for Energy and Environment. A key
recommendation was that electrical inspectors be charged with enforcing the
lighting provisions of the energy code.<p>
<p>
<b>
<a name="RTFToC8">
III. JUNE 1994 AMENDMENTS TO THE MINNESOTA ENERGY CODE
</a></b><p>
<b></b><u></u><p>
<u></u>The June 16, 1994 amendments to the Minnesota Energy Code make the code
significantly more stringent. The biggest 1994 changes were residential in
nature. Other recent amendments effected significant commercial changes. <p>
 <p>
<i>
<a name="RTFToC9">Table
2.  Summary of Significant Major Improvements in 
</a></i><p>
<i>	the Minnesota Energy Code (1992-1994)</i><p>
<i></i><b>			</b><p><UL>
 Provisions assuring the effectiveness of insulation			<p>
<LI> Ventilation issues addressed for houses, explicit that "infiltration 	does
not satisfy requirement."			<p>
<LI> Category 1 and Category 2 houses (regarding airtightness and 	ventilation)
<p>
<LI> Adoption of the Canadian Mortgage House Association R2000 	Technical
Requirements by reference, for houses after 1998 	<p>
<LI>Increased reliance on window rating systems of National 	Fenestration Rating
Council (NFRC )			<p>
<LI> Return-air duct sealing required to reduce negative pressures		<p>
<LI> Residential vaulted ceilings require R-5 sheathing and R-38 	between rafters
<p>
<LI> Multifamily residential, 3 stories and less:  major upgrade of wall and
ceiling insulation performance						<p>
<LI>Commercial buildings:  envelope provisions of ASHRAE 90.1 1989 	reduced to a
simplified table						<p>
<LI> Very aggressive standards for new commercial lighting efficiency, 	including
state-of-the-art controls (as of 1992)									<p>
<LI>Very efficient permanently-wired motors 1 horsepower+ 								<p>
<p></UL>
To prepare builders for the increasingly-efficient codes of 1998, the current
code allows for two classes of residences to be built -- Category 1 and
Category 2. Both are code-compliant, but Category 1 is more airtight, and
requires mechanical ventilation to be used. It anticipates the expected
minimums for 1998. The following sections will address the technical aspects of
the residential codes and these two levels of performance. The discussion will
focus on four critical performance issues: insulation performance,
airtightness, mechanical ventilation and combustion safety.<p>
<u></u><p>
<B>
<a name="RTFToC10">Effectiveness
of Thermal Insulation
</a></B><p>
<u></u><b></b><p>
<b></b>The Minnesota Energy Code seeks to assure that insulation will perform
in buildings as it is designed. In doing this, Minnesota has made a significant
contribution to the body of codes and standards over the past few years.
Minnesota DPS Senior Engineer Bruce Nelson became increasingly aware that the
performance of insulation materials in laboratory tests was not necessarily
equivalent to their performance in buildings. Minnesota code requires that "all
thermal insulation must achieve stated performance at 75deg.F...and no
less...at winter design conditions." <a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn15">[16]</a>
In addition, "building assemblies are required to maintain the thermal
performance of required insulation and the integrity of building materials
against cold weather water vapor condensation and intrusion of unconditioned
air."<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn16">[17]</a><p>
<p>
The most frequently-sited and controversial example is wind-washing. For
example, if a brisk wind moves through ventilation openings in the roof
overhang, and blows directly through insulation, a deterioration of performance
will result. To combat this, code requires a wind-wash barrier at three
locations: at the attic edge, at overhangs such as bay windows or cantilevered
floors, and at the exterior joints in the building envelope which may allow
wind to blow into a wall cavity. <p>
<p>
Secondly, the performance of some types of insulation is reduced at lower
temperatures, compared to laboratory measurements --namely fiberglass and
mineral fiber loose-fill insulation. Minnesota's performance requirements
effectively eliminates low density insulations in the field, or requires that
it be installed at extra thickness.<p>
<p>
Thirdly, fire stops are required in walls to block air movement:  this prevents
heat-robbing "convective loops" of air flow within the wall cavity. As cold air
falls on the outer surface and warm air rises on the inner surface behind the
wall finish, heat is transferred around the insulation and lost to the
outdoors. <p>
<p>
In addition, air leakage barriers prohibit moisture-laden air from entering the
insulated portions of the building envelope and deteriorating the performance
of the insulation. <p>
<B>
<a name="RTFToC11">Verification
of Insulation Levels
</a></B><p>
<u></u><p>
In addition to requirements that insulation must perform <u>in situ</u> as it
does in the laboratory, the code includes a consumer protection feature which
requires installers to verify insulation levels and quantities with physical
proof. This is generally well-supported by insulation contractors according to
the DPS, since it keeps competition honest. To do this, they must either:  1)
install "insulation thickness markers" at ten foot spacing around attic or 2)
affix a unique portion of each bag to an "attic card." For all residential
buildings, the attic card must be affixed to framing near the attic hatch and
must include the following information:<p>
<i></i><p>
<i>	
<a name="RTFToC12">Graphic
1. Sample Attic Card
</a></i><p>
<i></i><p>
<p>
      Type Of Insulation_______________ Installer's Company_________________<p>
<p>
      Insulation Manufacturer___________ R-Value Of
Insulation________________<p>
<p>
      Design Settled Thickness__________ Square Footage
Insulated_____________<p>
<p>
      Number Of Bags Installed_________<p>
<p>
      Installer Signature And Date_________________________________________ <p>
<p>
<p>
<B>
<a name="RTFToC13">Minnesota's
Airtightness Standards for Residences
</a></B><p>
<u></u><p>
In fifteen years of research into the energy performance of new homes, a focal
issue has always been control over the air leakage of buildings. The challenge
has been to reduce uncontrolled air infiltration and exfiltration as far as
technically feasible, within reason. Because air leakage is driven by wind and
the indoor/outdoor temperature differential, leakage for fresh air cannot be
reliably planned into a house design. <p>
<p>
Neither random nor planned leaks can be trusted to always meet the requirements
of the house and its occupants for fresh air. If leakage is sufficient to
provide adequate ventilation on mild windless days, excessive energy loss and
excessive ventilation will occur during much of the winter. Conversely, a house
with air leakage that provides suitable ventilation on a severe winter day will
have dangerously low levels of ventilation on a calm fall or spring day, unless
the windows are open. Pollutants may build up and result in occupant health
problems. Buildings can suffer rapid deterioration due to excessive humidity
and moisture. <p>
<p>
These analyses are well-documented by building science researchers in many
technical studies and publications, including many by Minnesota's leading
building scientist, Dr. David Grimsrud of the Minnesota Building Research
Center. The large body of work on the subject will not be reviewed here.<p>
	
<B><a name="RTFToC14">A.
Prescriptive Method of Airtightness</B>
</a><p>
<p>
The Minnesota Energy Code has aggressively restricted the allowable air
infiltration into residential buildings.<p>
<p>
The builder following the 1994 code amendments has three options to comply with
the code requirements for airtightness. Many builders strongly prefer
prescriptive standards to performance standards, so they can follow a check-off
list for airtightness. Within that check-off list, the builder can do those
minimum features required of all homes, i.e., Category 2. The minimum
airtightness requirement is that "a barrier against air leakage must be
installed to prevent the leakage of moisture-laden air from the conditioned
space into the building envelope."<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn17">[18]</a> This
is often the same polyethylene sheeting used as a vapor retarder. In addition,
items (b), (d) and (g) from the following Table of Requirements must be
present.<p>
<p>
<i>
<a name="RTFToC15">Table
3 .Table of Prescriptive Requirements
</a></i><p>
<i></i>

<pre>
     Requirement                                          Category 1   Category 2    
                                                            house      house         
a. Vapor retarder                                            yes       yes           
b. Continuous air barrier: plumbing and heating              yes       yes           
penetrations                                                                         
c. Fire stops installed to block air movement                yes       yes           
d. Electrical and telecommunications penetrations,           yes       yes           
including       recessed lights (except electric boxes                               
and fan housings)                                                                    
e. Wind-wash barriers at exterior edge of attic              yes       yes           
insulation                                                                           
f. Wind-wash barriers at cantilever floors and bay           yes       yes           
windows                                                                              
g. Window and door frames and utility penetrations           yes       yes           
must     be sealed                                                                   
h. Electric boxes and fan housings must be sealed to         yes       no            
prevent      air leakage                                                             
i. Rim joists sealed to prevent air leakage                  yes       no            
j. The top of interior partition walls must be sealed        yes       no            
to      prevent air leakage                                                          
k. All exterior joints that may be sources of air            yes       no            
intrusion      must be sealed                                                        
l. Between wall assemblies, rim joists and foundations       yes       no            
must     be sealed to prevent air leakage                                            

</pre>
<p>
In its Statement of Need and Reasonableness, the Department supported its
decision to established a two-tier residential code. The driving rationale was
the acknowledgment that many builders would inevitably continue to rely on air
leakage and operable windows to provide fresh air. "The Department proposes
that residential buildings, where infiltration and natural ventilation are
relied on to provide necessary year-round ventilation <u>must be constructed in
accordance with only certain provisions</u> of this subpart. Construction of
all other buildings must be in accordance with all items of the subpart"
<i>(emphasis added)</i>.<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn18">[19]</a>The code itself is explicit:  if any
measure "(h),(i),(j),(k),(l) is also installed in a residential building, then
a residential mechanical ventilation system must be installed."<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn18">[20]</a><p>
<p>
To build to a higher standard, the builder may do any of the items h-l from the
Table of  Requirements. If the home is to be a Category 1 home, all the items
on the Table of Requirements must be completed. The items required in order for
the building to qualify as a Category 1 building include air sealing strategies
at the following locations:  (h) electrical boxes and fan housings, (i) rim
joists which form exterior perimeter of floor assemblies (j) the top plates of
interior partition walls (l) the joints between rim joists and exterior walls
as well as the joints between rim joists and foundations. The balance of the
Table of Requirements is for protection of building components against
migration of water vapor [requirement (a)] and for the assurance of the
effectiveness of thermal insulation as described above. <p>
<p>
	
<B><a name="RTFToC16">B.
Performance Alternative for Air Leakage Requirements
</a></B><p>
<p>
Although many builders strongly prefer a prescriptive approach to code
compliance, the code allows for achieving high levels of airtightness through
any alternative means. If this option is selected, the builder must be able to
demonstrate with a blower door that when the house is depressurized to 50
Pascals, the air leakage of the building is no more than 0.24 cubic feet per
minute per square foot of conditioned space. Conditioned space typically
includes the basement, since it is maintained at an indoor temperature. For
example, a two story, 1800 square foot home with a full basement (2700 sq. ft.
conditioned) would be allowed 648 cubic feet of air leakage per minute, while
depressurized with a blower door. For the average weather condition, this is
roughly equivalent to 35 cubic feet per minute for normal house operation. This
is very tight construction. Comparable attention must be given to airtightness
details to meet the performance criterion as to meet the prescriptive
requirements.<p>
<p>
<i>
<a name="RTFToC17">Table
4. Summary of Airtightness and Ventilation Options for 			Residences (1994 Code
Amendments)
</a></i><p>
<i></i>

<pre>
Category      Airtightness requirements            Ventilation requirements          
Category 1    Table of Requirements (a) through    Mechanical Ventilation System     
              (l)                                                                    
Category 1    Performance alternative for air      Mechanical Ventilation System     
              leakage requirements: 0.24 cfm/ft2                                     
              at 50 Pa.                                                              
Category 2    Table of Requirements, excluding     Opening windows to provide        
              (h) through (l)                      necessary ventilation year-round  

</pre>
<B><a name="RTFToC18">Residential
Mechanical Ventilation
</a></B><p>
<u></u><p>
The efficiency of most appliances for residences cannot be established by State
code. When national appliance standards advanced during the mid-1980's,
manufacturers and efficiency advocates agreed on a higher national standard in
exchange for the prohibition of individual State standards. The preemption does
not cover all components of residential construction, but does apply to
furnaces, water heaters, refrigerators and many other major appliances. Most of
these are not included in the building energy code anyway.<p>
<p>
The mechanical issues which arise in the 1994 code amendments relate to health
and safety issues which result from progress in construction quality. These
issues will come to full fruition in the 1998 code. For example, the decision
to establish two categories of code compliance in the 1994 amendments was
primarily driven by the builders and the building scientists in Minnesota
agreeing that increased airtightness without attention to mechanical
ventilation was a prescription for increasing problems with air quality,
excessive humidity and building deterioration due to moisture. <p>
<p>
In a memorandum that significantly consolidated the views of stakeholders,
building scientist Gary Nelson of the Energy Conservatory wrote to the
Department of Public Service September 12, 1992:<p>
<p>
My main motivation for writing this memo is to strongly encourage you to
postpone the effective date of the requirements to seal ceilings and rim
joists. I am convinced that adopting these rules without dramatically improving
the quality of residential ventilation systems will substantially reduce the
quality of air in new Minnesota houses....It now seems quite obvious that in a
large percentage of today's new homes, natural ventilation does not provide
enough outside air to satisfy on an annual average, the minimum requirements of
our ventilation code.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn19">[21]</a><p>
<p>
The views of building scientists were joined by the Builders Association of
Minnesota (BAM). In a January 8, 1993 letter to the Department, BAM offered its
strategic plan for addressing these issues. BAM acknowledged that natural
infiltration does not meet the then-existing code requirements for ventilation.
BAM also called for delaying code requirements for air-sealing of rim joists
and the intersection of partition wall with ceilings. To its 3,000 members, BAM
urged voluntary use of sealed-combustion or induced-draft furnaces,
water-heaters and appliances by 1993, and urged members to begin installing
residential mechanical ventilation systems as well. Lastly, BAM urged the State
agencies to "actively take steps to adopt Combustion Standards and Ventilation
Standards."<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn20">[22]</a> The Association followed up
at the 1993 legislature helping to enact legislation requiring the two affected
departments to cooperate in these matters. In the ensuing months, the
Department incorporated into its proposed code amendments the views of the
builders and the building scientists on airtightness. The Department created a
Category 2 for homes that would not be as airtight as originally proposed, and
would be required to operate windows in the winter for adequate fresh air. This
became the official acknowledgment of what the builders and the scientists had
long been arguing:  many new houses were already in trouble with indoor air
quality. <p>
<p>
It is unlikely that the Category 2 house will be free from these problems, but
it was felt by code officials, builders, and building scientists that the
mechanical ventilation market was not mature enough to mandate that all houses
are mechanically provided fresh air. According to the new code, category 2
houses are buildings "where infiltration and passive ventilation are relied on
to provide necessary year-round ventilation." It is explicit that all houses
must comply with national ventilation requirements for all buildings (ASHRAE
Standard 62-1989). The natural leakiness of buildings cannot be relied upon to
achieve this. From the Minnesota Energy Code:<p>
						<u>				</u><p>
7670.0450 VENTILATION<p>
						<u>				</u><p>
Ventilation systems must be designed to conform with ASHRAE Standard 62-1989.
EXCEPTION: Infiltration does not satisfy the requirement for ventilation in
residential construction.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn21">[23]</a>	<p>
<p>
Therefore, in any category 1 home or any home which includes any of the
Requirements (h) through (l), a residential mechanical ventilation system must
be installed. It must be "capable of introducing and distributing outdoor air
to all habitable rooms and removes indoor air at a rate not less than .35 air
changes per hour, or 15 cubic feet per minute per bedroom plus an additional 15
cubic feet per minute, whichever is greater."<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn22">[24]</a> A very small percentage of new homes
currently comply with this provision, and for the near future, the great
majority of homes will be code-approved only with the representation by
builders that windows are being manually operated in the winter. It has been
suggested only half-jokingly that for buyers of new homes to be aware of this,
windows should be so labeled.<p>
<p>
The Builders Association has responded to this dilemma proactively. It has
convened a Residential Ventilation Standards Task Force to develop an Interim
Standard for Residential Construction. This Task Force is composed of many of
the State's most knowledgeable and capable experts from industry, government
and academia. A draft Voluntary Residential Mechanical Ventilation Standard has
been issued by the Task Force which is "intended to provide guidance and
specifications for the design and installation of residential mechanical
ventilation systems."<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn23">[25]</a> Once adopted and
used on a voluntary basis for 1995, 1996 and 1997, this standard will provide a
basis for proper design and installation of mechanical ventilation in all new
houses as it becomes mandatory after January 1, 1998. <p>
<p>
<B>
<a name="RTFToC19">Combustion
Safety: Furnace And Water heater Backdrafting
</a></B><p>
<u></u><p>
<u></u>In his September 12, 1992 memo to the Department, Gary Nelson expressed
the other major health and safety concerns of the builders:<p>
<p>
In addition, the new airtightness standards combined with current Minnesota
building practice with regards to combustion air, will greatly increase the
prevalence of pressure-induced spillage of combustion products including carbon
monoxide, into new houses.<p>
<p>
The concerns about combustion safety raised in the Nelson letter have are not
adequately address by current practice. A far-reaching solution to the problem
is contained in the 1998 version of the code, when no combustion appliances
capable of backdrafting will be allowed. These "sealed-combustion" or
"induced-draft" features are increasingly available and price competitive on
furnaces. The incremental cost is partially offset by a significant utility
rebate offered by some of Minnesota's gas utilities. In Wisconsin, the furnace
market has been substantially transformed, so that guaranteed-safe,
high-performance furnaces are the norm. This transformation is credited to
contractor marketing and utility rebates.<p>
<p>
One provision in the 1994 amendments that is designed to help reduce the
backdrafting problem is a clarification of a requirement for duct-sealing in
the Uniform Mechanical Code.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn24">[26]</a>  "Return
air ducts conducting air into a furnace through the same space as the furnace
must be continuously airtight."<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn25">[27]</a> If
followed by practitioners, this provision would prevent negative pressures near
the furnace caused by the furnace blower itself from backdrafting the
combustion gases into the home.<p>
<p>
Local research is underway to follow up on the significant technical and
scientific issues surrounding safety of furnaces and water heater combustion.
The Minnesota Building Research Center (MnBRC), with funding from the Gas
Research Institute is evaluating the problem.<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn26">[28]</a> Much anecdotal and observational data
already exist in Minnesota about combustion spillage. Energy auditors and
trouble-shooters for builders frequently identify homes where the furnace
cannot vent its gases up the chimney while the fan of the kitchen range hood is
operating. In the first phase, the project will develop a protocol for
assessment of the problem. In phase 2 in 1995, the protocol may be applied to a
significant group of Minnesota homes. The MnBRC project involves several local
entities with technical and field expertise, including Sustainable Resources
Center, who will supply field personnel to the work group to test the protocol,
and apply it to a larger group of homes if phase 2 proceeds.<p>
<B>
<a name="RTFToC20">Energy
Code Change Effective 1998: Canada's R-2000 Program 
</a></B><p>
<u></u><p>
For its impact on residential construction in Minnesota, the most significant
change in the June 1994 amendments are the last two sentences.<p>
							<u>				</u><p>
7670.1115 Effective Dates<u></u><p>
<u></u>						<u>				</u><p>
The effective date of amendments to this chapter is June 16, 1994.<p>
<p>
EXCEPTION:  Effective January 1, 1998, residential buildings (one and two
family and other residential buildings three stories or less in height) must
meet the requirements of the R-2000 Home Program Technical Requirements
Canadian Home Builders' Association, September 1992."<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn27">[29]</a><p>
<p>
In its statement of need and reasonableness for the June 1994 code, the
Department supported the need and reasonableness of this code provision.<p>
<p>
The proposed effective date for adoption of the Canadian Home Builders
Association R-2000 standard is needed because Minn. Statutes [[section]]
16B.165 requires the Department to adopt amendments to the State energy code
that are designed to equal or exceed the most energy-conserving codes adopted
by any other state. The standards of the R-2000 program do equal or exceed the
most stringent energy conserving codes adopted by any other state. The adoption
of the R-2000 standard is reasonable because thousands of homes in Canada and
many homes in the United States have been constructed to these standards.<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn28">[30]</a><p>
<p>
	
<B><a name="RTFToC21">A.
R-2000 History</B>
</a><p>
<p>
The R-2000 program was initiated as a pilot project in 1982. The main program
started in the spring of 1986 under the joint administration of Energy Mines
and Resources Canada and the Canadian Home Builders Association. This is a
critical aspect of the program -- it has the stamp of approval and is a
creature of the Canadian builders themselves. It now receives administrative
and technical support from the Canadian government through Natural Resources
Canada.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn29">[31]</a> Researcher Rob Dumont of the
Building Sciences Division of the Saskatchewan Research Council has followed
R-2000 from its beginning as a pilot in the early eighties. Dumont highlighted
some of the issues Minnesota will face when this Canadian demonstration program
becomes Minnesota's basic construction method in 1998.<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn30">[32]</a><p>
<p>
The R-2000 program was developed following Saskatchewan Research Council's
widely-publicized new construction project in 1980, where building scientists
constructed a very-low-energy home in Saskatoon's 11,000 degree-day climate. <p>
The remarkable home spawned interest among selected builders throughout Canada
wishing to bring low-energy homes to market and the R-2000 program was born. <p>
<p>
Starting with incentives of $7,500 to first-time R-2000 builders, and a small
number of demonstration homes, the program was well-received by Canadian
builders and consumers.  Over time, builder incentives were reduced to $500,
and then discontinued. The program is a voluntary one, not a code or a
requirement. Builders use it as a value-added option for home-buyers, giving
the home-buyers confidence that an energy-efficient upgraded home will meet a
uniformly high standard.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn31">[33]</a> Thousands of
homes have been certified by the Canadian Home Builders Association as R-2000.
<p>
<p>
In some provinces, such as New Brunswick where inexpensive natural gas is
unavailable, fully twenty percent of the new homes built receive the R-2000
certification, proving that the methods can be transferred to a large market
and a large pool of builders. Across Canada, approximately 1% of the new homes
are R-2000, so market penetration is still modest. <p>
<p>
	
<B><a name="RTFToC22">B.
R-2000 Costs and Benefits
</a><p></B>
<p>
It is required by Minnesota law that the code "shall be economically feasible
in that the resultant savings in energy procurement shall exceed the cost of
the energy conserving requirements amortized over the life of the building."<p>
<p>
A 1989 study by the Canadian government which monitored the energy performance
of selected R-2000 homes found that energy for space heating averaged 62% of
the energy use of homes built to the minimum requirements of the Canadian
building code. On average the homes used 4% less space heating energy than the
program target. For total energy use, the R-2000 home used 77% of a home built
to the existing energy code of Canada.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn32">[34]</a>
A few Canadian banks have formally recognized that lower operating costs leave
owners with more money to pay their mortgage loan. This reduced risk of default
led the Bank of Montreal to cut the interest rate on R-2000 homes by a quarter
point.<p>
<p>
The average incremental cost of an R-2000 home is approximately 2%-2.5%,
according to a 1989 study.  This was cost-effective, unless one assumes very
low natural gas costs (e.g., $2.00 MCF). The program was found to be most
cost-effective in Manitoba with gas prices comparable to Minnesota, but much
less cost-effective in Alberta where natural gas prices were 50% lower.<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn33">[35]</a> <p>
<p>
Lower energy costs can offset the amortized incremental cost, resulting in a
positive cash flow immediately. Some builders are particularly adept at meeting
the higher levels of performance with less investment. For example, Bigelow
Homes of Chicago is not an R-2000 builder, but builds homes comparable to the
R-2000 home. Bigelow's homes are so efficient that they need no furnace. Most
are heated with a high-efficiency water heater that serves a dual purpose.
Heating bills are guaranteed for three years as a marketing strategy, and are
often less than half of comparable new homes in the area. The cost of conserved
energy in a Bigelow Home is 10-20cents/therm compared to the cost of gas which
averaged 40cents/therm during the study period, according to Lawrence Berkeley
Laboratory.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn34">[36]</a> Some R-2000 builders report
that the very stringent airtightness standards have become inexpensive and
routine to meet, with the maturing of technical know-how and methods. Brian
Usher of Branta Homes in Vernon, British Columbia reports to Rob Dumont that
his incremental cost for achieving R-2000 airtightness is now under $100. A
Winnipeg consulting firm UNIES, Inc. has compiled what it thinks are the best
methods for achieving airtightness of various interstices of houses, and has
published drawings under the name Easy Air Tightness.<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn35">[37]</a> <p>
<p>
	
<B><a name="RTFToC23">C.
R-2000 Technical Requirements
</a><p></B>
<p>
It should be understood that the R-2000 airtightness standard is very
stringent. At 50 Pascals pressure difference using a blower door, the volume of
house air can exchange only 1.5 times per hour. Such homes are atypical in
Minnesota in 1994. For category 1 houses in the 1994 code, one option for
meeting the airtightness provision is to be able to demonstrate airtightness
levels of 0.24 cfm per square foot (about 1.8 air changes). So for all
Minnesota new houses beginning in 1998, construction will be about 15% tighter
than the value adopted for Category 1 homes in the current Minnesota code. To
be certified as R-2000 in Canada today, airtightness must be measured with a
blower door by a R-2000 certified individual. <p>
<p>
By far, the biggest cost increment for the R-2000 home is the mandatory
residential ventilation system. All homes must have a mechanical ventilation
system installed by an R-2000 certified installer, and all homes must have the
actual delivered fresh air flows to the living space measured and certified. To
achieve the energy consumption targets, almost all ventilation systems use heat
exchangers to recover energy from heated or cooled house air before the air is
exhausted. Because mechanical ventilation is required, R-2000 homes experience
very few problems with air quality and moisture.<p>
<p>
Neither do R-2000 homes face the health and safety risks of combustion
appliances failing to properly draft:  all furnaces and water heaters are
induced-draft or sealed-combustion appliances which are incapable of spilling
combustion gases into homes. Neither are open-hearth fireplaces allowed, but
only fireplaces which are atmospherically isolated from the living space. A
window to look in at the fire is fine, but the air to burn the fire must come
directly from outdoors, not the house. <p>
<p>
According to Dumont, the electrical energy demanded by the mechanical
ventilation system poses a significant opportunity for further technical
improvement. Due to the design of fans and heat exchangers, the power needed to
move the air is often about 125 watts -- comparable to having 10 standard
compact fluorescent light (CFL) bulbs on all the time. Considerable research
and development could improve the forward curved stamped-steel rotors often
used in fans, and could optimize core design, air flows and electricity
consumption. Much of the performance efficiency of ventilation systems is
related to the installation of ductwork in houses. To improve the performance
of installed ventilation systems, the Canadian Heating Refrigeration and
Air-conditioning Institute (HRAI) has offered certification courses for
installers of residential ventilation systems for several years. A certified
installer must be utilized to install the mechanical ventilation equipment in
R-2000 homes. <p>
<p>
Training heating contractors now to install ventilation systems is essential if
the market is to be ready to supply the expected 1998 demand. In 1990, the
certification course for energy-recovery ventilation systems was locally
offered. A mailing of 11,000 pieces to all heating and ventilating contractors
in a multi-state area surrounding Minnesota brought two responses. Presumably,
the view of contractors was that there was not a sufficient market to warrant
having the skill or the certification.<p>
<p>
Outside of some larger municipalities, heating and ventilating installers do
not require licensing in Minnesota. Statewide heating contractor licensing
following the model of statewide builder licensing may be desirable. Including
ventilation system skills in the knowledge necessary for a license may be one
way to significantly build Minnesota's capacity to correctly install
residential ventilation systems.<p>
<p>
Another key feature of the R-2000 home program is the computer simulation of
energy performance for the homes. The government supports and regularly updates
low-cost energy-use software HOT2000 for the PC and the Macintosh. The builder
applying for R-2000 certification must present a computerized energy use
analysis of the space heating and water heating of the proposed home and meet a
strict performance standard. This standard varies by climate, but for example,
in Saskatchewan's climate of 11,000 degree days Fahrenheit (colder than
International Falls), the design must use no more than 60 kWh/square meter of
floor area. With high performance windows and high efficiency heating
equipment, this could be achieved with the standard 2x6 wall construction which
is currently typical in houses complying with the Minnesota Energy Code. It is
more frequent for Canadian R-2000 builders to use an extra inch of thermal
insulation sheathing to reduce the heat loss through the wood framing
members.<p>
<p>
The R-2000 technical requirements pose new questions for Minnesota code
officials:<p><UL>
<LI> Airtighness must be verified by a certified blower door tester. Who will
test?<p>
<LI> How will these testers be certified, and who will be the certifying
authority?<p>
<LI> Ventilation systems must be installed by certified installers, but who will
certify?<p>
<LI> Who will run the HOT2000 computer simulations of energy use for each house?<p>
<LI> Will the State supply the needed technical support for the software? <p></UL>
<i>
<a name="RTFToC24">Table
5.	R-2000 Technical Requirements Summary 
</a></i><p>
<i></i><p><UL>
<i></i><LI>Annual energy budget modeled by Hot2000 software meet strict
climate-sensitive performance standard.	 <p>
<LI>Insulation levels about the same as current MN Energy Code.<p>
<LI> Blower door demonstration of airtightness below 1.5 Air 	Changes per Hour at
50 Pascals (comparable to 0.24 cf/ft<sup>2</sup>).<p>
<LI> No furnaces, water heater or fireplaces capable of spilling 	combustion gases
into home (typically high-efficiency).<p>
<LI> Certification of installers of ventilation systems.<p>
<LI> Ventilation system airflows certified. <p></UL>
<b></b><p>
<b>
<a name="RTFToC25">IV.
POLICY ISSUES RAISED BY THE MINNESOTA ENERGY CODE
</a></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b><B>Enforcement of the Minnesota Energy Code </B><p>
<u></u><p>
The DPS concedes in its current Quadrennial Report on Energy, <i>Transition to
the Twenty-First Century </i>that the energy code is not being adequately
enforced. "The full energy-saving benefit of the code changes are not being
realized because in many cases they are not being implemented."<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn36">[38]</a>Deficiencies exist related to geographic
availability of enforcement, state-level technical support, local staffing and
resources for enforcement, training for enforcement officials, training for
builders as well as architects, designers and specialty contractors.<p>
<p>
	
<B><a name="RTFToC26">A.
Geographic Availability of Enforcement</B>
</a><p>
<p>
Seventeen Minnesota counties have so far adopted the code, including Steele and
Winona counties in 1994. In the other 70 counties, most towns over a population
of 2500 do some code enforcement, although it is not uniform. Still, many local
municipalities have no capacity whatsoever for plan review, building
inspections or code enforcement. Non metropolitan counties have the authority
to decide by referendum that the building code is not applicable within their
jurisdiction.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn37">[39]</a> In the future, failure to
adopt the building code may cause property insurance rates to rise
dramatically. The secondary insurance markets are evaluating their risks in
every U.S. community, in the wake of building code problems that came to light
in the wake of Hurricane Andrew. Universal enforcement of the building code is
a difficult political issue that has not been addressed by the legislature in
many years. Builders who work to comply with the code are frequently strong
advocates for geographically-uniform enforcement, for competitiveness reasons.
More than 80% of new construction occurs in areas where the code is adopted. <p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation: The Minnesota legislature should assure that the energy code
is enforced throughout Minnesota.</b><p>
<b>	</b><p>
<b></b>	
<B><a name="RTFToC27">B.
State Support for the Minnesota Energy Code</B>
</a><p>
<p>
For all its accomplishments on energy codes, the Department of Public Service
has only one person (at .5 FTE) whose job is to research, upgrade and
administer the promulgation of codes amendments for both residential and
commercial buildings, and to provide education to builders, architects and
building officials. The Energy Information Center of DPS is available to answer
incoming questions about the code. The Building Codes and Standards Division
has no staff dedicated to energy.<p>
<p>
By contrast, in Washington State, where there is a very strong program to
support the implementation of energy codes, there are eight State-level
technical staff working solely on residential energy codes and four staff
working on commercial codes. Granted, this support has been well-funded by the
Federal Bonneville Power Administration (BPA), and may be gearing down due to
shifting priorities.  In partnership with BPA, Washington has been paying local
code jurisdictions to offer energy education to codes officials and builders.
In addition, software is being provided to local officials to run energy
consumption analyses with builders to assess the energy performance of
different combinations of measures.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation: Minnesota must provide significant additional statewide
technical support, either through contracts or staffing, to assure the proper
dissemination and implementation of the Minnesota Energy Code. This will
require additional financial resources.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
	
<B><a name="RTFToC28">C.
Local Resources for Code Enforcement
</a><p></B>
<p>
As the code increases in complexity, existing code enforcement will require
additional staffing in some capacities. For example, in the area of commercial
lighting, the Department made this finding in its November 1994 report to the
EPA. <p>
<p>
The resources needed for enforcement do not currently exist within code
enforcement departments. To perform a plan review and site visits to enforce
the lighting standard for a 50,000 square foot building would require a
knowledgeable inspector about 15 hours. Enforcement authorities do not have
excess staff time for this activity. Authorities will need to add a surcharge,
or rely on other sources of additional funds to pay for new staff or contract
enforcement. One city has recommended a permit fee of one percent of the
valuation of the lighting package to pay for enforcement of the lighting code.
<p>
<p>
In addition, the Final Report on the lighting standards implementation project
raised the issue of inspections. Lighting code compliance for commercial
buildings is generally achieved by plan review. It was determined that a site
inspection should include inspection of electrical components by an inspector
with a master electrician's license, so Minnesota statute should include the
lighting aspects of energy code within the enforcement responsibility of
electrical inspectors. <p>
<p>
Another example is in the area of residential airtightness and ventilation
system performance. Codes officials should have ready access to blower doors
and to airflow measurement devices. How airtightness provisions should be
verified in Minnesota after 1998 is yet to be determined. However, local codes
officials should begin to gain the capabilities and the hardware to help
builders understand the priority of the airtightness and the ventilation
provisions. This will increase the number of builders able to construct
Category 1 homes, and ease the transition to 1998 when they are mandatory.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation: Additional financial, staff and equipment resources should
be made available to local jurisdictions to enable enforcement of the code, and
to allow inspectors more time to assist builder education. Electrical
inspectors should be given the authority to inspect for lighting code
compliance. Surcharge fees of $3 million are annually raised, but Building
Codes and Standards Division costs are only $1.9 million. Any funds not needed
for training requirements should be returned to local jurisdictions to support
their increased costs of enforcement.</b> <b></b><p>
<b></b><p>
	
<B><a name="RTFToC29">D.
Training for Enforcement Officials
</a><p></B>
<p>
In its June 29, 1993 Statement of Need and Reasonableness (SONAR) for the code
amendments adopted June 1994, the Department acknowledges that code officials
have difficulty understanding the energy code. "Building officials who enforce
the code have expressed to the department that the present energy code is very
confusing."<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn38">[40]</a> Discussion with individual
inspectors indicate that building codes officials know parts of the code, and
enforce the parts with which they are familiar, or parts which seem most
important. To partially address this confusion, the 1994 publication of the
Minnesota Energy Codes Rules Package assembles all the information in one
document.  <p>
<p>
A common complaint of inspectors is the insufficiency of training on the energy
code. When asked for an opinion about whose job it is to train inspectors on
the code, an official from a fast-growing metro suburb presumed it was the
Department of Public Service, the same agency who authors the energy code. <p>
<p>
The Department has statutory authority to do builder training, drawing from a
late 1970's amendment to their authorization statute, but statutes are silent
on whether the Department may or should conduct energy training for codes
officials. The responsibility for code enforcement and by extension energy code
training may more squarely fall on the Building Codes and Standards Division of
the Department of Administration (BCSD). However, since BCSD has no authority
to write or promulgate energy codes, it devotes no full time staff to energy.
<p>
<p>
Pilot efforts to provide training to codes officials have been undertaken, such
as the USEPA-funded demonstration program under which the University of
Minnesota conducted lighting code training. Enforcement officials were a target
audience along with designers and lighting contractors. In addition, the
Department of Public Service has contracted with code inspectors David Drenth
and Ed Pierre of Bloom-ington to conduct some energy code training, and former
DOA codes official Duane Grace has independently offered training. In Ely, some
training is occurring as well. <p>
<p>
There is not, however, a well-developed, universally-available curriculum for
all officials, on the residential code or the commercial code. The high-caliber
training developed for lighting code implementation could continue to be
offered to codes officials if resources are available, but the pilot grant from
the EPA has expired.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation: </b> <b>All officials involved in the enforcement of the
Minnesota Energy Code should receive regular, on-going training. The Building
Codes and Standards Division (BCSD) of the Department of Administration is lead
agency, but does not have the required technical capacity in energy. The
Builders Association of Minnesota, the University of Minnesota and the
Department of Public Service should be given authority over technical content.
Costs can be minimized by combining code official training with builder
training as described in the following recommendation.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>	
<B><a name="RTFToC30">E.
Builder Training for Energy Code Compliance
</a><p></B>
<p>
Following legislation passed in recent years, the Department of Commerce
licenses builders statewide. Prior to testing for a building contractor's
license, the State provides builders some classroom training, which does not
include sufficient information on the Minnesota Energy Code. According to
Department of Commerce printed materials, about 5% of the contractors test will
cover "associated trades" -- including energy codes, plumbing, electrical and
heating, ventilating and air conditioning. The recommended reading list for the
contractor exam does not include the Minnesota Energy Code.<p>
<p>
In Minnesota, a major effort was undertaken in by the Builders Association of
Minnesota (BAM) and the University of Minnesota Building Research Center, in
cooperation with many private firms and educational organizations to develop a
program of advanced trainers for builders. It was developed in the first half
of 1993 and proposed as an Alternative Conservation Improvement Program to the
Commissioner of Public Service on July 28, 1993. Entitled "Effective
Implementation and Delivery of Energy-Efficient Technologies and Practices,"
the project was driven by the strategic plan of the Builders' Association of
Minnesota, and not by the newly emerging code amendments.<a
href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn39">[41]</a> <p>
In fact, the amendments adopted to the code in June 1994 were very much
influenced by the BAM strategic plan, which did not wish to continue to
increase building airtightness without simultaneously addressing the health and
safety issues of combustion appliances and necessary mechanical ventilation.
This is evidenced by the June 1993 DPS Statement of Need and Reasonableness for
the 1994 code amendments. "The BAM has adopted a Strategic Plan calling for all
residential construction to be airtight with mechanical ventilation." <p>
<p>
The proposed BAM training plan focused on understanding buildings as systems,
learning to recognize the complex interactions between building shell
components, mechanical components and occupants. This methodology was
recognized by all as superior to a mere step-by-step guidance to code
compliance, a method which would not have left a foundation for new design
problems, new technology and innovations which are continually presenting
themselves to builders.<p>
<p>
The plan combined many resources from institutions with the BAM as the lead
agency. BAM and its partners approached the state's regulated utilities for
financial support for its four-year plan to train the builders on the energy,
airtightness, thermal performance as well as the indoor air quality, combustion
safety and mechanical ventilation issues inherent in new construction.
Minnegasco and NSP, however, intended to develop their own version of support
for high-efficiency new construction, more focused at a pilot project level
with rebates for higher performing components or practices. Minnesota Power
already had such a rebate program. So BAM took its proposal to the Department
of Public Service, who holds final authority over utility conservation budgets
within the unfortunately restrictive caps imposed by the 1991 legislature.<p>
<p>
<p>
In its comments on the plan, the Sustainable Resources Center (SRC) urged the
Commissioner to accept the project, arguing that the project would be
"transformational" for the industry. "This project," the comments continued,
"does not promise small incremental changes that save energy one by one, but
instead envisions a quantum move forward for the whole industry." Comparing the
potential in Minnesota to the Swedish housing quality revolution in the 1980's,
SRC saw that a project initiated and controlled by the builders had the
potential for that kind of transformational impact. It was further argued that
the project will "create sufficient builder skills and consumer awareness that
market pressure will make it impossible to market homes that are not highly
efficient."<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn40">[42]</a> Half a dozen other groups
commented in support of the plan. It represented a significant start, yet it
was modestly budgeted at $2,373,000 over four years, and was flawed by a lack
of financial support from the State and from builders themselves. In addition,
it would have been strengthened if it had more heavily drawn on existing
materials of the Canadian Home Builders Association, developed in support of
the R-2000 program.<p>
In urging the Commissioner to decline approval of the BAM project, the metro
utilities also compliment the BAM on a "positive effort" and expressed
encouragement for "their desire to educate their builders." The basis for NSP
and Minnegasco opposition to the BAM proposal was that it constituted "utility
ratepayer support for professional training and duplication of available
resources."<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn41">[43]</a> The Commissioner declined
the project and instead encouraged the builders to work with the utility in
developing the small pilot for direct energy savings.<p>
<p>
NSP and Minnegasco continued to develop a joint program for promoting
high-efficiency new construction. The NSP/Minnegasco Energy Advantage Home
program is by many accounts a good start-up, receiving a national award for
innovation in late 1994. The scale of the project is small. Fewer than one
percent of housing starts can be served. In their submission of the program to
the Public Service Commissioner, the utilities acknowledge an unusually heavy
attraction of free riders, builders who are already building energy-efficient
homes. But the program is expected to help those builders reach a higher level
of performance.<p>
<p>
The scale of the approved program was such that it was never designed to be a
substitution for the BAM proposal -- it was never intended to be a
transformational effort to change the way houses are built in Minnesota. The
building industry itself has the willingness to bring along the needed
transformation, but must have resources to help. It is proposed that a
$1,000,000 annual training budget is needed from 1995 until 1999, to position
the industry for the coming change. This should suffice to meet the training
needs of both codes officials and builders.<p>
 <p>
To get a perspective on the potential cost-effectiveness of this approach,
recall the example of Washington State. The power planning agency estimated
that new codes deferred 215 megawatts of power plant construction. Power plants
typically have a capital cost of a million dollars per megawatt, or $215
million for power plants that need not be built. While acknowledging that many
more homes are heated with electricity in the Pacific Northwest than in
Minnesota, this example gives an order of magnitude estimate of the high energy
savings potential of effectively- administered high-level energy codes.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendation:  The State of Minnesota Building Codes and Standards
Division</b> <b>and Department  Public Service, the University of Minnesota and
the Builders Association of Minnesota should form a partnership for builder
training. BAM should be the lead organization and fees assessed to their own
membership should help support the training up to $150,000 per year. This
program should be supported by a legislative appropriation of $500,000 per year
for the next five years supported by existing revenue from the surcharge on
building permits. To support this effort, a Conservation Improvement Program
for $350,000 should be developed involving all regulated utilities, assuring
that utility funding supports energy-efficient construction within the utility
service territory. Unregulated utilities should be solicited for
participation.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
	
<B><a name="RTFToC31">F.
Training for Commercial Code Compliance and Enforcement
</a><p></B>
<p>
In 1993 the Northwest Conservation Act Coalition reported on an ambitious new
commercial code for the State of Washington. When announcing the adoption of
the code, the State's Building Code Council also announced a companion
training, education and enforcement support package to assure effective
implementation. Utilities agreed to fund costs of training and enforcement
until 1997. For the Northwest Power Planning Council that oversees resource
planning for the Bonneville Power Administration, it was a deal to cheap to
pass up. The new code was equivalent to buying those 215 average megawatts of
electricity over 20 years at a real levelized cost of only 15 mills per
kilowatt-hour, less than half the cost of their next cheapest option to buy new
power.<p>
<p>
Minnesota can also buy inexpensive energy-efficiency instead of large amounts
of new supply, but only if new commercial codes are fully implemented. For
lighting alone, one year of compliance with 1993 standards in new and remodeled
buildings in Minnesota would save 32,500 MWh of electricity (costing $1,950,000
and generating 35,000 tons of carbon dioxide), according to the November 1994
DPS report to the US EPA.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn42">[44]</a> The
recommendations here for the State are drawn in part from the Department of
Public Service's recommendations in its report to the US EPA on Commercial
Lighting Standards Implementation.<p>
<p>
<b>Recommendations:  The State of Minnesota and the University of Minnesota
should expand on its pilot effort to deliver training to implement the lighting
code by forming an on-going partnership for commercial energy code training.
The University's  Minnesota Building Research Center should be the lead
organization. The expansion should include enforcement personnel, lighting
designers, commercial architects, utilities and manufacturers representatives.
Where possible, training should be targeted for separate audiences. This
program should be supported by a legislative appropriation of $250,000 per year
for the next five years. To supplement the State appropriation, the DPS should
solicit and approve a Conservation Improvement Program for $150,000 per year
involving all regulated utilities pro-rated to utilities based on new
commercial meter connections. Unregulated utilities should be solicited for
participation.</b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b></b>	
<B><a name="RTFToC32">G.
Performance Verification Before Connection To Utility
</a><p></B>
<p>
An additional enforcement tool available to the State is to require
verification of code compliance for energy before allowing a utility to connect
a new building. Perhaps this would be most justifiable for electrically-heated
buildings, but there are disadvantages of this method. It would put a
significant hardship on builders or developers to prove code compliance before
hook-up. Costs of bringing buildings into compliance after final-finish would
be considerably higher than in-process.<p>
<b>
<a name="RTFToC33">V.
SUMMARY OF RECOMMENDATIONS
</a></b><p>
<b></b><p>
<b>1.</b> The legislature should assure that the energy code is enforced
throughout Minnesota.<p>
<p>
<b>2.</b> Minnesota must provide significant additional statewide technical
support, either through contracts or staffing, to assure the proper
dissemination and implementation of the Minnesota Energy Code. This will
require additional financial resources.<p>
<p>
<b>3.</b> Additional financial, staff and equipment resources should be made
available to local jurisdictions to enable enforcement of the code, and to
allow inspectors more time to assist builder education. Electrical inspectors
should be given the authority to inspect for lighting code compliance.
Surcharge fees of $3 million are annually raised, but Building Codes and
Standards Division costs are only $1.9 million. Any funds not needed for the
training requirements of recommendations 4 and 5 should be returned to local
jurisdictions to support their increased costs of enforcement. <p>
<p>
<b>4.</b> All officials involved in the enforcement of the Minnesota Energy
Code should receive regular, on-going training. The Building Codes and
Standards Division of the Department of Administration is lead agency for
training building officials, but does not have the required technical capacity
in energy. The Builders Association of Minnesota, the University of Minnesota
and the Department of Public Service should be given authority over technical
content. Costs can be minimized by combining code official training with
builder training as described in the following recommendation.<p>
<p>
<b>5.</b> The State of Minnesota Building Codes and StandardsDivision and the
Department of Public Service, the University of Minnesota and the Builders
Association of Minnesota should form a partnership for builder training. BAM
should be the lead organization and fees assessed to their own membership
should help support the training up to $150,000 per year. This program should
be supported by a legislative appropriation of $500,000 per year for the next
five years supported by existing building permit revenues which now flow into
the General Fund. To support this effort, a Conservation Improvement Program
for $350,000 should be developed involving all regulated utilities, assuring
that utility funding supports energy-efficient construction within the utility
service territory. Unregulated utilities should be solicited for
participation.<p>
<p>
<b>6.</b> The State of Minnesota and the University of Minnesota should expand
on its pilot effort to deliver training to implement the lighting code by
forming an on-going partnership for commercial energy code training. The
University's Minnesota Building Research Center should be the lead
organization. The expansion should include enforcement personnel, lighting
designers, commercial architects, utilities and manufacturers representatives.
Where possible, training should be targeted for separate audiences. This
program should be supported by a legislative appropriation of $250,000 per year
for the next five years. To supplement the State appropriation, the DPS should
solicit and approve a Conservation Improvement Program for $150,000 per year
involving all regulated utilities pro-rated to utilities based on new
commercial meter connections. Unregulated utilities should be solicited for
participation.<a href="ecoderpt_fn.html#fn43">[ ]</a><p>
</body></html>
