with the assistance of Minnesotans For An Energy-Efficient Economy, Janet
Lussenhop, Executive Director.<p>
<p>
Special thanks for advice and assistance on this project goes to Bruce Nelson,
Senior Engineer for the Minnesota Department of Public Service, one of
Minnesota's most focused and dedicated public servants. Special acknowledgment
for leadership in this field is extended to Joan Archer, Executive Director of
the Builders Association of Minnesota. <p>
<p>
Thank you to Sheryl Carter and Stewart Selman of the Center for Energy and
Environment who are working on similar issues for the Statewide Increasing
Energy Efficiency and Reducing CO2 Project, and who were very generous
discussing emerging views and findings; and to the other CEE staff whose
recommendations for the US EPA's Commercial Lighting Standards Implementation
Project are incorporated in my recommendations. Additionally, Gary Nelson of
the Energy Conservatory helped remind me why Minnesota could well get stuck,
and Rob Dumont of the Saskatchewan Research Council reminded me why we don't
have to. Steve Nadel of the American Council for An Energy-Efficient Economy
has provided thoughtful input into Minnesota policy-level discussions of energy
codes. David Grimsrud and Pat Huelman of the Minnesota Building Research Center
deserve enormous credit for keeping the ball moving forward on efficient,
healthy buildings, and have provided me useful advice on numerous occasions. I
recognize that Rick Korinek continues to shed light on my work from his post at
United Power Association; at DPS his expertise kept me from wandering in the
dark more than once. I appreciate that Peter Herzog of Herzog and Wheeler
talked me out of policy recommendations that wouldn't work. I am also grateful
to unnamed building inspectors who confided why the system doesn't work now. <p>
<p>
Credit for the original idea in 1990 that Minnesota's energy code should
logically be state-of the-art, goes to my friend and originator of many ideas,
David Morris. Finally, thanks to my directors and colleagues at SRC for their
continued commitment to policy-level work.<p>
