<DOCHDR>
http://www.me3.org:80/issues/solar/pvmn06.html 198.174.235.57 19970222002618 text/html 24784
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 22 Feb 1997 00:26:38 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 24612
Last-modified: Tue, 15 Oct 1996 19:10:08 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title> A Cost-Effective Market for Photovoltaics in Minnesota</title></head>
<body><p>
<p>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>A COST-EFFECTIVE MARKET FOR PHOTOVOLTAICS IN MINNESOTA</H2><P>
<p>
A Report to the Minnesota Legislature<p>
By the Minnesota Department of Public Service January, 1992<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
The following report is submitted as called for by Laws of Minnesota, 1991, Chapter 235, Article 7, Section 1 which states:<p>
<p>
The commissioner of public service shall conduct a study of the potential
market within the state for photovoltaic devices. The study shall focus on
applications where photovoltaics, with and without energy storage, cost less than conventional means of supplying energy and power for those applications. The commissioner shall submit the report to the appropriate committees of the legislature by January 15, 1992.<p>
<p>
<b>Summary of findings</b><p>
<p>
The Minnesota Department of Public Service identified
cost-effective uses of photovoltaics (PV), based on recent experiences in the photovoltaic industry in Minnesota and across the nation. It then identified the potential market for applications in Minnesota state government. In total, nine major types of applications in the Departments of Natural Resources, Transportation, and Public Safety were investigated.  Numerous specific potential installations were identified which, if implemented, would require an investment of $4.4 million. Since the study considered only cost-effective
applications, it is expected that this investment would prove less costly in
these applications than using conventional means to supply the electric
power.<p>
<p>
To realize the potential savings from these PV applications, however, program
managers and other decision makers in state government need to be thoroughly
knowledgeable about photovoltaics, and procedures and incentives need to be in
place that encourage adopting new technology. Currently this is not the case.<p>
<p>
<B>Focus of the study</B><p>
<p>
The Minnesota Department of Public Service searched for PV market
assessments across the United States, hoping that the Minnesota study could be
based on previous analysis. Although considerable experience has been gained in
the use of photovoltaics in many types of applications across the country, no
assessment of the broad market within a particular geographic area, such as a
state, has been conducted. Confined market sectors have been evaluated, such as
the utility sector<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#foot1">[l]</A> or the potential export market<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#foot1">[2]</A>. Evaluation have also
been made of the worldwide terrestrial (non-space) market for photovoltaics<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#foot1">[3]</A>
and for the entire United States<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#foot1">[4]</A>. These studies were either too narrow or
too general to apply to Minnesota, but their information on actual
installations was useful for our study.<p>
<p>
Cost-effective photovoltaic installations, described later in this report, more
often are in applications not connected to utility electric lines and having
low power requirements. Travel and tourism, rail transportation, and
agricultural industries are just some of the sectors of Minnesota's economy
with such applications; but the limited time and resources available for this
project have made it necessary to focus on just one sector. Because the best
documentation of opportunities for cost-effective photovoltaic applications is
in the governmental sector, this study examines state government applications
and their potential for cost-effective PV applications.<p>
<p>
<b>Background on Photovoltaics</b><p>
<p>
A photovoltaic cell is a semi-conductor device that converts
sunlight into direct current electricity. Cells can be combined to produce the
power (voltage and current) required for an application. The solar generated
electricity is frequently stored in batteries for use during non-solar periods.
If alternating current is required, an invertor is used to generate an
alternating current from the direct current produced by the photovoltaic
cells.<p>
<p>
The photovoltaic effect has been known for 150 years, but it wasn't until 1954
that scientists at Bell Laboratories created the first crystalline silicon
photovoltaic cell. Shortly thereafter, in 1958, the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration (NASA) selected a photovoltaic system as the electric
power source for the Vanguard space satellite. That was the first
cost-effective application of photovoltaics -- the PV system was the cheapest
means of providing electrical power for the application (even though the cost
was several hundred dollars per watt of power).<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#foot1">[6]</A><p>
<p>
The number of cost-effective applications has increased rapidly. By 1975, NASA
was using nearly a million PV cells per year. Costs continued to decline
through the decade of the 1980s, enabling photovoltaic systems to penetrate the
non-space market. Products such as watches and calculators began to have
photovoltaic systems. Then PV systems expanded into remote power applications,
such as mountain top communication system repeater systems. In the mid-1980s,
PV systems became the power source of choice for residences not connected to
the utility grid and for low power remote or mobile power loads. In all cases,
the PV systems were cost effective --the cheapest source of power for the
application.<p>
<p>
By 1990, the cost of a PV cell had dropped from the early $100-per-watt to just
$3.75 per watt of power.<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#foot1">[7]</A> The worldwide photovoltaic industry is expected to
rise to nearly $800 million in revenue for 1991.<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#foot1">[8]</A> PV systems have become cost
effective in even more applications -- the current rule of thumb is that if the
power requirement is less than 500 watts and it requires more than one power
pole extension to the utility grid, a photovoltaic system may be the preferred
cost-effective power supply option.<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#foot1">[9]</A><p>
<p>
<b>Cost-effective applications for PV systems</b><p>
<p>
Photovoltaic systems are most often cost effective today because
they avoid more expensive processes; they may not produce cheaper electricity.
This is why the search for cost-effective uses focuses on applications that
have no conventional electric power. Even at today's greatly reduced prices for
photovoltaic cells, the absolute energy costs -- the cost of the system
amortized over an estimated 20 year lifetime per unit of energy delivered --
may still be relatively high. The current statewide average retail residential
cost of electricity in Minnesota is just under 7cents per kilowatt-hour (kWh),
while the amortized cost of photovoltaic electricity may be over
25cents/kWh.<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#foot1">[10]</A> In some areas of Minnesota, however, electricity costs over
14cents/kWh and rates are projected to increase.  Conventional and photovoltaic
electricity costs are close enough that some utilities are currently evaluating
the use of photovoltaic systems in specialized applications.<!-- Anchor Link Tag --><A HREF="#foot1">[11]</A><p>
<p>
Photovoltaic systems are typically cost effective for one of two major
reasons:<p>
<p>
First, the initial cost (purchase and installation) of a photovoltaic
system may be substantially cheaper than-that of another option for new power
supplies. Some actual examples include:<p>
<p>
<UL>
<LI> A PV lighting system in Minnesota was cheaper than the $2,500 estimated cost
of running an underground electric line to a new boat ramp.<p>
<p>
<LI> A $1,500 PV system cost less than digging through a sidewalk to provide power
for a bus kiosk from an underground power line.<p>
<p>
<LI> A resort owner found it feasible to use a PV system to provide lights on a
dock not served by a utility power line.<p>
<p>
<LI> A billboard rental firm was able to add nighttime lighting with a PV system,
thereby increasing its advertising revenue.<p>
</UL><p>
Second, a photovoltaic system's operating and maintenance costs may be
low enough compared to an existing electric system to provide quick payback of
the initial PV purchase and installation cost. For example:<p>
<p>
<UL>
<LI> A PV system avoided the personnel time and fuel required to transport fresh
batteries to a remote water quality monitoring site every month.<p>
<p>
<LI> PV system avoided the loss of data from a weather monitoring station.<p>
<p>
<LI> A PV system avoided the cost and environmental risk of transporting diesel
fuel to a remote site.<p>
<p>
<LI> A PV system avoided the need to service a remote diesel generator each 250
hours of operation.<p>
</UL><p>
Although the exact financial costs of such problems are difficult to determine,
the agencies installing the PV systems are pleased with their decisions.<p>
<p>
Other favorable attributes of photovoltaics.  Besides cost
effectiveness, PV systems have other advantages that should be noted.<p>
<p>
<UL>
<LI>	They use sunlight, not a depletable fuel.<p>
<p>
<LI> They generate electricity with little impact on the environment.<p>
<p>
<LI>	They have no moving parts to wear out.<p>
<p>
<LI> They make no noise.<p>
<p>
<LI> 	They are modular, meaning that the power source can be expanded to match
changing loads.<p>
<p>
<LI> 	They are reliable and durable.<p>
</UL><p>
<b>Market identification</b><p>
<p>
<b></b>In analyzing potential markets, this study used the following
assumptions:<p>
<p>
<UL>
<LI> The photovoltaic application must be cost effective -- that is, photovoltaics
must be cheaper than any other option.  The procedures for estimating the costs
of photovoltaic systems and their payback periods are described in
<i>Photovoltaic Systems for Government Agencies, </i>published in 1989 by the
Sandia National Laboratories, U. S. Department of Energy. A copy of this
publication is included with this report.<p>
<p>
<LI> The purchaser has all the information and consumer confidence necessary to
make an informed decision and be comfortable with the new technology.<p>
<p>
<LI> The purchaser is making an objective rational decision: For instance, the
purchase is not being made to increase the image of the purchaser, nor is it
being avoided because of personal investments in the oil and gas industry.<p>
<p>
<LI> Equipment is available on the market today  -- no new breakthroughs
intechnology are needed -- and it is instantly available to fulfill an
immediate demand.<p>
<p>
<LI> Applications that can be shown to be cost effective but are not yet widely
used have not been included in the evaluation.<p>
<p>
<LI> Equipment is purchased at today's prices.<p>
<p>
<LI> Equipment will be purchased over a three-year period; after that, some of the
other assumptions will have changed.<p>
</UL><p>
Based on experience in the photovoltaic industry, cost-effective applications
could be found in three major sectors of our economy: governmental operations,
the tourism industry, and agriculture. These applications are listed below:<p>
<p>
<I>Government</I><BR>
Lighting, for public lake access, trails, and rest rooms;<BR>
Communications, including telecommunication repeating stations and emergency
call boxes; <BR>
Vehicle battery charging for snow removal equipment, earth moving equipment,
and emergency vehicles; <BR>
Monitoring, including water level monitors, water quality monitors, and remote
weather stations; <BR>
Warning signals, including weather warning sirens, traffic advance warning
arrow boards, and navigational lights; and <BR>
Off-grid facilities such as state park residences, remote equipment storage
buildings, and fire towers.<BR>
<p>
<I>Travel and Tourism</I><BR>
Residences, such as dispersed cabins and hunting facilities;<BR>
Battery chargers for recreational vehicles, trolling motors, and sailing
vessels; <BR>
Lighting for boat launches/docks and-parking areas; and <BR>
Water pumping for pond aeration and potable water.<BR>
<p>
<I>Agriculture</I><BR>
Fence chargers;<BR>
Stock tank aerators; and <BR>
Water pumps.<p>
<p>
<b>Potential PV applications in Minnesota state government</b><p>
<p>
Research was conducted on nine different classes of
installations.  Contact was made primarily with program managers in state
agencies, including the Minnesota Departments of Natural Resources (Trails and
Waterways, Parks and Recreation, Waters), Public Safety (State Patrol),
Transportation (Electronic Communications, Rights of Way, Traffic Engineering,
Maintenance Equipment Section), National Guard, and the Pollution Control
Agency. Other contacts included:<p>
<p>
Colorado Mountain College, Glenwood Springs, CO<BR>
Electric Power Research Institute, Palo Alto, CA<BR>
Florida Solar Energy Center, Cape Canaveral, FL<BR>
Florida Solar Energy Industries Association, Homestead, FL <BR>
Infinite Energy, Denver, CO<BR>
National Appropriate Technology Assistance Center, Butte, MT <BR>
National Renewable Energy Laboratory, Golden, CO <BR>
Photocomm, Scottsdale, AZ<BR>
Public Citizen, Washington, DC<BR>
Sandia National Laboratories, Albuquerque, NM<BR>
Solar Energy Analysis Laboratory, Fort Collins, CO<BR>
Strategies Unlimited, Mountain View, CA<BR>
<P>
Data on system components and costs are based on previous installations in
Minnesota, experiences from other states, and price quotations from Minnesota
businesses. Assumptions on the possible numbers of applications have been
derived from discussions with agency personnel and based on government and
industry experiences in other locations.<p>
<p>
Following is a summary of the research conducted and estimates of the number
and value of potential photovoltaic installations.<p>
<p>
<B>LIGHTING</B><p>
<p>
All of the PV lighting applications identified below would provide lighting
where conventional electric power is currently not available.<p>
<p>
<b>Public lake access</b><p>
<p>
There are 66 state parks in Minnesota, with 58 having fishing access to
lakes or rivers; the state maintains 1,200 public accesses to rivers or lakes.
According to the Department of Natural Resources, most of the public accesses
are in remote locations and need lighting.  Although a thorough evaluation has
not been done, DNR information suggests that perhaps 25 percent of the public
accesses may be appropriate for PV lighting. These installations could be
supplied by packaged systems each with a 200 watt PV panel, controller, and
battery storage costing $2,200 each. The 300 systems would cost a total of
approximately $660,000.<p>
<p>
<b>Trails</b><p>
<p>
The state maintains hiking, horse riding, biking, skiing, and snowmobile
trails. Presumably, cross country skiing could benefit from night lighting.
Installing underground electric power lines over such long distances is clearly
prohibitive. However, modular photovoltaic systems may allow the more heavily
used portions of the trails to be lighted throughout the evening ski period.
Assuming that 10 percent of the-existing 1,230 km of trails could use lighting,
and that the 30 watt systems would be placed each 50 meters, some 2,500 units
would be required. The units cost $400 each, making a total investment of $1
million.<p>
<p>
<b>State park facilities</b><p>
<p>
Minnesota owns and operates approximately 1,000 structures in the 66
state parks. The buildings include rest room facilities, equipment buildings,
meeting facilities, picnic shelters, etc. Lighting is used for security and
safety, as well as to increase the use of the facility, if electric power is
available. According to estimates by DNR, as many as 30 percent of these
buildings, currently without power, could benefit from nighttime lighting.
Photovoltaic system costs would range from $500 to $6,000, depending on the
lighting requirements. At an average of $2,000, lighting for the 300 buildings
needing power would cost $600,000.<p>
<p>
<b>Traffic warning arrow boards</b><p>
<p>
Mobile arrow boards are frequently used for traffic control around road
construction sites. Eight solar powered boards are currently being used by a
private Minnesota firm which leases them to road construction crews, including
crews in the Minnesota Department of Transportation. MNDOT owns about 300
diesel powered warning boards, which have a ten year projected life, and must
replace 10 percent of them each year. Over three years, 90 units could be
replaced with $5,900-solar-powered systems, for a total expenditure of
$530,000.<p>
<p>
<B>COMMUNICATIONS</B><p>
<p>
<b>Telecommunication repeating stations</b><p>
<p>
The Department of Natural Resources maintains 200 telecommunication
sites for the Department of Natural Resources, the Department of
Transportation, and the State Patrol. The vast majority of the existing systems
are connected to the utility grid; the rest are powered by diesel generators.
As the generators wear out, they can be replaced by photovoltaic systems. One
site could be repowered with photovoltaics over the next three years. In
addition, two new sites could be installed near their optimum location powered
by photovoltaics. A typical system requires about 1,400 watts of power and
costs about $24,000. Therefore, $70,000 would be required for the three
systems.<p>
<p>
<b>Emergency call boxes</b><p>
<p>
Solar powered emergency call boxes use cellular phones to Connect the caller
with emergency set/ices. Consequently, the systems can be placed virtually
anywhere served by cellular phone network. Typically, call boxes are placed
about every 500 meters along highways to aide motorists. The systems are
equipped with adequate solar power and storage to withstand many days of no
sun. There are about 400 km of interstate highways in the Twin Cities area
alone, requiring some 800 call boxes. Figuring an additional 25 percent as many
systems would be required, serving the Duluth, St. Cloud, and Rochester calling
areas would require about 200 more boxes, i.e., 1,000 systems in all. At $1,200
each, the total cost would be $1.2 million.<p>
<p>
<B>MONITORING</B><p>
<p>
<b>Water level monitoring</b><p>
<p>
The U.S. Geological Service uses photovoltaic systems extensively to
monitor water levels on navigable waters in the United States, including sites
in Minnesota. Data are collected at the site and relayed to a central office
via telecommunication.<p>
<p>
The Department of Natural Resources maintains approximately 500 surface water
level monitoring stations of its own across the state; however, levels are
monitored weekly by volunteers who visit the sites and read the level on linear
scales. More frequent data are rarely required, since water levels change
slowly in Minnesota.  Automating the recording stations would require major
changes in the procedures for monitoring water levels and a major capitol
investment, well beyond the cost of the PV systems; therefore, no water level
monitoring sites are included in this evaluation.<p>
<p>
<B>VEHICLE BATTERY CHARGING</B><p>
<p>
<b>Seasonal use vehicles</b><p>
<p>
The state maintains approximately 750 dedicated seasonal use vehicles
such as snow plows, snow blowers, road repair vehicles, and mowers. All are
subjected to low battery power and early battery failure from resting for long
periods with no use. Because some of these vehicles must be immediately
operable at all times, they are housed indoors. This more expensive indoor
storage may not be necessary if the battery charge levels could be maintained
by a solar battery charger. Moreover, the vehicles currently stored outdoors
(about 300) would benefit from a solar battery charger. At about $85 each,
these vehicles could be provided with chargers for approximately $25,000.<p>
<p>
<b>Military vehicles</b><p>
<p>
Minnesota has approximately 90 National Guard units across the state.
Each unit has from 6 to 60 vehicles under its jurisdiction. These vehicles are
typically used once per month, though the period of non-use is longer in some
cases. In addition, Camp Ripley has a pool of about 500 vehicles allocated for
two-week periods for training at the camp, though many of these remain idle,
depending on the type of exercises taking place. If 60 percent of the vehicles
in the individual units and 10 percent of the vehicles at Camp Ripley remain
idle for at least two weeks at a time, 1,130 vehicles could benefit from a
solar battery charger. Fitting the vehicles would cost $340,000.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Cost analysis</b><p>


<pre>
Application                                                          # Install    Cost (thou  
                                                                                          $)  
Public Lake Access Lighting                                                300           660  
Ski Trail Lighting                                                       2,500         1,000  
State Park Facilities                                                      300           600  
Traffic Arrow Boards                                                        90           530  
Telecommunication stations                                                   3            70  
Emergency Call Boxes                                                     1,000         1,200  
Water Level Monitors                                                         0             0  
Seasonal Use Equipment                                                     300            25  
Military Vehicles                                                        1,130           340  
                                              Total                      5,623         4,425  

</pre>
<p>
<p>
<b>Conclusions</b><p>
<p>
This study has investigated possible photovoltaic applications in
state government. It has identified $4.4 million worth of cost-effective
installations. Additional cost-effective installations may be: county, city,
and local governments have many similar types of operations that could
potentially be served by PV systems; other market sectors have many potential
cost-effective applications (utilities, agriculture, advertising,
tourism/travel, private home/lake home owners). A more comprehensive
investigation of these sectors would be expected to reveal additional
cost-effective PV applications in state government as well as other potential
market sectors.<p>
<p>
Such a study could also explore the feasibility of possible governmental
actions to make better use of PV's potential. Certainly at the top of the list
would be education. The cost analysis provided in the study could be used to
educate managers about cost-effective applications.  The current
Energy/Environmental Planning initiative may be a useful mechanism for
implementing such a program.  The study also could explore possible alternative
mechanisms for PV applications.<p>
<p>
JD:I/92<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>References</b><p>
