<HR>

<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="i"></A><H2>I.  FEATURE:  THE PRIMERGY MERGER</H2>
<!-- Font Tag --><B><FONT SIZE=5>Primergy:  Why the PUC?  Why Now?</FONT></B><BR>
by Diane Jensen, Clean Water Action<P>
In the next 120 days the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (PUC) will decide whether to approve a merger of NSP and Wisconsin Energy Corporation into a new $6 billion corporation called Primergy.  Two questions come to mind.  Why should the PUC be making that decision?  Why does that decision need to be made now?   <P>
Electricity is a big business, bigger than airlines or telephones.  Electricity is a necessity of modern life.  The PUC sets rates and oversees the operation of energy utilities.  But the job of deciding whether to allow one of the state's most important companies to merge, become even more powerful, and remove itself from state regulatory control should be the legislature's.  <P>
As of late November, two of the five PUC Commissioners removed themselves from the final decision because of ex parte communications with NSP.  Another Commissioner's seat will soon be vacant.  We could well end up with only two or three people making a decision that affects the lives of every Minnesotan.  Hardly an ideal situation.  The PUC has said it will make the decision by March 1997.  The legislature convenes in late January.  By that time legislators will have available all the substantive information the PUC has.   Isn't the legislature, with its elected representatives and open hearing process, a better venue for this type of decision?  <P>
The second question regarding the proposed merger has to do with timing.  The PUC has opened a restructuring docket whose goal is to study issues involved in redesigning the electric utility system to make it more competitive.  The merger would move us in the opposite direction by effectively reducing the number of competitors.   <P>
By allowing the merger we may be restricting future options.  For example, the PUC may well approve a merger that allows Primergy to own both transmission and distribution lines as well as power plants.  Yet a major component of the restructuring efforts around the country is the separation of the ownership of transmission and power generation.   What if Minnesota later on decides to adopt this strategy?  Would we demand that Primergy sell off its transmission capacity just after it has spent months integrating the transmission capacities of two giant utilities?  Some experts think we might not even have the legal authority any longer to unilaterally require this. <P>
In short, the merger decision may pre-empt restructuring decisions.   Which brings us back to the second question,  why now?   The PUC has launched an industry restructuring docket and has set up a handful of working groups.  There is no rush toward merger.  To our knowledge no one has argued that NSP or WEC would suffer losses if the merger decision were made in 1998 or even 1999 instead of 1997.  <P>
Legal experts tell us that in merger proceedings, the utilities have the burden of proving that it is in the public interest.  But in most states the opposite has occurred.  It is the opponents who have shouldered the burden of proof.   If NSP had the burden of proof theirs would be a difficult case to make.   Merger partners promise operational savings of $2 billion over 10 years.  This translates into about $7.00 per customer per month, if all savings are passed through to customers.  Regulatory staff in both Minnesota and Wisconsin believe the actual savings would be closer to $100 million a year, and the Minnesota Dept. of Public Service estimates they could be as low as $79 million a year. The Wisconsin Citizens Utility Board calculates that the merger actually increases costs.  <P>
<IMG WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=177 ALT="Coal Plant Graphic" SRC="coalplant.jpg">
The merger partners have a combined annual revenue of $4.2 billion.  NSP is proposing to share savings with ratepayers through a 1.5 percent rate reduction and a four-year rate freeze.   Their plan represents a reduction of $0.75 per month for the average consumer, about one-tenth of the total savings claimed by NSP and WEC.<P>
Two thirds of the savings will come from reducing the utilities' labor force, which may mean longer turnaround times for customer service or repairing outages.  <P>
That's the upside.  The downside is a loss of regulatory control to the federal government and the limiting of options available for consideration in the restructuring debate.   ME3 experts have argued that Primergy would increase the generation of electricity from low-cost Twin Cities' coal-fired power plants for sale to new markets thereby increasing pollution.<P>
We end where we began.  Why now?  Why the PUC?<P>
<HR>
<H3>Primergy:  Regulatory Misstep - Part II</H3>
The proposed marriage of Wisconsin Energy Corporation and Northern States Power has run into trouble, again.  First it was the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and Wisconsin Public Service Commission concerns that Primergy would have too much market power and too little independent oversight over the operation of their transmission system.  More recently, alleged ex parte communications between utility executives and regulators have turned the merger into a sticky affair in both Wisconsin and Minnesota.<P>
<H4>Minnesota</H4>
Let's begin with the Minnesota situation.  The PUC with the help 
of the Office of Attorney General (OAG) investigated possible ex parte communications between PUC Commissioners Joel Jacobs and Marshall Johnson and NSP lobbyist Merle Anderson.  The two PUC commissioners have recused themselves from voting on the merger even though other PUC commissioners subsequently ruled that the conversations were not serious enough to constitute illegal communication.  Commissioner Storm and the OAG agreed with ME3 that the law was violated. In their October 28th order  the PUC concludes,  " the commission finds tangential, glancing references not addressing the merits of the FERC staff report -- incidental, casual talk of fleeting duration and slight interest to the conversers and ultimately of insubstantial relevance to the merits and outcome NSP's proposed merger application."  ME3, and our coalition partners, Izaak Walton League and the Environmental Law & Policy Center filed a petition asking the PUC to reconsider its decision that NSP's communications with PUC members did not break the law.<P>
The merger case in Minnesota is moving forward with only 3 commissioners for the moment.  A future problem exists when Commissioner Dee Knaak's term expires at the end of December which will leave the PUC with only two members unless Governor Carlson makes a timely appointment.  Public hearings have been completed and the contested case hearing began November 20, 1996.  Three administrative law judges are hearing separate aspects of the merger case including; competitive issues, rate issues, and economic savings.  Separate hearings or testimony on the environmental effects of the merger was ruled outside the scope of the proceeding by the PUC.  It is unlikely that the Minnesota PUC will issue a final ruling on the merger before March 1997.<P>
<H4>Wisconsin</H4>
Ex parte communication and the resignation of one of three Wisconsin Public Service Commission (PSC) members has slowed the merger in our neighboring state.  In Early September, Scott Neitzel, one of the PSC's strongest voices increase competition stepped down to take a job in the private sector, and immediately, loudly condemned the merger.  Governor Tommy Thompson quickly replaced Neitzel with Joe Mettner, former legal assistant to the Governor.  Critics of the appointment note Mettner's lack of experience on utility matters and have suggested that the PSC wait on considering the merger until after his Senate confirmation.<P>
A news report in the November 8, 1996, Capital Times,  reported that PSC commissioner Dan Eastman engaged in private meetings with top executives at  Wisconsin Energy Corporation, since the filing of the merger proposal.  Eastman has denied any wrongdoing and PSC legal counsel has suggested that no illegal communications took place since the meetings were held prior to the official pre-hearing date of July 24, 1996.  Formal hearings opened last month in Wisconsin with PSC staff analysts stating that merger is likely to generate only one-half of the $2 billion in savings that NSP and WEC project over the next 10 years.  Unlike Minnesota regulators, Wisconsin decision makers are allowing testimony on the environmental impacts of the merger. The PSC is also preparing an Environmental Assessment of the merger, pursuant to an Environmental Coalition motion.<P>
Follow this link to <A HREF="http://www.me3.org/issues/merger/">ME3's filings and updates on the Primergy merger</A><P>
<A NAME="ii"></A><H2>II.  REGULATORY UPDATE</H2>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=2>
<TR><TD><H3>ME3 Position on Retail Wheeling - Adopted October 15, 1996</H3>
We oppose radical restructuring of the electricity industry as proposed by advocates of "retail wheeling".  Instead, we seek environmental improvement and economic development through energy efficiency and renewable energy. <P>
Retail wheeling would increase pollution, reduce reliability, shift costs to small consumers, and eliminate energy efficiency and renewable energy progress.  Retail wheeling masquerades as "customer choice", but customer choice is meaningless in an industry controlled by monopolies and oligopolies.  Winners will be lawyers, lobbyists and middlepersons, and the losers will be most customers and the environment.  Instead of retail wheeling, our proposals improve wholesale competition while increasing opportunities for renewables. <P>
Minnesota has made great progress towards a sustainable energy future.  We need to keep moving forward, instead of returning to a past that ignored energy efficiency and renewable power.  Minnesota needs to "cap" pollution emissions as it "capped" nuclear waste in 1994.  Now is the time to move to the technologies of the future. <P>
Here is a link to a <A HREF="http://www.me3.org/projects/dereg/wheelposition.html">detailed version of the ME3 position on retail wheeling</A><P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE><P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>PUC Externalities Ruling:  Climate Change Real But Barely Matters</FONT></B><BR>
by Michael Noble<P>
The five-year process to determine the environmental costs associated with electric power reached the Public Utilities Commission (PUC) for a final decision on September 16th.  By the end, controversy had subsided over the estimated costs of damages due to acid rain, smog, particulates, and ground-level ozone.  Reasonable estimates of environmental damages were assigned to each of the so-called criteria pollutants.  The issue of global warming took center stage.<P>
Final oral arguments by intervenors focused on the future costs of local climate change.  Those hoping for a decisiveness were left confused by the final decision, which as of press time, had not been issued by the PUC in a written order.  In their deliberations the PUC seem to leave open a possibility of assigning $0 to each pollutant.  They also did not indicate how the values would be applied.  The table below shows the range of externality values established by the PUC.<P>
<CENTER><B>PUC's Final Environmental Externalities Values</B><BR>
(dollars per ton)<BR>
<!-- Table Tag --><TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=1>
<TR><TD></TD><TD><B>Rural</B></TD><TD><B>Metropolitan <BR>Fringe</B></TD><TD><B>Urban</B></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><B>Particulate Matter </B>(PM10)</TD><TD>$562 - $855</TD><TD>$1987 - $2886</TD><TD>$4462 - $6423</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><B>Nitrogen Oxides </B>(NOx)</TD><TD>$18 - $102</TD><TD>$140 - $266</TD><TD>$371 - $978</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><B>Lead </B>(Pb)</TD><TD>$402 - $448</TD><TD>$1652 - $1995</TD><TD>$3131 - $3875</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><B>Carbon Monoxide </B>(CO)</TD><TD>$0.21 - $0.41</TD><TD>$0.76 - $1.34</TD><TD>$1.06 - $2.27</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><B>Carbon Dioxide </B>(CO2) (1995 $)</TD><TD>$0.30 - $3.10</TD><TD>$0.30 - $3.10</TD><TD>$0.30 - $3.10</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><B>Sulfur Dioxide </B>(SO2) Before year 2000</TD><TD>$10 - $25</TD><TD>$46 - $110</TD><TD>$112 - $189</TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><P>

The great climate change discussion resulted in a perplexing outcome--that global climate change is indeed real, but that its estimated costs in present value is very low.  Environmental intervenors sought a damage value for carbon dioxide of $25 per ton, which is within the mainstream of serious economic research into the subject, but is higher than the $15 per ton value adopted by the Wisconsin Public Service Commission.  The PUC adopted a range of $0.30 to $3.10 per ton. <P>
The environmental advocates were unsuccessful in getting the most recent findings of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) admitted into the record.  This was important because IPCC 1995 confirms that global warming is real, and their damage costs are a few times higher than the estimates recommended by the law judge who reviewed the expert testimony in the case.  The PUC ruled that IPCC 1995 should not be included, since it was issued after the record closed.<P>
To establish the range for carbon dioxide, the PUC concluded that the damage would likely be 1 percent of world economic output within about 35 years (as opposed to "a few percent" predicted by the IPCC ).  These staggering costs were then minimized by use of a discount rate of 3-5% per year.  In other words, trillions of dollars of damages worldwide -- and, by extension, a commensurate amount to Minnesota forests, fisheries, agriculture, wetlands, and human health -- become inconsequential if they are reduced 3-5% per year from the year 2030 back to the present.  <P>
The IPCC suggested that when calculating the costs of climate change, the choice of social discount rates is "a matter of policy preference", another way to say that this a "values" question more than an economics one.  IPCC cites social discount rates of 3-6 percent for long-term, risk-free public investments, but suggests using a 0.5 -3.0 percent discount method may be more appropriate for climate change.  As an example, IPCC says that a $1000 damage in 100 years would be valued in the present at $7.60 using a 5% discount rate, (the high end of the range chosen by the PUC), and would be valued at $370 using a discount rate of 1 percent at the low end of the range of methods preferred by economists concerned about fairness between generations.<P>
Perhaps the climate change debate needs its own Ross Perot, someone who can speak directly to the American people about the debt we are leaving to our children. Unlike the deficit problem which was attacked in a bipartisan way, the damages of climate change cannot be reversed in any timeframe of human significance. Once the climate is altered, our children, and their children and grandchildren will be unable to reverse the effects.  Perhaps the public will soon begin to grapple with this issue that goes to a question of human destiny. <P>

<H3>Search for Alternative Nuclear Storage Site Ends</H3>
The Environmental Quality Board held a special meeting on October 2, 1996 to address Northern States Power Company's (NSP's) application for the nation's first away-from-reactor spent nuclear fuel storage installation.  The EQB denied NSP's application for site approval but approved an order that gives the utility permission to add 4 more dry cask storage containers at the current spent fuel storage facility outside the plant.  This gives the utility permission to use up to 9 casks at the Prairie Island spent fuel storage installation.  The utility has filled five dry casks which are sitting on the concrete pad outside the plant and has the sixth cask on-site.  <p>
<IMG  ALT="Dry Cask Storage" SRC="drycasks.jpg"><BR>
Dry Cask Storage at Virginia Power<P>

The EQB decision was not a big surprise since they had voiced their desire to stop the alternative siting process during last year's legislative session.  The Prairie Island Community has filed to overturn the EQB decision in Minnesota's Court of Appeals. The community contends that the EQB violated state law by not approving an alternative site.  They contend that the 1994 Prairie Island law mandates that a site be established and, since NSP failed to find one, the EQB should have denied the utility any additional dry cask storage capacity.  The community is also asking the Court to prevent NSP from filling the sixth cask until final rulings on the appeal are settled. <p>
In early August, NSP initiated a parallel approval process with the Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) for an alternative site.  Since the site requires State certification and approval, which has now been denied, the EQB requested that NSP ask the NRC suspend or terminate its review of the application.  NSP agreed and on November 13th, 1996, asked the NRC to suspend any actions on the application at least until the appeals court decision is released.  Seven parties have been given intervener status in the NRC process including:  EQB, Department of Public Service, Prairie Island Community, City of Red Wing, City of Lake City, Florence Township, and the combined Prairie Island Coalition/ Citizens United for Responsible Energy.<p>
NSP estimates that the siting process will cost about $9 million.  The figure includes NSP's reimbursement of about $140,000 spent by the EQB.  It does not include costs incurred by other parties.<P>
<I>Contact:  Bob Cupit, EQB, 612-296-2096</I>

<A NAME="iii"></A><H2>III. RENEWABLES/CONSERVATION UPDATE</H2>
<H3>Interactive Wind Exhibit Opens</H3>
The Science Museum of Minnesota has opened a new exhibit called Wind Power.  Interactive activity areas, photographic displays, and historic and modern wind turbines allow visitors to learn about the rich history of wind power in Minnesota. <P>
The exhibit explores technical aspects of wind power through an experiment that shows how energy output is affected by varying wind speed and turbine length, with results calculated by a computer.  Another area will give visitors a glimpse into how people around the world have been using wind to do useful work for them.  Wind Power is a permanent installation in the Science Museum's Our Minnesota Hall.<P>
<I>Contact:  Adele Binning, Science Museum of Minnesota, 
612-221-9488</I><P>

<H3>Competitive Building Initiative Launched in Twin Cities</H3>
ME3 coalition member Center for Energy and Environment (CEE) is the lead organization for a five-year project that will reduce energy consumption by 25 percent, lower maintenance costs, and improve comfort levels in commercial and multi-family buildings in the Twin Cities.  Five years of administrative and monitoring expenses totaling $700,000 for the Competitive Building Initiative (CBI) is supported through a grant from the U.S. Department of Energy's Rebuild America program.  CEE will coordinate the project that includes ten public and private business partners.<P>
CEE will work with building owners in Minneapolis and St. Paul to (1) identify buildings with energy savings potential; (2) analyze building energy systems; and (3) provide an unbiased source of information for processes, products and services to reduce energy consumption by 25 percent.  After initial audits have been completed, building owners will work with CEE to find ways to finance the identified improvements.  A variety of funding sources including performance contracting, low-interest utility financing, commercial lending, and public school bonding authority will be tapped to support the $5 million in energy-efficiency investments projected for the project.  <P>
CEE expects that 200-300 buildings will be initially screened with 20-30 being selected for full audits and retrofits.  Commercial properties will likely comprise about 80-90 percent of the buildings covered under the project.  The CBI project will emphasize follow-up monitoring, tracking the effectiveness of improvements to help illustrate the cost-effectiveness of energy efficiency.  CEE's project leader Richard Szydlowski predicts that the CBI program will provide a solid foundation for building owners to asses the economic benefits of energy efficiency and will lead to further investments in remaining building stock.<P>
<I>Contact:  Richard Szydlowski, CEE, 612-335-5862,</I> <A HREF="MAILTO:rszydlowski@mncee.org">rszydlowski@mncee.org</A><P>
<H3>Federal Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy Funding Preserved</H3>
In response to intense efforts by energy advocates and bipartisan leadership of the 100+ member House Renewable Energy Caucus, Congress rejected proposals to slash the Department of Energy's energy efficiency and renewable energy programs by up to 20 percent.  Instead Congress approved a $839.8 million budget for the two program areas (a 1.4 percent increase).  Both houses also dropped provisions that would have extended the moratorium on any new lighting or appliance efficiency standards.  Over the years efficiency standards have helped advance technologies that have saved consumers billions of dollars in energy costs. <P>
<I>Contact:  Ken Bossong, Sustainable Energy Coalition, 301-270-2258,</I> <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:kbossong@cais.com">kbossong@cais.com</A><BR>
<H3>NSP Solicits Suppliers for 50 MW of Biomass Power</H3>
Northern States Power Company (NSP) has asked the Public Utilities Commission for permission to forgo a competitive bidding process for acquiring the next 50 MW of mandated closed-loop biomass power.  The utility wants to begin simultaneous negotiations with the remaining bidders from the Biomass Phase I bidding process, St. Paul District Energy, and any other potential bidder. NSP selected the 75 MW proposal by the Minnesota Valley Alfalfa Producers in July 1996 as part of Biomass Phase I.  <P>
NSP argues that the selection should take place quickly than allowed for in an extended bid process in order for potential projects to take advantage of renewable energy production credits and/or any grants through the Department of Energy's Biomass for Rural Development program.  <P>
NSP proposes that interested bidders must submit a letter of intent to NSP on or before December 15, 1996.  The utility expects that the simultaneous negotiation process would take 60 to 90 days.<P>
<I>Contact:  Audrey Zibelman, NSP, 612-330-2868</I><P>
<H3>NSP Issues Phase III RFP for Next 100 MW of Wind</H3>
Northern States Power Company is seeking for a supplier(s) for up to 100 MW of additional wind energy capacity in Southwestern Minnesota.  The request for proposal (RFP) represents the latest increment of a minimum 425 MW of wind energy that NSP must acquire in accordance with the 1994 Prairie Island legislation.  In an apparent attempt at spreading the 100-MW project among different suppliers, NSP is requiring that all bids over 25 MW must also include bids for 25-MW increments.  <P>
Final bids for the project are due on January 20, 1997 with power plant operation scheduled for June 1999.<p>
<I>Contact:  Rick Hallet, NSP, 612-330-7780
</I><A NAME="iv"></A><H2>IV. INFORMATION RESOURCES</H2>
<B><A HREF="http://www.ilsr.org/carbo/costs/truecosttoc.html">Oil Slickers:  How Petroleum Benefits at the Taxpayer's Expense</A></B><BR>
This August 1996 report issued by the <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.ilsr.org/">Institute for Local Self-Reliance</A> (ILSR) by Dr. Jenny B. Wahl examined and quantified the hidden subsidies the petroleum industry receives including preferential tax treatment, costs of protecting foreign oil supplies, and environmental and health costs associated with using oil.  Conservatively, these hidden costs amount to about 32 cents per gallon of gasoline.<BR>
Contact:  John Bailey, ILSR, 612-379-3815; <A HREF="MAILTO:bailey@ilsr.org">bailey@ilsr.org</A><P>
<B>Economic Impact Analysis of Wind Power Development in Southwest Minnesota</B><BR>
This September 1996 report prepared by DanMar and Associates indicates that wind energy development will provide needed economic diversification in Southwest Minnesota.  The report also concludes that local ownership of projects substantially increases the economic value of wind power within the region.<BR>
Contact:  Southwest Regional Development Commission, 507-836-8547<P>
<B>Environmental Taxes: Implementation and Environmental Effectiveness</B><BR>
This August 1996 report from the <A HREF="http://www.eea.dk/">European Environment Agency</A> (EEA) examines the effectiveness of Europe's green tax strategies and focuses on political barriers and solutions to their implementation.  The report emphasizes the value of non-energy taxes and addresses the issues of competition, policy coordination, conditional exemptions, and border taxes.<BR>
