This September 1996 compilation of the 7th National BioEnergy conference contains over 1000 pages of information on the status of biomass energy in the United States and abroad. To get a copy of the proceedings send $35 (payable to TVA) to SERBEP, PO Box 1010, CEB 3A, Muscle Shoals, AL  35662-1010.<BR>
Contact:  Philip Badger, SERBEP, 205-386-3086, <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:pcbadger@tva.gov">pcbadger@tva.gov</A><P>
<B>Wind Farm Feasibility Study for the IAMU</B><BR>
This April 1996 report by Thomas A. Wind, P.E. provides an economic analysis of installing a 1.4-MW wind farm in northwestern Iowa.  Prepared for the Iowa Association of Municipal Utilities (IAMU), the study shows that a municipal utility-owned wind farm could generate electricity in Iowa for an average cost of 4.8 cents per kWh (less than 3.5 cents per kWh including federal renewable production incentives).  <BR>
Contact:  Bob Haug, IAMU, 515-289-1999<P>
<B>Economic Impact of the Ethanol Industry in Minnesota:  Present Situations and Future Opportunities</B><BR>
This August 1996 report from the MN Dept. of Agriculture provides an analysis of the financial effects of increasing Minnesota-based ethanol production from 80 million gallons per year in 1996 to 200 million gallons per year.  Moving to a 200-million-gallon production level would result in economic impacts of $403-$437 million per year.<BR>
Contact:  Su Ye, MN Dept. of Ag., 612-296-6384<P>
<B>Alternative Windpower Ownership Structures: Financing Terms and Project Costs  </B><BR>
This May 1996 report (LBNL-38921) (UC-1321) from Ryan Wiser and Edward Kahn of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory examines how financing and ownership structures affect the levelized cost of utility-scale wind power projects.  <BR>
Contact: Ryan Wiser,  510-486-5474, <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:rwiser@violet.berkeley.edu">rwiser@violet.berkeley.edu</A>
