<HR>
<H2>I. SPECIAL FEATURE:  ELECTRIC UTILITY RESTRUCTURING
</H2>
<H3>Electric Utility Restructuring: Does it Make "Cents" for Minnesotans?</H3>
<I>By David Morris, Institute for Local Self-Reliance</I><P>
In New Hampshire 16,000 business and residential customers are shopping for their electricity supplier just as they shop around for their long distance phone company.  For many observers, this is the future face of electri-city.  At the moment, some 30 states are considering the most dramatic restructuring of the electric system since the 1930s.<P>
What is behind this unprecedented development and what does it mean for Minnesota?<P>
Let's back up a minute.  For 60 years electric utilities lived within a very stable environment.  Demand doubled every ten years, like clockwork.  Electric rates declined.  Profits were guaranteed.  Utilities never missed a dividend payment. <P>
And then came the 1970s.<P>
Fuel prices rose.  Electric prices increased.  Electric demand increased very slowly.  The future became unpredictable.
In 1978, to spur more efficient power plants, the federal government abolished the monopoly that utilities held over power generation.  That law created a new industryÐindependent power producers.  By 1992 over half of all new power capacity added each year came from independent power producers.<P>
In the late 1980s, natural gas prices plummeted.  The electric industry was faced with a remarkable situation.  Whereas in 1980 a new power plant generated electricity at a much higher price than an existing power plant, in 1995 a new power plant generated electricity at a much lower price than many existing power plants.  <P>
The electricity wars began.  Independent power producers wanted the opportunity to compete directly against utilities by selling electricity directly to their customers rather than having to sell the electricity to the utilities themselves.  Large industrial customers around the country were already demanding and obtaining lower rates by threatening to move out of town or to install their own power plants.  Many utilities had set up subsidiaries during the 1980s to build power plants in other utilities' jurisdictions and were interested in expanding those sales.  And finally, customers in high-priced electricity regions like California and New York and Chicago and New England were angry and demanded lower prices.<P>
In 1992 the federal government enacted the Energy Policy Act, which permitted independent power producers to sell power into utility markets at the wholesale level.  Many states began to develop rules that will take the next step and allow producers to sell power at the retail level.  <P>
Minnesota's regulatory commission has initiated a formal investigation of restructuring.  The Legislative Electric Energy Task Force has recently received a consultant's report on the possible effects of restructuring and will use it as the basis for discussions for policy initiatives next session.  The outcome of the debate will affect every Minnesotan.<P>
Over the coming months ME3, through the newsletter, the Web pages, and in a series of reports, will address the issue of electricity restructuring.  Here are some key issues.<P>
<B><CENTER>Cost and Price of Electricity</CENTER></B><P>
Will restructuring lower prices?  Free market devotees accept this as an article of faith.  Yet the issue is complicated.  The price of power is already declining, in part because of lower fuel prices, in part because of lower power-plant capital costs, and in part because power plants are smaller and can come on-line more quickly.  Few would argue that new power plants will become cheaper to build because of deregulation.  <P>
For a low-cost electricity state like Minnesota it is questionable whether prices will decline much if at all.  For high-cost electricity regions prices may well decline eventually, but here we confront another key issue, the question of stranded costs.  <P>
<B><CENTER>Stranded Costs</CENTER></B><P>
Let's say a utility has a power plant that is generating electricity at 10 cents per kWh and it can now buy electricity at 5 cents per kWh.  It can close down the first power plant and buy electricity from the second one, but the utility will still have to pay off the costs of the first power plant.  Who will pay those costs?  Some argue that the utilities made the decision to build the plants and their shareholders must now assume the loss.  Utilities respond that the regulatory commissions, acting on behalf of the people of a state, had given them permission to build these plants and therefore their customers should pick up the tab.  If the customers were to pick up 100 percent of the tab, there may be few price reductions from restructuring, at least in the short run.  <P>
This issue of stranded costs is complicated by two further factors.  Some utilities have estimated stranded costs that are higher than their total utility system investment, which enrages regulators and citizen activists.  A second factor is that other utilities will have low-cost plants that will become more valuable by suddenly being able to send low-cost electricity into higher priced markets.  In this case a utility will incur a net benefit under restructuring.  There-fore any deregulation must be able to define and balance stranded costs carefully against stranded benefits.<P>
An excellent and timely new paper by Martha Hewett and Sheldon Strom of the Center for Energy and Environment, "Stranded Costs:  A 'Bigger Rip-off than the S&Ls'", is available from ME3.  The piece explores in great depth the issue of stranded costs (This report is available on the Sustainable MN web site at:  <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/projects/dereg/">http://www.me3.org/projects/dereg</A>).<P>
<CENTER><B>Resource Planning, Conservation, and Renewables</B></CENTER><P>
Environmentalists in the late 1970s were the first to argue that the regulatory system encouraged poor investment decisions.  Utilities received a guaranteed return on their investment in power plants and therefore tended to build expensive and sometimes unnecessary power plants.  In the 1980s and 1990s environmentalists made great strides in convincing regulatory commissions to take a more sophisticated approach.  Regulatory commissions began to deny construction permits for power plants they believed were unnecessary (Wisconsin did this for NSP's proposed Tyrone nuclear power complex, to the everlasting gratitude of Minnesotans and Wisconsinites alike).  Regulatory commissions began to require utilities to invest in conservation whenever it was cheaper than new power.  Regulatory commissions began to quantify the environmental cost of power plants and required utilities to take these costs into consideration when deciding what type of power plant to build or purchase electricity from.  And finally, legislatures and regulatory commissions heeded their citizens and began to require utilities to diversify and develop renewable electric technologies as an environmental, economic development, and energy-security strategy.<P>
By the early 1990s states like Minnesota had developed an integrated resource planning process that, although needing serious refinement, was far better than what existed in the past.  A restructured and deregulated system would, and already is, encouraging utilities to jettison conservation and renewables and environmental programs.  Parties are struggling with the role of planning if new source choices are purely price driven.<P>
<B><CENTER>Structure of a New Electric System</CENTER></B><P>
What would a restructured electric system look like?  Would the transmission lines be under separate ownership from the generation system?  Who, if anyone, would be responsible for guaranteeing electricity to the final customer?  Although proponents argue that the electric system is like the telephone system, it is not.  If a utility in Illinois sells you electricity, the electrons don't actually travel from Illinois to you.  They come from the nearest power plant to you that has available electricity.  The best analogy would be to think of a restructured electricity system like a large lake.  Independent pumpers would pump water into the lake and individual customers would take water out of the lake.  Right now the incredibly complicated electric system is managed by utilities and regional power pools.  Who will manage the even more complicated system of the future? <P>
The electric restructuring debate is in high gear in the high-cost electricity regions of the country.  Minnesota is a low-cost electric state which has made great strides in managing its electricity system in recent years.  Does Minnesota need to rush into deregulation?  Some, like the consultants who submitted the recent report to the Legislative Electric Energy Task Force, argue that restructuring is inevitable and no state can maintain the old system after other states restructure.  Others believe Minnesota can be its own boss, that we control our own destiny.  What do you think?<P>

<H3>Minnesota's Utility Restructuring:  Timeline
</H3>
The Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (PUC) formally initiated an Investigation into Structural and Regulatory Issues in the Electric Utility Industry (Docket No. E-999/CI-95-135) in 1995 and issued a guiding set of principles and action steps in May 1996.<P>  
The working group's subcommittees are currently working on a variety of issues including; wholesale competition, flexible rates, public participation, and service quality.  Reports on each of these topics are expected to be issued incrementally between September and November.  Discussions of the issues related to retail electric competition will likely begin in September. The PUC views the working group and associated tasks as a way to promote a dialogue between interested parties and narrow the issues before the expected onslaught of legislative proposals during the 1997 legislative session.<P>

Materials related to this proceeding are available electronically at the Sustainable Minnesota web site at the following address:<BR>
<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/projects/dereg/">http://www.me3.org/projects/dereg</A>

<H2>II.  REGULATORY UPDATE</H2>
<H3>Nuclear Waste:  Coming to a Backyard Near You?</H3>
In June 1996, the Minnesota Dept. of Public Service (DPS) issued a Report of Investigation and Recommendations Regarding Payments by Ratepayers of NSP to the Nuclear Waste Fund to the Public Utilities Commission (PUC Docket No.  E002/DI-95-1137).  DPS Commissioner Kris Sanda, a longtime critic of how the federal government is handling the creation of a national nuclear waste repository, wants to divert any
further payments by NSP to the federal Nuclear Waste Fund (NWF) into a state-based dedicated fund to finance a solution to NSP's disposal problems.  By 2003, NSP ratepayers will have contributed about $250 million into the NWF.  Iowa is also considering a similar plan for their contributions to the NWF.<P>


Some believe that Commissioner Sanda's proposal is simply a tactic to put pressure on the federal government.  Others believe that she wants to use the diverted funds to finance a permanent waste site in Minnesota.  Comments on the DPS report were submitted on July 31 and reply comments will be accepted until August 21, 1996.<P>


Meanwhile, the Minnesota Environmental Quality Board (EQB) issued a report titled Staff Report to the EQB on the Siting of a Dry Cask Storage Facility in Goodhue County.  The 1994 Prairie Island legislation required NSP to find an alternative storage site within Goodhue County for Prairie Island's spent fuel.  The alternative siting process has proved to be very controversial throughout Goodhue County.  One township threatened to secede from the county.  A site advisory task force concluded, "that neither the [two] sites proposed by NSP nor any of the 16 properties proposed as alternates sites by concerned citizens was feasible and prudent and should be subject to further consideration by the EQB".  The EQB staff report identifies 4 options for consideration: <P>

<UL> 
<LI>Move ahead with the
	current siting process focusing only on sites in Goodhue County
<LI>Formally suspend the siting process and wait for the legislature to deal with the issue next session
<LI>Formally terminate the siting process
<LI>Broaden the scope of the site search to areas outside of Goodhue County</UL><p>
Comments on the EQB report are due by August 23, 1996.  This proceeding is a unique opportunity for Minnesotans to engage the very hard questions related to the storage of nuclear waste.  In the 1980s, the federal government was considering Minnesota as a possible home for a national nuclear waste repository.  Nevada, which has no nuclear reactors of its own, was chosen instead.  Now it appears that a permanent waste repository in Nevada may never be built. Is it time to begin talking about a permanent storage facility in Minnesota, this time to take responsibility for our own nuclear wastes?<P>


<I>Contact:  David Jacobson, PUC, 612-297-4562; Andrea Glass, EQB, 612-297-1257</I><P>


<B>Note</B>:  At press time several news stories appeared and discussions took place concerning the Federal government's responsibility for the nations nuclear-waste stockpile.  Check Sustainable Minnesota's "<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/whatsnew.html">What's New</A>" section on the web for continuing updates on this issue.  (http://www.me3.org/whatsnew.html)

<H3>Primergy Stumbles</H3><P>
The massive utility merger proposed to combine Northern States Power Company (NSP) and Wisconsin Energy Corporation (WEC) into the energy giant, Primergy, has felt the reins of regulation tighten recently.  <P>
The merger has been slowed in Wisconsin and at the Federal level.  Wisconsin regulators and staff at the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) are reported to be critical of the merger.  Primary concern is that Primergy will have unfair market power in the Midwest.  The merger partners have proposed a plan that would involve an independent system operator (ISO), an independent entity responsible for making electric power deals between Primergy and other power marketers and consumers.  According to the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel,  FERC staff believe the ISO will not be independent enough and FERC may require WEC to sell some of its generating or transmission capacity.<P>
The Wisconsin commission has announced that they will be preparing an environmental assessment of the merger in response to a motion by environmental intervenors, including ME3.<P>
The proposed merger received swift approval from shareholders and the go-ahead from regulators in North Dakota and Michigan, two of four state regulatory commissions that must approve the marriage.  In Minnesota, NSP and DPS are urging the PUC and the administrative law judge to fast track the merger for a decision before the end of the year.<P>
ME3 is concerned that the merger, as it is currently proposed, represents a serious threat to competition in the region.  In addition, the merger will allow NSP to have better access to higher priced electricity markets like those in Chicago.  This will probably result in the increased use of idled coal-fired capacity in Minnesota according to ME3's Kevin Bengtson.  He has prepared an analysis of the likelihood of increased pollution in the metropolitan area resulting from the merger (see Information Resources).<P>

<H2>III.  RENEWABLES AND CONSERVATION UPDATE</H2>
<H3>NAE Proposes 11.25 MW Minnesota Wind Farm</H3><P>
Minnesota wind developers, Northern Alternative Energy (NAE) and Micon Wind Turbines (US) Inc., have applied for permission to build a 11.25 MW wind project in southwestern Minnesota.  The project would use 15 Micon turbines on land acquired by NAE and Northern States Power (NSP).  Hutchinson Manufacturing, Inc.  of Hutchinson, MN, will manufacture some components and will be the site for final assembly of Micon's 750-kW turbines. <P>
The relatively small size of the project (<12 MW) allows NAE to avoid costly regulatory hurdles involved in the Certificate of Need process and eliminates any need of a competitive bidding process.  NAE has been involved in ongoing negotiations with Northern States Power Company and expects to sell the utility about 30 million-kWhs per year.  The 30-year power-purchase agreement is similar to the last wind power contract given to Zond Systems, Inc.; reportedly around 3.5 cents per kWh.  The NAE project would also qualify for the 1.6 cents per kWh federal renewable energy production credit.  If approved, site preparations will begin by the end of September.  Ideally, turbine installation could start as early as January and be fully on-line by February 1997.  <P>
NAE president, Greg Jaunich notes that NAE will be pursuing more of these "small, cluster-like" developments in southwestern Minnesota.  He has been pleased with the negotiating process with NSP and is happy that the utility is interested in looking at smaller-scale installations.  The project will count towards NSP's mandate to acquire 425-MW of wind energy by 2003.<P>
The Environmental Quality Board (EQB) has issued a Draft Site Permit and is looking for comments from interested persons by September 4, 1996.<P>
<I>Contact:  Larry Hartman, EQB, 1-800-657-3794, <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:arry.hartman@mnplan.state.mn.us">larry.hartman@mnplan.state.mn.us</A>;  Greg Jaunich, NAE, 612-341-1061</I><p>

<H3>NSP Awards Biomass Bid to 75-MW Alfalfa Project</H3>
On July 12, Northern States Power Company (NSP) selected the Minnesota Valley Alfalfa Producers (MnVAP), located in Granite Falls, MN, to supply 75-MW of "farm-grown, closed-loop biomass" electricity by December 31, 2000.<P>


This 75-MW Minnesota Agri-Power Project will fulfill part of the legislative mandate requiring NSP to have 125-MW of  biomass generation in place by the end of 2002.  MnVAP plans to eventually use advanced gasification technology to generate fuel gas from alfalfa stems (a byproduct of a planned animal-feed production facility).  NSP notes that, once the power plant is operating, it will be the first dedicated crop-fuel plant of its size in the world.<P>


In related news, MnVAP announced on July 10 that it had received a $4.1 million grant from the Dept. of Energy for the design phase of the project.  Most will go toward power-plant design.  One-fourth of the award will go towards alfalfa research and product development at the University of Minnesota, the Minnesota Department of Agriculture, and the Agricultural Utilization Research Institute (AURI).  MnVAP is seeking up to $40 million from DOE during the construction phase of the project.<P>


NSP chose MnVAP following a simultaneous negotiation process with three finalists ordered by the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission.  The PUC must still approve NSP's selection and the two parties must negotiate a power purchase agreement.<P>


<I>Contact:  Ken Campbell, MnVAP, 612-564-2400; Rick Peterson, NSP, 612-330-5831</I>

<H3>Kenetech Settles Wind Easement Dispute With NSP</H3>
NSP announced on June 28th that it had successfully negotiated the transfer of wind easements owned by Kenetech Windpower Inc. (KWI).  NSP and KWI had been involved in a protracted court battle over the wind easements, a dispute that delayed NSP's contract award to Zond Systems for the next 100 MW of wind development in Minnesota.  Kenetech has dropped all legal and regulatory disputes against NSP.  Landowners in the area are reported to be pleased with the settlement and are anxious to have turbines begin operating above their land.<P>


The turn of events was not unexpected.  On May 29, 1996, KWI of San Francisco, CA, filed a petition under chapter 11 for bankruptcy protection.  Problems with turbines, lack of demand, and plummeting stock values are blamed for the company's demise.  KWI was in no position to sustain any legal battles.<P>


Zond's 143-turbine project will now be able to proceed as originally planned on land acquired by NSP and approved by the Environmental Quality Board.  Due to the delay caused by the lawsuits, Zond will likely bring the plant on-line by 1998.<P>



<H3>Elk River to Become a Sustainable City Energy Showcase</H3>
The city of Elk River, MN, has been selected to become a Sustainable City Energy Showcase by the Minnesota Environmental Initiative's Energy Alley program.  The five-year project will by administered by Energy Alley staff, city officials, and energy efficiency and renewable energy business partners; each contributing personnel and financial resources to cover the estimated $200,000 annual administrative costs.<P>


The first phase of the program will be an energy use inventory of the city.  The inventory should be completed in six months.  Depending on the results of the inventory, up to $10 million could be invested in improvements according to Energy Alley spokesperson Joel Burns.  Improvements will generate up to 25% energy savings for the city.<BR>

<I>Contact:  Joel Burns, MEI, 612-334-3388</I>

<H3>DPS Seeks Comments on Minnesota Energy Policy Report</H3> 
The Minnesota Department of Public Service (DPS) has recently issued a Draft version of the 1996 Energy Policy and Conservation Report, a quadrennial report to the Minnesota Legislature on the Department's policy goals and strategies.  The DPS is looking for input on the Draft report and will seek public comments early this fall.  Deadline for written comments is September 20, 1996.<BR>

<I>Contact:  Susan Kosowski, DPS, 612-297-1769</I>


<H3>Green Pricing:  A Solution to Advance Renewable Energy?</H3>
Green pricing is the term used when electric utilities invite their customers to pay higher prices in return for the utility buying more power from renewable resources.  Green pricing comes in various forms.  Sometimes the customer pays a premium that covers only a portion of the total cost of the renewable energy system.  This is the case, for example, with the photovoltaic (PV) program at the Sacramento Municipal Utility District (SMUD) that involves installing residential rooftop systems.  A similar program is being implemented in Minnesota that will, by the end of the summer, involve 17 customers of Northern States Power.  Participants in NSP's Solar Advantage PV program will pay an additional $50 per month for 2-kW rooftop systems, about a third of the actual cost of the PV installation.  Participants can buy the system for $1 after 10 years.  Ratepayers cover the other two thirds of the cost.<P>


Sometimes green pricing programs cover the full cost of renewable electricity.  At Public Service Company of Colorado, ratepayers can contribute to a renewable energy fund that is used to finance small PV projects around the state.  In Colorado, 14,000 ratepayers contributed about $160,000.  A couple of hundred customers of Traverse City Light and Power, a Michigan municipal utility, are paying 20 percent more for electricity from the utility's 600-kW wind turbine which began producing electricity in May.<P>


Green pricing programs are controversial.  Some argue that since they are invariably very small, they distract attention from large-scale renewable energy projects that can really accelerate technological change.  Others argue that green pricing efforts are a grassroots effort that can let a thousand technological flowers bloom in many parts of the country.<P>


Some environmentalists worry that utilities may soon be introducing green pricing programs that aren't even green.  Wisconsin Electric Power Company (WEPCO) was recently given approval to offer customers the option of paying a premium "green rate" for renewable power.  The power will be generated from existing Canadian and Minnesota hydro resources and from a waste-wood-fueled power plant owned by Minnesota Power that has been idled in recent years.  As Renew Wisconsin and Wisconsin Environmental Decade ask of Wisconsin's regulatory commission, does waste wood and large- scale hydroelectricity from out of state really constitute "green"
sustainable power?  Don't consumers deserve assurance that they are indeed getting the ÒgreenÓ power that they paid for?<P>


<H2>IV.  INFORMATION RESOURCES</H2>
<B>Coal Plants in the Neighborhood:  Stopping Increased Air Pollution from the NSP Merger</B><BR>

This July 1996 report by ME3's Kevin P. Bengtson argues that, if it is approved, the proposed merger of NSP and Wisconsin Energy Corporation will inevitably result in increased pollution from coal plants in the Twin Cities metropolitan area.  In addition, the report suggests simple mitigation strategies that could be ordered by the PUC or the state legislature as a condition for merger approval.<BR>

<I>Contact:  Kevin Bengtson, ME3, 612-225-1133; <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/issues/merger/">http://www.me3.org/issues/merger</A></I><P>


<B>Evaluation of the Current Energy System In Minnesota</B><BR>
<B>Evaluation of Emerging Generation Technologies in Minnesota</B><BR>
Both of these reports were prepared by Appel Consultants for the Minnesota Legislative Electric Energy Task Force (LEETF).  The first report examines policy options for improve the electric system in Minnesota.  The second report examines the potential for sustainable electric production in Minnesota.
<I>Contact:  LEETF, 612-297-3697</I><P>

<B>Accounting for Climate Change and Mercury Pollution:  Problems Before the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission</B><BR>

This August 1996 report from ME3 member, Jeremy Schreifels summarizes the key issues in the Environmental Externalities Docket before the Minnesota PUC.<BR>

<I>Contact:  J. Hamilton, ME3, 612-225-1177, <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:hamilton@me3.org">hamilton@me3.org</A>, 
<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/projects/costs/">http://www.me3.org/projects/costs</A></I><P>

<B>Opportunities to Expand Cogeneration in Minnesota</B>
This June 1996 Draft report from the Center for Energy and Environment (CEE) looks into the history, characteristics, and existing markets for cogeneration, the production of heat and electricity through the same process, in Minnesota.  The in-depth report provides an economic analysis of cogeneration and identifies barriers to the increased use of cogeneration in the state.
Contact: Martha Hewett, CEE, 612-348-4835<P>


<B>Power for the People</B><BR>

This June 1996 report from Public Citizen's Critical Mass Energy Project outlines a set of policies designed to protect consumers and provide economic and environmental benefits in a more competitive electric industry.<BR>

<I>Contact:  Public Citizen, 202-833-3000; <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.essential.org/CMEP/">http://www.essential.org/CMEP</A></I><P>


<B>How The West Can Win:  A Blueprint for a Clean & Affordable Energy Future</B><BR>

This March 1996 report from the Land and Water Fund of the Rockies' Energy Project (LAW Fund) provides an analysis of how a six state region can economically and sustainably meet a projected 15,000 MW demand for new electric capacity over the next 20 years.<BR>

<I>Contact: LAW Fund, 303-444-1188</I><P>


<B>Is There a Future for Electric Industry IRP?</B><BR>

This May 1996 report by Eric Hirst (Oak Ridge National Lab) provides an historical look at Integrated Resource Planning (IRP) in the electric industry and offers some predictions on what form IRP will take in the future.  Hirst predicts a significant decline or disappearance of IRP in the deregulated system that many states are on the path to create.<BR>

<I>Contact:  Ethyl Schorn, ORNL, 615-576-8745 (fax), <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:schornem@ornl.gov">schornem@ornl.gov</A></I><P>




<H2>V.  MISCELLANEOUS</H2>
<H3>The More Things Change...</H3> 

At the beginning of this century, in order to encourage customers to buy more electricity,  utilities gave away light bulbs and electric appliances.   In the 1980s environmentalists taught regulators and utilities that energy efficiency made more sense and that if utilities were going to give anything away, it should be insulation and very high efficiency light bulbs.  In 1996 Centerior Energy's Cleveland Electric subsidiary has returned to the days of yesteryear by instituting a frequent kilowatt hour program, a  bonus programÐlike a frequent flyer programÐto give customers an incentive to consume more electricity.  Points are awarded for each kWh consumed, with bonus points awarded for actions such as purchasing a portable electric heater (3,000 bonus points) and replacing a gas hot water heater with an electric on (10,000 bonus points).  The more electric appliances the consumer buys, the more points they earn.  Earn enough points and you can get an electric sauna!  Go Cleveland.

