<HTML> <HEAD><TITLE>Sustainable Minnesota Newsletter-Winter 1997</TITLE></HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=475 HEIGHT=112 ALT="Sustainable MN Masthead" SRC="masthead.GIF"><BR>Winter 1997  -  Volume 7, Number 1<H2>TABLE OF CONTENTS</H2><B>I. Global Climate Change and Minnesota</B><!-- List Tag --><UL><LI>Global Climate Change Puts Minnesota at Ground Zero</UL><B>II.  Legislative Update</B><!-- List Tag --><UL><LI>Economic Efficiency and Pollution Reduction Act (EEPRA) of 1997<LI>Minnesota Electric Deregulation<LI>Alternative Siting of Nuclear Waste<LI>Public Utility Mergers<LI>Taxation of Utility Property<LI>Wind Energy Property Taxation<LI>Livable Communities Legislation<LI>Gas Tax Increase for Transit</UL><B>III.  REGULATORY UPDATE</B><!-- List Tag --><UL><LI>Protecting Efficiency and Renewables in a Deregulated  Electricity Market<LI>Administrative Meltdown For Primergy<LI>Federal Electric Restructuring Bills Introduced</UL><B>IV. RENEWABLES/ENERGY CONSERVATION UPDATE</B><!-- List Tag --><UL><LI>Windustry Workshop An Outstanding Success<LI>MN Coops Announce Green Pricing Program<LI>FERC Rules on Iowa Renewable Energy Mandate<LI>Enron Adds Minnesota Wind Energy To Portfolio<LI>Money Available for Energy Assistance in Minnesota<LI>Minnesota Wind-Project Contracts Nearing Completion<LI>Minnesota's Ethanol Industry Scrutinized</UL><B>V. INFORMATION RESOURCES</B><!-- List Tag --><UL><LI>Study of Minnesota Taxes Paid by Electric Utilities and the Implications of Utility Tax Assessments<LI>Analysis of Utility Taxation in Minnesota<LI>The Changing Structure of the Electric Power Industry:  An Update<LI>Providing Customer Financing Through Utility Energy Efficiency Programs<LI>NREL's Information Resources Catalogue, 1996<LI>Electricity:  The Road Toward Restructuring</UL><B>VI.  MISCELLANEOUS</B><P><UL><LI>Become an ME3 Electronic Activist</UL><HR><H2>I. Global Climate Change and Minnesota </H2><BLOCKQUOTE>"We must also protect our global environment, working...to reduce the greenhouse gases that challenge our health even as they change our climate." <BR><B>President Bill Clinton, February 4, 1997</B></BLOCKQUOTE><P><H3>Global Climate Change Puts Minnesota at Ground Zero</H3> Some Minnesotans might think global warming would be a boon to Minnesota because of our cold climate.  However, recent evidence shows that Minnesota's environment may be more seriously and adversely affected by modest changes in the climate than other parts of the country.  For some leading scientists, Minnesota is ground zero with respect to global climate change.  This was one of the major themes of last December's Twin Cities Conference on Global Climate Change.  <P>Professor Stephen Schneider, Stanford University and internationally recognized expert on climate said that, "Minnesota is at the ecological cross hairs of climate change."  As one of 2500 scientist on the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), he concludes that Minnesota is particularly vulnerable to changes in climate because of our geographical position at the intersection of Canada's boreal forests, the great plains and eastern Minnesota's hardwood forests.<P>While the climate is expected to warm gradually, changes in it can be abrupt.  Keynote speaker John Firor emphasized that any system as non-linear and chaotic as the climate can produce sudden changes in nature when experiencing gradually increasing stress.<P>About a month after the conference, the MN Pollution Control Agency (PCA) released a legislative update on their Global Climate Change Initiative.  The PCA used physical  models to predict how wetlands, forest, fisheries, and peatlands will respond to climate change.  The news is not good.  Among the findings:  the boreal forest typical of the Boundary Waters will retreat into Canada, cold water fish such as pike and trout will decline, prairie pothole wetlands in the western half of Minnesota will decline, and some species will become extinct in the state as habitats change.  The PCA will be monitoring national and international developments to prepare for the most appropriate and cost-effective actions to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.<P>Contact:  Peter Ciborowski, PCA, 612-297-5822<H2>II. Legislative Update </H2><!-- Font Tag --><B><FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT></B>he Minnesota Legislature has convened and will continue until late May.  Below are descriptions of some of the major energy-related initiatives already introduced or likely during the 1997 session.  ME3 will be tracking these and other initiatives on the web via the <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/leg/legwatch97.html">1997 Legislative Watch</A> <P><H4>Economic Efficiency and Pollution Reduction Act (EEPRA) of 1997</H4>This bill contains provisions for a $1.5 billion tax shift at the state level.  Similar to legislation introduced in 1996, a $50 carbon tax on fossil fuels would be imposed, raising $1.5 billion.  The tax increase would be offset by $1.5 billion decrease in other taxes.  For the residential sector the tax reductions would represent about $370 per household.  The business sector would receive a 22-percent reduction in the employer portion of payments to FICA (social security and medicare).<P>The proposal contains partial and conditional tax exemptions for energy-intensive industries.<P><H4>Minnesota Electric Deregulation</H4>Governor Carlson and legislative leaders of both parties have stated that no legislative initiatives to deregulate the electric industry will be considered in 1997.  Legislators will spend this session studying the issue in detail.  The Public Utilities Commission's Competition Working Groups and the Legislative Electric Energy Task Force will provide reports to the Legislature.<P><B>Note:</B>  On the federal level, several major industry-restructuring bills have been introduced that could have profound impacts on Minnesota.  The federal efforts could leave many details up to state policymakers, but may interfere with efforts to ensure the prominent role of renewable energy and energy conservation in a deregulated market.<P><H4>Alternative Siting of Nuclear Waste</H4>Bills have been introduced in both the Senate and House (S.F.  48, H.F. 153) that would eliminate a law requiring NSP to build an alternative storage site for nuclear waste being stored at Prairie Island.  The bill gives NSP permission to fill five more casks as part of the utility fulfilling a requirement to try and find an alternative storage site in Goodhue County.  By satisfying mandates for renewable energy, NSP may fill up to 17 casks on Prairie Island.  <P><H4>Public Utility Mergers</H4>Legislation has been proposed (S.F. 83, H.F. 295) that provides criteria that must be satisfied before any public utility merger is approved by the Public Utilities Commission (PUC).  Among the requirements are the merger must:  1) provide net benefits to all classes of ratepayers; 2) foster increased competition; 3) maintain or improve environmental protection, renewable energy, energy conservation, and integrated resource planning.  The bill also contains a provision putting the "burden of proof" on the utilities that are merging for demonstrating that these requirements have been satisfied.  If passed, the bill would apply to pending and future merger proposals.<P><H4>Taxation of Utility Property</H4>Property tax reform is one of the top legislative issues for 1997.  Included in the discussions may be the taxes on utilities' personal property, although many legislators prefer to leave this issue until deregulation is concerned.  The debate will center on the issues of fairness and competition.  Investor-owned utilities, unlike other businesses in the state, are assessed property taxes on both real and personal property.  <P><H4>Wind Energy Property Taxation</H4>A bill has been introduced (S.F. 181) that requires any utility that purchases wind electricity installed from June 1, 1991 to  December 31, 2002 to pay the property taxes assessed on the facilities.  The utility can recover the property taxes through rates.The bill modifies the property tax rates on wind energy.  Smaller-scale wind projects (< 2 MW) would remain tax-exempt.  Wind farms larger than 12 MW would be taxed at a much higher rate than under the current law.<P><H4>Livable Communities Legislation</H4>A bill has been introduced  (H.F. 217) that would address the issue of urban sprawl by limiting growth in metropolitan areas.  The legislation would require that full social, environmental and other external costs be paid up-front before increased development could take place in certain areas.<P><H4>Gas Tax Increase for Transit</H4>Many bills have been introduced that would raise the state tax on gasoline.  Most bills include a provision to amend the Minnesota Constitution to allow revenue from the tax increase to be used for mass transit.  Currently, the Minnesota Constitution directs any gas tax revenues to be used exclusively for building and maintaining roads.<P><H2>III. Regulatory Update </H2><H3>Protecting Efficiency and Renewables in a Deregulated  Electricity Market</H3>Over the last 20 years Minnesota and many other states have included in their utility regulatory processes provisions for energy efficiency and renewable energies.  These provisions slightly increase the short-term price of electricity although many experts argue that in the long term they are beneficial to the state economy because they avoid the need for new power plants, shift electricity generation to in-state renewable resources and reduce the costs from pollutants generated from electric power.  <P>Now a number of states are allowing electric customers to buy retail electricity from any power marketer.  In this deregulated environment the short-term price becomes paramount.  If in-state utilities or power producers are required to pay for the costs of energy efficiency or renewable energy then the price of their electricity may become uncompetitive in an increasingly national electric marketplace.  Already, as competition looms, utilities are slashing energy efficiency programs.  The $64,000 question is how to protect and sustain investments in improving energy efficiency and renewable energy in a deregulated system.<P>Fortunately, in most of the discussions of deregulation going on at the Federal level and in at least 40 states, this issue is on the table.  The  Renewable Portfolio Standard (RPS) and the System Benefits Charge (SBC) are two strategies for achieving environmental and social goals while still moving toward deregulation.  This article explains both concepts.  <P><B>Renewable Portfolio Standard (RPS)</B><BR>The RPS is simple.  In order to be permitted to sell power directly to end-consumers a power marketer must have a certain percentage of renewable energy in its mix.  To allow for some flexibility, a company without renewable capacity is allowed to purchase renewable energy credits from a generator with excess renewable capacity. <P>Sustainable energy activists involved in the deregulation debate at the Federal level have supported a national "portfolio standard".  Currently support is behind proposals that include minimum requirements that renewables (other than hydropower) make up at least 2.5 percent of all generation by 2000, 5 percent by 2005, and 10 percent by 2010.  In Minnesota, up to 950-MW of renewables is required by the Prairie Island legislation of 1994.  This would give Minnesota a head start in satisfying the minimum federal requirements.<P>Nationwide, the standards outlined above would increase renewable capacity dramatically since renewables (non-hydro) currently only make up about two percent of the total.  However, Minnesotans should be concerned about the adoption of a federal standard.  If left to federal government the portfolio standard may stall efforts to move renewables forward even further in Minnesota.  The Federal standard can provide a framework for states to work in but it also brings in the spectre of preemption.  Any examination of federal policy should address the question: Could Minnesota's commitment to a more robust renewable economy be undermined?<P><B>System Benefits Charge</B><BR>The SBC is a fee, either a percentage charge or a fixed rate per kWh, on electricity use.  All providers would have to pay the charge.  Sometimes this is called a "wire charge".  The money would be used to support key public policies such as energy-efficiency improvements, low-income energy services, and/or renewable-energy projects.  <P>SBCs generate controversy.  One controversy is over who controls the money and how it is spent.  Some energy activists want money from a SBC to be diverted into an independently-administered account out of the reach of utilities.  Often referring to the excessive administrative costs of many utility-sponsored conservation programs, activists want the money in the hands of people who are truly committed to aggressive energy conservation efforts.  Others feel that another level of public oversight is not the answer and power marketers should control the money with verifiable savings goals.<P>The SBCs that have been recommended, at best, will provide funding at current utility investment levels.  The difference is that the SBCs are often temporary by design.  They become "transition" fees until stranded costs can be paid off and the market can work on its own.  <P>Another problem develops because instead of the charge being embedded in a utility rate structure, the fee is a line item on the electric bill and will be viewed as a tax.  This leaves it more vulnerable for possible repeal.<P>A final concern is that a fixed charge per kWh will decrease in value over time if it is not adjusted for inflation.  A charge based on percentage rate would drop in real terms if electricity rates drop.<P><H3>Administrative Meltdown For Primergy</H3><B>Wisconsin -</B> On January 21, a Dane County judge put an abrupt halt to any action on the Primergy merger proposal being considered by the Wisconsin Public Service Commission (PSC) by issuing an injunction.  By court order the PSC must now complete an investigation of alleged improper conversations between PSC Commissioner Dan Eastman and Wisconsin Energy Corp. (WEC) executives.  A sworn statement presented to the court by former PSC commissioner Scott Neitzel alleges that Eastman was eager to approve the merger and told Governor Thompson's Chief of Staff that he wanted to "profit" from the decision. <P><B>Minnesota -</B> Similar setbacks have continued in Minnesota.  Concluding an openly hostile meeting on January 21, the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (PUC) reversed a prior decision that had prevented two commissioners from voting on the Primergy merger because of ex parte communications with NSP officials.  As a justification for the reversal, the Commission members cited their belief that that a motion requesting reconsideration was filed late.  The PUC's attorneys repeatedly advised that the timeliness of the motion should not be the basis for reversal.  Commissioner Don Storm strongly dissented from the majority action.<P>NSP and WEC are seeking approval to merge into Primergy and become the nation's 10th largest utility.<P>The issue of ex parte communications has proved to be unsolvable for the Commission. Originally the PUC found that, although the conversations took place, they were not "substantive".  On the motion of departing Commissioner Dee Knaak, the PUC did a 180 degree turn and decided that laws were indeed broken and two of five commissioners would be recused from ruling on the merger.  The recent ruling brings the PUC full circle.<P>After Commissioner Dee Knaak resigned, the PUC was left with only two people to rule on the $6 billion merger.  Governor Carlson replaced Knaak with the head of the Office of Environmental Assistance, Ed Garvey.  <P><B>More News -</B> Rulings by two Administrative Law Judges on the Primergy merger case in Minnesota have been issued.  Judge Klein ruled that the Independent System Operator being negotiated and other factors would protect the public interest and be enough to negate any concerns of Primergy having too much market control. <P>Judge Giles looked at economic savings issues.  He notes, "...the determination of the cost savings due to the merger requires considerable exercise of judgment."  He goes on to agree that savings proposed by NSP are valid even though the MN's Department of Public Service concluded that savings from the merger would be about half of what NSP has proposed.<P>Primergy on the Web: <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/issues/merger/">http://www.me3.org/issues/merger</A><H3>Federal Electric Restructuring Bills Introduced</H3>The deregulation debate is raging on Capitol Hill this year with bills introduced or expected from Senator Dale Bumpers (D-Ark), Representative Dan Schaefer (R-Colo.), Senator Frank Murkowski (R- Alaska), and a proposal  from the U.S. Department of Energy. <P>Early versions of the DOE-sponsored bill would let states decide whether to allow customers to pick their power supplier or require utilities to compete for power on the wholesale market.  DOE may also recommend a  national fund for state energy conservation.<P>Senator Bumpers bill was introduced on January 30, and will require full retail competition by the year 2003.  His bill includes provisions for a "wire service charge" that will be used to pay for utilities' stranded costs.<P>Schaefer's bill, introduced February 10, is similar to the Bumpers proposal in that it mandates deregulation but the deadline for full competition is the year 2000.<P>Stay on top of the latest deregulation developments on the web at <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/projects/dereg/">http://www.me3.org/projects/dereg</A><H2>IV. Renewables/Energy Conservation Update </H2><H3>Windustry Workshop An Outstanding Success</H3>About 4 dozen people attended the four-day "Windustry" workshop hosted by the Minneapolis-based Sustainable Resources Center (SRC), a partner along with ME3, Clean Water Fund, and Minnesota Project in the Sustainable Energy for Economic Development (SEED) project.  Local and internationally-recognized wind energy experts provided participants with the information they need to become local wind resource people and enable them to help make wind energy a reality in their communities.<P>SRC developed the training session to fill a "knowledge gap" that was hindering increased wind development.  Lisa Daniels of SRC noted, "farmers and landowners in Minnesota's windy areas want wind power but have a lot of questions.  The workshop and the Windustry curriculum will train people to become a wind energy resource for their communities."  She added that the participants can now go home and begin to make their local wind projects work.  The final version of the Windustry program will be available later this spring.  <P>Contact:  <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:srclisad@mtn.org">Lisa Daniels</A>, SRC, 612-872-3280, srclisad@mtn.org<H3>MN Coops Announce Green Pricing Program</H3>Wholesale power marketer Cooperative Power Association (CPA), and one of its customers, Dakota Electric Association want to offer their customers the option to buy renewable energy beginning April 1997.   Dakota Electric filed a petition with the Public Utilities Commission (PUC) which must approve  the rate structure for the program.  Dakota Electric is the only cooperatively-owned utility in Minnesota whose board voted to be regulated by the PUC.<P>CPA's participating cooperatives would charge their customers more for "green power".  Initial estimates by CPA, show that customers will pay an additional 2 - 3 cents per kWh.  Dakota Electric's residential customers currently pay 7.15 cents per kWh and commercial customers pay about 4.85 cents.  The renewable energy option will be available to residential, commercial or industrial customers.  Participants will be able to subscribe to 100 kWh blocks of green energy up to their average monthly usage for at least 12 months of service.<P>CPA supplies wholesale power to 17 electric distribution cooperatives in west central and southern Minnesota.  In addition to Dakota Electric, seven other cooperatives have expressed interest in providing their customers with the renewable energy option.<P>CPA is currently evaluating bids to deliver between 1 and 3 MW of renewable-fueled electric capacity.  The actual amount of renewable power will ultimately depend on how many people sign on to the program.  And the increased cost per kWh to participants will depend on the outcome of the competitive bidding process.<P>Contact:  Tim Seck, CPA, 612-949-8264<P><H3>FERC Rules on Iowa Renewable Energy Mandate</H3>On January 29, 1997, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) issued an order (Docket No. EL95-51-000) concluding that an Iowa Utilities Board (IUB) directive ordering renewables to be purchased from qualifying facilities (QFs) at a certain price is preempted by Federal law.  The FERC ruling stems from a complaint filed by Midwest Power (now MidAmerican Energy Company).  FERC notes that Iowa's state law requiring utilities to purchase a certain amount of alternative energy is "consistent with federal law".  Midwest Power argued that it was required to purchase up to 30.4 MW of renewable energy capacity and pay 6 cents per kWh for electricity when their avoided cost was only 1.5 cents per kWh.  Iowa requires utilities statewide to acquire about 105 MW of renewables.  Minnesota's renewable energy mandates do not contain language on pricing and have never been challenged. <P>The FERC ruling was confusing at best.  On one hand it said that a state has authority over its energy mix.   That is, it can mandate renewable energy.  On the other it said that the state's authority over pricing is superseded by the Public Utility Regulatory Policies Act (PURPA) of 1978.  PURPA was enacted to help spur the development of high-efficiency and renewable energy projects by independent power producers.  If read literally, the FERC ruling allows states to mandate renewables, but not if these cost more than the utilities would otherwise pay for traditional power.  The American Wind Energy Association's, Randy Swisher,  notes that the FERC ruling on pricing has effectively gutted PURPA .  However he adds, "FERC's preemption was relatively narrow and reaffirmed the authority of states to shape their own resource portfolios."<P>What happens next is unclear.  Some analysts argue that FERC has no legal authority to overturn the law and only a state or federal judge could do so.  The FERC ruling only covered independent power producers qualifying under PURPA but in Iowa a number of producers are not so-called QFs so they are exempt from the ruling.  Regardless, the decision sent a shockwave through renewable energy firms that have already signed long-term power-purchase agreements at the 6 cent rate.  Others chose to disregard the price-fixing arrangement and negotiated power purchase agreements that were less than the 6 cent per kWh rate set by the IUB.<P><H3>Enron Adds Minnesota Wind Energy To Portfolio</H3>Enron Corporation, one of the largest energy firms in the world, has added another company to its list of assets.  On January 3, U.S. wind developer Zond Corporation, developer of the next 100-MW wind project for Northern States Power Co., was purchased by the Houston-based energy services giant.  Zond became part of a new business unit, Enron Renewable Energy Corporation.  Zond completed its first wind power facility in 1981 and since then has installed and operates over 2,400 wind turbines comprising 260 megawatts (MWs).  Zond's 100-MW Minnesota-based project should be operating by next year. <P>The purchase clearly indicates Enron's intent to ensure that among its $15 billion portfolio is a dominant group of renewable energy companies.  Enron is betting that, in a world of increased competition, it makes sense to be able to offer "green power" to consumers.  In addition to its purchase of Zond, Enron also is a partner with Amoco in Amoco/Enron Solar, the largest U.S.-owned producer of solar photovoltaic cells and the second largest worldwide.  <P>Contact:  Carol Hensley, Enron, 713-853-6498, <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.enron.com/">http://www.enron.com</A> <P> <H3>Money Available for Energy Assistance in Minnesota</H3>This season's cold temperatures and high fuel costs will make it difficult for tens of thousands of Minnesota households to keep up with utility bills.  Over the last two years the U.S. Congress has slashed programs that help working poor families and the elderly heat their homes.  Pam Marshall, director of the low-income advocacy Energy CENTS Coalition, says that we are "fortunate that the state has released $9 million to make up for the 31% cut in federal energy assistance."   The federal contribution for low-income energy assistance dropped from $56 million in 1994/95 to $38.7 in 1996/97. <p>The Federal government has also released emergency funds for energy assistance that will bring Minnesota's working families an additional $13.7 million.<P>The criteria for getting assistance have changed recently, so even people who were denied assistance in the past should try again.  <p>Contact:  MN Energy Assistance Program, 1-800-657-3805<P><H3>Minnesota Wind-Project Contracts Nearing Completion</H3>Minnesota wind-energy entrepreneur Greg Jaunich, President of Northern Alternative Energy (NAE) has been busy this winter negotiating several wind power projects in southwestern Minnesota.  At press time, contracts for two projects totalling 22.65 MW were being finalized.  The power from the projects will be sold to Northern States Power (NSP).  If built, the projects will help satisfy NSP's requirement to contract for up to 825 MW of wind power by the year 2003. <P>NAE plans to develop the projects for NSP at a total cost of about $25 million.  The first is a 11.25 MW facility employing 15 of Micon's turbines with 48-meter rotor diameters.   Some components will be manufactured in the state and final assembly of the turbines will take place in Hutchinson, Minnesota.  The second will be a 11.4 MW project using 19 of Tacke Windpower's 43-meter turbines.  Expected annual output from the projects are 30 million kWhs and 38 million kWhs, respectively.<P>Both of the NAE projects will be installed on land near the site where Zond Systems will build their 100-MW project later this year.  NAE has secured about 40 percent of the land needed for the project and  NSP would provide the remainder.  Construction could begin as soon as June 1997 and be on-line by late this year.  Greg Jaunich said that the new projects would be a "big step" for NAE.  The company currently operates about a dozen turbines and could add as many as 50 turbines by 1998. <P>By next year, the area around Lake Benton, MN, will be home to wind farms using four different turbines.  ME3's Executive Director, Michael Noble, notes, "NSP has made a smart strategic decision by negotiating smaller projects with many different vendors.  This will allow the utility as well as the state to gain an enormous amount of knowledge about the operating performance of different wind energy technologies in Minnesota."<P><H3>Minnesota's Ethanol Industry Scrutinized</H3>Last year the Minnesota legislature ordered the Office of the Legislative Auditor to do a cost-benefit analysis of Minnesota's burgeoning ethanol industry.  Issued February 6, 1997, the Ethanol Program report (97-04) examines how a state can cost-effectively create a strong, locally-owned renewable energy industry.<P>The report found that, "Construction and operation of ethanol plants are a boon to the communities in which they are located, and there are significant benefits to the state as a whole."  The farmer cooperative ownership model of most Minnesota ethanol plants was found to be beneficial.  Last year when corn prices skyrocketed, many privately-owned ethanol plants around the country shut down while most of Minnesota cooperatives continued operating.   <P>The report was comprehensive but had drawbacks, according to Institute for Local Self-Reliance's (ILSR) David Morris. The report overestimated the cost of ethanol to gasoline customers.  And it understated the environmental benefits of ethanol by ignoring the reduction in benzene and other toxic components of gasoline that it displaces.  <P>Minnesota provides a 20 cents per gallon incentive to ethanol plants up to 15 million gallons a year.  This cap encourages smaller, more numerous plants.  By next year Minnesota will produce more than 120 million gallons of ethanol from 11 ethanol plants, 8 of which are owned by 7500 farm families.  In October 1997, the annual market for ethanol in the state will rise to 200 million gallons because of a state law requiring oxygenated fuel to be used year round throughout the state. <P>Contact: Ethanol and Biofuels page on the web at <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/issues/ethanol/">http://www.me3.org/issues/ethanol</A><P><H2>V.  Information Resources</H2><H3>Study of Minnesota Taxes Paid by Electric Utilities and the Implications of Utility Tax Assessments</H3>This December 1996 report (Appendix 4 of the Quadrennial Report) from the Minnesota Department of Public Service (DPS) analyzed the effects on rates of the taxes imposed on Minnesota electric utilities.  DPS recommends that utilities be treated the same as non-utility businesses in terms of tax burden.<BR>Contact:  DPS Energy Information Center, 612-296-5175<H3>Analysis of Utility Taxation in Minnesota</H3>This January 1997 report from the Minnesota Department of Revenue (DOR) and Department of Public Service provides an overview of the current taxes paid by Minnesota utilities.  The report is divided into four areas: 1) taxes paid and comparison to surrounding states; 2) comparison of taxes paid by different utility operations; 3) competitive implications; and, 4) recommended policy options.<BR>Contact:  Alan Whipple, DOR, 612-296-0338<H3>The Changing Structure of the Electric Power Industry:  An Update</H3>This January 1997 report from the Energy Information Admin-istration (EIA) examines a number of critical issues currently being debated by regulators, lawmakers, and industry participants will shape the future of the electric power industry.  Included are discussions of the history of utility regulation, cost reduction and recovery, and price differentials.<BR>Contact:  Robert M. Schnapp, EIA, 202-426-1211, <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:rschnapp@eia.doe.gov">rschnapp@eia.doe.gov</A>;  <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="ftp://ftp.eia.doe.gov/pub/electricity/eu_stru1.pdf">ftp://ftp.eia.doe.gov/pub/electricity/eu_stru1.pdf</A><H3>Providing Customer Financing Through Utility Energy Efficiency Programs</H3>This January 1997 report from the American Council for an Energy-Efficient Economy (ACEEE) examines how traditional utility demand side management programs will evolve as the electric industry restructures.  The report contains case studies of how utilities are designing financing programs such as loans, shared savings, leases, energy service charges, and end-use pricing to encourage efficiency. <BR>Contact:  ACEEE, 510-549-9914<H3>NREL's Information Resources Catalogue, 1996</H3>This December 1996 catalogue (Document No. NREL/BK-330-21680) from the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) contains hundreds of references to renewable energy and energy efficiency resources.  Many documents can be requested at no cost from NREL.<BR>Contact:  NREL, 303-275-4363, <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.nrel.gov/">http://www.nrel.gov</A><H3>Electricity:  The Road Toward Restructuring</H3>This January 1997 issue brief from the Congressional Research Service provides an historical portrait of federal regulation of energy and updates on Federal electric restructuring initiatives.<BR>Contact: On the Web at <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.cnie.org/nle/eng-7.html">http://www.cnie.org/nle/eng-7.html</A><H2>VI.  Miscellaneous</H2><H4>Send Us Your E-Mail Address To Stay On Top Of The Latest Developments in State Energy Policy! </H4>ME3 wants you to get involved before decisions are made.  Communications through e-mail will allow you to stay on top of the latest developments.  Increasing electronic communications with our members is a high priority for ME3 over the coming year.  As more and more of you gain internet access, we can begin to interact with our members more frequently.  <P>Become one of ME3's electronic activists!  It doesn't cost a thing.  Just send a message saying "Make Me A ME3 Electronic Activist" to John Bailey at <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:bailey@ilsr.org">bailey@ilsr.org</A><P>You can also register on-line at the Sustainable Minnesota Web Site at <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/activist.html">http://www.me3.org/activist.html</A><P>Thanks.<HR>Minnesotans for An Energy-Efficient Economy (ME3) is a coalition working to improve the quality of life, the environment and the economy of Minnesota by promoting energy efficiency and the sound use of renewable energy.  Through a program of research, public education, and intervention in the decision-making process, ME3 seeks to develop and build consensus for an energy vision that will ensure the well-being of future generations.<P>Newsletter Editor:  <a href=mailto:bailey@ilsr.org>John Bailey</a> - <A HREF="http://www.ilsr.org/">Institute for Local Self-Reliance</A><P><B>ME3-Minnesotans for an Energy-Efficient Economy</B><BR>Minnesota Building, Suite 1106<BR>46 E