<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Part 3-Biological Energy:  Opportunities and Obstacles
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<CENTER><H2>Biological
Energy:  Opportunities and Obstacles</H2>
<H4>David Morris, Institute for Local Self-Reliance</H4></CENTER><p>
<HR>
<H3><b>Part 3: Solar Energy and Biological Energy</b></H3>
	 Solar energy comes in four forms:  direct sunlight, wind, rain, and plant
matter.  Plant matter has two important advantages over the other kinds of
solar energy.  <p>

	First, it comes with its own built in storage system.  This means biomass
energy can provide baseload electricity.  Therefore biomass is a perfect
complement to intermittent energy sources like wind.  And since wind turbines
will for the most part be sitting in the middle of farmland the link between
the two becomes even more intimate.<p>

Biomass developers confront a major obstacle not encountered by developers
looking to harness wind or direct sunlight.  The latter need only to harness
renewable resources available in any case.  Biomass developers, on the other
hand, must not only learn how to harness the biomass in an economical fashion
but must convince farmers to raise large quantities of these resources, often
years in advance of the time the resource will be converted into energy.  This
presents a classic chicken and egg dilemma.  Farmers will not plant energy
crops unless guaranteed a market while power plant builders cannot attract
sufficient financing unless they have a guaranteed supply of raw materials.<p>

This is not a problem for starch to ethanol plants since the plant
matter--corn, wheat, potatoes, etc.--is being grown anyway.  Nor is it a
problem if waste wood is used to fuel power plants.  But it does represent a
major obstacle to the introduction of cellulose to ethanol plants or for
biomass electricity that relies on crops or trees dedicated for energy uses.<p>

	Biomass has a second advantage over direct sunlight and wind.  It contains
physical matter that can be converted into gaseous, liquid or solid forms to
meet the various needs of final customers.  That can also create a disadvantage
for biofuels. If wind is harnessed, it will be to generate electricity.  On the
other hand, biomass can be used for many purposes and many compete with one
another.<p>

Cellulosic materials can be converted into liquid fuels like ethanol or
methanol or into gaseous fuels or into solid fuels.  Or they can be converted
into high priced chemicals or construction materials or paper.  Indeed, in the
final analysis the principal competitor to biofuels may not be wind or fossil
fuels but biochemicals and bioproducts.<p>

One hundred years ago the vast majority of the industrial materials we
consumed--dyes, inks, paints, medicines, clothing, synthetic fibers, plastics,
industrial chemicals--were derived from plant matter.  Just as fossil fuels
supplanted biofuels they also displaced biochemicals.<p>

In the last ten years the carbohydrate economy has made a comeback.  Advances
in biological processing have lowered the cost of making high quality
industrial products from plant matter while environmental regulations have
raised the cost of extracting, using and disposing of petroleum derived
products.<p>

A decade ago virtually the only plant-based products on the market were
adhesives and lubricating oils and a handful of intermediate chemicals. Today
plant matter based products compete in almost every major product category.  In
1980, for example, the vast majority of glycerol based compounds were made from
petroleum.  Today 85 percent are made from plant matter.  In 1980 most
industrial grade ethanol was made from petroleum.  Today most is made from
grains, even though this type of ethanol does not qualify for a tax credit.
Biopaints have captured about 3 percent of the paint market.  Vegetable oil
based inks have 8 percent of the printing ink market.  About 5 percent of
commodity plastics contain some plant matter based compounds.<a
href="bspch2fn.html#fn6">[6]</a>  ILSR estimates that over the next
five years the increase in biochemicals may surpass the increase in liquid
biofuels.<p>

In the future we may see millions of tons of starch diverted to the production
of plastics and away from lower cost ethanol.   One Seattle based company has
worked with ADM to convert sorbitol into polyols via a bioreactor process.
International Polyol Chemicals Inc.(IPCI) points out that ethanol's market
price is about 15 cents per pound while ethylene glycol, the least expensive
polyol, is 21 cents per pound, and propylene glycol costs more than 40 cents
per pound.<p>

Many proponents of biofuels point to the 350 million tons of agricultural and
forestry wastes available at the national level for further processing.<a
href="bspch2fn.html#fn7">[7]</a>  But a growing number of companies
are converting these wastes into construction materials or paper or chemicals.
Weyerhaeuser in Oregon may soon convert seed straw into boxboard.  Phenix
Composites in Minnesota is converting waste paper into a granite like board
that competes with very high priced hardwoods.  Agriboard in Iowa is producing
a particle board substitute from wheat straw.  In the Pacific Northwest
companies like Potlatch are raising tens of thousands of acres in fast growing
trees to be used for pulp.<p>

These companies may be able to pay a higher price for the raw or waste plant
matter than those seeking to convert it into fuels.  For example,  a Minnesota
forest products firm might pay a higher price for fast growing trees used for
making oriented strand board than another Minnesota company could to convert
these into competitive electricity.<p>

In the future we may find that plant matter goes not into a single product
facility but into biorefineries which, like petroleum refineries, take a single
feedstock and convert it into a variety of final products.  Corn based wet
mills do this now, producing corn meal, corn oil, carbon dioxide, starch, corn
syrup and ethanol from the basic feedstock.  Several companies now use a
pyrolysis process to break down wood wastes into carbon black, number six fuel
oil, and intermediate chemicals.<p>

<HR>
