<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Part 4-Biological Energy:  Opportunities and Obstacles
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<CENTER><H2>Biological
Energy:  Opportunities and Obstacles</H2>
<H4>David Morris, Institute for Local Self-Reliance</H4></CENTER><p>
<HR>
<H3>Part 4:  The Economics of Biomass Electrification</H3>
Let me concentrate most of the remainder of this paper on biomass
electrification.<p>

The latest figures from EPRI show that conventional wood fired stoker boilers
are not competitive with fossil fueled power plants.  But new technologies like
Whole Tree Energy may reduce the cost of wood fired electricity to where it is
competitive with a new coal plant although higher than a natural gas combined
cycle plant.<p>

<b>Performance and Cost Estimates for Biomass Electric Technologies</b><a
href="bspch2fn.html#fn8">[8]</a><p>
<!-- Table Tag -->
<TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=1>
<TR><TD>Technology</TD><TD>MW</TD><TD>Btus/kWh</TD><TD>Effic.</TD><TD>$/kW</TD><TD>cents/kWh</u></b><p></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Cofiring coal w/15% wood</TD><TD>200</TD><TD>10,283</TD><TD>33.7</TD><TD>$105</TD><TD>2.3<p></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Natural gas combined cycle</TD><TD>120</TD><TD>7,900</TD><TD>43.2</TD><TD>$770</TD><TD>4.0<p></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>WTE</TD><TD>100</TD><TD>10,654</TD><TD>32.0</TD><TD>$1,341</TD><TD>5.1<p></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>WTE</TD><TD>50</TD><TD>10,661</TD><TD>32.0</TD><TD>$1,722</TD><TD>6.0<p></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Wood fired stoker boiler</TD><TD>50</TD><TD>13,883</TD><TD>24.6</TD><TD>$1,780</TD><TD>7.5<p></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Current wood/GCC<a href="bspch2fn.html#fn9">[9]</a></TD><TD>50</TD><TD>12,369</TD><TD>27.6</TD><TD>$2,466</TD><TD>8.7</TR>
<TR><TD>Advanced Wood/GCC<a href="bspch2fn.html#fn10">[10]</a></TD><TD>100</TD><TD>9,769</TD><TD>34.8</TD><TD>$2,128</TD><TD>7.3</TR>
<TR><TD>New Coal/FGD</TD><TD>200</TD><TD>10,020</TD><TD>34.1</TD><TD>$1,900</TD><TD>6.0</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
<p>
The widespread use of biological energy can occur in various ways.<p>

<H4>-Co-Firing</H4>
Co-firing of biomass with coal is not a new practice.<a href="bspch2fn.html#fn11">[11]</a>   Several dozen  utilities use 5-20 percent or
more biomass mixed with coal in at least one of their power plants.   The
potential market for biomass through co-firing is enormous.<p>

Wisconsin has 22 coal fired power plants with a combined capacity of 7,133 MW.
The Bayport NSP pant and the Blount Street plant of Madison Gas and Electric
Company are co fired, the first with wood and the second with densified
municipal solid wastes.   If biomass substituted for only 5 percent of the coal
used in Wisconsin's power plants,  it would create the equivalent of a 350 MW
baseload plant and would require more than 1 million tons of biomass a year.
If the ratio of biomass to coal rose to 20 percent, more than 4 million tons of
biomass would be needed.  About 4.5 million tons of wood residues are available
annually in Wisconsin.<a href="bspch2fn.html#fn12">[12]</a><p>

Co-firing can be done with wood waste, fast growing trees, or new energy crops.
 Northern States Power will be building a 50 MWe biomass fueled power plant by
1998, probably fueled by alfalfa.  Displacing 10 percent of its coal from its
Sherco complex would create the equivalent of about a 200 MWe biomass plant.<p>

A major study of co-firing is taking place at the Tennessee Valley
Authority(TVA).<a href="bspch2fn.html#fn13">[13]</a>  TVA owns and
operates 59 coal fired steam generators at 11 plant sites.  A preliminary
resource assessment found that 1-2 million oven dry tons of mill residues were
available and 12-25 million tons of logging residuals.    Biomass in the TVA
region could supply a baseload capacity of almost 3,000 MWe if this waste
biomass were fully recovered.   TVA's analysis also found that fast growing
trees, assuming a 3.5 dry tons per acre average yield, could produce about 75
million dry tons, sufficient to displace all of TVA's coal fired capacity.<p>

A case study analysis by TVA found that sufficient low cost biomass(less than
$1 per MMBtu) is available in unused mill residue to displace at least 15
percent of the coal.<p>

Co-firing may offer a major opportunity for expanding the use of biomass for
electricity generation.  But the use of biomass often requires investment in
plant modifications and also may require a higher cost overhead in order to
monitor the quality of the biomass.  Thus utilities may be interested in
co-firing only if large quantities of biomass can be purchased for a price
significantly less than the cost of coal($1.10-$1.40 per MMBtus).  Some waste
wood is available at this price but energy crops and fast growing trees would
probably be slightly more expensive than coal.  If Conservation Reserve Program
acreage were used, or if an environmental credit were given because of reduced
emissions, biomass would become more directly competitive with coal.<p>

<H4>-Whole Tree Energy(WTE)</H4>
Currently the cost of biomass electrification from wood fired stokers is 7-9
cents per kWh,  too high to compete in any scenario.  Energy Performance
Systems(EPS) of Minnesota has developed a patented technology that promises to
reduce these costs.   Harvesting costs are cut by $4-6 per ton by eliminating
the need for a skidder and chipper.  The very small furnace reduces capital
costs.  The system design achieves a heat rate of about 10,000 Btus per kWh
compared to 14,000 Btus for recent wood stokers.  Most wood fired plants
operate at low pressures and low temperatures and have a cycle efficiency of
15-25 percent.  EPS projects a 33 percent efficiency for its first plant, a 42
percent efficiency rate for its second plant and an ultimate efficiency
approaching 50 percent.<p>

EPS projects a cost of electricity from a 100 MWe plant of 5 cent per kWh.
This assumes the fuel is grown on CRP land.  EPS reportedly has offered to sign
a long term contract with performance guarantees with one utility at that
price.  EPS predicts that the price of electricity from future plants of
similar size would be 4.3 cents per kWh.<p>

<H4>-Energy Crops</H4>
Several agricultural energy crops are being seriously investigated.  In the
late 1980s Minnesota researched the feasibility of using sweet sorghum, with
its high sugar and fiber content, as an energy crop.  At least one company is
presently contracting with farmers for sweet sorghum for a combined biomass
electricity and ethanol plant.   Northern States Power is testing alfalfa as an
energy crop.  Iowa's Agricultural Extension Service is examining switch grass.
Each crop has its advantages and disadvantages.   Given the Minnesota law, an
alfalfa fueled plant will probably be the first to come on line.<p>

A preliminary calculation by the University of Minnesota found that if farmers
receive a $60 per ton price they would benefit from inserting alfalfa into a
corn-soybean rotation.<a href="bspch2fn.html#fn14">[14]</a>  The
annual return per acre was higher for the farmer than the conventional
soybean/corn rotation "with or without government program payments".<a
href="bspch2fn.html#fn15">[15]</a><p>

The vast majority of the revenues for the alfalfa processing facility would
come from stripping off the leaf protein and selling it as a mid grade bypass
protein.  Assuming a $125 per ton price for the protein, the stems, which
represent 50 percent by weight of the plant, might be sold for $20 per ton.
That would put the cost of the alfalfa fuel at about $2 per MMbtus.
Preliminary calculations from Iowa indicate a fuel cost from switchgrass of
about $2.50 per MMbtus.<p>

Both Iowa and Minnesota are looking to introduce their agricultural energy
crops at first by co-firing them with coal, then by gasifying them and
co-firing the gas with coal and finally, by gasifying the plant matter and
using it to run an advanced combustion turbine.<p>
<p>
Biomass gasifiers are relatively common and can be burned in conventional
boilers.  But the gas contains contaminants:  particulates, alkali gases, tars.
These must be removed before the gas can be used in an advanced gas turbine.
The cleanup of this gas constitutes the major obstacle to using biomass gas in
high efficiency gas turbines.<p>

Several biomass gasified turbine plants are about to become operational. A
pressurized gasifier fueled by wood chips will come on line this year in
Sweden.  It will generate 6 MW of electricity and 20 MW of heat for a district
heating system.  A 25-30 MWe Brazilian gasification plant will become
operational in 1995.  A third type of gasifier that uses as its feedstock
bagasse from sugar cane will begin operating in Hawaii next year.<p>

These three gasification power plants will provide the first concrete economic
information about biomass gasification.  A Shell Oil evaluation of the
Brazilian plant estimates a capital cost of $1300 per kW and a feedstock cost
from eucalyptus wood chips of $2.50 per MMBtus giving a total cost of 5.0-6.0
cents per kWh.  The most optimistic estimate predicts a price as low as 4.0
cents per kWh.<a href="bspch2fn.html#fn16">[16]</a><p>

<H4>-Fuel Cells</H4>
Fuel cells, which convert chemical energy directly into electricity, bypassing
the combustion stage, are entering the market for both stationary and mobile
applications.  These fuel cells currently run on natural gas or methanol or
directly on hydrogen but they could run on biogas, bioethanol or biomethanol.<p>

The Energy Research Corporation(ERC) of Connecticut is  evaluating for the
National Rural Electric Cooperative Association the use of low proof ethanol
for fuel cells.  Ethanol for ERC's fuel cells can be used in concentrations of
15-30 percent rather than 100 percent.  This could lower the production cost of
ethanol by as much as 30 percent.  Even with this 30 percent reduction, ethanol
is still more expensive than natural gas but if the ethanol tax credit were
available the price would be more competitive.<p>

It is also possible to gasify biomass or convert that gas into methanol and use
either the gas or the methanol in a fuel cell.  Currently one company, H Power
Corporation of New Jersey is powering a bus with fuel cells that make their own
hydrogen from methanol.  A General Motors study found that these buses would be
competitive with conventional buses if produced in significant quantities.
These fuel cells could use ethanol as well as methanol, although methanol is
cheaper and easier to use.<p>

Another company, M-C Power is also developing fuel cells that will run on
natural gas.  The company forecasts higher cost natural gas in the future and
views ethanol as a potential backup fuel that would allow the developer to
lower the rate he or she pays for natural gas by purchasing it under an
interruptible rate. M-C Power estimates this would reduce the price of the
natural gas by 30-70 cents per MMBtus.  This in turn could make ethanol a more
cost effective fuel for the 5-10 percent of the year it might be needed.<a
href="bspch2fn.html#fn17">[17]</a><p>

Most observers envision a hydrogen economy based on water.  But biomass
contains a great deal of hydrogen.<a href="bspch2fn.html#fn18">[18]</a>  Tests at Battelle's Columbus Laboratories have
found that 600,000 tons of dry biomass per year could generate sufficient
hydrogen to fuel 150,000 passenger cars.   This comes to about 3/4 of an acre
per car.  A 100 percent ethanol fueled car would require corn from about 2
acres and cellulose from about 1 acre.<p>

Battelle concluded that hydrogen would cost $6.20-$8.90 per MMBtus,  based on a
biomass feedstock cost of $2.10-$4.20 per MMBtus.   Assuming electricity at 4
cents per kWh, hydrogen from the electrolysis of water would cost about $20 per
MMbtus.<a href="bspch2fn.html#fn19">[19]</a><p>

<HR>
