<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Part 5-Biological Energy:  Opportunities and Obstacles
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<CENTER><H2>Biological
Energy:  Opportunities and Obstacles</H2>
<H4>David Morris, Institute for Local Self-Reliance</H4></CENTER><p>
<HR>
<H3>Policy Questions</H3>
The biological energy potential for agricultural or forestry states like
Wisconsin and Minnesota is very large.  Both Minnesota and Wisconsin have the
potential of completely displacing petroleum based transportation fuels with
biofuels.  Minnesota could do this by converting all of its existing corn
starch to ethanol.   Wisconsin can do this by converting a little over half of
its wood residues to ethanol.  Several dozen vehicles running on 85 percent
ethanol are already being used in Wisconsin and Iowa.  Buses powered by ethanol
are being used in Iowa and Illinois.  The midwestern states are organizing an
"ethanol highway", that is, a network of E85 ethanol refueling stations that
will allow the traveler to drive from the Canadian border to southern Kansas on
almost pure ethanol.<p>

Neither Wisconsin nor Minnesota has the potential for displacing a majority of
its electricity from biomass.  But in Minnesota, biomass electricity combined
with wind energy offers the possibility of renewable electricity becoming the
primary form of power generation.<p>

As we move into the biological energy era a number of important issues must be
addressed.<p>

<H4>-Tailoring Renewable Energy Incentives</H4>

Should we subsidize one form of bioenergy over another?  Ethanol receives a
federal tax credit of 54 cents per gallon and receives additional tax credits
in states like  Minnesota.  Nationally the average incentive for a gallon of
ethanol has been dropping over the past 15 years, from a high of $3.50 in 1980
to about 60 cents on average in 1991.<p>

The federal ethanol tax credit is almost as large as the wholesale price of
gasoline.  When combined with Minnesota's 40 cent state tax credit it is 50
percent greater than the price of gasoline.  Diesel fuels derived from
vegetable oils do not yet receive a federal tax credit.  The 1.5 cent per kWh
tax credit for biomass electricity is meaningful only if the recipient pays
sufficient economic taxes to use it.  And as noted above, the credit as
currently structured cannot be easily used.  In any case, the 1.5 cent credit
represents only half the cost of existing electricity and as low as a third of
the cost of new power plants. <p>
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG  SRC="bspch2f1.GIF"><p>
A good case can be made for extending the renewable energy tax credit to
vegetable oil derived diesel and to amend the Energy Policy Act to make the
biomass tax credit more readily available,  To pay for this, the ethanol credit
might be reduced.  Initially the ethanol credit needed to eliminate the cost
differential between ethanol and gasoline.  Today ethanol competes, not with
gasoline but with higher priced gasoline additives like MTBE.  Moreover, given
the mandates for ethanol in Minnesota and, soon on the national level, it seems
reasonable to reduce or restructure the ethanol tax incentives.<p>

<H4>-Fostering Local Economic Development</H4>

As we develop incentives to foster a biological energy economy we might
consider how to tailor those incentives to meet a variety of objectives.   For
example,  biological energy is more labor intensive than fossil fuel or uranium
derived energy.  Biorefineries are smaller than petroleum refineries and
biomass electric plants are much smaller than nuclear or coal fired power
plants.  Finally,  the fuel for biological energy plants can be locally
purchased.  The end result of these three factors is that biorefineries can be
an important element in a rural development strategy.<p>

Do we want to tailor incentives that maximize local economic development?
Almost 10 years ago Minnesota converted half of its state tax incentives for
ethanol into producer credits available only to in-state producers.  The
so-called "pump credits" were used to create a market for ethanol no matter
where it was produced. The producer credits are targeted to nurturing a
homegrown manufacturing capacity.<p>

On the other hand, Wisconsin's Public Service Commission introduced a .75 cents
per kWh incentive for renewable electricity plants payable to Wisconsin utility
shareholders so long as the electricity is consumed inside the state no matter
where the electricity is produced.    The first such credits were applied to
wind electricity generated in Minnesota.  Do we want to fashion incentives that
encourage in-state producers?<p>

Do we want to fashion incentives that encourage small scale and dispersed
production?  The Minnesota producer credit for ethanol, for example, has a
ceiling per producer.  The federal tax credit for ethanol does not.<p>

Do we want to favor certain organizational forms?  Cooperatives are ubiquitous
in the agricultural sector.  More than 4 million farmers belong to over 4,500
cooperatives with annual sales of $80 billion.  Biomass energy production lends
itself well to ownership by producer cooperatives.  Such cooperatives return a
significant share of the profits generated back to the local economy.  In
Minnesota more than 75 percent of the ethanol produced comes from a 2000 corn
farmer cooperative and three of the next four plants coming on line will
probably be cooperatives.  The University of Minnesota is actively
investigating the possibility of structuring an alfalfa cooperative which would
own the processing equipment, although not the power plant.<p>

<H4>-Protecting Wildlife and Soil</H4>

Dramatically expanding the use of biological energy raises important
environmental issues.  In the last few years we have gained increasing
sophistication about the relationship of farming techniques to soil erosion and
groundwater pollution.  We need to make certain that as we move toward a
biological economy we do not mine the soil, pollute the groundwater or destroy
native wildlife habitats.<p>

The Audubon Society, EPRI and other organizations have been engaged in a
several year roundtable discussion concerning how to design future energy
farms.  Their final report will be available soon.  Today fast growing trees on
CRP land must be planted in a way that does not exceed soil erosion tolerance
levels.  Minnesota biologists will soon release a preliminary analysis of the
impact of fast growing trees on small mammals and birds in and around Prairie
lands.  Those investigating the widespread use of alfalfa are examining how
harvesting can be done to minimize the disturbance to nests.<p>

No one can predict the future.  But together we can invent the future.  In the
last 15 years we've radically altered the rules regarding energy generation and
use.  In the next 15 years we will introduce new rules and create technologies
and new fuels consistent with these new rules.  Biological energy can and
should play an important role in this future, especially in agricultural
states.  How fast we move toward a biological economy and what the structure of
that economy looks like, depends on the decisions we make today.<p>


</BODY> 
</HTML> 
