<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Part 1-Biological Energy:  Opportunities and Obstacles
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2>Biological
Energy:  Opportunities and Obstacles</H2>
<H4>David Morris, Institute for Local Self-Reliance</H4></CENTER><p>

<HR>
<I>Biological Energy: Opportunities and Obstacles was originally delivered as a speech to the Biomass Energy Infrastructure Workshop in Madison, WI, on June 7, 1994.</I><P>

The speech is in five parts.  Please follow link at bottom of each page to get to the next section.
<HR>
<H3>Part 1:  Introduction and Background</H3>
Biological energy's time has come again.   I say again because 130 years ago
plant matter was our primary fuel.  Just before the Civil War wood generated 70
percent of the nation's total energy.  Ethanol was one of our leading chemicals
and lighting fuels.   But coal displaced wood and oil replaced ethanol and by
the late 1970s biological energy had virtually disappeared except a relatively
modest quantity of wood consumed in fireplaces and industrial boilers.  
<p>
We've come a long way since then.  In retrospect we can identify the specific
year the breakthrough occurred:  1978.  <p>

<H4>1978:  The Breakthrough Year</H4>
<p>
In 1978 five separate energy laws were enacted by Congress.  One of these, the
Public Utilities Regulatory Policies Act(PURPA) required utilities to purchase
power so long as the independent power plant was fueled by renewable energy or
used cogeneration.  A second law provided substantial tax incentives for fuel
ethanol.<p>

PURPA drastically changed the structure of the electric utility industry.
Before 1978 there were virtually no independent power producers.  By 1993 about
60 percent of all new capacity brought on-line was owned by independent
developers, not utility companies.  PURPA made it possible for the forest
products industry to harness its vast supply of waste wood for electric
generation.  The amount of wood fired electricity soared from 200 MWe in 1978
to some 5,000 MWe today.  Today biomass accounts for about 3 percent of the
nation's electricity.    	<p>
The incentives for fuel ethanol made that fuel competitive with gasoline.  Yet
it is important to note that even with these incentives, ethanol had to
overcome many obstacles before it was widely used.   Gas stations owned by oil
companies, for the most part, refused to handle a non-petroleum derived
product.   Car companies in the early 1980s told their customers they would
void their warranties if they used ethanol.  Car mechanics were skeptical.  <p>

Ethanol producers overcame these obstacles and production rose from 20 million
gallons in 1978 to over 1 billion gallons by 1993.  Fuel ethanol has captured a
little over 1 percent of the transportation fuel market.   And ethanol's
biological brethren, vegetable oil based diesel is poised to enter the
commercial market.<p>

Having painted this somewhat rosy picture of recent history, it is important to
identify some less optimistic trends for biological energy.  The development of
renewable electricity has been accelerated by the high prices paid by utilities
on long term contracts in the early 1980s.  These prices were predicated on a
rapid growth in electricity in future years and the increased cost of new power
plants.  But the decline in oil and coal prices, the rise of low cost high
efficiency natural gas fired power plants and a surplus in conventional power
capacity because of an economic recession resulted in a stabilization and then
decline in electricity prices.   <p>

Wind developers are more prepared to deal with the lower price of electricity
since their basic technology has rapidly matured in the last decade.  The cost
of generating electricity from wind has dropped by some 80 percent since 1980,
according to the American Wind Energy Association.  Biological energy has not
done nearly as well.<p>

In 1986 1839 MWe of wood fueled generators went into operation, more than 60
percent of the 3054 MWe of power introduced from 1980 to 1985.  In 1989 614 MWe
went into operation.  In 1990 that number dropped to 250-300 MWe and may have
been below 200 MWe in 1993.<a href="bspch2fn.html#fn1">[1]</a>  In
New England a number of utilities are buying back the high priced contracts
they signed with owners of wood fired power plants back in the mid 1980s in
order to prematurely close these plants.<p>
  
Ethanol production is still expanding, thanks to the 1990 Clean Air Act, which
requires that gasoline contain oxygen during the winter months in certain urban
areas.  But the tax incentives for ethanol were originally expected to be
temporary, as gasoline prices were expected to be over $1.50 a gallon by now.
Ethanol production costs did decline, from about $1.80 to $1.10-$1.20 per
gallon.   But ethanol faces a sunset of its federal tax benefits in the year
2000.  And today it competes with a new generation of low cost non-petroleum
fuels that are more environmentally benign and lower cost than ethanol, like
natural gas,  electricity, propane or methanol.  The only major market where
ethanol might be able to compete straight up as a fuel is in air
transportation.  The first aircraft engines that run on ethanol are just now
being certified. <p>

Fuel ethanol has come under a savage attack by a powerful combination of oil
companies and environmentalists.  Environmentalists are concerned that ethanol
is not really a renewable fuel because certain agricultural practices appear to
mine the soil rather than husband it.  Others worry that if we feed our cars
with plant matter we may end up diverting scarce arable land from the more
important objective of providing food and feed to a growing population.  Still
others worry that ethanol in the gas tank can cause air quality problems.   Oil
companies argue against ethanol's direct tax incentives and find powerful
allies in federal and state highway departments who need more money to maintain
their extensive and aging road networks.   This powerful coalition is trying to
ban the use of ethanol in major urban areas beginning in 1995.<p>

Today we are at an energy crossroads.  There is no question we will continue to
expand our use of alternative forms of energy.  But it is not clear how or
whether this will translate into a major expansion in the use of biological
forms of energy.<p>
<HR>

