<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Part 2-Biological Energy:  Opportunities and Obstacles
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<CENTER><H2>Biological
Energy:  Opportunities and Obstacles</H2>
<H4>David Morris, Institute for Local Self-Reliance</H4></CENTER><p>
<HR>
<H3>Part 2: Changing the Rules</H3><p>
<p>
In 1978 we began to significantly change the rules governing our generation and
use of energy.  In the mid 1990s that process is continuing and accelerating.
Let me describe four examples of these new kinds of rules.<p>
<p>
<H4>-The 30 Percent Renewable Standard</H4>
Last December EPA proposed a renewable oxygenate rule which should become final
this month.  The rule would require that 30 percent of all oxygenates the Clean
Air Act requires to be added to gasoline sold in ozone non attainment areas
must be derived from renewable resources.  In practical terms this is an
ethanol mandate but its importance goes far beyond ethanol.  For this is the
first time the federal government has enacted a renewable energy standard.
<p>
The renewable oxygenate standard might be viewed as an environmental bookend to
President Clinton's Executive Order issued late last year that required 30
percent of all printing and writing paper purchased by the federal government
to contain 30 percent recycled content.  The recycled content standard speaks
to our need to conserve resources. The renewable oxygenate standard speaks to
our need to switch from non-renewable to renewable resources.<p>

The renewable oxygenate standard could be broadened into a more widely applied
renewable energy standard.  For example, federal law requires public and then
private vehicle fleets to use clean fuels.  The President, by Executive Order,
has shortened the phase-in period for federal fleet conversion.  Why not have
the federal fleet set an example by requiring that at least 30 percent of all
additional fleet vehicles purchased by the federal government be capable of
running on renewable fuels?  Not only ethanol but electric vehicles when the
electricity used by them is generated from renewable resources would qualify
under such a standard.<p>

The federal government also could require that 30 percent of all new
electricity purchased or generated by federal agencies be renewable fueled.  At
the state level, that is what Minnesota did last month.   The legislature
required Northern States Power to build or purchase 550 MW of renewable
electricity by 2002.  One hundred twenty five megawatts of that must be biomass
fueled.  That translates into 30 percent of all new electricity generated by
NSP and more than 20 percent of all new electricity consumed by Minnesota.<p>

A few years ago the Minnesota legislature also required that by 1997 all
gasoline sold throughout the state must contain oxygen year round.  Although
there is no quota for renewable energy in this law, the long distance from MTBE
production facilities and the quantity of homegrown ethanol available means
that realistically we might expect that in three years ethanol will account for
7.5-9 percent of all fuels consumed by Minnesota's automobiles and light
trucks.<p>

<H4>-The 1.5 cent per kWh Tax Credit</H4>
The Energy Policy Act of 1992 provided a 1.5 cent per kWh tax credit for
renewable electricity, including biomass grown specifically as an electric
fuel.  That tax incentive may make wind and biomass competitive with coal and
nearly competitive with natural gas.<p>

The Minnesota legislature this session created an additional tax credit that
specifically links biofuels and bioelectricity.  A 1.5 cent per kWh tax credit
was enacted for biomass fueled cogeneration that supplies steam and electricity
to an ethanol facility.<p>

The federal renewable electric tax credit has several shortcomings.  While in
theory it applies to both public and privately operated power plants, in
practice it does not. Tax credit for private companies can be taken off their
taxes while the tax credit for tax exempt entities like municipal or
cooperative utilities must come in the form of direct payments from Congress.
To date Congress has provided no money for this purpose.  The impact on the
national budget is the same, but Congress finds it much easier to subsidize by
reducing revenue rather than by increasing expenditures.   The result is that
cooperatives and municipal utilities or municipalities in general are not
benefiting from this incentive.  This significantly dampens public sector
enthusiasm for becoming more directly involved in renewable electricity
generation.<p>

The lack of Congressional appropriations burdens both wind and biomass
electrification.  The other shortcoming of the federal renewable electric tax
credit burdens only biomass.  The incentive applies only to "closed loop"
biomass, that is, to plant matter grown specifically for energy production.
Waste wood and existing trees do not qualify.  It is reasonable that the
government doesn't want to subsidize increased forest cutting or to create a
situation which will drive up the cost of lumber.  But some plant matter takes
5-10 years before it can be economically harvested.  The federal credit is
available only to power plants that come on-line by mid 1999.  Therefore plant
matter that will take more than 4 years to come to maturity will be ineligible
for this ten year tax benefit.<p>

The tax credit could still boost the prospects of energy crops like switchgrass
or alfalfa. These could conceivably be cultivated and harvested in substantial
quantities by 1999.  But another provision may hamper the rapid expansion of
this market.  The credit will apply only to plants where biomass is the primary
fuel, that is, where more than 50 percent of the fuel mix in terms of Btu
content is derived from plant matter.<a href="bspch2fn.html#fn2">[2]</a>   This means the tax credit is not available for
co-firing 5-20 percent biomass with coal. Co-firing may represent the largest
and most economical short term entry point for large scale biomass
electrification.<p>

<H4>-European Developments</H4>

The rules are changing not only in this country, but in Europe as well.
Several years ago Europe allowed farmers to take 15 percent of their land out
of food production and use it for raising non-food crops while receiving
financial benefits.   The program is somewhat similar to our Conservation
Reserve Program, but a wider variety of crops are covered:  rapeseed,  hemp and
kenaf.  The European Parliament is about to give countries the authority to
reduce or eliminate fuel taxes on ethanol and biodiesel.  France and Italy have
already done this.  We can expect a very dramatic expansion in the use of
biomass fuels, both liquid and solid as well as other industrial products made
from plant matter, in Europe in the coming months and years.<p>

<H4>-The Conservation Reserve Program</H4>
The Conservation Reserve Program(CRP) is set to expire next year.  It is
unclear what form, if any, it will take in the new farm bill.  The U.S.
Department of Agriculture has for several years been promoting the use of fast
growing trees on this land.   Currently farmers can get a 5 year extension if
they plant their acres in fast growing trees.  In some southern states trees
account for more than 90 percent of the CRP acreage planted.   Southern farmers
already have an established market for southern pine.  In Minnesota trees
account for only 2-3 percent of CRP acreage.  Minnesota farmers have no
established markets for hybrid poplars.   CRP payments can reduce the cost of
biomass by more than $1 per MMBtus, making biomass competitive or nearly
competitive with coal.<p>

<H4>-Internalizing Environmental Costs</H4>
States are moving toward a full cost accounting system by taking into account
the environmental costs of fuels.   Eight state regulatory commissions,
including those in Wisconsin and Minnesota, have quantified the environmental
costs of electric generation and require utilities to take these costs into
account when they decide which resources to acquire.<p>

A cost estimates of environmental damage vary widely.   By far the largest cost
element is carbon dioxide emissions.  The Wisconsin Public Service Commission's
estimates presented below fall in the mid-range of environmental cost
estimates.  If biomass is credited for the carbon dioxide absorbed as it grows,
utilities would be able to pay about 1.5 cents per kWh more for biomass
electrification than coal fired electricity.  Biomass would have a half penny
per kWh advantage over high efficiency gas turbines and a one cent advantage
over conventional gas fired combustion turbines.  Of course, environmental
adders also make wind and other forms of solar energy more competitive.<p>
   
<b><u>Environmental Costs</u></b><a href="bspch2fn.html#fn3">[3]</a><p>
(cents per kWh) <p>
