<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>The Minnesota Wood Energy Scale-up Project</FONT></B></CENTER>

<CENTER>July 26, 1995</CENTER><HR><BR>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4><B>Cooperators:</B></FONT><BR>

Oak Ridge National Lab - Biofuels Feedstock Development Program, 
Oak  Ridge, TN<BR>
Minnesota Department of Natural Resources - Division of Forestry, 
St. Paul, MN<BR>
Electric Power Research Institute, Palo Alto, CA<BR>
Energy Performance Systems, Minneapolis, MN<BR>
Northern States Power, Minneapolis, MN<BR>
USDA - US. Forest Service, Rhinelander, WI<BR>
USDA - Natural Resources Conservation Service<BR>
Consolidated Farm Services Agency<BR>
WesMin Resource Conservation & Development (RC&D) Council, 
Alexandria, MN</CENTER><BR><BR>

<B>Background</B><BR><BR>

     The Minnesota Wood Energy Scale-up Project planning began in 
late 1993.  The purpose of the project is to track and monitor 
economic costs of planning, maintaining, and monitoring larger 
scale commercial plantings of hybrid popular.  For 15 years, only 
smaller scale research and experimental plantings of hybrid 
popular have been utilized to screen for promising high-yielding 
candidate species.  Currently, 1,850 acres of hybrid popular 
trees have been planted on Conservation Reserve Program (CRP) 
lands near Alexandria, Minnesota.  Progression of the work has 
proceeded in phases; Phase 1 (1994) planted 1,000 acres, and 
Phase 2 (1995) planted 850 acres.  To date, eighteen landowners 
have recontracted with the CRP for five-year extensions of their 
existing 10-year contracts in order to plant hybrid popular.  The 
5-year extension continues annual "rental" payments to landowners 
for five mroe years.  The extended contracts will begin to expire 
in 2001, or when the first plantings will be 7 years old.<BR><BR>  
     There are no current contracts in place for the wood these 
trees are projected to supply.  The structure of the wood 
fiber-farming industry in Minnesota has changed drastically over 
the past 5 years.  Stumpage values for fiber have risen to more 
that $30 per cord in some areas raising the possibility that 
these trees could be used for fiber rather than energy.  Several 
legislative mandates have forced the Sate of Minnesota to pursue 
a strong commitment to renewable energy.  These mandates, a 
potential need for an additional 1,700 megawatts of power by 2008 
by Northern States Power Company, and the upcoming 1995 Farm Bill 
deliberations will all play strong roles in developing markets 
for wood produced much like agricultural crops. <BR><BR> 
     There has been a tremendous of local and international 
interest in the project.  Many tours have been provided for local 
decision makers, resource managers, fiber and energy industry 
representatives, and others including a group of forestry related 
professionals from Australia.  A tour of international 
researchers coordinated with an International Energy Association 
workshop will be held September 25-26, 1995.  The Natural 
Resource Conservation Service (NRCS) has indicated support of a 
role for energy corps in the 1995 Farm Bill.  Recent local and 
national press has highlighted this project (e.g. The Wall Street 
Journal, TVA Southeastern Regional Biomass Energy Program 
Newsletter, Agri-News, The Land Magazine, Wadena Pioneer Journal, 
Alexandria Echo Press, Morris Sun, and local television 
stations).<BR><BR>  
     Contractual negotiations between the MN Department of 
Natural Resources - Division of Forestry, the Oak Ridge National 
Lab, the WesMin RC&D Council, and others are currently underway 
to secure funding for the planting of an additional 3,000 acres 
in 1996.<BR><BR>

<B>General Information</B><BR><BR>

     WesMin became an interested partner in the venture as an 
opportunity to create jobs, offer alternative income to farmers, 
improve the environment, and help reduce Minnesota's energy 
dependence.  Partners in the project requested WesMin to submit 
funding proposals, receive project funding, and serve as project 
administrator.  Many questions regarding wildlife impacts, soil 
suitability, growth characteristics, maintenance systems, and the 
environment also supported implementation of this project.  The 
WesMin Resource Conservation & Development (RC&D) Council has 
assumed responsibility for operations management and oversight, 
coordination and procurement of services, materials, and needs in 
establishing and maintaining all project acreage planted.   The 
WesMin RC&D Council receives funding from many sources and makes 
disbursements in a coordinated manner to ensure accurate audited 
payments and quality control of work.  WesMin also monitors 
results, reports on progress, conducts surveys, works out 
procedural approaches, offers coordination among several 
agencies, holds meetings, and serves as the information center 
for the project.<BR><BR>

<B>Project Objectives</B><BR><BR>

     <UL><LI>Plant 2,000 acres of Short Rotation Wood Crops (SRWC) within 
a 50 mile radius of Alexandria, MN as a scale-up demonstration, 
using National Biofuels Roundtable principles and guidelines.
     <LI>Use knowledge and experience gained to improve efficiency.
     <LI>Improve yield information by planting more acres of 
preferred hybrid poplar clones to the extend they are available 
from nurseries.  
     <LI>Expand available sites for continued monitoring of the 
infra-structure, economic, and environmental aspects of scale-up 
size plantations.  Target larger tracts in 1995.
     <LI>Continue work with nurseries to expand both clonal varieties 
and numbers of hybrid poplar cuttings produced.  
     <LI>Refine protocol for a scale-up requiring up to 10,000 acres 
per year.
     <LI>Expand public meetings to encourage increased landowner 
interest and opportunities for future expansion.
     <LI>Demonstrate viable alternatives for land in the soon to be 
expired Conservation Reserve Program.</UL><BR>
<BR>

<B>Additional Activities</B><BR>
<BR>
     The WesMin RC&D Council recently hosted a meeting to 
determine landowner/grower interest in forming a cooperative.  
The MN Extension Service, the Cooperative Development Service, 
the Agricultural Utilization and Research Institute are providing 
invaluable technical and planning assistance.  The cooperative 
would serve many purposes including;<BR>
<BR>
<OL> 
     <LI>Marketing
     <LI>Technical Transfer
     <LI>Communication
     <LI>Technical Assistance
     <LI>Technical Assistance
     <LI>Other Services</OL><BR>
<BR>
     
     The formation of a growers association is very likely.  
Project sponsors continue to work toward commercialization of 
hybrid poplar plantings.  Planning is now in progress to invite 
private industry to take an active role in the planting of hybrid 
poplar plantations to help meet their resource demands.  Several 
companies have indicated an interest to becoming partners to 
plant hybrid poplar.  A consortium of people directly involved 
with hybrid poplar commercialization and research was recently 
formed to improve communications and maintain continuity in 
Minnesota.<BR>
<BR>

     WesMin is directly involved in research efforts focused on 
herbicide trials, plastic mulch, and genetic trials.  Additional 
research activities led by the University of Minnesota and the 
Natural Resources Research Institute relate to small mammal and 
soil resource studies.<BR>
<BR>
 <FONT SIZE=4>For more information about this project contact WesMin RC&D at 612-763-4733, Fax: 612-763-4174.</FONT><BR>
<BR>


