Development".  <i>Advances in Solar Energy.</i>  Annual Review of Research and
Development.  Volume 7. American Solar Energy Society. 1992<p>
<a name="fn3">[3]</a> In many cases waste wood costs significantly less than coal, on a
dollars per million Btus basis. The cost of wood to the Blandin plant in Grand
Rapids, Minnesota, for example, is $7 per ton for sawmill wood waste, equal to
about 80 cents per million Btus(MMBtus).  <p>
<a name="fn4">[4]</a>  Williams and Larson project the lowest costs.  See Robert H.
Williams and Eric D. Larson. "Advanced Gasification-Based Biomass Power
Generation"  in Thomas B. Johansson, et. al.  editors, <i>Renewable Energy.</i>
Island Press.  1993.  Williams and Larson base their estimates on the use of
forest residues. Mark Paisley of Battelle Institute projects a cost of about
6.0 cents per kWh.  Conversation with Mark Paisley.  March 22, 1994.  Shell Oil
estimates the cost of electricity from a soon-to-be-operational Brazilian
gasifier/gas turbine at 5-6 cents per kWh.  Conversation with Eric Larson of
Princeton University.  March 18, 1994. <p>
<a name="fn5">[5]</a> George A. Wiltsee, Jr., Charles R. McGowin and Evan E. Hughes.
<i>Biomass Combustion Technologies for Power Generation</i>.  First Biomass
Conference of the Americas.  Burlington, VT. September 1993 and George A.
Wiltsee Jr. <i>Strategic Analysis of Biomass and Waste Fuels for Electric Power
Generation</i>.  Electric Power Research Institute.  November 1993. <p>
<a name="fn6">[6]</a> Assuming a cost of wood of $2.22 per MMBtus.  George A. Wiltsee,
Jr., Charles R. McGowin and Evan E. Hughes. <i>Biomass Combustion Technologies
for Power Generation</i>.  First Biomass Conference of the Americas.
Burlington, Vermont. September 1993<p>
<a name="fn7">[7]</a>  The cost of western coal is $1.10-1.40 per million Btus.<p>
<a name="fn8">[8]</a> The Irland Group and Dames &amp; Moore. <i> Assessment of
Situation and Potential for Co-firing Coal and Biomass in Energy
Facilities.</i> Report to Great Lakes Regional Biomass Energy Program.  March
24, 1993. <p>
<a name="fn9">[9]</a>
 Conversation with Ed Woolsey, Iowa Department of Natural Resources.  March 21,
1994.
<a name="fn10">[10]</a> Higher efficiencies will come about primarily through the use of
supercritical technologies used in Europe.  These operate at very high
pressures.<p>
<a name="fn11">[11]</a> Conversation with David Ostlie. President, Energy Performance
Systems.  March 21, 1994<p>
<a name="fn12">[12]</a> Ralph P. Overend and Christopher J. Rivard. <i>Thermal and
Biological Gasification</i>.  National Renewable Energy Laboratory.  Golden,
Colorado.  1992. <p>
<a name="fn13">[13]</a> Conversation with Eric Larson, Princeton University.  March 18,
1994. <p>
<a name="fn14">[14]</a> Donald R. Glenn, <i>Direct Fuel Cell Program.</i>   Fuel Cell
Engineering Corporation. Danbury, CT. 1993<p>
<a name="fn15">[15]</a> ERC, in association with United Power Association of Minnesota
and several other utilities, is examining the potential for using landfill gas
as the fuel for its fuel cell.  A commercial operation of such a system would
lead to increased research and development in the use of biogas. <p>
<a name="fn16">[16]</a> Richard Woods and James Lefeld.  <i>Assessment of Ethanol-Fueled
IMHEX Fuel Cell Power Plants in Distributed Generation</i>.  First Biomass
Conference of the Americas.  Burlington, Vermont. September 1993.<p>
<a name="fn17">[17]</a> Assuming a cost of poplars of $18 per green ton. <p>
<a name="fn18">[18]</a> A tax exempt authority like a municipal utility would qualify for
a direct payment while a profit making entity would be entitled to a tax
credit.  Regrettably, at this writing, although the tax credit is immediately
available, Congress has provided no funds for the direct payment.<p>
<a name="fn19">[19]</a> Blair G. Swezey, Kevin L. Porter and J. Sherman Feher, <i>The
Potential Impact of Externalities Considerations on the Market for Biomass
Power Technologies</i>. National Renewable Energy Laboratory.  August 1993.
First value for biomass represents total externalities without carbon dioxide
credits for carbon dioxide absorbed in the growing of the plant matter.  Second
value assumes offsets. <p>
<a name="fn20">[20]</a> Minnesota estimates were not used.  This was done in part because
they are interim values and may change significantly in the next few months.
And also because the MPUC used a wide range of values. For example, the interim
values for SO2 range from zero to $300 per ton.  For Carbon Dioxide, the single
most important pollutant, comprising up to 90 percent of the total pollution
cost of fossil fuels,  the interim values range from $5.99 to $13.60 per ton.
Wisconsin used a $15.00 per ton cost of carbon dioxide.   
