<HTML> <HEAD><TITLE>ILSR Press Release 2/5/97-Ethanol Report</TITLE></HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> PRESS RELEASE<BR>Date:  February 5, 1997<P>Contact:  <!-- MailTo Tag --><A HREF="MAILTO:dmorris@ilsr.org">David Morris</A>, dmorris@ilsr.org<H3>Institute:  While Comprehensive, Errors in Legislative Auditor's Report Reduce its Value</H3>Minneapolis, MN- The director of the Institute for Local Self-Reliance said that a legislative auditor's report on Minnesota's ethanol industry, while comprehensive, contains several major errors of fact which mar the report's overall value.<P>"I am pleased that the legislative auditor apparently has recognized the comprehensive and remarkably successful strategy Minnesota has used to promote a homegrown transportation industry", says Dr. David Morris, Vice President of the Minneapolis and Washington, D.C. based Institute for Local Self-Reliance.  "Unfortunately, several major errors of fact and interpretation mar the report's overall value and endow it with an unnecessarily negative tone." <P>Morris said the success of Minnesota's homegrown fuels strategy is evident.  The industry started with one small plant in 1987 and will grow by the end of 1997 to 11 plants with nearly 1400 workers are employed in jobs that pay from $9-14 per hour, with health insurance and other benefits.   Almost two thirds of the 150 million gallons of ethanol Minnesota drivers consume each year is now produced in the state.  Ethanol accounts for about 4 percent of the state's transportation fuel.  <P>"As the auditor's report recognizes, the farmer-owned nature of Minnesota's ethanol plants combined with their small scale have combined to give the industry the flexibility they need in an era of volatile corn prices.  When corn prices hit their historic highs last summer the very large corporate owned ethanol plants in Iowa shut down while Minnesota's smaller cooperatively owned plants continued to operate", says Morris.  "These are not branch plants of some large corporation.  These are locally owned businesses that are figuratively and literally rooted in their communities."<P>Morris said that, unfortunately, these important facts are overshadowed by errors in the auditor's cost-benefit analysis of the state's ethanol industry.  The auditor estimates that if all of the state's ethanol incentives showed up in the pump price, the cost would be 1.1-3.3 cents a gallon.  Morris said the lower estimate is the equivalent cost of the state's tax incentives for ethanol, which is accurate.  The higher figure is inaccurate.<P>"The higher figure assumes that even with the tax incentives, the price of ethanol is higher than the price of competing oxygenates or gasoline octane enhancers.  This is untrue.    It may be that the cost of gasoline in oxygenated areas is higher than in non-oxygenated areas but that has nothing to do with the price of ethanol.  As farmers know from long experience, the retail price can go up while the price they receive stays low," Morris said.<P>Morris said that he was disappointed and somewhat surprised that the auditor failed to compare the economic incentives provided to ethanol with those provided to gasoline.  Last summer, the Institute issued a widely reported study entitled,  "Oil Slickers: How Petroleum Benefits at the Taxpayers Expense",  that provided a detailed expert examination of gasoline subsidies. <P>In that report, Dr. Jenny Wahl, one of the nation's leading tax experts, estimated that Minnesota pay over 30 cents per gallon in subsidies for tax and other incentives provided to the petroleum industry.  The study looked at tax incentives provided to the petroleum industry, the cost of cleaning up pollution associated with gasoline and defense costs to protect access to oil reserves.<P>The study found that Minnesota motorists pay 1.45 cents per gallon more for gasoline because of tax incentives provided to the oil industry.  Minnesotans also pay 1-2 cents per gallon more to fund the cleanup of the pollution caused by underground gasoline tanks.<P>"The bottom line is that for 1.1 cents per gallon Minnesotans have created a vibrant, highly competitive and constantly innovating homegrown industry based on renewable resources.  On the other hand, Minnesotans continue to pay over 30 cents per gallon in incentives to a nonrenewable fuels industry increasingly based on imported crude oil that provides few if any long term benefits to this state," Morris said.<P>Morris was critical of the audit's environmental conclusion because it focuses almost entirely on ethanol's impact on carbon monoxide and relies entirely on a highly controversial report by one scientific body.  He said that conclusion is "counter intuitive and is contradicted by many peer reviewed studies on the subject."<P>The report by the National Research Council, which the auditor used in reaching its environmental conclusions, was also criticized by the Environmental Engineering Program at the University of California, Berkeley.  In a letter to the NRC, two professors from the Program raised questions concerning the report's findings on air quality impacts of oxygenated fuels and said there was a "systematic bias in the NRC report against studies where oxygenated gasoline was found to reduce carbon monoxide."<P>Morris said he was also disappointed that the auditor did not take into account the comparative environmental impact of ethanol versus the elements of gasoline it displaces, which he refers to as a "chemical stew."  He said that when ethanol is used in the gas tanks of cars, it displaces the most toxic parts of gasoline.    One scientific analysis found that a 10 percent ethanol blend reduces the overall toxicity of gasoline by an astounding 21 percent. <P>"Overall, it's a very comprehensive report that provides probably the most complete analysis of ethanol I have ever seen.  Unfortunately, because of errors and misinterpretations, its use is limited", Morris concluded.<P>The Institute for Local Self-Reliance is a 22 year old organization established to foster environmentally sound economic development.  Working in the energy field for more than 20 years, Dr. David Morris has written three books on energy and has served as an advisor to local, state, and federal governments in the U.S. and abroad, as well as to private businesses, on economic development policy.<P><HR>Return to the <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/">Sustainable Minnesota Home Page</A></BODY> </HTML> 
