<HTML> <!-- Head Tag -->
<HEAD><TITLE>GAO Report Says Cutting Ethanol Tax Incentives Would Increase Deficit</TITLE>                  

</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>GAO Report Says Cutting Ethanol Tax Incentives Would Increase Deficit</H2>
 
                      
    According to a new report by the General Accounting Office (GAO), the investigative arm of Congress, eliminating the ethanol tax incentive "results in a
net loss to the U.S. Treasury and lower farm income from corn."<P>

   Over a five year period from 1996 to the year 2000, the GAO said, the Treasury
could lose from $2.5 billion to more than $6.3 billion because of increased farm
support payments to corngrowers.<P>

   GAO calculated the effect on government agricultural payments in two ways --
one, assuming a 50 percent cut in ethanol production because of the proposed tax
change, and two, a much sharper 90 percent drop in ethanol.<P>

   Estimates of the effects ranged from $2.5 billion to $3.2 billion
in increased government payments to farmers if ethanol production were cut in
half.  If production suffered a 90 percent drop, government costs could soar
from $5.4 billion to as much as $6.3 billion over the 1996- 2000 period.<P>

   GAO also pointed out that farmers' incomes would suffer dramatically as a
result.  Not only would corngrowers be affected, but so would growers of wheat,
sorghum, barley and other crops.<P>

   The plan to cut ethanol's tax incentive program is being pushed by Rep. Bill
Archer (R-Tex.), chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.<P>

CONTACT: Dean Reed at Fuels for the Future, 202-223-3532

   
<P>

<I><FONT SIZE=2>From:  PR Newswire, September 20, 1995</FONT></I>
</BODY>
