</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Speech Biomass Electricity Economics</title></head><body><p>
<H2>The Economics of Plant Matter Derived Electricity</H2><p>
David Morris, Vice President<p>
Institute for Local Self-Reliance<p><p>

<I>Originally delivered at the conference titled, "Renewable Electricity:  Farming a Sustainable Energy Crop", in Collegeville, Minnesota, March 22, 1994.</I>
<p>
	Plant matter fueled power plants are not a new phenomenon.   But when electric
utilities gained a monopoly over electric generation in the 1920s they
forestalled any further development of small scale, biomass power plants.  In
1978 there was only about 200 MW of biomass electric generating capacity in the
U.S.  <p>
<p>
	In 1978 the Public Utilities Regulatory Policy Act(PURPA) abolished the
monopoly utilities had on electric power sales and required utilities to
purchase power from, and supply electricity at non-discriminatory rates to
independent power producers.   <p>
		<p>
	PURPA, plus the rising cost of oil in the early 1980s, increased biomass
electric generating capacity to over 6,000 MW by 1992.  Almost 90 percent of
this was generated from wood.  The rest was primarily generated from municipal
garbage incinerators.  <p>
<p>
	Estimates of the number of wood fired power plants ranges from 600 to almost
1,000.  Most are small, in the 10-25 MWe range.    Only a third of these plants
offer electricity for sale.  The rest are owned and operated by the paper and
wood products industries for their own use.  <p>
<p>
	In the last eight years the rate of introduction of wood electric plants
peaked and then fell dramatically. In 1986, 1839 MWe from wood burning
generators went into operation,  more than 60 percent of the 3054 MWe of power
introduced from 1980 to 1985.  But as the price of oil declined and federal tax
incentives ended the rate of introduction of wood fired power plants dropped.
In 1989, 614 MWe of wood fueled electricity went into operation.  In 1990 that
number fell to 250-300 MWe<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn1">[1]</a> and
may have been below 200 MWe in 1993.  <p>
<p>
	The cost of electricity from wood fired power plants is 6.5 to over 9.0 cents
per kWh.  With heat rates of 14,000-18,000 Btus per kWh these plants have
efficiencies of 18-24 percent.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn2">[2]</a>
They are competitive only inasmuch as they can receive feedstock at very low
prices.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn3">[3]</a> <p>
<p>
	Although a considerable quantity of waste wood is still available for electric
generation, the rising cost of lumber and the increasing use of waste wood for
engineered wood products dims the prospects that this would constitute a large,
reliable long term feedstock.  Today biomass electricity focuses on new
feedstocks like fast growing trees or cellulosic crops like switchgrass or
alfalfa.   <p>
<p>
	Yet except for the use of wood as a feedstock in a mix with coal in power
plants,  the new forms of biomass electrification have not yet been
commercially tested.  That makes a discussion of their economics highly
speculative.    Unlike wind turbines, which have a 10 year track record of
reliable operation, an installed capacity of over 1500 MW in the United States
and a price, based on competitive bidding, of 5 cents per kWh or below, the new
biomass electric plants lack a track record and in some cases do not even have
significant demonstration test data.  <p>
<p>
	Biomass electrification has certain disadvantages compared to wind
electricity.    Wind electric developers could focus on improving the
conversion efficiency of their turbines.  The wind was going to blow and
although it might vary in speed and direction it would not vary in content.
Biomass electric developers, on the other hand, must convince farmers to grow
their fuel or they cannot build a power plant.  And the compositiono f biofuels
varies substantially among different crops.  Farmers will not raise a fuel crop
unless guaranteed a market.  This represents a classic chicken-and-egg dilemma.
<p>
<p>
	Biomass has one important advantage over wind.  It comes with its own built-in
storage system.  Therefore, biomass electric plants can operate as baseload
plants as well as intermediate and peaking plants.   Thus biomass based
independent power producers can earn capacity credits for generating
electricity.  And since baseload plants, either coal or nuclear, are the
dirtiest kinds of power generation because of their air pollutants or wastes,
biomass power plants might be able to gain significant pollution credits .<p>
<p>
	Table A offers an overview of the comparative economics of various biomass
electric technologies, a new coal plant with flue gas desulfurization and a
natural gas fired combined cycle turbine.  These figures should be viewed with
caution.  They are more useful as a measure of comparative costs than of actual
costs.  The greatest controversy are might be in the estimates of the cost of
advanced wood gasification combined cycle(GCC). Some have estimated a cost of
electricity at 4-6 cents per kWh.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn4">[4]</a><p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Table A:</b> <b>Performance and Cost Estimates for Electric Technologies</b><a href="bspch1fn.html#fn5">[5]</a><p>
<p>
<!-- Table Tag -->
<TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=2>
<TR><TD><B>Technology</B></TD><TD><B>MW</B></TD><TD><B>Btus/kWh</B></TD><TD><B>Efficiency</B></TD><TD><B>$/kW</B></TD><TD><B>¢/kWh</B></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Co-firing coal w/15% wood</TD><TD>200</TD><TD>10,283</TD><TD>33.7</TD><TD>105</TD><TD>2.3</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Natural gas combined cycle</TD><TD>120</TD><TD>7,900</TD><TD>43.2</TD><TD>770</TD><TD>4</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>WTE</TD><TD>100</TD><TD>10,654</TD><TD>32</TD><TD>1,341</TD><TD>5.1</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>WTE</TD><TD>50</TD><TD>10,661</TD><TD>32</TD><TD>1,722</TD><TD>6</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Wood fired stoker boiler</TD><TD>50</TD><TD>13,883</TD><TD>24.6</TD><TD>1,780</TD><TD>7.5</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Current wood/GCC</TD><TD>50</TD><TD>12,369</TD><TD>27.6</TD><TD>2,466</TD><TD>8.7</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Advanced Wood/GCC</TD><TD>100</TD><TD>9,769</TD><TD>34.8</TD><TD>2,128</TD><TD>7.3</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>New Coal/FGD</TD><TD>200</TD><TD>10,020</TD><TD>34.1</TD><TD>1,900</TD><TD>6</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD></TD><TD></TD><TD></TD><TD></TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
<p>
<p>
	I would like to briefly discuss each of these technologies, beginning with
those with the nearest term prospects and clearest economics and ending with
the more speculative technologies.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>*	CO-FIRING BIOMASS WITH COAL</b><p>
<p>
	Mixing biomass with coal is not uncommon in the pulp and paper industry or the
utility industry.    Ratios of 10-20 percent biomass are often used in
co-firing.  An Electric Power Research Institute analysis concluded that the
cost of electricity from co-firing coal with 15 percent wood is about 2.8 cents
per kWh.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn6">[6]</a>    The economics of
co-firing look very good if wood can be purchased for less than the cost of
coal.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn7">[7]</a>  However, biomass could
cost more than coal and still be economically attractive if the power plant or
independent power producer were to gain environmental benefits.  NSP's Bayfront
power plant in northern Wisconsin reportedly has sufficiently reduced sulfur
dioxide emissions by using wood that it has qualified for a $2 per ton emission
credit under the Clean Air Act.  And ash from its wood fired boilers is
suitable for land spreading as an agricultural amendment.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn8">[8]</a><p>
<p>
	Agricultural crops could also be co-fired with coal but since they contain
high levels of contaminants they would be used in smaller proportions.
However, Denmark has built a dedicated boiler to burn small grain straw with
coal at very high percentages and has reported a 50 percent reduction in SO2
emissions.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn9">[9]</a> <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>*	WHOLE TREE ENERGY (WTE)</b><p>
<p>
	WTE is a patented technology developed by Energy Performance Systems of
Minnesota.  Aside from co-firing, WTE is the nearest term candidate for
generating significant biomass electricity.  <p>
<p>
	WTE reduces costs below those of conventional wood fired stoker boilers in
several areas. Harvesting costs are cut by $4-6 per ton by eliminating the need
for a skidder and chipper.  The very small furnace reduces capital costs.  The
system design achieves a heat rate of about 10,000 Btus per kWh compared to the
14,000 Btus for recent wood stokers.  Most wood fired plants operate at low
pressures and low temperatures and have a cycle efficiency of l5-25 percent.
WTE projects a 33 percent efficiency for its first plant,  a 42 percent
efficiency rate for its second plant and an ultimate efficiency approaching 50
percent, in the range of gas fired combined cycle turbines.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn10">[10]</a>  <p>
<p>
	The developers of WTE, Energy Performance Systems estimate that the cost of
electricity from a 100 MWe plant would be about 5 cents but that subsequent
plants would generate electricity at 4.3 cents per kWh.  According to EPS,
sufficient private capital is available to build a 100 MWe electric plant at a
long term contract price of 5.0 cents per kWh.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn11">[11]</a>  <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>* 	GASIFICATION</b><p>
<p>
	Gasifiers are quite common throughout the world.  They are mostly small units
but several larger ones have been built recently in Finland and Sweden.<a
href="bspch1fn.html#fn12">[12]</a>    Biomass can be gasified and
the raw gas run into a boiler to generate steam that goes into a turbine.   For
many people, the real goal is to gasify biomass and run it into a high
efficiency gas turbine.  However,  biomass generated gas contains a large
amount of contaminants:  particulates, alkali gases, tars.  These must be
removed before the gas enters the turbine.  The cleanup of this gas constitutes
the major obstacle to using biomass gas in gas turbines.<p>
<p>
	There are several gasification turbine plants about to become operational.  A
pressurized gasifier will be operational in Sweden by the middle of 1994.  It
will be fueled by wood chips and will generate 6 MW of electricity and 20 MW of
heat for a district heating system.  A Brazilian gasification plant of 25-30
MWe will be operational in 1995.    A Shell Oil evaluation of the Brazilian
plant estimates a capital cost of $1300 per kW and, with a feedstock cost from
eucalyptus wood chips of $2.50 per MMBtu a total cost of 5-6 cents per kWh.<a
href="bspch1fn.html#fn13">[13]</a>  A third type of gasifier that
uses as its feedstock bagasse from sugar cane will be operational early next
year in Hawaii. <p>
<p>
	These three gasification power plants will provide the first concrete economic
information at significant scale operations.  That information should be
available by late 1995.<p>
<p>
	At least one company in Wisconsin is currently looking to repower an abandoned
coal fired power plant by gasifying switchgrass.  The coal plant lacks a grate,
a necessary and expensive item for a wood fired power plant.  Gasifying the
switchgrass would avoid the need for a grate and constitute about the same
capital investment.<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>*</b>	<b>FUEL CELLS</b><p>
<p>
	Although biomass is rarely discussed with regard to fuel cells, recent
developments may make that appropriate.  Energy Research Corporation(ERC) has
developed an unusual purchasing collaborative with many municipal and
cooperative utilities to develop a small scale molten carbonate fuel cell.
Unlike conventional power plants, fuel cells do not convert water to steam to
generate electricity.   A fuel is fed into the fuel cell and the cell generates
electricity directly.  Furthest along toward commercialization among the
various fuel cell technologies is ERC's 2 MW molten carbonate uel cell, the
first of which will be operational in Santa Clara in 1995.  <p>
<p>
	For the National Rural Electric Cooperative Association ERC has evaluated the
use of low proof ethanol for their fuel cell.  Ethanol as an automotive fuel is
blended with gasoline and thus must eliminate virtually all of the water
normally contained in alcohol.    Ethanol for ERC's fuel cell can be used at
concentrations of 15-30 percent rather than 100 percent.  This can lower the
production cost of ethanol by as much as 30 percent.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn14">[14]</a>  Even with this 30 percent reduction, ethanol is
still much more expensive than natural gas, but if the ethanol tax credit were
available the price would be much more competitive.  It could also be possible
to gasify biomass and use that as a fuel or to convert that gas into methanol,
an easier to use alcohol than ethanol as the fuel for a fuel cell.<a
href="bspch1fn.html#fn15">[15]</a> <p>
<p>
	Another company, M-C Power Corporation, is developing fuel cells projects a
higher cost for natural gas in the near future and sees ethanol being used as a
backup fuel to allow the developer to contract for interruptible natural gas.
Presently this would lead to a 30-70 cents per million Btu price reduction.
According to the company, this could allow for a cost effective operation of
the power plant on ethanol for 5-10 percent of the year.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn16">[16]</a>  <p>
<p>
	<p>
<b>FEEDSTOCKS</b><p>
<p>
	It appears that in the next 3-5 years,  biomass electrification will come in
three forms:  wood fired power plants where very low cost waste wood is
available;  co-firing of biomass with coal;  whole tree energy plants.    In
the 5-10 year time frame biomass gasification into gas turbines will come
on-line, using a variety of feedstocks.  Whole tree energy plants will depend
on fast growing trees--probably willows or poplars in Minnesota's climate.
Co-firing or direct combustion or gasification can rely on either fast growing
trees or crops.  <p>
<p>
	The two crops examined in the Minnesota situation are switchgrass and alfalfa.
In Wisconsin and Iowa the focus appears to be on switchgrass.  Minnesota is
focusing on alfalfa. <p>
<p>
	Plans for an alfalfa powered electric plant presume an alfalfa processing
facility that strips off the high protein leaves.  This portion of the plant
will be sold as a high value feed.  Assuming a $125 per ton price for the
leaves, the remaining 60 percent of the plant that is cellulose can be used as
a fuel at a cost of about $1.60 per MMbtus, a price competitive with fast
growing trees and only slightly higher than coal.  If the price for the alfalfa
were to drop to $90 per ton, the cost of fuel would have to increase to $2.50
per MMbtus to achieve the same profit.  This is twice the price of coal and is
in the upper range of the cost of fast growing trees.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn17">[17]</a><p>
<p>
	An alfalfa based power plant would have two revenue centers.  The revenue from
the sale of the protein meal would be significantly greater than the sale of
the electricity.  <p>
<p>
	It is projected that farmers will grow alfalfa for a fuel crop if they receive
$60 per ton.  Switchgrass requires a selling price of around $36 a ton.  But
switchgrass will not have a significant feed market, so its cost on a million
Btu basis will be in the same range as alfalfa.  Indeed, the economics of both
of these crops depends to a significant degree on the yield and the operating
expenses and these depend both on the farmer and on the evolving learning
curve.<p>
<p>
	It is quite possible that in the future we will see a combination of energy
crops, depending on the kind of soil and location.  For example, some in Iowa
are thinking of planting switchgrass on the hilly sections of land as a soil
erosion reduction crop and planting woody crops like willows or poplars near
rivers that might flood.    <p>
<p>
	Aside from the construction of a Whole Tree Energy plant, the strategy for
many is to encourage dedicated energy crops by substituting biomass for coal in
coal fired power plants.  The next step is to move to gasification and finally
to gasification into a gas turbine or conceivably, into a fuel cell.  <p>
<p>
	Many coal fired power plants are operating at low capacities or are in the
process of being shut down.  One Wisconsin developer is seeking to purchase an
abandoned coal power plant.  Capital costs could be as little as $300-500.  The
plant would initially use up to 15 percent biomass.  The biomass would then be
gasified and the raw gas sent directly into the boiler.  This particular coal
plant lacks a grate, a necessary ingredient for a biomass plant and the cost of
installing a grate is in the same range as the cost of gasifying the biomass.
A final step would be to install a high efficiency gas turbine.   <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>ENVIRONMENTAL ADDERS AND REGULATORY INTERVENTION</b><p>
<p>
	The discussion to date has ignored current and possible future incentives for
biomass electrification.  These should be factored into any economic
discussion.  The Energy Policy Act of 1992 provides for a 1.5 cent per kWh tax
credit or producer payment.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn18">[18]</a>
This production payment is available to a biomass electric plant that is in
operation by December 1999 and runs for 10 years.  It is only available for
power plants that rely on dedicated fuel crops.  Biomass electric plants that
use feedstocks like existing forest stands are ineligible. <p>
<p>
	The 1.5 cent per kWh producer payment would bring even wood fired stokers near
the 5.0 cent per kWh level, assuming they used dedicated fuel crops.  It would
bring the cost of WTE technology to as low as 4.0 cents per kWh.<p>
<p>
	Feedstock costs might also be much lower than $1.50-$2.50 per million Btus if
Conservation Reserve Program land were used.   This might not affect
agricultural crops like alfalfa that have existing markets but could affect
fast growing trees.  CRP farmers receive an annual payment plus money to offset
part of their costs of establishing fast growing trees.  About 1.8 million
acres of cropland is in CRP in Minnesota.  <p>
<p>
	Changing federal regulations might affect agricultural crops.  In the
beginning of 1994 the federal government gave kenaf growers the right to
substitute kenaf for program crops without losing federal program payments.
Thus a farmer in Texas could grow kenaf rather than cotton or corn and still
receive his or her program payment for the acreage formerly planted in cotton
or corn.  Kenaf is not a food or feed crop and therefore such an incentive
encourages a new crop that has industrial uses but does not compete with
existing crops.  A federal exemption for agricultural crops like switchgrass
that are grown specifically as an energy crop might be viewed in the same
light.<p>
<p>
	Finally,  eight state regulatory commissions, including Minnesota's have
quantified the environmental costs of power plants.  Minnesota's Public Utility
Commission issued interim rates in January 1994. A formal proceeding is
currently in process to estimate the final rates.  In almost all cases such
rates are used by regulatory commissions or utilities to decide what type of
power plant to build or what kind of electricity to buy.  <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<b>Table B: </b>
<b>Environmental Adders</b><a href="bspch1fn.html#fn19">[19]</a><b></b>
<b>(cents per kWh )</b><p>

<p><!-- Table Tag -->
<TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=1 BORDER=2>
<TR><TD>Technology</TD><TD>Wisconsin</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Coal</TD><TD>1.8</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Coal IGCC</TD><TD>1.4</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Coal pulverized NSPS</TD><TD>1.7</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Natural Gas-Combustion Turbine</TD><TD>1.2</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Natural Gas-Combined Cycle</TD><TD>0.7</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Wood-steam</TD><TD>2.7/0.1</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Biomass Advanced Gasification</TD><TD>1.1/0.1</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
	Table B provides the environmental costs of various power plants based on the
Wisconsin Public Service Commission's estimates.<a href="bspch1fn.html#fn20">[20]</a>  The dual values for wood are based on whether wood
is given credit for the carbon dioxide absorbed as it grows.  If, as seems
reasonable, this is done, then biomass electrification in virtually any form
would have almost a 1.5 cent per kWh advantage over coal and almost a penny
advantage over even high efficiency natural gas.  A state or federal carbon tax
or regulations regarding carbon dioxide emissions would increase the
comparative advantage of biomass.  <p>
<p>
	Both the federal tax credit and environmental adders also make wind and other
forms of solar energy more competitive.    As noted at the beginning of this
paper,  although wind may displace some baseload capacity it is primarily an
intermediate power plant.    A biomass power plant may also be an intermediate
or even peaking power plant but it can substitute for base load plants that run
almost all of the times.  Unlike a wind farm that may generate electricity at
full power only 25-30 percent of the year, a biomass fueled power plant can
operate at 75-85 percent capacity factors. <p>
	 <p>
<p>
<b>BIOREFINERIES</b><p>
<p>
	The proposed NSP alfalfa fueled power plant offers the vision of multiple
market crops.  In that case the alfalfa is processed into a high protein feed
with the residue burned or gasified to generate electricity.    In the future
we might see high fiber sugar crops like sweet sorghum also used to make liquid
fuels like ethanol as well as electricity.  Already at least one company is
using an advanced pyrolysis process--similar to the process used to make
charcoal--to make intermediate chemicals like carbon black and phenolic acid
and number six fuel oil.   Another company is seeking financing to convert
cellulosic feedstocks like yard waste or grasses into ethanol.  The byproduct
of that process will be lignin, a potentially very valuable chemical that
currently is burned but may soon become more valuable for industrial uses.<p>
<p>
	The value of plant matter used for generating electricity is very low--$15-30
per ton.  Compare that with the value of plant matter as a food or feed--$75
for corn.  And if the plant matter were used for industrial uses it might have
a still higher value.  <p>
<p>
	The basic point is that even as environmental regulations change and new
biomass electrification technologies are introduced,  we are learning to make
even more valuable end products from plant matter.   Thus it may be that while
we will see some dedicated woody crops used solely for generating electricity,
in many other cases rural communities will be dotted with multiple product
biorefineries, producing not only electricity but liquid fuels and feed and
even chemicals.  <p>
<p>
<p>
<b>CONCLUSION</b><p>
<p>
	Dedicated energy crops as well as agricultural and wood wastes can already
compete with coal in certain cases, specifically, as a low cost way to reduce
pollution by using up to 15 percent biomass mixtures with coal.  Whole tree
energy technology may be competitively priced with wind in Minnesota in 1994.
More exotic technologies like biomass gasification for high efficiency gas
turbines and biomass derived liquid and gaseous fuels used in fuel cells will
have to await the late 1990s before concrete economic information is
available.<p>
<p>
</body></html>
