<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>ME3 Comments on DPS 1996 Energy Policy and Conservation Report-September 25, 1996</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>ME3 Comments on Minnesota Department of Public Service's 1996 Energy Policy and Conservation Report</H2>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>September 25, 1996</H3>
<HR>

Commissioner Krista Sanda<BR>
Minnesota Department of Public Service<BR>
Suite 200, 121 7th Place East<BR>
St. Paul, Minnesota   55101-2145<P>

Dear Commissioner Sanda:<P>

The following are the comments of the coalition Minnesotans for an Energy-Efficient Economy (ME3) on the energy policy goals and strategies presented in the Department's draft 1996 Energy Policy and Conservation Report.  The ME3 Coalition represents the range of policy views of all the major organizations working in Minnesota to promote sustainable energy and limit the environmental impacts of energy decisions. <p>
We greatly appreciate the availability of this and other forums for commenting on the proposed quadrennial report.   ME3 Coalition members have formulated consensus positions on sustainable energy policies, and submit the following as proposals for consideration in the Department's final report.  We would be pleased to meet with you at any time to discuss and elaborate on our policy positions. <P>

We find that the report as drafted does not address compelling issues, including social costs and climate change.  The conservation and renewable energy goals presented are far too timid and narrow in scope.  The strategies and action steps resemble suggestions for private initiatives, and not  state-level policy statements that can drive the state toward achieving a sustainable energy system.  In order to serve as a blueprint for the state's actions, the report needs to be revised to focus on propelling the energy transition that the state legislature has already set in motion.<P>

<H3>I. State Energy Goals Should Lead the Transition to a Sustainable Electric Generation System</H3>

The goals presented in the draft report will not promote the transition to a sustainable electric generation system that the legislature has initiated.  Indeed, most notable is the amount of space in the draft report devoted to unsustainable energy sources.  There is lengthy discussion of nuclear power issues, nuclear waste storage and disposal, and nuclear plant relicensingÐall issues that demonstrate the need for state policies leading to a transition to sustainable energy technologies.  <P>

The 1994 legislature established the Electric Energy Task Force (EETF) under Minnesota  statute 216C.051.  The task force's instruction was to study future electric energy sources and costs and to make recommendations for legislation for an environmentally and economically sustainable and advantageous electric energy supply.<P>

The statute provided detailed guidelines for preferred electric generation sources as follows:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The highest priority is conservation of energy and management of demand.<P>

	The following energy sources are listed in descending order of preference:<BR>
		-wind and solar;<BR>
		-biomass and low-head or refurbished hydropower; <BR>
		-decomposition gases produced by solid waste management facilities, natural gas-fired  cogeneration, and waste materials or byproducts combined with natural gas;<BR>
		-natural gas, hydropower that is not low-head or refurbished hydropower, and solid waste as a direct fuel or refuse-derived fuel; and<BR>
		-coal and nuclear power.<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

Although this statute is advisory to the work of the Electric Energy Task Force, the legislature has stated its goals: (1) to encourage the transition to a sustainable, environmentally cleaner and safer electric generation system; and (2) to generate jobs and income in the state of Minnesota so that the state becomes a net exporter rather than an importer of electric energy goods and services.<P>

Early in 1996 the EETF engaged a consulting team led by Appel Consultants, Inc. to provide information and analyses to support policy development aimed at improving the electric energy system in Minnesota.  Appel's  June 28, 1996 report to the EETF concludes with a statement that encourages pursuit of the transition while exhorting political leaders to take a strong leadership role:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Minnesota's political leaders have a big job to do in the energy policy arena.  Through strong leadership both within the state and at national and international levels, they can set the stage for Minnesota's fledgling renewables industry to grow and to capture major national and international markets.  In the process, the renewable energy industry and the energy efficiency industry can transform Minnesota's own electric energy system into a sustainable one that can ably support the prosperity and health of many future generations of Minnesotans.<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

In comparing the Appel report with the draft Department report (both reports were  issued in July 1996), ME3 is struck by the disparities in the two documents' visions and conclusions.  We consider several of the Appel findings particularly compelling, and ask the Department to incorporate into its report  goals and action steps that reflect the opportunities that Appel has uncovered.<P>

For example, the EETF consultants note that a transition to sustainable energy sources such as wind and biomass presents an opportunity to move in the direction of energy self-sufficiency.  Minnesota expenses for out-of-state energy will double by 2016 to $1.4 billion in the unsustainable scenario.  In the sustainable, self-sufficient scenario, less than $100 million will still be paid out for energy imports, primarily Canadian hydropower.  The Department should push beyond its goal number 4 Ð Promote a self-supporting, innovative industry emphasizing renewable energy and alternative energy development Ð to an eventual  goal of a sustainable, self-sufficient energy system.  The Appel report enumerated the benefits of a sustainable, self-sufficient scenario to include (1) the elimination of the environmental externalities associated with fossil and nuclear generation, and (2) the creation of new jobs and income in the state (possibly offset by job losses caused by higher energy prices).  Two major environmental externalities that will be eliminated are (1) the emission of carbon dioxide and other pollutants, and (2) the production of additional radioactive spent fuel that needs long-term safeguarding.  It is obvious that proceeding toward a sustainable energy system will reduce or eliminate the social costs of energy decisions that the Department calls attention to in its draft.<P>

The Department forecasts that production of alternative energy in Minnesota will increase by 26% from 1994 to 2020.  The proposed Department goal for renewable and alternative energy is that the State should promote an energy industry that emphasizes renewable and alternative energy development.  Therefore, it is important to consider where a 26% increase in alternative energy production will place us:  In 1994, according to the Department, less than 1% of the fuel sources of electric utilities serving Minnesota were indigenous, clean fuels (wind, low-head hydropower, solar, closed- cycle biomass).   The state's renewables promotion policies should seek to greatly improve the proportion of the generation mix that is renewable.  Over the planning horizon of the report, penetration of renewables to 20-25% of the state's fuel sources is a reasonable possibility.  A renewables portfolio standard (discussed below) is one way to achieve that goal.<P>

What is the prospect for clean energy technologies in Minnesota?  One viewpoint was expressed by the expert consulting team picked by the EETF to advise that body on energy technology for the future.  The Appel team advised that up to 20 percent of Minnesota's energy could be readily derived from wind power Ð without the need for energy storage technologies.<P>

What awaits the states or nations that lead the world in energy technologies that mitigate climate change?  The answer seems to be jobs and wealth. Considering just one such clean technology Ð wind Ð Royal Dutch Shell has estimated a $30 billion dollar annual world market in wind energy in 2030, this in a technology area where Minnesota arguably has a competitive advantage over most US states.  A recent study by the American Council for an Energy-Efficient Economy shows that every dollar invested in clean technologies (e.g. renewables and energy efficiency) creates at least twice as many jobs as a dollar spent on dirty technologies (e.g. coal or oil).<P>

<BR>
<H3>II.  The Draft Advocates Consideration of All Social and Environmental Costs,  Yet Omits Any Discussion of Global Climate Change and Mercury Emissions</H3>

The Department calls for consideration of all social costs, including environmental costs,  in evaluating energy policy options, but fails to detail how this will be accomplished.  Chapter 3 of the report alludes to the notion that polluters should bear the costs of externalities.  Again, this concept is not discussed in depth.  We note that the virtue of  pricing energy at its true social cost was highlighted several times in the 1992  quadrennial report.  Four years later, it is time to offer specific recommendations on how to incorporate social costs in evaluating energy alternatives.  The recent order of the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission in the environmental externalities case offers policy direction that should be incorporated in the final Department report.  Specifically, the final report should devote a separate chapter to the explicit social and environmental costs of energy that the state will consider in evaluating future policy options. <P>

Two vital social costs of electric generation Ð global climate change and mercury emissions Ð are mysteriously absent from the draft, yet the Department committed substantial resources to the inclusion of reasonable estimates of the cost of climate change in the recent PUC externality proceedings.  The final report must examine closely how the state can consider these costs in its energy decisions.<P>

<P>

<H4>Global Climate Change</H4><P>

The draft report entirely omits any reference to the problem of global climate change.  By this omission, the report is surely one of very few energy policy reports published this year that omits a discussion of global warming.  As the DPS and the MPCA have forcefully argued in the PUC externality proceedings, the scientific evidence clearly identifies a link between anthropogenic emissions of carbon dioxide and global climate change. The Department is aware that electric utilities produce more than one-third of the CO2 emitted from anthropogenic sources in the United States, and that 80% of those emissions come from coal-fired power plants.  <P>

Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) reports are the most authoritative sources available for information on climate change issues.  The IPCC consists of 2,500 experts from throughout the international scientific community.  The IPCC research and peer review process evaluates all available scientific information on factors affecting climate change.  <P>

Indeed, the IPCC's work has spurred actions by a variety of governments and entities.  Both the cities of Minneapolis and St. Paul, for example, have adopted CO2 reduction plans.  Many other cities, states, and countries are taking action in response to the global warming problem. Similarly, the Minnesota legislature made a political and policy judgement that we should proceed to place a value on environmental costs to the extent practicable. <P>

An Administrative Law Judge (ALJ)  in March of this year concluded that there was sufficient data to support an externality value for carbon dioxide.  In so ruling, the ALJ denied that the uncertainties associated with the general circulation model predictions were sufficient to discredit the IPCC's predictions of global warming.  When it adopted the CO2 value range recommended by the ALJ, the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission sent a signal to coal interests that the State of Minnesota is ready to recognize global climate change.<P>

Scientific consensus on the anthropogenic sources of climate change continues to mount. This summer the IPCC released its Second Assessment, which was widely reported as scientists having found the smoking gun in the close correspondence between the climate record and computer simulations.  The IPCC consensus was that the evidence suggested a discernible human influence on global climate change.  NASA's James Hansen was quoted in a January 1996  Newsweek cover story that he believes that humans are now pushing the earth's climate hard enough that climate change will become obvious to the man on the street in the next decade.<P>

The views of many Minnesotans were sought by the researchers from Appel Consulting,  who conversed extensively with people from across the state.  To Appel, it appeared that citizens' interest in sustainable electricity supply derives not just from concern about Minnesota's environment, but also for that of the entire planet Earth.  Thus their report to the legislature discusses climate change, with the conclusions that man-made emissions are at least partly responsible, and that  a growing public consensus is that something should be done about it.  The Appel report clarifies that climate change also points to an increasing frequency of weather anomalies.  Their economic effects may be most immediately apparent to farmers. Also observing global climate change reports are insurance companies, which must cover insured losses.  "(And) these phenomena have not gone unnoticed by the American public.  Since the late 1970s, every poll in which opinions were solicited has shown an increasing fraction of the public is concerned about environmental issues in general and about global climate change in particular. "<P>

In applying the costs of climate change to Minnesota energy policy, the state must arrive at a common sense discount rate by which to calculate the present costs of future climate change.  Huge, long-term, and irreversible damages such as those likely to be incurred by global climate change cannot reasonably be discounted to negligible costs in present value.  Instead, common sense dictates that social decisions use discount rates of from zero to 2 percent. Discount rates any larger have the effect of trivializing enormous damages, marginalizing our grandchildren, and force the policy conclusion that it is not cost-effective to avoid future damages. A low discount rate is consistent with the requirements of the Minnesota Environmental Policy Act. That statute requires all state departments and agencies to recognize that environmental problems can be global and long-term in range, and thus to lend appropriate support to initiatives designed to prevent a decline in the quality of the world environment. <P>

<BR>
<H4>Mercury </H4><P>

There is sufficient evidence that mercury poses a serious threat to wildlife, human health, and the economy of Minnesota.  There is also sufficient evidence to prove that between one-sixth and one-fourth of all anthropogenic emissions of mercury in the state of Minnesota come from coal-fired power plants.<P>

The weight of this evidence is likely to increase with completion of current research efforts targeted at estimating mercury's environmental damages in the US and in Minnesota.  At the federal level, the Clean Air Act requires the EPA to perform several studies dealing with mercury.  One of those studies is a general review of mercury sources, emission rates, control technologies, and health and environmental effects.  The second is a study focusing on toxic emissions from coal-burning power plants.  Both studies are now overdue to Congress.  At the state level, the MPCA has developed a mercury task force. The 1995 legislature authorized Minnesota-specific studies of the mercury problem.  Given the current level of pertinent research, the state should have adequate information to assign a reliable externality value to mercury emissions in the near future.  Thus the Department 's final report should specifically advocate consideration of mercury emissions costs in future energy policy evaluations, as advocated by the Administrative Law Judge.<P>

<P>

<H3>III.  The Need for Strong State Policies to Promote Sustainable Energy and Protect the Environment Under Restructuring</H3><P>

The state must provide both interim support for renewables and long-term policy to guide any market restructuring in such a way that the long-term public benefit of these technologies is recognized and fostered.  Strong incentives for renewables must be enacted as part of any electric industry restructuring plan.<P>

We believe it is imperative for the state to establish policies to protect Minnesota's environment and its emerging renewables industries.  We call departmental attention to the strong warning issued by Appel Consultants--disinterested parties Ð  regarding the impacts of restructuring:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The deregulated, truly competitive market will select generation technologies and fuels <EM>based on lowest cost</EM> , more effectively than the regulated market does now.  <EM>Renewables will not be selected unless strong measures support them.  Emissions will rise as consumer energy efficiency programs are reduced, and in response to greater consumption of low-priced, coal-based electricity.</EM> (emphasis added)<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

Some of the lowest cost electricity producers in Minnesota are old, paid-off coal plants that were grandfathered under the Clean Air Act and do not meet modern emissions standards.  Most of the old coal units have low capacity factors.  Wholesale wheeling could increase the output from these old, dirty plants.  For Minnesota, this is an environmental downside to wholesale wheeling.  The Appel report suggested an obvious remedy: the state should sunset the grandfathered exemption from new source performance standards that some power plants received as part of the Clean Air Act of 1970.<P>

Appel's caveats about restructuring extend beyond concerns for the future of the state's environment and its renewables industries.  Appel, like the Department, is wary of the emergence of market power and warns legislators in the strongest language to<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>(g)uard against establishing a process that allows the existing dominant firms (utilities) to dominate the process of designing the new system.  This would be a case of having the fox design the henhouse; it may look secure, but be riddled with hidden trap doors.<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

The Department's stated goal number two is to promote competition and customer choice.  Indeed, promoting competition is not merely a future strategy proposed by the Department; pervasive throughout the report is the assumption of imminent retail competition, together with the presumption that retail competition will be in the public's best interest.  The final report  should enumerate the precautionary steps the Department will take to ensure that increased competition does not endanger affordable and reliable electric service for all Minnesotans, or derail the state's transition to a sustainable energy system.<P>

The Department states its support for continued conservation and renewables development.  However, a statement of support in principle is no substitute for public policy.  In the absence of concrete, policy initiatives, public goods like renewable energy and energy efficiency will vanish from the energy landscape.  Policy makers in other states are working to craft  policies suited to their states' situations.  For example, California will be using a non-bypassable wires charge to fund DSM, renewables, and other programs including low income services.  New York, Rhode Island, and other New England states likewise intend to use a wires charge as a funding mechanism.  At the federal level, legislation to mandate renewables portfolio standards has been introduced in the House of Representatives (the Schaefer bill).<P>

<H3>IV.  A Renewables Portfolio Standard as the Preferred Policy Incentive for	Phasing in Renewables</H3>

The Department offers two suggestions for promoting renewable energy industries in a scenario of restructuring.  We are confused in that these prospects are not given equal policy weight, and represent contradictory policy views.<P>

<H4>Customer Choice</H4> <P>

In a reversal from its 1992 stance, the 1996 draft report now de-emphasizes mandated penetration rates and numerical goals for renewable energy.  Instead, it advocates an emphasis on direct incentives.  The Department's preferred approach for supporting renewables is its second energy goal: customer choice.  In the case of electricity choice, the Department is perhaps alluding to the idea generally known as green pricing.  Through green pricing programs, customers may choose to pay a premium rate for renewably generated electricity.  <P>

ME3's position is that green pricing cannot replace comprehensive state policy aimed at creating strong renewables markets with multiple competitors.  Important public policy ends like clean air, clean water, and solutions to climate change cannot be left to the goodwill of a few citizens volunteering by their "vote" in a marketplace.  <P>

What is the underlying demand for green power?  The few green pricing programs that are underway now reveal that fewer customers choose to pay the premiums than willingness-to-pay surveys would suggest; they have also resulted in green power generation on the order of kilowatt-hours, not megawatt-hours.  The market could prove too weak to support anything beyond a few boutique-scale projects.  Green pricing would then have the effect of preventing the development and expansion of cost-effective renewable electricity markets.  It is unlikely that the small voluntary market for green power would be large enough to drive down production costs enough to create an orderly infrastructure build-up of renewables. <P>

The concept of green pricing also has a "free rider" problem.  Every ratepayer receives the benefit of a cleaner environment, but only a few actually pay. Since green pricing is merely an option rather than a public interest policy goal, the method does not acknowledge the idea that renewable energy is important to everyone. Although individual consumers are often willing to pay for public goods when every other consumer is required to do so, they are much less willing to pay for public goods when the program is voluntary.   As an example, few citizens would argue that catalytic converters have helped improve air pollution problems.  But consider how few consumers would be willing to pay an additional fee to have a catalytic converter on their new car if those devices were not mandatory.  <P>

Green pricing is best used as a complementary overlay on a robust integrated resource planning process and other forms of utility support for renewable energy.  Green pricing alone is the equivalent of no renewables policy. If the idea is to use green pricing as a supplement to a portfolio policy, we urge the Department to examine mechanisms for strengthening any green pricing proposal.  For example, green pricing plans should include a price cap with the potential for downward movement in the price premium, in order to prevent inflated pricing on renewables.  Moreover, there would need to be a certification process to ensure that customers really get what they pay for--some state or state-sanctioned certification that the "green" power is actually clean power, and that it is actually being dispatched. <P>


<H4>Renewables Portfolio Standard</H4><P>

The Department's second suggestion for promoting renewable energy in a restructured environment is the portfolio approach.  While it is not clear whether the Department intends to pursue both a renewables portfolio standard and voluntary premium rates for renewables, ME3 prefers that state energy policy focus on the policy mechanism of promoting green generation portfolios, rather than on green pricing.  The draft report mentions only that the renewables portfolio standard "should be considered."   In its final report, the Department needs to commit to<P>

(1)  evaluate the impact on the state renewables industries of enactment of a renewables portfolio standard (including annual increases in the requisite renewables percentage);<P>

(2) evaluate the impact of enacting a non-bypassable wires charge, through which all electricity consumers in Minnesota would support renewables and conservation programs, including research and development into emerging technologies like photovoltaics and fuel cells; and <P>

(3) study combinations of these mechanisms as possible policy thrusts for promoting renewables development and research, and efficiency measures.<P>

<BR>
No matter which policy mechanism or combination is selected to promote efficiency and renewables development, state policy makers need to debate several important questions.  In a more market-oriented electricity system, consumers will need access to impartial information regarding their electricity choices.  For example:<P>

Who will provide the basic consumer education in the options that are available for electric services, and the social costs as well as the private costs of different options?<P>

How can the public be better informed of the importance of social costs and environmental externalities of energy and motivated to support positive change in the electric supply system? <P>

<BR>
<H3>V.  ME3 Supports More Aggressive Energy Efficiency Goals, and a Funding 	Mechanism Such as a Non-bypassable Charge</H3>

As with renewable energy development in Minnesota, the Department has clearly expressed its commitment to energy efficiency improvements. However, the Department's third goal, the "aggressive" efficiency target of at least 30% decrease by 2020 is terribly modest (only slightly more than 1 percent per year!), particularly given the forecast of a 56% increase in energy consumption by 2020.  The state needs to set a truly aggressive efficiency goal in order to propel the sustainable energy transition.<P>

We turn once more to the Appel report to the legislature, which addressed current trends toward utility disinvestment in DSM  and proposed a wires charge as a remedy:  <P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The trend represented by Minnesota utilities' proposed plans to scale back DSM programs appears to be driven primarily by utilities' desire to minimize rates in anticipation of increased competition. <BR>
The trend toward reduced utility involvement in DSM could be reversed by imposing a non-bypassable charge on the retail sales of electricity, and using the funds for public purpose programs such as conservation, energy efficiency, and renewables.<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

The consultants further warned state policy makers that efficiency investments in other, deregulated markets have suffered as a result of restructuring:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>It is not realistic, based on deregulation experiences in the UK, Norway, Argentina, and New Zealand, to expect energy service companies (ESCOs) to achieve energy savings as great as those achieved by traditional utility DSM in the United States.  ESCOs have limited access to funding relative to funding levels associated with traditional utility DSM.<P></BLOCKQUOTE>

Here again, a wires charge for energy efficiency may be the simplest mechanism for ensuring that sufficient funding is available to achieve an aggressive level of energy savings that is in the best interest of all Minnesota energy consumers.  The Department, in its final report, should identify possible structures for strategic reinvestment of DSM dollars through a system-wide wires charge.<P>


Thank you again for this public comment opportunity.  <P>

On behalf of the Board of Directors of the ME3 Coalition,<P>


J. Drake Hamilton<BR>
Policy Coordinator<BR>
<HR>
Return to the <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.me3.org/">Sustainable Minnesota Home Page</A>

