<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HEAD><TITLE>Albuquerque Journal - Featured Story on Access Computer Section</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<body bgcolor="FFFFf4">

<CENTER>
<table width=600>
<TR><TD WIDTH=250>
<CENTER><BR><H1>Native Americans hope to revolutionize Business via Internet</H1></CENTER>
</TD><TD width=200>
<a href="./access2.jpg"><IMG ALIGN="LEFT" border=0 src="./access1.jpg" alt="Albuquerque Access page graphic"></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=150>
<P><i>Reprinted from: The Albuquerque Journal, Access edition (Front Page), December 12, 1995, Albuquerque, NM</i></P>
</TD></TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>Let's say you live among the sandstone buttes in Monument Valley, where the sunburned landscape attracts photographers and rattlesnakes. Where the nearest city of any size is 100 miles away. Where the big technology news of late has been the installation of an automatic teller machine 20 miles down the road in Kayenta, Ariz.</P>
<P>Now let's say you're thinking about <a href="./process.htm">getting on the Internet.</a></P>

<P>It all sounds crazily familiar to Roland Dixon, who runs a business that takes tourists through the Four Corners park in open-air four-by-fours.

Dixon is considering signing on with ATIIN Inc. to develop and post a home page on the World Wide Web, the democratic town square of the Internet. ATIIN, an Albuquerque based company, offers a range of services, from <a href="./website.htm">Web sites</A> to <a href="./lanwan.htm">server networks</A>, primarily to Native American tribes and businesses.</P>

<P>Dixon's Navajo Land Tours already has a fax machine and a toll free phone number. 

Dixon is thinking that a Web page might advertise his tour business in a way that brochures or magazine ads can't.

If everything clicks, he will be able to send out color photos of Mitten Butte and the other wonders of Monument Valley, along with tour information, to millions of Internet users worldwide for an initial investment of several hundred dollars and then $50 a month.</P>

<P>ATIIN stands for Advanced Tribal Integrated Information Networks, the mouthful of a name that Evans Craig, Laurence Brown and Robert Mora have chosen for their fledgling company.

But the word has another meaning to the men, all members of the Navajo tribe. In Dine, the native language of the Navajo people, atiin means "road" or "pathway."</P>

<P>Their slogan: <a href="../cybertrade/">"We put natives on the Net."</A></P>

<P>It is a tall order, for the contradictions between reservation life and computer technology are spiritual as well as physical.

What are the prospects of high-tech finding a home on rural reservations where there is only a 50-50 chance a family grill have a telephone, much less a computer? And what is the relevance of machines and information in culture based on living creatures and nature? </P>

<P>Answers to those questions are the forces behind ATIIN. </P>

<P>"What we saw was a huge need for telecommunications technology," says Craig, a graduate of the Anderson schools of Management at the University of New Mexico. 

Rather than being handicapped by being left on the outside of emerging technology, tribes and individual Indian business people can use the technology to control their messages and build on their strengths, says Craig. </P>

<P>"It levels the playing field," says Brown, a former engineer at Sandia National Laboratories. "If you're on the Web, it doesn't matter if you're out there on the reservation. You can look just as professional as everyone else - even if you don't have a computer or don't even have a phone."</P>

<P>Says Craig, "Ninety percent of the people we deal with say, 'I don't know what a Web page is."</P>

<P>Clients so far include the Gathering of Nations Powwow, Santa Fe Indian Market, the <a href="../uniband/">Turtle Mountain Chippewa's</A> technology corporation, Hopi painter Dan Lomahaftewa, the Mescalero Apache and Navajo tribes, a calendar that features Navajo men and women and a <a href="../arrowfax/">directory</A> for tribal governments and businesses in Canada.</P>

<P>The partners are Craig, a 37 year old native of Shiprock with degrees in management information systems and distance education; Brown, a 33 year old from the Navajo community of Carson who has degrees in chemical engineering and material science engineering; and Mora, a 32 year old native of Ganado, Ariz., who is an electrical engineer.</P>

<P>Craig and Brown were working for Sandia and Mora was employed by Digital Equipment Corp. when the three became acquainted through the American Indian Science and Engineering Society, a professional organization for Native Americans who work in the sciences.

They started the company in June with equipment, business space and a $10,000 grant from Technologies Ventures Corp., a nonprofit organization founded by Lockheed Martin Corp., to transfer Sandia technology into the marketplace.</P>

<P>Brown is the company's president and Craig and Mora serve as vice presidents.</P>

<P>The first step for the company is opening up something they call <a href="../cybertrade/">Native CyberTrade</A>, an on-line shopping mall for Indian businesses. Traders don't have to have their own computer or know anything about the technology.</P>

<P>For a few hundred dollars, Craig, Brown and Mora will design a Web page with text and graphics as well as sound or video. ATIIN has the server, the large computer drive that stores and maintains Web sites. And it has the high-speed data phone lines used to connect servers to the Internet.</P>

<P>It also registers the Web sites by key words&#151;say "Monument Valley," "Southwestern tours," "travel" or anything else that would lead interested browsers to Dixon's page. And it keeps track of the number of "hits," or times someone clicks open the page. ATIIN's server is already seeing 80,000 hits a week.</P>

<P>Santa Fe jeweler Kenneth Johnson has found his Web site, on line since early August, to be better than a printed catalog.</P>

<P>"Every time I hand out my business card, it's like I'm handing out a catalog," says Johnson.</P>

<P>Although he has encountered some surprise on the part of customers, Johnson, who studied engineering with Evans in college before turning to silversmithing, thinks high-tech is the way to go.</P>

<P>"I'm getting 'should an Indian be involved in technology?' " says Johnson, who is Muscogee Creek and Seminole. "And these are the same people who want to know whether I take Mastercard and Visa. They want the past and the future, too."</P>

<P>On Johnson's Web site, browsers may click on any number of small silver disks to call up larger-than-life high-resolution images of Johnson's unique silver hair ties. The site includes information on ordering the items as well as information about Johnson and his work.</P>

<P>Johnson, 28, doesn't mass produce his work and isn't banking on a rush of orders from his Web page, but he hopes the technology will show his art worldwide and carry the message that he is a modern person.</P>

<P>"I think it's prestigious to have a Web site on a business card," Johnson says. "It's like, hey, I have a college education. People don't think of us that way."</P>

<P>They call it the World Wide Web for a reason. It is meant, in futuristic, virtual community speak, to bring people together intellectually no matter how far apart they may be physically.</P>

<P>Let's say you live in Perth, Australia, and you like to prowl the Internet in the evenings as you look out on the lights of the city. If you find yourself browsing under the key words "Indian" or "casinos," you might pull up the Isleta Gaming Palace's web page. you may click on a box labeled "specials" and find an up-to-date listing of monthly specials. Then, more curious, you might click on a fuzzy little box in the middle of your screen. In the darkness you will hear a jingle familiar to any New Mexican with a TV: <A HREF="../images/isleta.wav">"More games! More winners! More fun!"</A></P>

<P>Loopy connections like worldwide exposure to the Isleta Gaming song are a bizarre byproduct of the Net. Other connections have more meaning for the Native Americans who are posting through ATIIN and the worldwide community that is getting their message.</P>

<P>The Mescalero Apache tribe is developing a Web page where it can control the information that goes out about the tribe.</P>

<P>Instead of trusting the filter of television, newspapers, books or magazines to tell the story of their history, government or business ventures, the Mescaleros will be able to write their own text, take their own pictures and, if they choose, include their own sounds and video.</P>

<P>"It's all coming from them," says Brown. "They are saying, 'This is us.' "</P>

<P>Other tribes are interested in using the Internet to speak to their own people. Isleta is looking into using the technology to teach its Tiwa language to pueblo members. Elders will be able to archive the language on tape, the sounds can be incorporated into a teaching program and users will eventually be able to click on words and hear the Tiwa translation.</P>

<P>"The technology is now culturally relevant," says Craig. "We see this as going in and showing them the potential, letting them know the power of what they have."</P>

<CENTER><img src="../images/bow.gif"></CENTER>
</CENTER>


</BODY></HTML>
