<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Native CyberTrade - about Native CyberTrade</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/parch.gif">

<P></P>

<IMG align=left SRC="../images/cyberex.gif"> 

<ADDRESS>Reprinted from: The Albuquerque Tribune - Friday, Oct. 13, 1995 (FRONT PAGE)<BR></ADDRESS>

<H1>Indian trading post sets up on info highway</H1>

<H2>A Sandia Labs Engineer has started a new business that takes American Indian businesses onto the Internet.</H2>

<ADDRESS>By Lawrence Spohn, Tribune Reporter<BR></ADDRESS>

<H3>THE ELECTRONIC MALL</H3>

<P>Companies create "Homepages" - graphic representations of goods and information that can be viewed at home with a computer.  By pointing and clicking with a mouse, users can "move" around the store. For example, a shopper might click on a picture of a <A  href="http://www.atiin.com/kjohnson/johnson2.htm">bracelet</A> to find out its cost and information about the artist.</P>

<P></P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">Next time you're on the Internet, mosey on down to the electronic trading post and check out the American Indian silver jewelry or drums.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">An Albuquerque company, organized by American Indians out of <A  href="http://www.sandia.gov/">Sandia National Laboratories,</A> is bringing the electronic version of the Western trading post to the Internet.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">It's "Native CyberTrade&#174;," an electronic mall, offers some of the same goods that old-fashioned reservation trading posts sold.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">It also is providing national and international exposure to American Indian businesses and interests, including reservation gambling.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">"It's all the way from blankets to drums," said Laurence Brown, president of <A  href="http://www.atiin.com/">Advanced Tribal Integrated Information Networks</A> .</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">Brown, a Navajo who has two Navajo partners, said that in Navajo, ATIIN means "roadway" or "pathway."  The name is symbolic of the company's effort to provide American Indians with access to the "information superhighway," he said.  The superhighway is the computer equivalent of the interstate highway system, linking millions of users around the world.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">The tribal network has already created several Internet "home pages" - computer screen storefronts that introduce electronic browsers to catalogs of goods, services or information.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">Among the company' clients: <A  href="http://www.atiin.com/kjohnson/">Kenneth Johnson</A> , a Santa Fe Indian artist who specializes in silver-coin hair ties; the Santa Fe Indian Market; and the Southwest Association for Indian Artists . And a deal is in the works with a Taos artist who makes drums.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">Generally, each client has a separate Homepage on the tribal network's computer server, which is connected to the Internet and potentially accessible to millions of home and business computers.  The pages list addresses and phone numbers customers can use to make a purchase or get information.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">When commercial transactions become more secure over the Internet through coding, Brown expects, many transactions will be made electronically.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">He says he will be translating the home pages into German and Japanese, (currently <A  href="http://www.atiin.com/atiin/about_spanish.html">spanish</A> ) because of the strong interest in those countries in American Indian <A  href="http://www.atiin.com/cybertrade/Arts_and_Crafts.html">arts and crafts</A> . </P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">"But we're also helping Indian companies to reach a wider market for their businesses," Brown said.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">Among the tribal network's corporate clients are the <A  href="http://www.atiin.com/isleta_gaming/">Isleta Gaming Palace</A> , the Mescalero Apache Tribe and the Gathering of Nations Pow-wow.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">The Navajo Nation is working with the network to develop a Homepage for it's growing array of business interests, and Brown says the company just got a contract with Navajo Community College.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">"It feels good." he said of the company's rapid success. "Some of the tribal enterprises are a long way from high-tech, but they still need to link into the Internet to boost their sales.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">"We handle the high-tech, from beginning to end," he said.  "They don't have to do much more than tell us what they want."</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">Brown says the company is benefiting from his experience as a project manager at Sandia and his exposure to the broad scope of computer technology.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">He expects shortly to offer clients virtual-reality environments - a Sandia strength in which a computer simulates a real place. Brown says they will enrich Internet computer pages and enhance the marketing of goods and services.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">One good approach might be to present goods within a trading-post atmosphere, he said.  Another might be to feature them in an electronic rendition of the artisan's studio or workshop.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">A vital step for the tribal network was getting Technology Ventures Corp.'s help in securing a $25,000 lease agreement for a Silicon Graphics computer server.  It can create high-resolution graphics at very high speeds.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">The service has attracted American Indian business "from <A  href="http://www.atiin.com/mccracken/">Florida</A> and San Diego to <A  href="http://www.atiin.com/uniband/">North Dakota</A> and Canada," he said.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">Brown says he is also "branching out" in his own marketing effort to attract Spanish-speaking artist and businesses in New Mexico and "really any client interested in getting on the Internet."</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">The grant from TVC was vital, as was TVC's help in giving the company legitimacy in the business world, Brown said.  The tribal network is in <A  href="../images/1tech.gif">TVC's new building</A> on University Boulevard Southeast in the University of New Mexico's research Park.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)">The TVC grant was the fifth it has made in two years. It also has been instrumental in landing $10 Million in private funding for local technology-commercialization ventures.</P>

<H2>TO VISIT THE MALL</H2>

<P>Connect to address  <A  href="http://www.atiin.com/cybertrade/">http://www.atiin.com/cybertrade</A> on the World Wide Web.</P>

<P><IMG src="../images/dot_clr.gif" alt="(tab)"></P>

<P><CENTER><IMG src="../images/bow.gif"> </P>

</BODY>
</HTML>
