<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HEAD><TITLE>Article - The Albuquerque Business Times</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<body background="../images/parch.gif">
<img align="left" src="../images/tvcad.gif"><BR><H1>Native American business sets up on the Internet</H1>

<address>Reprinted from: The Albuquerque Business Times - October30 - November 13, 1995 (page 3)</address>

<P>ALBUQUERQUE &#151; Native American businesses and tribes throughout the United States soon may be opening stores in a new cybermall on the Internet created by a local company.</P>

<P>Known as the Advanced Tribal Integrated Information Networks, (ATIIN), it is a New Mexico company built with the assistance of Technology Ventures Corporation (TVC) on technology developed at Sandia National Laboratories.</P>

<P>The first enterprise of its kind, ATIIN's main activity for now is creating Native CyberTrade&#151; an Internet "mall" in which the company creates and maintains Internet home pages and the server to put them on&#151; for Native American tribes and enterprises.</P>

<P>The company's acronym, "atiin", means roadway or pathway in Navajo, said a company official.</P>

<P>Isleta Gaming Palace, the Mescalero Apache tribe and the Gathering of Nations Powwow are among the company's growing client list. </P>

<P>"We're branching out now," said Laurence Brown, ATIIN president and former Sandia Labs scientist. "We are broadening our base to include service for the Spanish-speaking community and larger business community."</P>

<P>ATIIN started up "on a shoestring" in June. TVC provided incubation office space and other services, including planning. But the future really depended on "us being able to lease a $25,000 piece of equipment," Brown said. "We needed the lease because we couldn't afford to buy".</P>

<P>At one point, the equipment maker, a leader in Internet technology, wouldn't grant the lease because ATIIN was a startup with no history. </P>

<P>That's when TVC stepped in.</P>

<P>"We introduced them to people they needed to know to come up with the $25,000 for the equipment purchase, " said Bob Gibson, TVC's director of investor and venture funding recruitment.</P>

<P>TVC also awarded the company a $10,000 grant, the sixth such grant TVC has awarded in the past two years. </P>

<P>"TVC has given us legitimacy," Brown says. "People looked at what we were doing, and saw that TVC thought it was a good idea, and they saw that Sandia thought it was a good idea, too."</P>

<P>As a result, ATIIN was able to open its doors for business in June.</P>

<P>"Not only is it based on lab generated technology, which adds to the value of the laboratories' role as a research leader, it also holds great potential for aiding economic development at both regional and national levels for the Native American community," TVC President Sherman McCorkle said.</P>

<P>Albuquerque-based TVC is a non-profit organization dedicated to the successful commercialization of technology from Sandia National Laboratories and other public research facilities.</P>

<P>Brown, a Navajo from Bloomfield NM, had gained a reputation at Sandia as a successful project manager with deep roots and contacts in the Native American community. When he suggested that he could use technology to bring the benefits of the Internet to Indian businesses and communities across the country, "they gave me the green light to go ahead and do it," Brown said.</P>

<P>Brown took with him Evans Craig, a consultant working at the labs who specializes in educational technologies for Indian education, and also recruited Robert Mora, a former Digital Equipment Corp. engineer. Evans is vice president of research and development and Mora is vice president of engineering.</P>

<P>"Some of the tribal enterprises are a long way from high tech, but they still need to link into the Internet to boost their sales," Brown said.</P>

<P>Another major ATIIN project, which is waiting to be funded, is developing a multimillion dollar database that will put high resolution graphics for the Southwest American for Indian Arts on the Internet.</P>

<P>In addition, the company is providing computer consulting services. After developing a local-area network at the Isleta Gaming Palace, ATIIN is working on a six-month project to get the Palace integrated into a wide-area network.</P>

<P>"The important thing for the Native American community&#151; and our other customers&#151; to know is that they don't have to be high-tech themselves to work with us. We handle the high-tech from beginning to end. They don't have to do much more than tell us what they want," Mora said.</P>

<P>"In Navajo, 'atiin' means 'roadway' or 'pathway'," Mora said. "That's what we want to be... in the process of getting the Native Community onto the information highway.</P>

<P>"And that's what Technology Ventures has been to us - the path to a successful startup."</P>
<CENTER><img src="../images/bow.gif"></CENTER>

