<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HTML 
VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HEAD>
<TITLE>Indian Gaming...Its Working for New Mexico</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER>
<H1>Indian Gaming...Its Working for New Mexico</H1>

<h3>INTRODUCTION</H3>

<TABLE WIDTH=90%>
<TR>
<TD>

<P>Indian gaming is working for New Mexico. We are happy to say that Indian gaming is directly providing over 2,650 jobs to tribal and non-tribal individuals. These employees are paid $46.6 million annually, almost all of which will be spent in New Mexico. These employees will provide food, clothing, and housing for their families and will have the self-respect employment brings. Our wage and salary payments, along with our purchase of supplies, goods, services and the tourist dollars we draw into the state with our gaming operations generate, in total, 13,300 jobs and $215.5 million in employment income statewide. These figures do not include the tribal government spending for economic diversification, community projects and tribal government services. Through Indian gaming, our people are just beginning to address many infrastructure problems created by years of neglect. For the first time, our people are enjoying services that we have been economically unable to provide. Indian gaming is working for New 
Mexico, it is working for our people and for the people of the state.
</P>
</TD>

<TD WIDTH=300>
<CENTER><a href="./about3b.jpg"><IMG src="./about3a.gif"></A></CENTER>
<BR>
<CENTER><P><I>Acoma Governor Ron Shutiva presents a check to the Cibola County School Board in accordance with the State-Tribal Compact Revenue Sharing Agreement.</I></P></CENTER>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></center>

<center><TABLE WIDTH=90%>
<TR><TD colspan=2>
<P>There is clearly a need for economic development among New Mexico's Indian pueblos and tribes. Indian gaming has proven to be a bright spot in an otherwise bleak picture. All of the tribal gaming operations are 100% tribal owned and operated. Many of the tribes have borrowed heavily, based on the existence of the compacts, to start
their own operations, and have pumped several million dollars into the New Mexico economy on construction and start-up costs. For many tribes, Indian gaming is the
first successful Tribal enterprise that provides confidence and capital to venture into other businesses. Tribal members employed by the gaming operations are gaining
experience at every level of the operations. For many tribal members, this is their first job, and the experience they gain at gaming operations prepares them to compete in
the larger job market.
</P></TD>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=300>
<CENTER><a href="./about4b.jpg"><IMG src="./about4a.gif"></a></CENTER>
<BR>
<CENTER><P><I>New Mexico Indian Gaming Association members meet with the press. Pictured from left are, NMIGA Co-chair Ken Paquin, Santa Ana Governor Lujan, Isleta Governor Alvino Lucero, NMIGA Co-chair Frank Chaves, Acoma Governor Ron Shutiva, Pojoaque Lt. Governor George Rivera and Tesuque Governor Herman Vigil.
</I></P></CENTER>
</TD>

<TD>

<P>Our gaming operations are providing more than just jobs, though. They are providing confidence and renewed pride in our people. Our gaming operations are providing the resources to fund programs for our elders, and programs for our children. Our gaming operations are providing the capital for economic diversification projects on our land. Our gaming operations are providing the funds to fix the problems we have never been able to deal with financially. Our gaming operations are providing the resources for a renewed respect for our culture and our people.</P>
<P><B>This is a sampling of the many programs and projects undertaken by the tribal governments.</b> We hope these photographs will clarify the picture of Indian gaming in New Mexico. There is a great deal at stake here, including the lives of many people,
both tribal members and non-tribal members. This is about much more than politics. This is about people.</P>
<P><B>Indian gaming is working for New Mexico.</B></P>
  
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<H4>| <a href="./tesuque1.htm">Continue on to Tesuque Pueblo</a> | <a href="../nmiga/">Return back to Index</a> | </h4>
</CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
