<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>News &amp; Destinations (pt. 1)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFEBD7" LINK="#7F0000" VLINK="#000000"><CENTER><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./destinr.gif"></CENTER><P><BR></P><TABLE
BORDER="1" CELLPADDING="10" ALIGN="CENTER"><TR><TD
VALIGN="TOP" COLSTART="1" WIDTH="49%"><IMG ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./newsban.gif"><H4>Lannan Foundation announces grants</H4>

In 1994 Lannan Foundation inaugurated a national grant program to support the urgent needs of rural Native American communities.  This program supports the resolve of Native People to renew their communities through their own institutions and traditions.  More than $5 million dollars has been awarded as part of this program.  The grant recipients are:
<UL><LI>American Indian Science and Engineering Society - Boulder, Colorado</LI><LI>Center for Community Change - Hogansburg, New York</LI><LI>Don't Waste Arizona, Inc. - Pinon, Arizona</LI><LI>Gwich'in Steering Committee - Anchorage, Alaska</LI><LI>International Indian Treaty Council - San Francisco, California</LI><LI>Native Lands Institute - Hilo, Hawaii</LI><LI>Piegan Institute - Browning, Montana</LI><LI>Regeneration Del Norte - The Dalles, Oregon</LI><LI>Seventh Generation Fund - Arcata, California</LI></UL><BR><H3>Indian Arts and Crafts Association Selects President</H3>
Andy Abeita (Isleta) has been selected by the Indian Arts and Crafts Association (IACA) to head the organization.  The IACA is an international organization representing wholesale and retail dealers, galleries, museums and collectors worldwide since 1974.<BR><BR>Mr. Abeita is the first Native American president of IACA.  He began sculpting stone at the age of nineteen  as an expression of the traditions and religious values taught by his father and grandfather.  Mr. Abeita  believes &quot;As an artist I feel an obligation to give back all that I have learned and am learning through the traditions of my culture.&quot;
</TD><TD COLSTART="2" WIDTH="40"></TD><TD
VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="3" WIDTH="49%"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./atlatl2.jpg"><BR><FONT Color=#FF0000 <BR>P O Box 34090<BR>Phoenix, AZ<BR>85067-4090<BR>(602) 253-2731<BR>e mail: <A
HREF="mailto:atlatl@artswire.org">atlatl@artswire.org</A></FONT><P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">Atlatl, National Service Organization for Native American Arts, announces Native Arts Network:  1996, to be held at the University of Tulsa and the Adam's Mark Hotel in Tulsa, Oklahoma, October 10-13.  The theme of this year's gathering is We Have No Word For Art, and discussions will center around economic, political, international, social and community forces affecting the cultural environment of Indian country.  Keynote speaker is Oklahoma State Senator Enoch Kelly Haney (Seminole).</P><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./montclair.jpg"><BR><FONT Color=#0000FF <BR>3 South Mountain Ave<BR>Montclair, NJ 07042-1747<BR>(201) 746-5555</FONT><P
ALIGN="CENTER"><B>October 4</B></P>Friday Night Lecture at 7:30 pm on the Metropolitan Museum of the Art's Corot. Call for registration and admission fees.<BR><P
ALIGN="CENTER"><B>October 6</B></P>Gallery Talk, Passionate Pursuits: Hidden Treasures from the Garden State at 3 pm.<BR><P
ALIGN="CENTER"><B>October 13</B></P>Native American Program, guest lecturer is Alan Wardwell, Senior Consultant of Tribal Art for Christie's, New York.<BR><P
