<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Download Study Guide</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><CENTER><H2><I>Native People&#146;s</I> Study Guide<BR>Summer Edition 1996</H2></CENTER><P>Many of the articles in this edition of Native People&#146;s magazine emphasize the integral relationship between the story and creativity. Mythology expert Joseph Campbell explains the importance of myth saying, &quot;Myth comes in the same zone as dream, and this is the zone of what I would call the Wisdom Body.&quot; It is the innate wisdom inherent in these stories which the people recognize as universal wisdom.  Thus, they are motivated to live in harmony with these beliefs and inspired to share them in art and story.</P><P>As you read, notice how the creation story in the article. The Mississippi Band of Choctaw in the Shadow of Nanih Waiya&quot; motivate the people to live close to the land from which they originated.</P><P>Also inspired by creation stories, the Wounaan People in the article &quot;Spirit Weavers&quot; weave symbols of their beliefs into their baskets.</P><P>In the article &quot;Woven by Grandmothers&quot; three women share their feelings about the single event of bringing priceless blankets back to the Navajo reservation.</P><P>In the article &quot;German Silver&quot;, the stories fathers tell to their sons are as essential to the art of metalsmithing as are the techniques of manipulating the mallets and metal stamps used to create religious accessories.</P><P>Finally, in the article &quot;Where There Is No Name for Art&quot; The children of northern New Mexico tell their stories in voice and art of the freedom they experience living in a pueblo.  
</P><P><BR></P><CENTER>Click <A HREF="./SummerStudyGuide96.txt">here</A> to download Study Guide</CENTER><P><BR></P><CENTER><A
HREF="./index.html"><IMG ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./np.gif" BORDER="0"><BR>Go back to the Home Page</A></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
