<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HEAD><TITLE>Technology Ventures Corporation - Clients</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><H1>Technology Ventures Corporation</H1>

<H2>Creating Opportunity for Technologists and Investors</H2>
<img src="../images/barpurpl.gif"></center>
<I><P><b>Technology Ventures is an important contributor in the formation of new businesses built on leading-edge technologies developed at Department of Energy laboratories, and in the expansion of existing businesses. It also assists in obtaining funding offers for many of its client companies. Among Technology Ventures clients:</b></P></I>

<H3>Quantum Manufacturing, Inc.</H3>

<IMG align="right" src="./qmi.gif"><P>QMI recently received a commitment of $4.2 million in funding from private investors. The company's technology uses a rapid-fire, high-power pulsed ion beam to harden the surfaces of metals, ceramics, plastics and other materials. It enhances corrosion resistance and increases the lifetime of surfaces in hostile environments. This core technology has uses in the tool-and-die industry, aircraft manufacturing, automobile engines and medical implants and tools, to name a few.</P>

<H3>Boissiere Engineering &amp; Applied Robotics, Inc.</H3>

<P>BEAR's technology focuses on telerobotic excavation systems for waste water remediation applications. The technology was developed at Sandia National Laboratories' Intelligent Systems and Robotics Center and incorporates real-time graphic displays, graphic operator interfaces, computer control of on-board systems, model-based motion planning and sensor-controlled dynamic path controls.</P>

<P></P>

<IMG align="left" src="./atiin.gif"><H3>ATIIN, Inc.</H3>

<P>Native American owned, ATIIN provides Internet and World Wide Web technologies and services to the Native American community nationwide as well as to the general business community. The company also provides educational technologies and LAN/WAN development. A focal point of the company's program is Native CyberTrade, an Internet pathway for Native American related products and services. ATIIN founders developed their technologies while scientists at Sandia National Laboratories.</P>

<H3>JEC Technologies, Inc.</H3>

<P>The company has created a family of software products for the Internet. Developed by Sandia National Laboratories scientists, the main purpose of the software is to help Internet users navigate the net as they search for information. Formed in 1995, JEC estimates the market for its software could grow as high as 400 million users by the year 2000.</P>

<P></P>

<H3>Micro-Optical Devices, Inc.</H3>

<P>MOD, Inc. has received seed equity investment from private investors to develop, manufacture and market vertical cavity, surface emitting lasers. Vertical cavity lasers are compound semiconductor lasers with applications in data communications, printing, scanning, sensing and other markets. Their commercial promise has been developed through research efforts at Sandia National Laboratories and the University of New Mexico's Center for High Technology Materials.</P>

<P></P>

<H3>MuSE Technologies, Inc.</H3>

<P>Hailed as a major advance in virtual reality, MuSE's technology has attracted substantial funding from private investors. Put simply, MuSE technology provides a way to adapt the computer to the human &#151;not the other way around as current programs and systems do. MuSE is a means of traveling through any space and providing sensory tools to interact with that space&#151;very much as a human simultaneously absorbs and acts on different types of information while driving a car. With MuSE, a surgeon, for example, can "step inside" the human body, moving about for a complete view. MuSE was developed at the Department of Energy's Sandia National Laboratories .</P>

<P></P>

<IMG align="right" src="./smdi.gif"><H3>Silicon MicroDevices, Inc.</H3>

<P>SMDI recently entered a joint venture agreement with a major US manufacturer to develop and bring to market a micro-mechanical drug delivery technology. The technology developed at Sandia National Laboratories, is a micro-mechanical drug delivery system that administers a broad range of medications directly into the bloodstream by overcoming the present harrier to nearly all such drug delivery, the human skin. This product is radically different from existing transdermal drug patches currently on the market or under development, which use only chemical or electrical methods to deliver only a small number of unique drugs through the outer layers of the skin.</P>

<P></P><center><img src="../images/barpurpl.gif"></center><P></P>
<P>Direct inquires to:</P>

<center><B><ADDRESS>Technology Ventures Corporation</ADDRESS>

<ADDRESS>One Technology Center</ADDRESS>

<ADDRESS>1155 University Boulevard SE</ADDRESS>

<ADDRESS>Albuquerque, New Mexico 87106</ADDRESS>

<ADDRESS>Phone: 505.246.2882</ADDRESS>

<ADDRESS>Fax: 505.246.2891</ADDRESS>

<ADDRESS>E-mail: <a href="mailto:sherman.mccorkle@den.mmc.com">sherman.mccorkle@den.mmc.com</a></ADDRESS></b></center>

