<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HEAD><TITLE>New Mexico Tribal Government Gaming</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<H1>TRIBAL GOVERNMENT GAMING</H1></Center>

<P></P>

<P></P>

<H2>FUNDAMENTAL ISSUES:</H2>

<P></P>

<H3><U>Indian Tribal Government Sovereignty</U></H3>

<P></P>

<CENTER><H4>ORIGINS</H4></CENTER>

<P></P>

<P>	At its most basic, the term sovereignty refers to the right or power to govern. At the time of European entry to America, the tribes were sovereign by nature and necessity; they conducted their own affairs and depended upon no outside source of power to legitimize their acts of government.</P>

<P></P>

<CENTER><H4>CONTEMPORARY TRIBAL SOVEREIGNTY</H4></CENTER>

<P></P>

<P>	The United States Congress and the Supreme Court of the United States have upheld the principal attributes of tribal sovereignty generally as follows: (1) Indian tribes possess inherent governmental power over all internal affairs; (2) the states are precluded from interfering with the tribes in their self-government; and (3) Congress has plenary power to limit tribal sovereignty. The New Mexico Constitution expressly disclaims state jurisdiction over Indian lands.</P>

<P></P>

<P></P>

<H3><U>Tribal Government Regulation of Indian Gaming</U></H3>

<P></P>

<P></P>

<CENTER><H4>INHERENT RIGHT TO REGULATE</H4></CENTER>

<P></P>

<P>	Based on tribal inherent right to self-government and to create laws and be governed by them, Indian tribes enacted laws to regulate gaming within their territorial jurisdictions or reservations. Several New Mexico tribes had enacted gaming laws early in the 1980's to regulate high stakes bingo operations on Indian lands.</P>

<P></P>

<P>	Indian Gaming occurs on Indian land, not State land. The right of an Indian tribal government to conduct gaming under its own regulatory framework and free from state interference is a right affirmed in 1987 by the United States Supreme Court in the case of California v. Cabazon Band of Mission Indians, 480 U.S. 202, 209-10 (1987).</P>

<P></P>

<CENTER><H4>TRIBAL AND FEDERAL REGULATION</H4></CENTER>

<P></P>

<P>	The United States Congress, in 1988, enacted the Indian Gaming Regulatory Act, 25 U.S.C. 2701 et. seq. (IGRA). Tribal government is the primary regulator of Indian gaming. The IGRA created a second (federal) and the New Mexico compacts create the third (state) layer of government regulation.</P>

<P></P>

<P>	The IGRA categorizes gaming into three classes for regulatory purposes. Class I gaming includes social games for prizes of minimal value and traditional forms of gaming. Class I gaming is within the exclusive jurisdiction of tribal government.</P>

<P></P>

<P>	Class II gaming is defined as bingo-type games and certain card games. Class II gaming regulatory authority is under the jurisdiction of tribal government and the National Indian Gaming Commission (NIGC). The NIGC was created by Congress under the IGRA.</P>

<P></P>

<CENTER><H4> TRIBAL AND STATE REGULATION</H4></CENTER>

<P></P>

<P>	Class III gaming is all other forms of gaming not considered Class I or Class II. The IGRA provides that tribal/state compacts will determine the regulatory scheme of Class III gaming. Senate Report No. 100-446, which accompanied the IGRA, noted: "A compact may allocate most or all of the jurisdictional responsibility to the tribe to the State or to any variation in between. The committee does not intend that the compacts be used as a subterfuge for imposing State jurisdiction on tribal lands."</P>

<P></P>

<P></P>

<H3><U>Tribal, IGRA, and NIGC Regulatory Requirements</U></H3>

<P></P>

<P></P>

<CENTER><H4>IGRA AND NIGC REQUIREMENTS</H4></CENTER>

<P></P>

<P>	Prior to the passage of IGRA in 1988, tribal governments enacted gaming laws in accordance with their particular tribal government requirements. With the advent of the IGRA, national standards are applied to the regulation of Indian gaming. The following apply primarily to Class II gaming; however, they have also been incorporated into Class III tribal/state gaming compacts along with a host of other regulatory provisions:</P>

<P></P>

<UL>
<LI><P>A tribal government must adopt a gaming ordinance and the ordinance must be approved by the NIGC.</P>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><P>A tribal gaming operation must be audited annually by an independent auditor and the results of this audit must be submitted to the NIGC for its review.</P>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><P>All gaming related contracts for purchases of supplies, services, or concessions of   more than $25,000 in any year must be audited by an independent auditor.</P>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><P>A tribe must issue licenses to key employees and primary management officials. Further, a tribe may not issue a license to any person who poses a threat to the public interest or to the effective regulation of gaming.</P>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><P>Prior to issuing a license, a tribe must perform an extensive background check on each principal (major stockholder, directors, etc.) of a management contractor. The tribe's background check must include an investigation into the applicant's criminal history (through the FBI), as well as an investigation into the applicant's previous business relationships (both gaming and non-gaming). </P>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><P>A tribe must submit a detailed report to the NIGC for each background check it performs on an applicant. This report must describe the steps taken in conducting the background check, and the basis for the tribe's conclusions.</P>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><P>In cases where a tribe enters into a management contract with a non-tribal entity, the contract must be approved by the NIGC. The regulations promulgated by the NIGC impose numerous requirements on management contracts including, among other things, the maintenance of adequate accounting an internal controls as well as the preparation of verified monthly financial statements that comport with generally accepted accounting principles.</P>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><P>Although IGRA authorizes tribes to make per capita distributions of gaming earnings to tribal members, tribes may not do so without the approval of the Secretary of the Interior.</P>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><P>The regulations of the National Indian Gaming Commission implementing the Indian Gaming Regulatory Act are published in 25 CFR Chapter III.</P>
</UL>

<CENTER><H4>TRIBAL REGULATORY BODIES</H4></CENTER>

<P>Tribal governments have established regulatory commissions, gaming boards, compliance officers or monitors to ensure compliance with all applicable gaming laws, regulations, and policies.</P>

<P></P>

<CENTER><H4>TRIBAL REGULATORY TOOLS</H4></CENTER>

<P></P>

<P>	Tribal regulatory bodies use many tools that go beyond the standards required under New Mexico law including:</P>

<UL>
<LI><P>Background checks and licensing</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>Internal accounting controls</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>Internal cash accounting controls</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>Internal audits</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>Security systems</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>Surveillance systems</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>Operations manuals</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>Dispute resolution procedures (gaming public)</P>
</UL>


<P></P>

<P></P>

<H3>Law Enforcement</H3>

<P></P>

<P></P>

<P>	Tribal government law enforcement departments are fully operational law enforcement agencies and exercise general law enforcement jurisdiction over gaming operations. Many tribes have cross commissioned officers with the local non-Indian governments, and many tribal officers are commissioned peace officers by the New Mexico State Police. Tribal law enforcement agencies work with local, state, and federal agencies to prevent criminal activity and enforce laws against offenders.</P>

<P></P>

<P>
</P>

<H3>Why Indian Gaming?</H3>

<P></P>

<CENTER><H4>A LEGACY OF POVERTY</H4></CENTER>

<P></P>

<P>For centuries, negative impacts have been endured by the tribes:</P>

<P></P>

<UL>
<LI><P>		Destruction of traditional economies</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		Population decimation</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		Loss of land and other natural resources</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		State regulatory barriers to economic development</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		State taxation of tribal natural resources</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		Denial of access to state services</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		Degradation of the environment</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		Indian culture commercialized to benefit state tourism</P>

</UL>

<P></P>

<P>	The legacy of these historical facts is poverty. According to the 1990 census, 46% of all New Mexico Indians are living in poverty; nearly half of these are poor children. Only 585 of adult Indians are high school graduates; only 6% are college graduates. Nearly a quarter of all Indian homes lack complete plumbing facilities.</P>

<P></P>

<CENTER><H4>USE OF GAMING REVENUES</H4></CENTER>

<P></P>

<P>	Under the IGRA, 25 USC 2710.Sec. 11(b)(2)(B), net revenues from tribal gaming may only be used for:</P>

<P></P>

<P>	(i)	Tribal government operations or programs:</P>

<P></P>

<P>	(ii)	The general welfare of the Indian tribe and its members;</P>

<P></P>

<P>	(iii)	Tribal economic development;</P>

<P></P>

<P>	(iv)	Donations to charitable organizations; or</P>

<P></P>

<P>	(v)	Operations of local government agencies.</P>

<P></P>

<P>	The New Mexico Gaming tribes are spending gaming revenues on the following types of projects:</P>

<P></P>

<UL>
<LI><P>		Senior Citizen centers</P>
<LI><P>		Day Care Centers</P>
<LI><P>		Fire Stations</P>
<LI><P>		Health Facilities</P>
<LI><P>		Environmental Clean-up and Protection</P>
<LI><P>		Scholarships</P>
<LI><P>		Elementary School Improvements</P>
<LI><P>		Educational Programs</P>
<LI><P>		Infrastructure Development and Maintenance</P>
<LI><P>		Law Enforcement</P>
<LI><P>		Cultural Preservation</P>
<LI><P>		Government Operations</P>
</UL>


<P></P>

<H3>Economic Impact ( As of June 1995)</H3>

<P></P>

<P>	Indian Gaming has positive economic and social impacts on the state. It creates jobs and jobs produce tax revenues. Indian Gaming has contributed the following to the state's economy:</P>

<P></P>

<UL>
<LI><P>		$4.6 Million State Tax Revenue</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		$35.7 Million Additional Tourism Spending</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		13,334 Total Jobs Created by Indian Gaming</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		$62 Million in Goods and Services Purchased </P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		$46 Million in Wages and Salaries</P>
<P></P>
<LI><P>		2,650 Direct Gaming Jobs</P>
</UL>


<P></P>

<P>	The above figures do not include tribal government spending on projects and programs nor the impact of deposits and investments in financial institutions which are loaned out for economic and other purposes.</P>

<P></P>

<H1></H1>
<center><P>| <a href="../nmiga/">Return to main menu </a> |</P></center>


