<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> New Mexico Indian Gaming - Chronology of Events</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER><H2>NEW MEXICO INDIAN GAMING 
CHRONOLOGY OF EVENTS</H2></CENTER>

<H2>1983</H2>


<P><STRONG>1983</STRONG> - Pueblo of Acoma, under its inherent right to enact laws and be governed by them, enacts an ordinance to regulate gaming and begins operation of high stakes bingo.


<H2>1984</H2>

<P><STRONG>1984 </STRONG>- Pueblo of Sandia, under its own duly enacted ordinance, begins high stakes bingo and more Tribes follow in subsequent years.


<H2>1985</H2>


<P><STRONG>1985 </STRONG>- New Mexico gaming Tribes form ad-hoc committee on Indian gaming and begin cooperative efforts to protect tribal government rights to conduct gaming within their 
homelands.

<H2>1986</H2>

<P><STRONG>1986 </STRONG>- At least one New Mexico Tribe begins video bingo and pull tab operations.  This form of gaming was also permitted under State law.

<H2>1987</H2>

<P><STRONG>1987 </STRONG>- The US Supreme Court, in Cabazon Band of Mission Indians v. California, affirms the right of Indian Tribes to conduct gaming operations on Indian lands without state law interference. 

<H2>1988</H2>

<P><STRONG>October 17, 1988</STRONG> - Indian Gaming Regulatory Act, Pub. L. No. 100-497, 102 Stat. 2467 (25 U.S.C. 2701 et seq.) signed into law.  Under the IGRA, Tribal governments are the primary regulators of Indian Gaming. Due to states demand for a role in Indian gaming, Tribes are required to negotiate with states in order to conduct Class III gaming operations.  The IGRA creates a federal regulatory layer for Class III gaming and permits a third, state regulatory layer to be established by state-tribal compact agreements.  The Act contains a grandfather provision to allow gaming operations conducted prior to the passage of the Act to continue for a specified period of time and further provides such activities are proper subjects for negotiation.

<P><STRONG>November 1988</STRONG> - Sandia Pueblo notifies the Office of Indian Affairs of its request to enter negotiations for Indian gaming compacts with the State pursuant to NMSA Section  28-12-7 which designates the New Mexico Office of Indian Affairs as the coordinating agency for intergovernmental programs concerning tribal governments and the state.

<H2>1989</H2>

<P><STRONG>January 1989</STRONG> - The FIRST New Mexico legislative session after notice and request to negotiate gaming compacts begins.

<P><STRONG>March 1989</STRONG> - Governor Garrey Carruthers, by letter, informs the Office of Indian Affairs of his administrations position is that the Office of the Governor has sole authority to negotiate Indian gaming compacts with Indian tribes.  He requested that all Office of Indian Affairs negotiations on gaming cease and that all records be sent to him.

<P><STRONG>November 1989</STRONG> - Bruce King elected governor.

<P><STRONG>December 1989</STRONG> - Carruthers administration ends with no compact agreement.

<H2>1990</H2>

<P><STRONG>January 1990</STRONG> - The SECOND New Mexico legislative session after notice and request to negotiate gaming compacts begins.

<H2>1991</H2>

<P><STRONG>January 1991</STRONG> - The THIRD New Mexico legislative session after notice and request to negotiate gaming compacts begins.

<P><STRONG>January 1991</STRONG> - Negotiations resume under Governor King.

<P><STRONG>October 1991</STRONG> - Agreement reached on form of compact with the Pueblo of Sandia and a signed compact was forwarded to Governors Office for signature.  However, Governor King refused to sign the compact. 

<P><STRONG>December 9, 1991 </STRONG>- Attorney General Tom Udall advises Governor King, by letter,  as to the Governors authority to sign gaming compacts with Tribes.  Udall advises that the Mutual Aid Act (NMSA 29-8-1 et seq.) and the Joint Powers Agreement Act (NMSA 11-1-6) authorize such agreements with the Tribes since their primary purpose is regulatory and law enforcement.


<H2>1992</H2>

<P><STRONG>January 1992</STRONG> - The FOURTH New Mexico legislative session after notice and request to negotiate gaming compacts begins.

<P><STRONG>January 22, 1992</STRONG> - Mescalero Apache Tribe files suit to compel the State to negotiate gaming compacts and asserting the states failure to negotiate in good faith.

<P><STRONG>May 1992</STRONG>- Additional Tribes request negotiations with Governor King to enter into gaming compacts.  The Governors Office failed to respond directly.  

<P><STRONG>June 12, 1992</STRONG> - Sandia Pueblo files the second tribal suit to compel state to negotiate compacts and asserting states failure to negotiate in good faith after four years of Tribes attempts to reach agreement.

<P><STRONG>November 1992</STRONG> - The States Superintendent of Regulation and Licensing communicated to Tribes that it was not appropriate to enter negotiations at the time.

<P><STRONG>November 13, 1992</STRONG> - US District Court Judge John Conway dismissed Sandia Pueblo and Mescalero Apache suits against the state holding that IGRA does not waive states immunity from suit.

<H2>1993</H2>

<P><STRONG>January 1993</STRONG> - The FIFTH New Mexico legislative session after notice and request to negotiate gaming compacts begins.

<P><STRONG>January 13, 1993</STRONG> - Tribes file Notice of Appeal to 10th Circuit.  Mescalero and Pueblo of Sandia suits consolidated for appeal.

<P><STRONG>January 1993</STRONG> - Representative Roger Madalena introduces HB41 to authorize the Office of Indian Affairs to negotiate Indian gaming compacts.
 
<P><STRONG>February 1993</STRONG> - New Mexico House passes HB 41 to authorize the Office of Indian Affairs to negotiate Indian gaming compacts.

<P><STRONG>March 1993</STRONG> - Senate passes HB 41 29 for 4 against.  Bill sent to Governor for signature.

<P><STRONG>April 9, 1993</STRONG> - Governor King vetoes House Bill 41 authorizing the Office of Indian Affairs to negotiate Indian gaming compacts.

<P><STRONG>June 23, 1993</STRONG> - US Attorney Don Svet issues subpoenas requiring gaming Tribes to provide certain records.  Tribes respond with Motion to Quash which was granted by Federal Magistrate Judge Deaton July 6, 1993.

<P><STRONG>November 8, 1993</STRONG> - Oral argument held in Sandia/Mescalero case (consolidated with cases from Oklahoma and Kansas).

<P><STRONG>December 1993</STRONG> - John Kelly appointed United States Attorney for the District of New Mexico.

<H2>1994</H2>

<P><STRONG>January 1994</STRONG> - SIXTH New Mexico legislative session after notice and request to negotiate gaming compacts begins.

<P><STRONG>January 1994</STRONG> - Discussions between US Attorney and Tribes operating video gaming devices begin.

<P><STRONG>May/July 1994</STRONG> - US Attorney enters into non-prosecution agreements with gaming Tribes which limits number and location of video games.  The agreements, referred to as standstill agreements, temporarily halts the expansion of Tribal operations.

<P><STRONG>August/September 1994</STRONG> - All gubernatorial candidates, with the exception of Bruce King, announce their intention to sign compacts with the gaming tribes.

<P><STRONG>September 2, 1994</STRONG> - 10th Circuit opinion overrules lower court dismissal of suits against state rejecting the states sovereign immunity defenses and holding that the state must negotiate in good faith.  No appeal is taken.

<P><STRONG>September 13, 1994</STRONG> - New Mexico Court of Appeals issues its opinion in Infinity Group, Inc. v. Manzagol (188 N.M. 632, 884 P.2d 523 (Ct. App.)).  The Court of Appeals rules that electronic simulations of pull tab games are not expressly prohibited under New Mexico statute and therefore pull tab mechanical devices are permitted by the Bingo and Raffle Act.

<P><STRONG>September/October 1994</STRONG> - Six Tribes file separate suits to compel the state to negotiate gaming compacts in good faith.  Several of these suits are pending.

<P><STRONG>October 18, 1994</STRONG> - The New Mexico Supreme Court refuses review of the Appeals Court decision in Infinity Group, Inc. v. Manzagol (188 N.M. 533, 882 P.2d 1046 (1994)).

<P><STRONG>October 27, 1994</STRONG> - 10th Circuit denies the States request for en banc rehearing.

<P><STRONG>November 6, 1994</STRONG> - Gary Johnson defeats incumbent Bruce King for the Office of the Governor.  New Mexico voters approve a constitutional amendment to allow video gaming in New Mexico and a statewide lottery to provide additional revenues for funding state programs.

<P><STRONG>December 1994</STRONG> - Private citizen and others, including three legislators,  file suit challenging the voter approved constitutional amendment to permit video machine games of chance in the state.  The suit seeks to invalidate the constitutional amendment because the amendment as written puts two separate items together to a single vote.

<H2>1995</H2>

<P><STRONG>January 1995</STRONG> - The SEVENTH New Mexico legislative session after notice and request to negotiate gaming compacts begins.

<P><STRONG>January 11, 1995</STRONG> - Five days before the legislature opens, the State Supreme Court rules the voter approved constitutional amendment authorizing a state lottery and video machine games of chance invalid.

<P><STRONG>January 1995</STRONG> - Representative Richard Knowles introduces HB 29 Definition of Game of Chance to repeal the state Permissive Lottery Act NMSA § 30-19-6 1978 (being Laws 1963, Chapter 303, Section 19-6, as amended).  The Permissive Lottery Act, along with the Bingo and Raffle Act, were the bases under which charitiable organizations and political organizations operated Las Vegas or casino nights featuring blackjack, poker and roulette games for over 15 years.

<P><STRONG>February 1995</STRONG> - New Mexico legislature passes bill to repeal the Permissive Lottery Act.

<P><STRONG>February 13, 1995</STRONG> - Governor Johnson signs Indian gaming compacts with 14 Tribes.

<P><STRONG>March 7, 1995</STRONG> - The National Indian Gaming Commission publishes notice of approval of Class III Tribal Gaming Ordinances.

<P><STRONG>March 15, 1995</STRONG> - Department of Interior, Assistant Secretary Ada Deer, approves New Mexico Indian gaming compacts.  

<P><STRONG>March 15, 1995</STRONG> - Governor Johnson vetoes Permissive Lottery Act repeal.

<P><STRONG>March 22, 1995</STRONG> - Notice of New Mexico Indian gaming compacts published in Federal Register.

<P><STRONG>April 1995</STRONG> - Two legislators and a private citizen petition the State Supreme Court for ruling that Governor Johnson exceeded his authority in signing Indian gaming compacts.  State Attorney General refuses to represent the Governor in suit.

<P><STRONG>May 15, 1995</STRONG> - Federal approval notice published for two more gaming compacts.

<P><STRONG>July 1995</STRONG> - New Mexico gaming Tribes forward payments to the State Treasurers Office in accordance with gaming compact revenue sharing agreement.  Total amount forwarded to the State $971,606.

<P><STRONG>July 13, 1995</STRONG> - New Mexico Supreme Court decides Governor Johnson lacks authority to sign Indian gaming compacts and that legislative approval is required to bind the State to gaming agreements.  

<P><STRONG>July/August 1995</STRONG> - Tribes forwarded payments to local governments under the revenue sharing agreements including the Town of Bernalillo, Sandoval County, City of Rio Rancho, Albuquerque Public Schools, Santa Fe County and the City of Santa Fe.

<P><STRONG>August 4, 1995 </STRONG>- New Mexico Supreme Court amends its July 1995 opinion by adding statements that Indian gaming compacts cannot be valid without legislative blessing.

<P><STRONG>August 9, 1995</STRONG> - State Treasurer Michael Montoya announces his intention to retain money remitted by Tribes.

<P><STRONG>August 21, 1995</STRONG> - After consulting Attorney General Tom Udall, State Treasurer announces his intention to return Tribes revenue sharing monies.  Attorney General urges that local governments should also return any revenue sharing checks received from Tribes.  

<P><STRONG>September 7, 1995</STRONG> - State Treasurer cancelled his plans to return Tribes revenue sharing monies because a constitutional provision does not allow the Treasurer to issue checks from the General Fund without legislative action.

<P><STRONG>September 1995</STRONG> - Governor Johnson calls for legislative special session to address Indian gaming.  The Legislative leadership refuses to call the special session.

<P><STRONG>November 29, 1995</STRONG> - New Mexico Supreme Court decides Citation Bingo v. Otten, and narrowly construes the states gaming statutes.  The Court ruled that the state statute does not permit electronic devices for use in power bingo.   The opinion includes statement that Las Vegas nights conducted by charitable organizations are both against public policy and criminally prohibited.

<P><STRONG>December 6 , 1995</STRONG> - New Mexico Legislative Indian Affairs Committee votes to recommend adoption of Indian Gaming Compact procedural bill and Resolution to ratify existing compacts.  The IAC requested that the Legislative Council set a date for hearing in late December and to work with Tribes lawyers to draft bill for consideration.  The Legislative Council failed to set a date.

<P><STRONG>December 1995</STRONG> - Pro se plaintiffs file suit in state court against the Pueblo of Isleta - Isleta Gaming Palace alleging gambling losses.

<P><STRONG>December 13, 1995</STRONG> - US Attorney John Kelly demands that gaming tribes close down casino operations by January 15, 1995, or face prosecution and forfeiture of gaming equipment.

<P><STRONG>December 22 - 31, 1995</STRONG> - Tribes refuse US Attorneys demand to close.

<H2>1996</H2>

<P><STRONG>January 2, 1996</STRONG> - Private citizens file suit in state court naming banks and credit agencies in federal court for alleged violations including racketeering and others.

<P><STRONG>January 3, 1996</STRONG> - Nine Tribes file suit to keep casinos open.  The suit names Attorney General Janet Reno, Secretary Bruce Babbit and US Attorney John Kelly and includes request for injunctive relief to prevent Department of Justice action against Tribes including civil forfeiture proceedings until the validity of the compacts has been determined as a matter of federal law.

<P><STRONG>January 16, 1996</STRONG> - The EIGHTH New Mexico legislative session after notice and request to negotiate gaming compacts begins.  The Governors call includes Indian gaming compact ratification.
<BR><BR>
<center><P>|  <a href="../nmiga/">Return to main menu </a> |</P></center>           

