HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Enterprise/2.0a
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 08:57:27 GMT
Last-modified: Thu, 25 Jan 1996 16:53:00 GMT
Content-length: 24360
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> type_Document_Title_here </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><H2>
POSITION PAPER<BR>
OF THE NEW MEXICO INDIAN GAMING ASSOCIATION<BR>
ON PROPOSED AMENDMENTS TO THE INDIAN GAMING REGULATORY ACT<BR>
JULY 1995
</H2></CENTER>
<H4><CENTER>Introduction</CENTER></H4>
<P>
	Congress is considering, at the urging of many state governments, a number of amendments to the Indian Gaming Regulatory Act ("IGRA"), the 1988 federal law governing gaming establishments on Indian reservations.  The Indian tribal governments that make up the New Mexico Indian Gaming Association present this paper to provide their position on the issue of Indian Gaming for the members of the New Mexico congressional delegation, other members of Congress, tribal governments in other states, and the people of New Mexico.  </p>
<P>
	Gaming on reservations has emerged in New Mexico and throughout the Nation as a means for tribal communities to climb out of the most dismal economic conditions that exist anywhere in the Nation.  Formidable obstacles impede economic improvement on the reservations, and, to date, they have proven largely insurmountable.  Gaming on reservations simply must be considered against this defining backdrop.</P>
<P>
	It is helpful, therefore, first to discuss the economic climate in which New Mexico Indian gaming exists.  New Mexico is one of our poorest states, ranking forty-sixth in the nation in per capita income.  In New Mexico, as in virtually every other western state, Indian people are the poorest of the poor.  According to the 1990 census, the average per capita income of New Mexico Indians was $5,141.  Of 34,170 Indian households in the state, 17,417 (51%) earned less than $15,000 in annual income.  Of 27,883 Indian families in the state, 12,092 had income in 1989 below the poverty level.  That translates to 60,431 Indian people, 46% of the state's total Indian population, living in poverty; 26,643 of these poor are children.</P>
<P>
	Other measures of economic well-being tell an equally grim story.  Of 63,991 Indians age 25 or older, 13,484 had less than a ninth-grade education, and another 13,287 failed to finish high school.  Only 58.2% of adult Indians were high school graduates; only 5.8% had college degrees.  Twenty-three percent of the state's Indian homes lack complete plumbing facilities.  The numbers are even worse in New Mexico's Third Congressional District, in which the majority of New Mexico's Indian reservations are located.</P>
<P>
	Clearly there is a compelling need for economic development on New Mexico's Indian reservations.  Many of the most impenetrable barriers to reservation economic development are the direct result of state government interfering in reservation affairs, sometimes with federal acquiescence.  For example, the state routinely claims the authority to tax reservation enterprises, even where the tribe and federal governments are taxing that enterprise and the state provides few or no services to either the enterprise or the Indian community.  This results in a ruinous double or triple tax burden on reservation enterprises that discourages the initial investment of capital and inhibits the growth of existing businesses.  Similarly, the states claim the authority to impose their environmental laws, their liquor laws, and their zoning laws to reservations, thereby either discouraging investment in or prohibiting altogether activities that might profit an Indian community.  We are dismayed that the states would attack the highly profitable business of Indian gaming in light of the states' uninterrupted history of discouraging reservation economic development through attempts to apply state laws, in addition to federal and tribal laws, to tribal development projects.  Only a few tribes have had the resources to fight these state laws in court but, when they have, tribes often have won.  In light of this history, we cannot accept the states' statements that they are concerned with economic conditions in Indian communities.  </P>
<P>
	One of the few bright spots in the bleak picture of Indian economies is Indian gaming.  Of the twenty-two Indian tribes in New Mexico, ten have tribal gaming operations located on their Indian lands.  All of the tribal gaming operations are 100% tribally owned and operated.  Several of the gaming operations were started with outside investors spending several million dollars in New Mexico on construction and start-up costs.  For many tribes, Indian gaming is the first successful Tribal enterprise that provides confidence and capital to venture into other businesses.  Tribal members employed by the gaming operations are gaining experience at every level of the operations.  For many tribal members, this is their first job, and the experience they gain at gaming operations prepares them to compete in the larger job market.  In addition to tribal members we each employ, we provide employment to individuals from surrounding Indian and non-Indian communities.  Based upon data gathered by the Center for Applied Research in Denver, Colorado, tribal gaming has created directly 2,650 jobs in New Mexico for both Indians and non-Indians.  These jobs mean that employees can provide the basic necessities of life: food on their tables, shelter for their families, school supplies and clothes for their children.  The multiplier effect (the impact of employees' income that is spent by employees on goods and services in the community) of these jobs, plus jobs related to our purchasing of goods and services, translates into over 13,000 jobs in the State of New Mexico.  Our annual payrolls exceed $46,000,000, and we purchase over $69,000,000 worth of goods and services, primarily from surrounding non-Indian communities.  (The multiplier effect of these expenditures is in excess of $215,000,000.)  Through our promotional out-reach, we have transported and attracted customers from all across the nation.  With few exceptions, these gaming customers stay at hotels, eat at restaurants, and spend money in shops located off our reservations. </P> 
<P>
	In addition, we make contributions to Indian and non-Indian charitable and non-profit organizations.  One gaming tribe, for example, has donated well over 1 million dollars to various charitable organizations since beginning operations nine years ago.  Unlike commercial non-Indian gaming profits, which go into the pockets of the few, the profits from our tribal gaming enterprises go to our tribal governments' general funds and support tribal government services, programs, and projects that benefit our people.  These revenues provide salaries for our employees and repair and maintenance of our community facilities, such as sewer and water systems.  These revenues provide funds for training and education programs, fire and law enforcement departments, and a variety of other programs and services.  These revenues provide investment capital for business acquisitions and reduce unemployment and the financial burden that unemployment brings.  </P>
<P>
	Despite these successes and contributions to the economy at large, we now find the Indian gaming industry in the State of New Mexico in serious jeopardy.  In a strange, though--to us--not surprising, move, the state Supreme Court ruled on July 13, 1995, that the Governor of New Mexico did not have the authority to sign the compacts on behalf of the state.  The court did not rule on the validity of the compacts already signed by the Governor and approved by the Secretary.  The Pueblos and Tribes in New Mexico are confident that the compacts are valid and we remain bound to our obligations under the compacts, and we will fulfill those obligations to the extent we are able, notwithstanding the state's recent action.  We expect and insist that the federal government stand with us to protect the validity of the compacts under the solemn trust responsibilities to protect tribal assets and under the Indian Gaming Regulatory Act.  We have placed too much reliance on our compacts to provide economic stability through economic diversification to have them threatened after these long years of struggle.  </P>
<P>
	The reason so many tribes have turned to gaming is that the tribes have few viable economic development options.  As discussed above, we believe that our inability to develop viable reservation economies is in large part due to state efforts to tax and regulate economic activities on our lands.  We also note terribly unfair federal laws that either give states jurisdiction over Indian lands or allow the states economic advantages that we are not granted.  If the states are genuinely concerned about the development of viable reservation economies, let them support legislation that levels the playing field between tribes and states, gives the tribes the same tax advantages the states enjoy, guarantees fair forums for the resolution of tribal-state disputes, and guarantees tribes the same ability states have to create a legal and regulatory climate that encourages economic growth.  Rather than attacking Indian gaming, Congress should:</P>
<menu>
<UL>
<LI>Prohibit state taxation of any person, property, or activity that the tribes have jurisdiction to tax;
<LI>Prohibit the application of state and local environmental and zoning laws to persons, property, and activities within Indian country;
<LI>Amend the Internal Revenue Code to allow tribes to issue tax-exempt bonds for the same purposes that states may do so, and modify the volume caps on such bonds to reflect the small populations and greater need for capital in Indian communities;
<LI>Amend Public Law 280 to require states, upon the request of an Indian tribe, to retrocede any jurisdiction they may have acquired under the statute;
<LI>Repeal the McCarran Amendment, which gives state courts jurisdiction to adjudicate tribal reserved water rights; and
<LI>Ensure that tribes are given equitable shares of federal funds for highways, sewage treatment facilities, solid waste facilities, drinking water systems, and other critical infrastructure.
</UL>
</menu>

<P>	In our judgment, the issue is a simple one.  The states claim the issue is one of morality or infiltration by organized crime or state sovereignty.  It is nothing of the sort.  The issue, pure and simple, is competition for resources.  It is the same battle we have fought with the states for two hundred twenty years.  Indian tribes have always had something the states want.  First it was our land; then it was our water; then it was our timber, our fish and game, and our oil and gas; then it was our tax revenues.  Now it is our gaming revenues.  The states have always couched the issue in terms of "what is good for the Indians."  As discussed above, after two hundred twenty years of the states dictating "what is good" for us, our people are poor, ill-housed, and under-educated.  We encourage all Americans to see this battle for what it is: yet another effort by the states to take from the tribes.</P>
<H3><CENTER>
Position on Proposed Amendments to the IGRA
</CENTER></H3>

<P>1. <EM>New Mexico tribal governments believe that the states have failed to demonstrate a genuine need for changes to the IGRA.  Before amendments are considered, the states should be required to prove the facts they allege about infiltration by organized crime and adverse impacts on the states. </EM> The states are complaining that, because of the IGRA and the states' lack of authority over Indian gaming, there either is or will be infiltration by organized crime of Indian gaming facilities and adverse impacts on non-Indian communities in the states.  Unlike most petitioners to Congress, however, the states have not been required to show, by credible proof, that the negative circumstances exist.  The facts that have been produced before Congress show that the concern about organized crime is unjustified and that Indian gaming is proving a boon, not only to Indian communities, but also to the non-Indian communities that surround them.  The problems with the implementation of the IGRA arise from the refusal of certain states to participate faithfully in the processes required by the Act.  Under these circumstances, we are not persuaded that the Act requires amendments, particularly amendments of the type being proposed by the states.  The only amendment that may be necessary to ensure effective implementation of the Act is an express waiver of the states' Tenth and Eleventh Amendment immunity.  However, even this may not be needed, as the United States Supreme Court has granted certiorari on the issue of whether the current IGRA waives the immunity of the states and, if so, whether such waiver is enforceable.  If the Court rules in the tribes' favor, there will be no need to amend IGRA. </P>
<P></P>
<P>
	2.	<EM><U>New Mexico tribal governments support the efforts of Senator McCain and Senator Inouye to find an approach to this issue that is acceptable to both the tribes and the states</U></EM>.  Senators McCain and Inouye have proven their commitment to tribal sovereignty and the advancement of tribal interests.  We support the Senate Indian Affairs Committee's efforts to develop legislation and accept Senator Inouye and Senator McCain as honest and knowledgeable mediators between the tribes and the states; we take them at their word when they say they will not allow tribal interests to be harmed.  We do, however, reserve the right to withhold our support of any legislative proposal that emerges from the Congress if it does not adequately address the concerns of New Mexico tribes.</P>
<P>
	3.	<EM>The tribes of New Mexico believe that the IGRA currently allows the states the ability they need to control the scope of games in which Indian tribes may engage. </EM> The states complain that the courts have interpreted the IGRA in such a way that, if a state allows any form of Class III gaming within its borders, then Indian tribes may engage in all forms of Class III gaming.  That is not the law.  Both the IGRA and the courts have said that, where a state allows a particular form of gaming under any circumstances, then the tribes may engage in that form of gaming.  Only if a state flatly prohibits a particular form of gaming may the state refuse to negotiate a compact with a tribe for the conduct of that particular game.  If the states wish for tribes not to offer particular games, the IGRA gives the states the practical ability to prevent the tribes from doing so; all a state need do is prohibit the game to all of its citizens.</P>
<P>
	4.	<EM>The tribes of New Mexico will oppose any amendment to IGRA that would increase state jurisdiction over Indian gaming. </EM> State governments in general, and the government of New Mexico in particular, have proven completely unresponsive to the economic needs of tribal communities.  We see absolutely no reason to believe that, if the states are given further authority over Indian gaming, they will exercise that authority in ways that advance tribal interests.  	
	In fact, very recent events in our state indicate why states' role in Indian gaming should be limited.  New Mexico tribes spent years attempting to negotiate a compact with then Governor Bruce King, who consistently refused even to sit at the negotiation table.  The tribes, after years of good faith efforts to negotiate, were eventually forced to pursue litigation, and two tribes sued the state in 1991 for failing to negotiate in good faith.   The state asserted that it was immune from suit, and the tribes litigated the immunity issue all the way to the Tenth Circuit.  The Tenth Circuit ruled in favor of the tribes.  The Governor still stalled the negotiations.  Then the 1994 elections took place, and New Mexico elected a new Governor.  After intensive and prompt negotiations with Governor Johnson, the tribes and the state executed comprehensive gaming compacts in February, 1995.  The Secretary of the Interior approved the compacts and published the compacts in the Federal Register.  At that point, after spending years of painstaking effort and enormous amounts of attorneys' fees and other related expenses, the tribes reasonably believed that the matter was finally over.  Acting pursuant to their clearly established rights under the federally-approved compacts, the tribes have invested millions of dollars to expand existing facilities, upgrade equipment, and make other improvements. </P>
<P>
	However, the New Mexico Supreme Court ruled just this month that Governor Johnson had no authority to execute the compacts.  Thus, after years of intensive efforts by the tribes to negotiate a gaming compact, and after diligently pursuing all the steps outlined in the IGRA, including hard fought battles in the federal district court and the Tenth Circuit, the New Mexico Supreme Court, consisting of political appointees of the former Governor, has attempted to invalidate the compacts.  (We do not know the repercussions of the court's ruling given, among other things, the fact that we believe the compacts remain valid as a matter if federal law, and the state court's ruling on federal law issues is not binding on a federal court.) </P>
<P>
	This turn of events is discouraging, as the tribes believe that the New Mexico Supreme Court's opinion is clearly wrong and politically motivated.  These recent events further underscore the fact that, if tribes are left to the mercy of the state political apparatus (including the state's court systems), the tribes will more often than not be left out in the cold.  For these reasons, it is essential that states' involvement in Indian gaming be reduced or eliminated, not expanded. </P>
<P>
 	Given the fact that some in Congress sincerely believe more regulation is needed on reservations, we are willing to consider a redefinition, and perhaps even an expansion, of federal regulation of high stakes or Class III Indian gaming.  However, state control must be reduced or eliminated.</P>
<P></P>
<P>
	5.	<EM>The tribes of New Mexico are willing to explore alternatives to the provisions of the Act that have given rise to litigation over the "good faith" of the states, so long as there is a federal authority to whom we may turn for relief and the acts of that federal authority are enforceable in court against the states. </EM> We are willing to consider alternative means of resolving tribal-state disputes.  Whatever the forum for dispute resolution, there must be clear and enforceable time limits; the decision whether to turn to the alternative forum must be available to the tribes and the states on an equal basis; the forum must be a federal or tribal one; and the decisions of the forum must be enforceable against the states in federal court.</P>
<P>
	6.	<EM>The tribes of New Mexico will oppose any effort to expand the authority or influence of states in federal decisions whether to take land in trust. </EM> The IGRA carves out a prominent role for state governors in the Secretary's decision whether to take off-reservation lands into trust.  We believe it is too large a role, and we strongly support the proposed amendments in S. 487, that require the Secretary of the Interior to review the recommendations of the Governor of a state where the trust land is located, but no longer requires the consent of the Governor.</P>
<P>
	7.	<EM>The tribes of New Mexico would not oppose legislation to expand the coverage of federal criminal law where there is a demonstrated gap in the coverage of tribal, state, and federal law and where such an expansion is not an attempt to expand the application of state law to Indian reservations. </EM> We believe that federal criminal law now adequately covers gaming-related crimes on Indian lands.  If, however, the states can demonstrate that this is not the case, we are willing to discuss the expansion of federal law to cover identified gaps in coverage.  We also believe that any problems that exist are more likely the result of inadequate enforcement of existing laws, and we would support legislation providing additional resources to federal and tribal law enforcement agencies.  We will oppose any legislation that is an attempt to expand the application of state criminal laws to Indian country.</P>
<P>
	8.	<EM>The compacting process established in the IGRA provides a proper format to address the costs to the states of Indian gaming within their boundaries. </EM> We doubt that the net impact of Indian gaming to state treasuries is negative.  However, if the states can demonstrate such an impact, we believe that it is an appropriate issue to address in the compacting process established under the Act.  In fact, in the compacts we executed with the State of New Mexico, we agreed to pay the state a certain percentage of our revenues, in part to help defray any costs the state would incur as a result of Indian gaming.  If other satisfactory procedures were established for Class III gaming, we would not object to language allowing the financial impact on a state to be considered in establishing the conditions for the conduct of Class III gaming.  We must note, however, that the states have never offered to help the tribes offset the costs to the tribes of dealing with the impact of the activities of non-resident non-Indians on the reservations, and we find it somewhat disingenuous for the states to complain about their financial concerns under the circumstances.</P>
<P>
	9.	<EM>The Tribes of New Mexico have no objections to the imposition of minimum standards regarding internal controls, even though we do not think they are necessary. </EM> We do not believe that minimum internal control standards are necessary, as tribes in New Mexico, as well as tribes throughout the country, have demonstrated that they are fully capable of operating their gaming establishments in a responsible manner.  Further, we note the inequity of requiring tribal gaming establishments to meet minimum federal standards, even though there are no federal standards that apply to non-Indian gaming establishments throughout the country.  Nevertheless, if Congress determines that minimum standards are essential, we will not object, provided, of course, that the promulgation of these standards includes consultation with tribal representatives and that the standards acknowledge that not all Indian gaming establishments are alike.  Some are large operations, whereas others are very small, and there must be some flexibility in the standards so as not to impose unreasonable burdens on tribes. </P>
<P>
 	10.	<EM>The New Mexico tribes strongly support the proposal that tribes be allowed to negotiate a compact directly with the Secretary of the Interior if tribes and states cannot reach a compromise.</EM>  If a state does not wish to be involved in the compact negotiation process, it should not have to be.  In such cases, it would be in the best interests of tribes and states for tribes to deal directly with the Secretary of the Interior. </P>
<P>
	11.	 <EM> The New Mexico tribes support the general regulatory scheme proposed in S. 487, 
under which, absent compacts to the contrary, tribes will have the sole authority to issue licenses and 
carry on regulatory functions, and the federal government will act in an oversight capacity only.</EM>  
There is no need for the federal government (or a state) to issue licenses and\or carry on regulatory 
functions.  We recognize, as does S. 487, that in those unusual cases in which a tribe fails to regulate 
its gaming operation adequately, the federal government needs to step in and take a more active regulatory 
role.  However, the presumption should always be that, absent reliable evidence to the contrary, tribes are 
capable of, and in fact do, regulate their gaming operations responsibly.  </P>	
<P></P>
	       
<center><P>| <a href="../nmiga/">Return to main menu </a> |</P></center>


