</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Summary of Tribal-State Revenue Sharing Agreement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<H2><CENTER>SUMMARY OF TRIBAL-STATE REVENUE SHARING AGREEMENT</CENTER></H2> 

<BR>
<P><LI>	<MENU><EM>Summary</EM>.     The Tribe agrees to contribute a percentage of its class III gaming revenues to the State and local governments.</MENU></P>

</P><LI>	<MENU><EM>Purpose</EM>.     The Tribe shall contribute a percentage of its class III gaming revenues to the State and local governments <EM>in exchange</EM> for the State's promise not to restrict class III gaming under the compact or to expand off-reservation class III gaming beyond the limits specified in the revenue sharing agreement.</MENU></P>

<P><STRONG>NOTE:</STRONG>     The Indian Gaming Regulatory Act restricts an Indian tribe from using "net revenues" derived from class III gaming for purposes other than tribal government operations, general welfare, economic development, and charity.  25 U.S.C. 2710(b)(2)(B) & (d)(2)(A).  The Secretary of the Interior has determined that the revenue sharing agreement is a legitimate 
bargained-for-exchange and hence a legitimate cost of doing business (i.e., operating expense) 
that is not subject to the net revenue use restriction of the IGRA. </P>

<P><LI><MENU><EM>Revenue Sharing Payments.</EM>     The Tribe will make semi-annual revenue sharing payments to the State and local governments (located on or near the Tribe's reservation) as follows: 60% to the State and 40% to the local governments.  An Indian tribe does not qualify as a local government. </MENU></P>

<P><LI><MENU><EM>Calculation of Revenue Sharing Payments.</EM> </MENU></P>

<P><MENU><OL TYPE=A>
<LI>	<MENU><EM>Net Win</EM>.     The Tribe's revenue sharing payments to the State and local governments are based  upon a percentage of the "net win" derived from class III gaming.  The revenue sharing agreement defines "net win" as the gross class III gaming revenues less (1) the amounts paid out as prizes, (2)  federal, state, and tribal regulatory fees, and  (3) taxes.</MENU>
</OL></MENU></P>

<P><STRONG>NOTE:</STRONG>     Tribal "operating expenses" for class III gaming are <EM>not</EM> deducted from the net win under the revenue sharing agreement.  Compare the definition of "net revenues" in the IGRA, which states that the "'term net revenues' means gross gaming revenues of an Indian gaming activity less amounts paid out as, or paid for, prizes, and <EM>total operating expenses</EM>, excluding management fees,"  25 U.S.C. 2703(9)(emphasis added), with the definition of "net win" in the revenue sharing agreement. </P>

<P><MENU><OL TYPE=A START=2>
<LI><MENU><EM>Tiered Percentage</EM>.     The percentage payable to the State and local governments is based upon two tiers:</MENU>
</OL></MENU></P>

<MENU><P><MENU><OL>
<LI><MENU>3% of the net win under $4 million.</MENU>
<BR>
<LI><MENU>5% of the net win over $4 million.</MENU>
</OL></MENU></P></MENU>

<P><STRONG>NOTE:</STRONG>   Assume the Tribe makes $24 million in net win from class III gaming for the year.  The Tribe would pay the State and local governments $120,000 (3% of $4 million) plus $1,000,000 (5% of $20 million) for a total of $1.4 million or $840,000 to the State (60%) and $560,000 to the local governments (40%). </P>

<P><MENU><OL TYPE=A START=3>
<LI><MENU><EM>Due Dates</EM>.     The Tribe shall make the revenue sharing payments no later than 25 days after December 31 and June 30 of each year. </MENU>
</OL></MENU></P>

<P><MENU><EM>Limitations.</EM>     The Tribe's obligation to make revenue sharing payments is contingent upon the compact being in effect and the obligation shall terminate if: </MENU><P>

<P><MENU><OL TYPE=A>
<LI><MENU>The State restricts class III gaming allowed under the compact; or</MENU>
<BR>
<LI><MENU>The State expands off-reservation class III gaming. However, the following events do not constitute an expansion of off-reservation class III gaming: (1) the enactment of a state lottery, (2) the operation of electronic gaming devices by veterans or charitable organizations as of February 10, 1995, and (3) the operation of electronic gaming devices by horserace tracks, except that the Tribe shall only have to pay one-half of the percentage of net win on the days the horserace tracks operate such devices for <EM>less than</EM> 12 hours and the Tribe shall not pay any percentage of the net win on the days the horserace tracks operate such devices for <EM>more than</EM> 12 hours. </MENU>
</MENU></OL></P>

<P><MENU><EM>Effect of Variance.</EM> </MENU></P>

<P><MENU><OL TYPE=A>
<LI><MENU><EM>Compact Effective</EM>.     If the State violates the limitations of the revenue sharing agreement and the Tribe's obligation to make revenue sharing payments ceases, then the compact shall continue to remain in effect, but the Tribe's obligation to reimburse the State for documented regulatory expenses shall "automatically increase" to $100,000 per year.</MENU>
<BR>
<LI><MENU><EM>State Regulatory Expense Increase</EM>.     If the Tribe's revenue sharing payments to the State and local government amount to less than $100,000 per year, then the Tribe's obligation to reimburse the State for documented  regulatory expenses shall "automatically increase" to $100,000 per year less the revenue sharing payments. </MENU>
</OL></MENU></P>

<P><STRONG>NOTE:</STRONG>   Under section 4(E)(5) of the compact, the Tribe agrees to reimburse the State for regulatory expenses not to exceed $25,000 per year. </P>

<P><MENU><EM>Interpretation</EM>.     The revenue sharing agreement shall be interpreted broadly to accomplish its purpose. </MENU></P>

<P><MENU><EM>Dispute Resolution</EM>.     The dispute resolution procedure set forth in the compact shall govern all disputes under the revenue sharing agreement. </MENU></P>

<P><MENU><EM>Effective Date</EM>.     The revenue sharing agreement is effective on the day the compact becomes effective. </MENU></P>

<P><MENU><EM>Amendments</EM>.     The revenue sharing agreement may be amended in writing by both parties. </MENU></P>

<P><MENU><EM>Definitions</EM>.     Unless otherwise defined, the terms in the revenue sharing agreement  have the same meanings used in the compact. </MENU></P>

<P><MENU><EM>Equal Treatment</EM>.     The Tribe is to be treated equally with other tribes so that if any other tribe enters into a revenue sharing agreement that has more favorable terms, then the Tribe may operate under the more favorable terms without amending the revenue sharing 
agreement or the compact.</MENU></P>
<BR>
<center><P> | <a href="../nmiga/">Return to main menu </a> |</P></center>
</BODY>
