<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HTML 
VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HEAD>
<TITLE>The Pueblo of Pojoaque - education and tradition</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<CENTER>
<H2>The Pueblo of Pojoaque - education and tradition</H2>

<TABLE WIDTH=90%>
<TR>
<TD ROWSPAN=3>

<P>Pojoaque has used the revenues from gaming to donate money to the 
local schools, the Pojoaque Valley school district. The children of 
Pojoaque attend this school district, but due to inadequate state 
funding, there are very few funds available for extracurricular 
activities. The money donated by Pojoaque Pueblo is being utilized 
for travel to academic and athletic activities. The emphasis on 
education is important to Pojoaque, for they believe the only way to 
beat the cycle of poverty is through education.</p>

<p>In a more practical application to education, when the Pojoaque 
Valley public schools water storage system broke down and left the 
school without water for a few days, Pojoaque Pueblo donated the 
money to have it repaired.</P>

<P>Pojoaque places high value on the preservation of the Indian 
culture. Pojoaque provided funds for the construction of a kiva, 
for use in religious and spiritual ceremonies. Pojoaque is continuing 
in its defense of the Indian culture of New Mexico by using its gaming 
revenues for the construction of the Poeh Center. The Poeh Center 
offers sculpting, clay and pottery, Tewa classes, and many other 
traditional activities known by the Pueblo Indian people. Pojoaque 
Pueblo is also taking an active role in the patronage of promising 
Indian artists. By sponsoring a young artist, the Pueblo feeds it 
can Promote Indian art in the art world internationally. The Poeh 
museum is also participating in cultural exchanges with Asia and 
Europe
</P>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=325>
<CENTER><a href="./poj4b.jpg"><IMG src="./poj4a.gif" ></a></CENTER>
</center>
<br>
<CENTER><P><I>Kivas among the other New Mexico Pueblos and tribes have 
been maintained through hundreds of years and are price-less. 
However, because Pojoaque had been abandoned by its tribal members 
in the past, its Kiva had not been maintained therefore $300,000 in 
gaming revenues were used to build this traditional Kiva. </I></P></CENTER>
</TD>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=325>
<CENTER><a href="./poj5b.jpg"><IMG src="./poj5a.gif" ></a></CENTER>
<BR>
<CENTER><P><I>Poeh Cultural Museum is another step towards building 
Pojoaque's historic culture by providing classes in pottery, 
sculpture and claywork. Also, Tewa speaking classes are provided. </I></P></CENTER>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=325>
<CENTER><a href="./poj6b.jpg"><IMG src="./poj6a.gif" ></a></CENTER>
<BR>
<CENTER><P><I>Otis soapstone is work done by Pojoaque Pueblo artist 
George Rivera located at the Poeh Cultural Center.
</I></P></CENTER>
</TD>
</TR></TABLE>
<H4>| <a href="./pojoaq3.htm">More on the Pueblo of Pojoaque</a> | <a href="../nmiga/">Return back to Index</a> | </h4>
</CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
