<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN">
<HTML VERSION="-//IETF//DTD HTML STRICT LEVEL 2//EN"><HEAD>
<TITLE>NMIGA - Summary of Tribal/State Compact</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<H1>SUMMARY OF TRIBAL-STATE COMPACT</H1>

<P></P>

<H3>1.	Authorized Gaming</H3>

<P><I>State Public Policy</I>. The Tribes may conduct any class III gaming permitted by 
State law for any purpose by any person, organization, or entity. <A href="#note1">(Note 1)</A> Compact, Section 3.</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Operation Standards</I>. The Tribes may establish the number and types of class III gaming, the hours and days of operations, and betting and pot limits. <A href="#note1">Id.</A> </P>

<P></P>

<H3>2.	Location of Indian Gaming.</H3>

<P></P>

<P><I>Indian Lands</I>. The Tribes may conduct class III gaming only on "Indian lands." <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 2(B). </P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Definition.</I> "Indian lands" is defined as lands over which the Tribes exercise jurisdiction and governmental control and which are either located within an Indian reservation (including Pueblo Spanish land grants), held in trust by the United States for the "exclusive" benefit of a tribe or a member thereof subject to federal restrictions against alienation. <A href="#note1">Id.</A> </P>

<P></P>

<H3>3.	Regulation of Class III Gaming.</H3>

<P></P>

<P><I>Tribal Gaming Agency</I>. The tribal gaming commissions are designated as the governmental bodies primarily responsible for overseeing, regulating, enforcing, and controlling gaming activity on Indian lands in accordance with applicable laws. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 4(A).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>State Oversight</I>. State is entitled to review any and all records, inspect gaming facilities, and monitor tribal gaming activity. See id. At Sections 4(E), 5(D), 5(E), and 8(A).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>18-Year Olds</I>. Any person under the age of 18 may not participate in gaming activities as either a customer, a key employee, or primary management official. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 4(B)(1).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Tribal Laws.</I> The tribal gaming commissions must provide the State with copies of all tribal laws and amendments thereof affecting class III gaming. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 4(B).</P>

<P></P>
<P><a name="note1"><B>Note 1:</a> The Compact acknowledges that the State permits charitable and fraternal organizations to conduct a full range of gaming activities under Section 30-19-6 NMSA 1978 (1994 Repl. Pamp.), otherwise known as the Permissive Lottery Exception. Compact, at Recitals, 5th Whereas clause.</B></P>
<P></P>
<H3>4.	Accounting Requirements.</H3>

<P></P>

<P><I>Books and Records</I>. The Tribes must maintain detailed books and records in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. Copies of books and records must be kept for six years. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 4(C).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Annual Audit</I>. The tribal gaming operation must be audited on an annual basis by certified public accountants licensed in the state. <A href="#note1">Id.</A> </P>

<P></P>

<H3>5.	State Responsibilities.</H3>

<P></P>

<P><I>Background Investigations</I>. The Tribes must provide the State with information about key employees, primary management officials, providers of gaming equipment, devices and supplies, and management contractors to allow the State to conduct an independent background investigation and consider the recommendations of the State regarding the licensing of a person or entity. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 4(E)(1).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Right to Inspect</I>. The State may inspect all gaming facilities, gaming activity, and records pertaining to gaming, subject to proper notification to the Tribes. The State is not compelled to carry out its right to inspect, but may do so when authorized by proper legislation. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at 4(E)(2).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Confidentiality of Records</I>. The State will keep confidential all information provided by the Tribes under the Compact to the extent allowed by law. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 4(E)(3).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Payment to the State.</I> The Tribes must reimburse the State up to $25,000 per year to compensate the State for any monitoring activities under the Compact. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 4(E)(5).</P>

<P></P>

<H3>6.	Licensing and Background Investigations.</H3>

<P></P>

<P><I>Required Licenses</I>. The tribal gaming commissions must license all key employees, primary management officials, and management contractors.<A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 5(A).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Required Information</I>. All individuals and entities subject to licensing must submit detailed information about themselves to allow the tribal gaming commissions to conduct background investigations. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 5(B).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Background Investigations</I>. The tribal gaming commissions are required to conduct extensive background investigations of key employees, primary management officials, and management contractors. The purpose of the background investigation is to determine whether the employees, officials, and contractors are suitable for employment in the gaming industry and do not pose a threat to the public interest, the effective regulation of gaming, or create or enhance the danger of unfair or illegal gaming practices. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 5(C).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Federal and State Review</I>. The tribal gaming commissions must submit all background investigation reports to the National Indian Gaming Commission ("NIGC") and the State for review and comment. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 5(D).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Grant of License</I>. The tribal gaming commissions may issue a license if neither the NIGC nor the State has notified them of any adverse information concerning the applicant. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 5(E).</P>

<P></P>

<H3>7.	Management Contractors.</H3>

<P></P>

<P><I>License Required</I>. Any management contractor, including its principals, must be licensed. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 5(F)(1).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Conditions for Management Contracts.</I> The management contract must, among other things: (a) require the contractor to comply with the Compact and the Indian Gaming Regulatory Act ("IGRA"); (b) establish a satisfactory accounting system and internal controls to permit an audit and verifiable financial reports; and (c) establish a mechanism for resolving disputes between the contractor and the Tribes. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 5(F)(2).</P>

<P></P>

<H3>8.	Gaming Equipment and Supplies.</H3>

<P></P>

<P><I>Minimum Technical Standards</I>. The Tribes must adopt minimum technical standards for gaming equipment, devices, and supplies that are at least as strict as the standards adopted by the State of Nevada for comparable equipment, devices, and supplies. All gaming equipment, devices, and supplies not meeting the minimum technical standards must be upgraded or replaced so as to comply with such standards within one year of the date of the Compact. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 6.</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Background Investigations</I>. The Tribes must conduct background investigations of and license all providers of gaming equipment, devices, and supplies. <A href="#note1">Id.</A> </P>

<P></P>

<H3>9.	Dispute Resolution.</H3>

<P></P>

<P><I>Procedure.</I> (A) Notice of Non-Compliance. A party to the Compact may notify the other of an alleged violation of the Compact; (b) Informal Resolution. The parties meet to informally resolve the dispute; (c) </P>

<P>Notice to Cease. If the problem is not resolved by informal resolution, then a party may notify the other to cease the offending activity; (d) </P>

<P>Election to Cease or Invoke Arbitration. The party served with a notice to cease may elect to cease the offending activity or invoke arbitration; (e)</P>

<P>Arbitration. The dispute is resolved by binding arbitration; and (f)</P>

<P>Enforcement of Arbitration Award. Arbitration awards may be enforced by an action for injunctive relief in any court of competent jurisdiction. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 7(A).</P>

<P></P>

<H3>10.	Protection of Customers and Public Safety.</H3>

<P></P>

<P><I>Public Liability Insurance</I>. The Tribes must carry public liability insurance policies of not less than $1 million to cover personal injury and property damage to any customers. Neither the Tribes nor their insurance carriers may assert the Tribes' sovereign immunity as a defense to a claim for damages made under the policies, subject to certain limitations set forth in the Compact. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 8(A).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Safety Codes</I>. All gaming facilities must be constructed to meet the Uniform Building Code, Uniform Plumbing Code, National Electrical Code, and Uniform Fire Code. The gaming facilities must be inspected annually and the State may be present during the inspections. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 8(B).</P>

<P></P>

<H3>11.	Criminal Jurisdiction.</H3>

<P></P>

<P><I>United States Jurisdiction</I>. The Compact acknowledges that under federal law the United States has exclusive criminal jurisdiction to prosecute violations of the IGRA. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 10.</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Memorandum of Understanding</I>. The United States Attorney, the Tribes, and the State may enter into a Memorandum of Understanding to permit the State concurrent jurisdiction to prosecute non-Indians for violating state gambling laws on Indian lands. <A href="#note1">Id.</A> </P>

<P></P>

<P></P>

<H3>12.	Binding Effect and Duration.</H3>

<P></P>

<P><I>15-Year Term</I>. The Compact is effective for 15 years and is automatically renewed for successive 5 year terms, unless modified or terminated by agreement. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 11(A).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Renegotiation of Compact</I>. Either the State or the Tribes may request renegotiation of the Compact by giving notice of its desire to do so at least one year before the Compact expires or is renewed. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 11(B).</P>

<P></P>

<P><I>Reopening Negotiations</I>. While the Compact is in effect, the State and the Tribes may reopen negotiations regarding any provision in the Compact or any issue not addressed therein. Any amendments to the Compact must be approved by the Secretary of the Interior. <A href="#note1">Id.,</A> at Section 11(D).</P>

<P></P>

<center><P> | <a href="../nmiga/">Return to main menu </a> |</P></center>
