<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Navajoland Attractions</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/sand.gif">
<CENTER><A HREF="seal.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="./images/attract.gif" ALT="Navajoland Attractions" BORDER="0"></A></CENTER>
<P><A HREF="./images/pole2.jpg"><IMG
ALIGN="RIGHT" SRC="./images/pole1.jpg" ALT="Monument Valley Yei' bi' Chei' & Totem Pole"></A></P>
<P><B>Window Rock Tribal Park</B><BR>For many decades this rock formation was
very important in the Navajo Water Way Ceremony and still has a significant role
in the Navajo religion.  For more information write to: Navajo Parks and
Recreation Department, P. O. Box 9000, Window Rock, AZ, 86515 or call (520)
871-6647 or 7307.</P> 
<P><B>Navajo Nation Council Chambers</B><BR>Considered the most sophisticated
form of Indian government, it was reorganized in 1991 to form a three branch
government - executive, legislative and judicial. For more information about
tours of the council chambers please call (520) 871-6417 or write: Navajo
Council Chambers, P.O. Box 1400, Window Rock, AZ 86515.</P> 
<P><B>Navajo Nation Zoo &amp; Botanical Park</B><BR>The zoo includes animals
that are native to the Navajo Nation and domestic animals that are culturally
important to the Navajo people, especially large mammals and birds of prey.
Visitor hours are from 8 am - 5 P.M. daily.  For more information call (520)
871-6573 or write: Navajo Nation Zoological &amp; Botanical Park, P.O. Box 9000,
Window Rock, AZ 86515</P> 
<P><B>Navajo Arts &amp; Crafts Enterprise</B><BR>Established in 1941, Navajo
Arts &amp; Crafts Enterprise (NACE) houses some of the world's  most exquisite
and authentic (Navajo) Native American Art. For more information call (520)
871-4090, 4095 or write to: Navajo Arts &amp; Crafts Enterprise, P.O. Drawer A,
Window Rock, AZ 86515.</P> 
<P><B>Navajo Tribal Museum</B><BR>Housed within the premises of the Navajo
Arts and Crafts Enterprise is a hidden world of Navajo history and present day
Navajo culture. Visitor hours are from 8 am - 6 P.M. , during the summer, 8 am -
5 P.M., during the winter, Monday through Friday.  For more information about
related publications or Navajo music, call (520) 871-6673 or write to: Navajo
Tribal Museum, P.O. Box 9000, Window Rock, AZ 86515.</P> 
<P><B>Navajo Nation Fairgrounds</B><BR>The Navajo Nation Fairgrounds is the
site of the &quot;Largest North American Indian Fair&quot; - The Navajo Nation
Fair, which is held the first weekend after Labor Day in September.  For more
information call: (520) 871-6478, 6702, Telefax: (520) 871-6729,  or write to:
Navajo Nation Fair Office, P.O. Box 2370, Window Rock, AZ 86515. </P> 
<P><A HREF="./images/hubbell2.jpg"><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="./images/hubbell1.jpg" ALT="Hubbell's Trading Post"></A></P>
<P><B>Hubbell Trading Post National Historical Site</B><BR>Located 28 miles
west of Window Rock on State Highway 264, Hubbell Trading Post is home of the
nation's oldest known trading post.  Visitor hours are 8 am - 5 P.M. daily and 8
am - 6 P.M. during the summer, except on Thanksgiving, Christmas and New Year's
Day.  For more information call: (520) 755-3475 or write to: Hubbell Trading
Post National Historical Site, P.O. Box 150, Ganado, AZ 86505.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>St. Michael's Historical Museum</B><BR>This museum provides an overview
of the early influence of the Franciscan Friars upon the Navajo people.  Visitor
hours are 8 am - 5 P.M. , Monday through Friday, and 9 am - 5 P.M., April to
Labor Day.  For more information call (520) 871-4171 or write to: St. Michael's
Historical Museum, P.O. Box 680, St. Michaels, Arizona 86511.</P> 
<P><B>Navajo Nation Lake's</B><BR>Fishing is allowed year-round at 12 major
lakes on the Reservation.  The three most popular lakes Wheatfields, Whiskey and
Tsaile are stocked with Rainbow and Cutthroat Trout.  There are also Assayi,
Chuska Red Lake and Berland Lake, with channel catfish, warm water catfish.  For
more information on fishing permits call: (520) 871-6451 or write to: Navajo
Fish and Wildlife, P.O. Box 9000, Window Rock, AZ 86515.</P> 
<P><B>Shiprock Peak</B><BR>Navajo legend says that this jagged rock structure
was once a giant bird.  Today, it is called the rock with wings or in Navajo - &quot;Tse
Bitai.&quot;</P>
<P><B>Four Corners Monument Navajo Tribal Park</B><BR>This is the only site
in the country where the corners of four states - Arizona, New Mexico, Colorado,
 and Utah - come together. For more information call (520) 871-6647, 7307 or
write to: Navajo Nation Parks and Recreation Department, P.O. Box 9000, Window
Rock, AZ 86515.</P> 
<P><B>Chaco Culture National Historical Park </B><BR>You can immerse yourself
in the mysterious traces and spirit of the Anasazi or as the Navajo people call
them the &quot;Ancient Ones&quot; at Chaco Culture National Historical Park.  
For more information call (505) 786-7014 or write to: Chaco Culture National
Historical Park, Star Route 4, Box 6500, Bloomfield, NM 87413.</P> 
<P><A HREF="./images/ruins2.jpg"><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="./images/ruins1.jpg" ALT="Canyon de Chelly Whitehouse Ruins"></A></P>
<P><B>Canyon de Chelly National Monument</B><BR>Canyon de Chelly National
Monument houses about five periods of Indian culture dating from 350 AD to 1300
AD.  The 26-mile canyon or red stones rises from 30 to 1,000 feet which provides
a spectacular backdrop for hundreds of Anasazi ruins, Navajo homes and farms. 
For more information call: (520) 674-5436, 5500 , 5501, or write to: Canyon de
Chelly National Monument, P.O. Box 588, Chinle, AZ 86503.</P> 
<P><BR><BR></P>
<P><B>Navajo Community College/Hatathlie</B><BR>The first Indian - owned
community college in the country, features a six story, hogan shaped cultural
center.  For more information call: (520) 724-6600 or write to: Navajo Community
College, Tsaile, AZ 86556</P> 
<P><B>Dinosaur Tracks</B><BR>Over 200 million years ago a dinosaur sauntered
across some mud flats at the edge of a tropical sea, and today his tracks are
visible within 100 feet of the unpaved road to Moenkopi.  Located five miles
east of U.S. Highway 89 and one-quarter mile north of U.S. Highway 160 near the
Tuba City community.</P> 
<P><B>Elephant Feet</B><BR>Situated just of Red Lake, Arizona on U.S. Highway
160, are two giant stone remnants that truly resemble an elephant's feet.  There
are no facilities available.</P> 
<P><BR></P>
<HR SIZE="4" ALIGN="CENTER">
