<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Native Peoples Magazine - Passing the Torch (pt. 2)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#C9B49A" LINK="#445900" VLINK="#000000"><CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD
VALIGN="MIDDLE" COLSTART="1"><IMG ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="./seminole.gif"></TD><TD
VALIGN="BOTTOM" COLSTART="2"><H1 ALIGN="LEFT">People in the 1930s</H1></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P><BR></P><TABLE
BORDER="2" CELLPADDING="25" ALIGN="CENTER"><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><P>Adaptable is the word which best describes the i. laponki. people of
southern Florida. The i. laponki. are the Mikasuki speakers of the Seminoles who
have adapted to a constantly changing environment by learning various unusual
trades in order to remain independent of public assistance handed out by the
United States government. Their resentment of the U.S. government developed as a
result of  wars of removal which reduced their population from about 6000 to two
hundred people.</P>
<P>After these wars, the i. laponki. wanted to be left alone in their home in
the Florida Everglades. Living  off the lush plant and animal life found in the
Everglades, they traded such items as alligator hides, furs, and bird plums with
traders for necessary goods.</P>
<P>In time, the invading outside community changed the lives of the i. laponki.
In spite of these changes, the adaptable i. laponki found ways to modify their
lives in order to survive and prosper. After the eastern Everglades were drained
and the i. laponki. were no longer able to live off the land, they prospered by
entertaining the growing number of tourists visiting Florida with alligator
wrestling shows and selling patchwork clothing to the curious audience. Headsmen
who negotiated with the attraction owners were the communication link between
the i. laponki and the press. This connection kept the i. laponki. headsmen
informed of political events which might affect their people.</P></TD></TR><TR><TD
VALIGN="MIDDLE" ALIGN="CENTER" COLSTART="1"><IMG
SRC="florida.jpg" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><P>The matrilineal society of the i, laponki. maintained the cultural and
spiritual life in the community. These matriarchs traveled with their families
no matter where the tourist attractions ked them.</P>
<P>Disturbed that some i. laponki. preferred the independence of working in the
tourist attractions business to government assistance on the reservation, the
U.S. government sponsored surveys that condemned these people as being degrading
and bad. This bad press and the lure of increased government aid, found more and
more i. laponki. accepting the security the reservations offered, Unfortunately,
even on the reservation, the nativistic i. laponki. isolated themselves from the
Seminoles and Creeks who were influenced by different Christian missionaries.</P>
<P>Today, the i. laponki are still surviving both on and off the reservation.
Tourists can still see the i. laponki. wrestling alligators and selling their
crafts in Florida. Those on the reservation have chosen different occupations to
improve their lives.</P>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE><P><BR></P><CENTER><P><FONT SIZE="+1">S</FONT>end <FONT SIZE="+1">U</FONT>s <FONT
SIZE="+1">Y</FONT>our <FONT SIZE="+1">S</FONT>tories!<BR><FONT SIZE="+1">E</FONT>mail to: <A
HREF="mailto:native_peoples@amcolor.com">native_peoples@amcolor.com</A></P></CENTER><CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD
COLSTART="1"><A HREF="./readme.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="./back.gif" BORDER="0"></A><IMG
SRC="./tab.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></TD><TD COLSTART="2"><P ALIGN="CENTER">| <A
HREF="./index.html">Home Page</A> |<BR>| <A HREF="./readme.htm">Read Me</A> | <A
HREF="./news.htm">News &amp; Destinations</A> | |<A HREF="./products.htm">Buy Our Stuff</A> |<BR>| <A
HREF="./study.htm">Study Guide</A> |</P></TD><TD COLSTART="3"><IMG
SRC="./tab.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="./news.htm"><IMG
ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="./forw.gif" BORDER="0"></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>

</BODY></HTML>
