<html><head><title>AMERICANS FOR A BALANCED BUDGET</TITLE></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<center>
<blockquote>
<img src="/abb/images/hdr-pr.gif">
<h3>BLASTS AFL-CLO CONGRESSIONAL ELECTION EFFORT<BR>
$35 MILLION TARGETED FOR 75 DISTRICTS<BR>
</H3></CENTER>
<BR><P>
<b>For Immediate Release<br>
Contact: Ben Magliano<br>
202-638-6124<br>
<p>
             February 1, 1996</B> -- The AFL-CIO is planning to punish Republican congressmen who voted in favor of a 
balanced federal budget by pouring over $35 million dollars into 75 congressional races this 
year. Their goal is to win back Democratic control of the House of Representatives.<p>

This years $35 million dollar expenditure is seven times the normal amount spent by the 
ALF-CIO during an election year and represents an average of $466,000 per race. This figure is 
substantially higher than the $322,929 expended on all 1994 congressional races, according to 
current FEC data.<p>

&quot;I am amazed at the lengths the AFL-CIO will go in order to kill the balanced budget 
initiative, &quot; says Tony Zagotta, President of Americans For a Balanced Budget. &quot;Next to Bill 
Clinton, organized labor is a balanced budget's worst enemy.&quot;<p>

Americans For a Balanced Budget recently launched a nationwide radio campaign to 
correct the lies being told by the AFL-CIO over Medicare. These ads have run in Illinois, 
Massachusetts, New Jersey, Nevada, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Tennessee, Washington, and 
Wyoming over the past month.<p>

&quot;The AFL-CIO launched a dishonest campaign last year against 27 Congressmen for their 
courageous votes to balance the budget,&quot; says Zagotta, &quot;It now appears that the union leadership 
is poised to take their deceitful message to an even greater audience.&quot;<p>

In addition to the millions of dollars the AFL-CIO will pour into these congressional 
races, the labor giant will also make in-kind contributions of AFL-CIO personnel and facilities. 
These in-kind donations could easily double the $35 million dollar independent media campaign.<p>

&quot;The Oregon Senate race is a good example of the in-kind support that the AFL-CIO will 
be extending to upcoming congressional races, &quot; says Zagotta. &quot;More than 25 union activists 
were sent to Oregon to work full-time for Ron Wyden - that's a force nearly as big as Gordon 
Smith's entire campaign staff! In addition, the AFL-CIO paid for over 200,000 pieces of direct 
mail and set up phone banks throughout the state.&quot;<p>

AFL-CIO Leaders met with President Clinton for nearly two hours on January 8th 
and urged him to hold fast against Republican budget demands. In particular, the union 
representatives wanted to kill Medicare reform and reject any budget proposed 
tax cuts.<p>

&quot;Actions speak louder than words, so it is readily apparent that Bill Clinton lied to the 
American people during his State of the Union Address, &quot; says Zagotta. &quot;The era of Big 
Government is alive and well and has a good friend in the White House.&quot;<p>

Americans For a Balanced Budget is one of the leading groups fighting for a balanced federal 
budget. Founded in 1990, the non-partisan grassroots organization has over 200,000 members in 
all fifty states.<p>

-30-

