<HEAD>
<TITLE>guidlines</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="/bradley/bg.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<P><B>APPLICATION PROCEDURE</B>
<P>
<P>Two steps are required in the application process.  
First, the applicant should prepare a brief letter of 
inquiry, describing the applicant's organization and intended project. 
 If the Foundation determines the project to be within 
its current program interests the applicant will be invited 
to submit a formal proposal.
<P>
<P>The second step is the actual submission of the proposal. 
 Applicants should submit a letter presenting a 
concise description of the project, its objectives and 
significance, and the qualifications of the organizations and 
individuals involved.  Included with the letter should be a project 
budget, the amount of the grant sought from The 
Bradley Foundation, and other sources of support.  The 
applicant should complete the &quot;Grantee Tax Exempt 
Status Information&quot; form included with the Program 
Guidelines and submit a copy of the IRS letter confirming 
the organization's tax exempt and public support status 
under Sections 501(c)(3) and 509(a), respectively, of the 
Internal Revenue Code.
<P>
<P>Meetings between the Foundation staff and 
applicants, where necessary, will be arranged after the receipt of 
a written proposal.  Final authority for making grants 
rests with the Board of Directors, which meets four times a 
year, February, May/June, September, and November.  
The Directors act on grant requests after proposals have 
been comprehensively reviewed by Foundation staff.  
Each proposal is reviewed according to its unique characteristics. 
 To be considered at one of these meetings, proposals 
should be submitted by the following dates:  December 1, 
March 1, July 1, September 1.
<P>
<P>Whenever possible, proposals submitted by these 
deadlines will be considered at the next Board meeting.  
However, circumstances may sometimes require a lengthier period 
of review.
<P>
<P>Because of the necessarily limited resources of 
the Foundation, many worthwhile projects cannot be supported.  The demands on the Foundation's 
resources also limit the size of particular grants and the ability of 
the Foundation to make commitments for extended periods.
<P>
<P><B>DEVELOPING A DETAILED PROPOSAL</B>
<P>
<P>This is a checklist which we hope will be useful to you 
in developing a detailed proposal.  It is intended as a 
guide only on points to make in a request.  We do not expect 
or want a lengthy proposal but need only sufficient detail 
to go forward with our review.
<P>
<P><I>Program Description</I>
<P><ul>
<P><li>     Statement of the basic objective of the 
proposal (one paragraph).
<P><li>     Definition of the problem to which the proposal 
is addressed.
<P><li>     Statement of potential impact of the proposal 
on the problem.
<P><li>     Whom will it benefit and how?
<P><li>     Description of work plan and time frame 
for accomplishing the objectives of the proposal.
<P><li>     Length of time Bradley Foundation aid will 
be needed and most desirable times to start and terminate the grant.
<P><li>     How will the project be supported beyond 
the period of funding requested from the Foundation?
<P><li>     Is this a new or an ongoing activity on the part 
of sponsoring institution?
<P><li>     Has the field been researched to find similar efforts?
<P><li>     Has a similar project succeeded or failed?  Why?
<P><li>     Description of evaluation plan:
<P>     <ul><li>  ongoing evaluation of program during period of
<P>         the grant
<P>     <li>  criteria by which the effectiveness of the grant
<P>         should be judged at the end of the grant period.
<P></ul></ul>
<P><I>Project Personnel</I>
<P><ul>
<P><li>     Brief description of the qualifications of 
individuals who will be conducting the project and administering the grant if awarded.  Include 
resumes for key personnel.
<P></ul>
<P><I>Sponsoring Institution or Agency</I>
<P><ul>
<P><li>    Brief background of sponsoring institution.  
Include evidence of institution's appropriateness to 
sponsor work.
<P><li>     List of Board of Directors/Trustees.
<P><li>    Evidence of institutional approval of proposal.
<P><li>    Evidence of responsible fiscal accounting on 
part of sponsoring institution. Include most recent audit.
<P><li>    Other institutions participating in the project 
(if appropriate).  Note:  Foundation policy 
prohibits the use of Foundation funds for payment of 
fund-raising consultants.
<P></ul>
<P><I>Budget</I>
<P><ul>
<P><li>     Please use the following budget form as a guide 
for providing a budget for your project.  Where applicable indicate what funds have been 
requested from other sources and whether or not they 
have been granted. 
</ul>
<P><B>BUDGET INFORMATION</B>
<P>
<P>Sponsoring Institution's Overall Budget
<P><ul>
<P>    <li> Current Fiscal Year     
<P>    <li> Last Fiscal Year
<P>
<P>
<P></ul>
<P>Project Budget (Where not applicable, enter N/A)
<P><ul>
<P>    <li> Salaries
<P>    <li> Benefits
<P>    <li> Rent
<P>    <li> Utilities
<P>    <li> Reproduction Expenses
<P>    <li> Telephone
<P>    <li> Travel
<P>    <li> Subscriptions
<P>    <li> Publications
<P>
<P>
<P></ul>
<P>Institution's Sources of Support (General)
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>Sources of Support, This Project:
<P>(Indicate Status of Outstanding Requests)
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
