<html><head><title>CRC Foundation Watch Vol. II No. 1</title></head><body><a name="top"><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" background ="/crc/images/bg.gif"><a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation bar" border="O" align="left" ISMAP></A><BLOCKQUOTE><center><IMG ALT="Foundation Watch" src="/crc/images/hdr-fw.gif"></center><font size=+1><i>Foundation Watch Vol. II No.1</i></font><P> <FONT SIZE=+1><B>December, 1996</B></FONT><p><hr><P><FONT SIZE=5>A Television Network of Their Own: 
How the Great Foundations Established PBS</FONT><P>by Laurence Jarvik<BR><P><FONT SIZE=2>What we know as our present Public Broadcasting Service
began with a $5 million federal appropriation in 1967. Over thirty years PBS has grown 
into a multi-billion dollar worldwide multi-media empire.  While its public sources of funding and its 
commercial enterprises are common knowledge, its foundation ties are little understood.  PBS is largely the 
creation of the great private foundations.  The most important of these are the Ford Foundation -- which has 
poured over $300 million into the television market to support non-commercial broadcasting -- and the 
Carnegie Corporation of New York, whose 1967 Carnegie Commission report led to the establishment of 
the federally-funded Corporation for Public Broadcasting in the Johnson Administration. </FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Today, public radio and television comprise the largest networks on the air.  When judged by 
number of affiliates, PBS is bigger than Fox, CBS, NBC, or ABC.  Public broadcasters also publish 
magazines and newsletters, and they provide computer programs, on-line services, sites on the World Wide 
Web, and classroom study guides and textbooks.  They host conferences; license toys, games, and clothing; 
stage live shows; run mail order catalogs and retail stores; and distribute videocassettes and compact disks.  
These activities have created a large industry that parallels commercial broadcasting.  Yet the natural 
checks and balances of the marketplace do not govern their operations, nor are they regulated by the 
political checks and balances of a federal agency.
</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>The bureaucratic structure of PBS is deliberately complicated and very difficult to describe.  
Former PBS president Larry Grossman has said it is "a system no one in the outside world understands or 
can penetrate. It is a system that ensures that public television will remain mired in second-class status with 
a top-heavy, expensive and stifling bureaucracy..."  But in other ways it is like the other broadcast 
networks.  MacNeil-Lehrer Productions president Al Vecchione testified to Congress in 1988 that "all of 
the same functions, duties and responsibilities that exist for commercial broadcasting also exist for public 
broadcasting.  Commercial networks have a corporate division which does the allocating of money and 
establishes the priorities through policies; we have CPB.  They have a network division which obtains, 
schedules, and distributes the national programming; we have PBS."</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>In 1993 New York's Twentieth Century Fund, a liberal foundation based on the Boston 
department store fortune of Edward I. Filene, assembled a blue-ribbon task force to examine the finances 
and practices of PBS.  (PBS stations declined to open their books and therefore research was dependent on 
what station managers estimated rather than actual figures).  The panel was chaired by Brown University 
president Vartan Gregorian and included executives Eli Evans from the Revlon Foundation and Lloyd 
Morrissett from the Markle Foundation as well as former PBS president Larry Grossman and current PBS 
president Ervin Duggan.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>The task force's conclusions were presented in a final document, <I>Quality Time?</I>, which 
described a system that wastes three-quarters of its money, produces mediocre programming, and depends 
on British imports to please its audience.  The Twentieth Century Fund task force recommended that all 
federal aid to local PBS stations be ended, a conclusion that it based on the principle that "individual 
station operations should be supported by the communities they serve."  While the diagnosis of PBS's 
problems was telling, the task force prescriptions were not implemented.
</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT><P><I><B><FONT SIZE=2>BUNDY, FRIENDLY, GARDNER: PRESENT AT THE CREATION<BR></FONT></B></I><P><FONT SIZE=2>The origins of public broadcasting lay in a 1960's era decision by the Ford Foundation to shift its spending 
on television programming from support for <I>Omnibus</I>, a cultural affairs program hosted by Alistair 
Cooke in the 1950's on all three networks, and to invest instead in the creation of a national educational 
network.  That decision had the unintended consequence of drawing educational and cultural programs out 
of the commercial networks and putting it into the television equivalent of a fancy suburban subdivision 
insulated from civic life.  "Quality" programs like <I>National Geographic</I> specials, Texaco 
broadcasts from the Metropolitan Opera, and Leonard Bernstein's symphony concerts switched to PBS 
from the networks where they originated, and became the corollary to the hollowing out of American cities 
that resulted as the upper-middle classes retreated to secure enclaves of safe streets and good schools.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>In the 1950's, the commercial networks did a good job in exposing large audiences to cultural 
programming.  NBC mingled adaptations of Shakespeare (e.g. Sir Maurice Evans's 1954 <I>Hallmark Hall 
of Fame</I> production of "Macbeth") with its popular fare.  CBS's Ed Sullivan Show exposed audiences 
to the Bolshoi Ballet as well as Elvis Presley, and Agnes De Mille's ballets along with The Beatles. The 
networks in the 1950's and 1960's did much to provide "highbrow" entertainment for the mass audience, a 
fact that academic critics of television have tended to overlook.  Indeed, much PBS programming was 
poached from the commercial sector.  The <I>MacNeil-Lehrer Newshour</I> was produced by a team 
from NBC News and resembled the <I>Huntley-Brinkley Report</I>.  Bill Moyers shuttled between CBS 
News and PBS.  William F. Buckley's <I>Firing Line</I> first appeared on RKO General stations before 
moving to PBS.  <I>Frontline</I>'s first anchorwoman was NBC News' Jessica Savitch.  Veteran Moyers' 
producers from CBS News launched <I>The American Experience</I> while <I>National 
Geographic</I> specials simply moved from CBS.  <I>Nova</I>'s science producers came from the 
BBC.  The makers of CBS's <I>Captain Kangaroo</I> produced <I>Sesame Street</I>.  Even the 
Muppets had done early commercials for La Choy Chow Mein.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Yet, in his best-selling 1967 memoir, <I>Due to Circumstances Beyond Our Control</I>, Ford 
Foundation television consultant Fred Friendly called for the establishment of National Educational 
Television _ what would become PBS _ by postulating a conflict between "common stock"  and "the 
common weal."  Friendly claimed that ratings, commercials, and the profit motive were obstacles to first-
rate television coverage and argued that television would never live up to its potential until it abandoned its 
connection to the commercial marketplace.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Friendly recognized what writer Jane Jacobs in <I>Systems of Survival</I> (1992) has described 
as a conflict between the "commercial moral syndrome" based on trade and the "guardian moral syndrome" 
based on power and position.  But unlike Jacobs, who argues that each has its appropriate function, 
Friendly clearly disdained trade.  He argued that "television will gain the most if it is given a less profit-
minded base; instead, its health would be guaranteed by the nation's intellectual well being, which it must 
help develop in order for both the country and the medium to survive."  Simply put, Friendy wanted to 
replace popular and entertaining shows with programs acceptable to his personal taste and notions of 
quality.  He even boasted to readers that Ford Foundation president McGeorge Bundy recently had hired 
him to develop projects in "public service" broadcasting in opposition to the principles of commercial 
television.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Bundy and Friendly were an odd couple.  Friendly had built his personal fortune as Edward R. 
Murrow's radio and television producer:  their <I>Hear It Now</I> records were bestsellers.  He was an 
autodidact, a middle-class striver from Providence, Rhode Island who never graduated from college yet 
became a Columbia University professor.  By contrast, Bundy was a genuine Boston Brahmin who had 
won all the glittering prizes in education and public service.  The grandson of Harvard president A. 
Lawrence Lowell, Bundy moved from elementary school classmate of John F. Kennedy to dean of the 
Harvard faculty.  As a young man he had helped Secretary of War Henry Stimson write his memoirs, and 
in 1961 he left Harvard to serve as national security advisor to presidents Kennedy and Johnson, helping to 
develop the policies that led to the Bay of Pigs, the Cuban Missile Crisis and the war in Vietnam.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Bundy's reward for public service was the Ford Foundation.  As president from 1966 to 1979 
Bundy authorized the expenditure of hundreds of millions of dollars for television _ for projects selected 
and overseen by Friendly.  The largest grant recipient was WNET channel 13, a flagship operation in New 
York City, America's largest television market and the nation's media center.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Sizeable grants also went to WGBH, Boston, whose president, Hartford Gunn, was McGeorge 
Bundy's Harvard roommate.  Not surprisingly, WGBH became the largest supplier of programs to PBS 
after Gunn became PBS's first president in 1969.  In public television lore the Boston station's call letters 
stand for "God Bless Harvard."</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Like many of the "best and brightest," Bundy could not have helped but be affected by one of the 
most influential books of the period, John W. Gardner's <I>Excellence: Can We Be Equal and Excellent 
Too?</I>, which appeared in 1961.  Gardner was a foundation man, too, heading up the Carnegie 
Corporation.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Gardner's arguments provide an intellectual roadmap for one of the great exertions of the early 
1960s:  The attempt by those in and around the Kennedy and Johnson administrations to foster a national 
program of cultural uplift and, with it, a new social and cultural elite.  Public broadcasting was but one 
element alongside New York City's Lincoln Center, Washington D.C.'s Kennedy Center, and the National 
Endowments for the Arts and Humanities in the mission to create American equivalents to Europe's 
national monuments of culture and learning and a social class to appreciate them.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>In his book, Gardner argued that America's leadership class at the close of the 1950's was 
inadequate for a great world power.  A Ph.D. in psychology with expertise in intelligence testing, Gardner 
was appalled by what he perceived as the middle-brow mediocrity of Eisenhower's America.  Like Bundy, 
he worked for the OSS during World War II and was obsessed by the idea of "excellence" and the 
possibility of engineering it.  Gardner wanted to make a clean break with middle-class values in order to 
properly organize America's "natural aristocracy."</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Because leadership responsibility in America was too widely dispersed among different interest 
groups at different social levels, Gardner argued that leaders were failing to recognize the "obligations 
which they have incurred as a result of the eminence they have achieved."  Lacking badges of rank, they 
could not recognize one another let alone claim "their responsibility to the larger community. Opposed to 
notions of middle-class individualism, Gardner sought ways to encourage opinion leaders "to help a society 
achieve the best that is in it."  One way was clearly to establish a broadcasting system dedicated to "public 
service" and aimed at a target audience of the social strata that ought to hold sway in society.  Watching 
such a network would be a marker of respectability.
</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Like Bundy, Gardner was a philanthropist, educator, and government official.  As president of 
Carnegie, he personally approved the initial $500,000 grant which made possible the 1967 Carnegie 
Commission report on public television.  As President Johnson's Secretary of Health, Education, and 
Welfare, Gardner testified before Congress in 1967 to urge federal funding of the Corporation for Public 
Broadcasting.  And shortly after that he approved the first HEW grants to produce <I>Sesame Street</I>.
</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2><i><b>THE ORIGINS OF PUBLIC BROADCASTING</i></b><BR></FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>On September 16, 1962, the his-tory of American television changed when the legendary broadcast 
journalist Edward R. Murrow hosted the dedication of WNET channel 13 to the cause of public 
broadcasting.  It became the first non-profit educational television station to broadcast in New York City.  
This event marked the transition of what was then called "educational television" from an instructional 
medium for extension courses carried in secondary broadcast markets into what would become at decade's 
end the PBS network.  FCC chairman Newton Minow appeared with Murrow on the maiden broadcast.  
Minow's position was made clear the year before when, in a speech to the National Association of 
Broadcasters (NAB), he had scolded his audience for creating a "vast wasteland" - two words that 
influenced public perceptions of commercial television for a generation.  In due course Minow became 
chairman of PBS and later of the Carnegie Corporation of New York.  But on that day Murrow and Minow 
were celebrating the start of a public broadcasting system whose origins began in an earlier era of radio.  
Foundation financing, however, was always a key ingredient in the attempt to shape its development.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>The first educational stations were established by colleges and schools on radio in the 1920's.  
They tended to depend on the goodwill of state legislatures, boards of regents, and local philanthropists.  In 
1929, however, two major New York philanthropic institutions, the Carnegie Corporation and the Payne 
Study and Experiment Fund, evinced interest in the new trend by financing an Advisory Committee on 
Education by Radio.  The committee issued its report in 1930 with recommendations that the federal 
government reserve broadcast bandwidth for educational purposes and that it work to obtain funding for 
education programs.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>In July 1930, the Rockefeller Foundation commissioned its own report.  Unlike the Carnegie-
Payne study, Rockefeller recommended that educational programming be integrated into commercial 
broadcasts.  The straightforward reason: money.  Educators, it concluded, could not be expected to raise 
the budgets necessary to finance their own stations.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>A third group, the National Committee on Education by Radio (NCER), opposed a commercial 
takeover and supported the college and university stations.  Established in 1931 and financed by the Payne 
Fund, its members included the National Education Association and the National Association of State 
University Presidents.  The Committee urged the federal government to reserve 15 percent of available 
radio bandwidth for noncommercial educational use.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>The Federal Radio Commission, the FCC's predecessor, eventually agreed to set aside five radio 
channels for non-commercial use in 1938,  and it added fifteen more by 1945.  After World War II radio 
expanded into the FM portion of the dial, and the FCC reserved still more room for educational radio, a 
precedent that subsequently would be applied to television channels in the 1950's.
</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>At the end of World War II, fledgling commercial television broadcasters did not see educational 
broadcasters as potential rivals.  In October 1950, the University of Iowa began broadcasting on 
commercial channel WOI-TV, making it the first educational television station in the United States.  (It 
received funding from the Ford Foundation's Fund for Adult Education.)  Commercial broadcasters even 
offered educational institutions free television air time because in those early days they could not generate 
enough advertising to support a full schedule of paid programming.  For instance, DuMont (the forgotten 
fourth and least profitable television network, many of whose stations eventually became Fox affiliates 
when Rupert Murdoch set up shop in the 1980's), made a deal with the New York Board of Education to 
carry instructional programs at no charge.  Philadelphia's WFIL-TV collaborated with the University of 
Pennsylvania and the Annenberg Foundation, headed by publishing magnate Walter Annenberg (later 
funder of the Annenberg/CPB Project) to produce Penn faculty lectures grandly labelled "University of the 
Air."  So poor was the National Association of Educational Broadcasters (NAEB) that it resorted to 
"bicycling" - routing from television station to station - sound tapes (and later films) for broadcast among 
its 52 member stations.
</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>In 1948 the FCC froze new licenses for commercial television channels, an act that would have 
far-reaching consequences.  Officially, the action was caused by a dispute between CBS and NBC over 
incompatible color broadcasting systems that delayed the introduction of color television by a decade.  But 
one effect was that it helped to preserve the commercial networks' broadcasting oligopoly and, with it, the 
industry's dominance by Democrats.  The networks' FCC television licenses had been issued during the 
Roosevelt and Truman administrations, and many Democratic leaders considered that their partisan 
advantage in the new medium of television merely balanced the predominantly Republican owners of the 
major daily newspapers.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>A second consequence of the freeze was that it gave an opening to advocates of noncommercial 
broadcasting.  NAEB took quick advantage.  It retained the law firm of Leonard Marks and Marcus Cohn, 
both former FCC officials, and filed to reserve for educational use ten Ultra High Frequency (UHF) 
television channels.  UHF was a new television technology, analogous to FM in radio.  To discredit 
commercial VHF channels NAEB conducted a study of violence on television (a tactic repeated today in 
the debate over the so-called "v-chip").  Supported by a grant from the Ford Foundation, it documented 
2,970 "acts of violence" on commercial television in the single week, seventeen in children's viewing hours 
before 9 p.m.  This would be the first of many such studies that supporters of public broadcasting would 
use for political ends.  The National Education Association (NEA) and the American Council on Education 
(ACE), both Washington, DC-based education lobbies, supplied funds to prepare testimony before the FCC 
supporting channel reservation for educational purposes.  The NEA and ACE also supported the Joint 
Committee on Educational Television (JCET), a new group whose purpose was also to lobby for channel 
reservation.  It had a $90,000 grant from the Ford Foundation's Fund for Adult Education to pay for legal 
expenses incurred in preparing testimony on this issue before the FCC. </FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>JCET hired Telford Taylor to prepare its case.  He was the former prosecutor at the Nuremberg 
War Crimes Trial, a former FCC general counsel, and one of the most prominent attorneys in the United 
States at the time.  Exuding high-mindedness yet not lacking in political connections, Taylor prepared his 
testimony using the NAEB violence study as evidence of the need for commercial-free television channels.  
With financial help from the Ford Foundation's Fund for Adult Education, the JCET compiled over seventy 
statements supporting its case.  They came from the AFL-CIO, the PTA, and many prominent educators.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>By the time the FCC "freeze" on commercial licensing ended in 1952 American educational 
institutions had succeeded in obtaining exclusive rights to 242 radio and television frequencies for the 
purposes of non-commercial instructional broadcasting.  They were divided between 80 VHF stations and 
162 UHF stations.  Although educational television proponents did not have the equipment, staff, or 
programming to fully use all 242 channels, they promised a golden future.  In 1953, KUHT at the 
University of Houston, Texas, became America's first non-commercial educational licensee.  By 1960 there 
would be 49 educational television stations operating on the 257 channels reserved by the FCC.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2><I><B>HIS MASTERS' VOICE</I></B> <BR></FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>In 1952 the Ford Foundation set up the National Citizen's Committee for Educational Television with a 
$90,000 grant to lobby for educational broadcasting.  That same year the Ford Foundation's Scott Fletcher 
became director of the Educational Television and Radio Center, which was established in Ann Arbor, 
Michigan to provide programs to educational broadcasters.  Ford gave the Center an initial grant of 
$1,350,000; a year later the grant was more than doubled.  By 1960, Ford's annual support was around $14 
million.  By 1970, Ford would pour over $300 million into a variety of educational stations and 
programming, creating in the process the National Educational Television network (NET).  "Without 
repeated Ford Foundation transfusions," Erik Barnouw, a Columbia University professor and historian of 
American television has said, "NET and the whole system might have soon collapsed."  NET would be the 
dominant force in educational television until the Corporation for Public Broadcasting (CPB) was 
established in 1967.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Other events in the 1950s helped to taint commercial broadcasting and aid Ford's cause.  Public 
broadcasting's proponents would argue that commercial interests were vulnerable to McCarthyism and that 
noncommercial broadcasting was less susceptible to blacklisting and the "Red Scare."  The television quiz 
show scandals of the late 1950s also helped discredit commercial sponsorship.  After English instructor 
Charles Van Doren confessed that producers had coached him to give the right answers on a popular quiz 
program, Congress in 1960 passed legislation prohibiting rigged contests and requiring notice of paid 
consideration.  The "payola" scandals involving recording company payments to radio disk jockeys 
followed in 1961.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Under these circumstances the commercial networks came to see support for educational 
broadcasting as a good way to relieve the pressure from Congress while transferring requirements for 
public service programming to a third party. As one commercial broadcaster told an interviewer, "PBS got 
the crazies off our backs."  From its inception, then, public broadcasting has been a servant of many 
masters. It was the result of a deal struck in the 1950's which has not come undone.  Commercial 
broadcasters seeking to maximize profits and reduce congressional interference sealed a pact with 
academic and foundation professionals seeking prestige, money, and influence.
</FONT><P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>USING PULL TO GET A TV STATION IN NEW YORK<BR></FONT></B></I><P><FONT SIZE=2>There was no national program schedule in educational television's early years.  Viewership of the mostly 
UHF stations was extremely sparse, and the quality of their instructional programs was low.  Almost none 
of Ford's money had gone to the creation of original programming.  And out of constitutional concerns, no 
federal funds were used to produce programming for educational stations in the 1950's.  John F. White, 
NET president from 1958 to 1969, adamantly opposed federal support, warning that a domestic United 
States Information Agency was a danger to democracy.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>The major purpose of the NET organization was to overcome the shortage of quality 
programming.  But NET was not a genuine network in the manner of NBC, CBS, or ABC.  Instead, it 
syndicated programs to educational television stations by bicycling films and tapes from station to station.  
In fact, a Ford Foundation grant enabled many stations to purchase their first videotape recorders in 
exchange for using NET materials in their broadcasts.  Still, John White wanted to create a national 
educational "fourth network," and he pushed for electronic interconnections over telephone lines and for 
more national programming, often against the objections of local university stations that had their own 
priorities.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>White's most important accomplishment was to establish an educational television station in New 
York City.  Although it was the nation's cultural and media center, New York had no educational non-
commercial television station until WNET was launched in 1962.  White understood that this single station 
would promote the political cause of his entire NET system.  He was right.  As television critic Martin 
Mayer has observed, "The breakthrough in non-commercial television came in 1962, when a self-
perpetuating nonprofit corporation raised the money to buy channel 13 in New York.  Educational 
television lost its state-college, school-system image and became something the New York-based national 
media started to discuss more seriously.  Congress responded with the first appropriations to help build and 
equip non-commercial stations, and Ford escalated its support."</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>White decided that the New York station had to be on a VHF channel because VHF had a better 
quality signal than UHF, where most educational stations were found.  To facilitate plans to purchase such 
a station, he assembled some of the wealthiest and most influential men in the city in the fall of 1959.  
They included Standard Oil heir John D. Rockefeller III, New York University chancellor George 
Stoddard, Corning Glass chairman Arthur A. Houghton, Jr. and New York Life chairman Devereux C. 
Josephs.  In November 1960, he met again with Josephs as well as Howard C. Sheperd, retired chairman of 
First National City Bank, and Henry G. Fischer, who later served as NET's FCC attorney.  As a result, 
Fischer tendered a $4 million offer to purchase station WNTA in Newark, New Jersey on February 9, 
1961.  The owner was National Telefilm Associates, whose chairman was a New York producer, Ely 
Landau.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Meanwhile, White had met with his friend Charles Heald,  president of the Ford Foundation 
(before Bundy)  to secure Ford's help on the purchase.  Heald's only condition was that NET not be 
publicly identified with the station's purchase.  White and Heald agreed that the New York station could 
not be perceived as more important to NET than any of the other 79 stations then subscribing to the 
network.  Rural stations were already worrying that NET might be "going New York" when its corporate 
headquarters earlier had moved from Ann Arbor to Manhattan.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>White also met with FCC Chairman Newton Minow.  Minow's primary interest was to keep the 
station out of commercial hands.  "As far as I'm concerned," he threatened Ely Landau at the time, "we're 
going to get a non-commercial station in there, one way or the another.  I don't know how yet, but I'm 
going to be very straight with you.  I'm going to oppose any transfer to another commercial licensee."  In 
other words, Minow intended to use his power as a regulator to force Landau to sell his station to the group 
he preferred.  Minow unsuccessfully tried to persuade his fellow FCC commissioners to pass a rule 
requiring cities with seven VHF channels to set aside one channel for educational broadcasting.  However, 
the FCC did agree to a special inquiry, which created a credible threat.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>On May 9, 1961, Minow delivered his "vast wasteland" speech.  "The public is your beneficiary," 
he said to the assembled broadcasters.  "If you want to stay on as trustees [of the airwaves], you must 
deliver a decent return to the public -- not only to your stockholders."  Minow went on to differentiate 
between shows he found worthwhile -- "CBS Reports," "The Twilight Zone," and Fred Astaire -- and the 
westerns and police dramas (many now regarded as classics) he scorned for their violence and 
simplemindedness.  And he denounced the "screaming, cajoling, offending" commercials that paid for such 
programming.  At a later press conference President Kennedy chimed in:  "Mr. Minow has attempted not to 
use force but to use encouragement in persuading the networks to put [on] better children's programs, more 
public service programs."  Then JFK tried to calm those who feared greater government involvement in 
broadcasting: "I don't know of anyone -- and Mr. Minow has already denied -- changing the basic 
relationship which now exists."</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>In fact, the chairman of the FCC had made clear to the American public how federal funding for 
educational broadcasting would be justified, and the President had endorsed his position.  Although most 
non-commercial broadcast frequencies were still unused, educators were determined not to relinquish them 
to the private sector.  In 1962 the federal government authorized $32 million dollars in matching grants for 
the construction of educational television facilities.  The educators and foundation heads had secured a 
beachhead to federal money and power over educational broadcasting and would use it for their political 
purposes.</FONT><P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>BRINGING UP BABY: CARNEGIE AND FORD SIRE PBS<BR></FONT></B></I><P><FONT SIZE=2>The 1960's were the most important decade in the development of public broadcasting.  "Public" replaced 
"educational" television under the aegis of Lyndon Johnson's Great Society.  In 1964, the federal Office of 
Education sponsored an educational broadcasting conference whose most significant result was the 
formation the next year of the Carnegie Commission on Educational Television.  It looked at issues in 
long-range finance.  When MacGeorge Bundy and Fred Friendly arrived at the Ford Foundation in 1966 
they focused on NET's potential for news and "public affairs" (i.e. political) programs unconstrained by a 
popular audience or commercial advertising.  Bundy had doubled to $40 million the annual budget of 
Ford's Division of National Affairs and he saw educational television as an outlet to promote "public 
discussion of issues which are controversial."  That meant Ford's agenda to shore up Great Society 
measures in race relations, poverty programs, and community action.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Bundy and Friendly drew up ambitious plans for satellite programming distribution and the 
establishment of a national broadcasting network.  At its peak the foundation was spending $100 million a 
year on educational television, sponsoring NET projects to influence the development of local and regional 
flagship stations around the country.  What Ford really needed now was a way to more clearly promote its 
political agenda on the most powerful station under its control in the largest market in the country, New 
York.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>In January 1967, the Carnegie Commission delivered its report and almost answered Ford's every 
wish (Ford had actually paid for some of Carnegie's costs).  It called for a Corporation for Public 
Television, guaranteed federal support of educational stations, the establishment of two production centers 
and telephone or satellite facilities to make possible live broadcasts to the entire network.  In short, it 
recommended the basis for public broadcasting as it is today.  Legislation was introduced in Congress and 
LBJ declared his support for passage of the Public Television Act.  In 1967 Johnson signed the bill 
establishing the Corporation for Public Broadcasting.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>The baby sired by the great Foundations had finally been born.</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=2>===<BR></FONT><P><a name="review"></a>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>The Dramas of Donorship</FONT></B><P>by Robert Huberty<BR><P><FONT SIZE=2>Waldemar A. Nielsen, <I>Inside American Philanthropy: The Dramas of Donorship</I> (University of 
Oklahoma Press, 1996), 279 pages.<BR></FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>The transfer of private wealth from one generation to the next will soon reach astounding 
magnitudes.  Assuming that fortunes currently accumulated will continue to grow, it has been estimated 
that Americans will inherit $225 billion annually for the next forty years, an amount totalling $3.2 trillion 
by the year 2010 and $10.3 trillion by 2040.  It is also estimated that one percent of all heirs will receive 
one-third of the wealth transfer, nine percent will receive the second third, and the rest of us will get the 
remainder.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Waldemar Nielsen, author of <I>The Big Foundations</I> (1972) and <I>The Golden 
Donors</I> (1985), ponders what this will mean for philanthropy.  As of 1994 there were about 39,000 
American foundations with combined assets of $196 billion.  Nielsen predicts that if only two percent of 
estimated private wealth is dedicated to philanthropy it is likely that the number of American foundations, 
their assets and their grantmaking will double by 2010.  That's only thirteen years away.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2><I>Inside American Philanthropy</I> is a fast-paced survey of dozens of American donors and 
the foundations they created.  Neither a scholarly history nor a research analysis of current philanthropic 
practices, it wears its learning lightly and its opinions are couched in careful and discreet language.  Yet 
Nielsen is a preeminent observer of the foundation scene, and the authority of his prescriptive judgments is 
implicit in the little parables he tells.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>For Nielsen the most salient feature of American philanthropy is that it is giving by individuals.  
No matter that their staffs think themselves professional and their procedures grow bureaucratic, American 
foundations are the creations of individual donors.  Each donor is differently motivated and all take 
distinctive courses of action.  The resulting "dramas of donorship" vary: some develop into heroic odyssey 
(Andrew Carnegie) while others take on the appearance of tragedy (Edwin Land) and farce (Andy Warhol).  
Good intentions yield bad results and vice versa.  Nothing can be taken for granted about the future 
creation of foundations because each donor is differently motivated, has a different end in mind, and 
chooses different means to achieve it.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Nielsen's book is a collection of stories.  California's Arnold O. Beckman, who has advanced 
scientific knowledge through the discriminating distribution of major gifts during his lifetime, is a 
philanthropist in the classic mold.  More innovative is George Soros, who is using his wealth to open 
markets and promote political integration in the formerly Communist states of Europe at the same time that 
he is wheeling and dealing to make money in those markets.  Nielsen applauds the scope and creativity of 
Soros's giving but worries that it may move beyond "its proper boundaries."  He says nothing about Soros's 
giving for drug legalization.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Arts philanthropy seems especially prone to high-handed and questionable behavior.  The uranium 
tycoon Joseph Hirshhorn seems to have outsmarted the federal government by giving it his enormous but 
less than mediocre art collection on condition that the Smithsonian build a museum on the Mall with his 
name on it.  And Occidental Petroleum's Armand Hammer for years hindered sensible art planning by the 
Los Angeles County Museum of Art.  It deferred to his demands because it expected to get his art 
collection, only to discover that he was building his own museum down the street.  Such entertaining 
examples are reminders that philanthropy involves dealmaking as well as generosity.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>Nielsen also identifies new trends in philanthropy.  For instance, it is likely that women will have 
more power over philanthropy as more become successful entrepreneurs or inherit vast estates (a 
consequence of the "unlimited marital deduction" permitted by tax reforms in 1986).  Women now create 
about one-quarter of new foundations.  One welcome result, Nielsen speculates, is that foundations 
increasingly will stress the importance of family life.  But he also notes that women seem more apt to treat 
private giving as an initial investment in social programs whose upkeep can then be transferred to the 
federal government.</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2>The notion that private foundations should fund ideas to make government more active is another 
recent development.  Nielsen gives major credit to Mary Lasker, president of the Albert and Mary Lasker 
Foundation, for promoting the concept of foundations as  public interest lobbyists.  Beginning in the 1940s, 
she helped launched the war on cancer and lobbied Franklin Roosevelt for government funding of medical 
research.  The Lasker Foundation also pioneered such then-innovative devices as soliciting celebrity 
endorsements for disease prevention, offering public awards for achievements in medical journalism, and 
publishing an annual health fact book.  This makes her in Nielsen's book "one of the half-dozen greatest 
American philanthropists ever."</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>If it is ironic that philanthropists who made their money in the marketplace should want to see 
government spending replace it, it is doubly so that Nielsen should have such confidence that government 
can carry out their intentions.  Whatever their flaws and idiosyncracies, individual donors are Nielsen's 
heroes.  They are the driving force behind what might be considered a final stage of capitalism: the urge to 
give away voluntarily the wealth that one has spent a lifetime acquiring.  Donors fuel philanthropy's vessels 
and set the course; foundation executives only steer.</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Indeed, Nielsen's convictions are so strong that he makes a concluding argument against 
foundation perpetuity.  Using the example of the Carnegie Corporation, Nielsen shows how chance and 
circumstances have shaped its leadership and grantmaking since Andrew Carnegie's death in 1919.  Nielsen 
has a high regard for the post World War II initiatives of Carnegie president John Gardner and his 
successors, but he thinks Carnegie might just as easily have followed other unnamed prominent 
foundations into "stagnation, fragmentation, and bureaucratization of programs."</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Waldemar Nielsen looks forward to the next century's explosion of private wealth and the 
prospects for a flood of major giving by individuals.  Whatever his own political convictions, this makes 
<I>Inside American Philanthropy</I> a socialist's nightmare.</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=2></FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=2>===<BR></FONT><P><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times">Letters to the Editor</FONT></B><P>
<blockquote>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Times">You made a valuable contribution to unmasking the Ford Foundation's ethnic agenda with the 
insightful and very informative article by Linda Chavez and Jorge Amselle ["Inside the Ford Foundation's 
Plan to Split Apart America,' vol.1, no.10].</FONT><P><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Times">Chavez and Amselle are absolutely on target when they describe the leaders of La Raza and 
MALDEF as crated and "kept" by Ford Foundation funding and in their description of how these self-
styled Latino leaders do not represent what a majority of Latinos perceive to be in their best interest.  
Nevertheless these Ford Foundation-nurtured organizations merit close scrutiny because they exert political 
influence and they tned to shape news in the Spanish media.</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=2>A good example is California's Proposition 187 initiative. During the petition phase, opinion 
polling found that about a three-fifths majority of Latinos supported the measure. Alarmed by these results, 
the Latino activist groups launched a major public relations campaign to convince Latinos that the measure 
was racist and inspired by anti-Latino sentiment. By the time the vote took place, the Latino vote in support 
had fallen to about 40 percent.</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The Latino organizations and their supporters in the Spanish-speaking media have also conducted 
major efforts to convince Latinos that immigration reform is racist-inspired and anti-Latino. Yet, as Chavez 
and Amselle document, Latino opinion still favors reduced immigration.  It is not hard to figure out why.  
The survey data indicate that the strongest support for immigration reduction among Latinos is by those 
who immigrated themselves most recently, and whose job might be readily taken by another new 
immigrant.</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Even though the Latino activist organizations have been cowed by public opinion for the moment 
into dropping defense of illegal immigration, that still is on their agenda, albeit in disguise.  That really is 
what the call during the Hispanic March for an extension of the amnesty for illegal aliens was all about. 
Yet, in one of the ironies of having so much money to spread around, the Ford Foundation also funded 
research on the conditions of the US migrant labor workforce that came to the conclusion that their best 
hope for the future lies in restricting the supply of illegal aliens taking those jobs. A Latino leader who 
wanted to advance the working conditions of his fellow Latinos would be a strong supporter of a system of 
verifiable identification along with employer sanctions against employing illegal aliens. Instead it appears 
that the Ford Foundation-backed Latino leaders are focused only on building the size of their supposed 
constituency as fast as possible through wide-open immigration.</FONT><P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Your readers who want to pursue information on the Ford Foundation's 
social agenda with Latinos might want to read <I>Importing Revolution: Open Borders and the Radical 
Agenda</I>, by William Hawkins. Like Chavez and Amselle's article, and Georgie Anne Geyer's 
investigative reporting, it documents how the Ford Foundation has been relentlessly pursuing a social 
policy designed to remake the American society in ways that most of us would oppose.</FONT>
<p>
&nbsp;
<p>
&nbsp;
<p>
<P ALIGN="right">
<FONT SIZE=2>
Dan Stein<br>
Executive Director<br>
Federation for American<br> 
Immigration Reform<br>
Washington, DC</FONT></P>
</blockquote></BODY></HTML>
