<head>
<title>CRC Foundation Watch Vol. I No. 11</title>
</head>
<body>
<a name="top">
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" background ="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation bar" border="O" align="left" ISMAP></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><IMG ALT="Foundation Watch" src="/crc/images/hdr-fw.gif"></center>
<font size=+1><i>Foundation Watch Vol. I No.11</i></font><P> 
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>December, 1996</B></FONT><p>
<hr>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Inside the Council on Foundations &quot;Fishbowl&quot;:
How Foundation Executives Wash Each Other's Brains</FONT>
<P>
by Laurence Jarvik<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The foundation world is deeply into self-examination.
 A num ber of recent events _ President Clinton's signing of the
welfare reform bill, passage of the California Civil Rights Initiative,
the bitter legislative struggle over the Istook amendment to limit
federally-subsidized lobbying, and Republican retention of both
houses of Congress _ have led top foundation leaders across the
country to return to the query first posed by Admiral Stockdale:
&quot;Who am I?  Why am I here?&quot;  Since the May 1996 annual
gathering in Atlanta of the Council on Foundations [see <I>Foundation
Watch </I>vol. 1, no. 5 &quot;The Council on Foundations Message
to America: The Era of Lady Bountiful is Over'] foundation staff
and executives have been meeting, and meeting, and meeting.  They
have gathered together in affinity groups and planning sessions,
attended workshops and made on-site visits, and endlessly reconfigured
conference table and chair arrangements to facilitate dialogue,
optimize understanding, and in general decide what to do next.
 </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>To see how foundation grantmakers wrestle with challenges
they face<I> Foundation Watch </I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>attended an unprecedented &quot;National Symposium
on Foundations and the Public Sector&quot; held in the Dupont
Circle Hotel in Washington, D.C. on November 14 and 15.  We were
also at an October session of the Communications Network in Philanthropy
in Detroit.  Not-for-profit self-scrutiny is further on display
in the latest publications from the foundation world.  See, for
example, Gerald Freund's new book <I>Narcissism and Philanthropy
</I>which chastises foundations for their insularity and urges
them to recognize and support talent [see review by Robert Huberty
on page 7]. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> In the methods they are adopting to confront what
they see as a threat to their legitimacy, the foundation aristocracy
is repeating the mistakes of group-think which helped create the
initial pattern of problems they confront and that have generated
so much anxiety.  Indeed, their choice of guru, former Federal
Trade Commission Chairman Michael Pertschuk, insures the continuation
of what Heather MacDonald characterized as a pattern of &quot;Destructive
Philanthropy&quot; in a recent <I>Wall Street Journal </I>article.
 Pertschuk, who now heads a Washington organization called the
&quot;Advocacy Institute,&quot; encourages nonprofit support for
liberal political advocacy _ precisely the type of activity drawing
the attention and ire of the Republican majority in Congress.</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></I>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>THE GODFATHER  OF ADVOCACY<BR>
</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Michael Pertschuk is not as well known as Ralph Nader
and he has less public visibility than Common Cause founder John
Gardner or Fred Wertheimer, the group's campaign finance lobbyist.
 But wherever an observer inquires into foundation and nonprofit
advocacy of government social welfare programs Pertschuk's imprint
is today visible.  More than any of the others, Pertschuk _ who
earns a $71,000 annual salary from the Advocacy Institute _ represents
the view that the purpose of philanthropy is to use private dollars
to leverage tax revenues for left-of-center causes. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Pertschuk has been called &quot;the Grover Norquist
of the Left&quot; by those familiar with his activities.  He helped
draft the strategy which defeated Robert Bork's nomination to
the Supreme Court, and he has been a consultant to the American
Cancer Society in its fight against the tobacco industry _ work
he began over thirty years ago as the coordinator of the Surgeon
General's first conference on Smoking and Health. More recently,
he assisted ABC News producer  Deborah Leff become president of
the Joyce Foundation  [see vol.1 no.6, &quot;How does the Joyce
Foundation deal with dissent? Squash  it!&quot;].<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> A  prep school graduate who attended both Yale University
_ as an English major, Pertschuk studied with <I>All the King's
Men</I> novelist Robert Penn Warren _ and Yale Law School.  Coming
to Washington in the Kennedy administration, Pertschuk served
for about a decade as chief of staff to Senator Warren Magnuson
(D-WA), chairman of the powerful Senate Commerce Committee.  Magnuson
was in his dotage near the end, and Pertschuk's power and influence
over legislation before the Committee grew so great that he gained
the reputation of being &quot;the 101st Senator&quot; and enjoyed
the social clout that accompanies power in Washington.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Pertschuk currently lives in the fashionable Northwest
section of the city and his children attended the Georgetown Day
School, an expensive academically prominent private school in
the Capital, alongside spawn of the Graham family, owners of <I>The
Washington Post</I>.  Pertschuk was named chairman of the Federal
Trade Commission in the Carter Administration.  In his ironically-titled
memoir <I>Giant Killers</I> (Norton, 1986), he boasts of enjoying
lunch at the pricey Four Seasons restaurant on the expense account
of a founding member of Washington's exclusive Congressional Country
Club.  His plutocratic habits extend to a taste for fine cigars,
which he smokes discreetly, inasmuch as he is professionally committed
to the anti-tobacco lobby's attempt to ban smoking in public.
 Pertschuk told <I>Foundation Watch </I>that he now only smokes
on hikes far from civilization and &quot;at my daughter's wedding.&quot;
 (James Miller, the FTC chairman during the Reagan administration
and Pertschuk's successor, recalls, &quot;When in fact he smoked
cigars, he made a point of not smoking in public, or when the
TV cameras were around.  But he smoked cigars.  I smoke cigars,
too.&quot;)  As a consultant to the American Cancer Society, Pertschuk
co-ordinates global anti-smoking programs.  Invited to acknowledge
this small personal weakness, Pertschuk retorts that his opposition
is to large corporations that profit from harmful products, not
to smoking<I> per se</I>.  By such ideological logic are Cuban
cigars preferable to Marlboro cigarettes.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> When he was chairman of the Federal Trade Commission
Pertschuk tried to ban television advertising to children, a move
that earned him the sobriquet &quot;the national nanny&quot; in
a critical <I>Washington Post </I>editorial. Pertschuk dismisses
the <I>Post</I>'s criticism, claiming that the paper's opposition
was motivated not by its editorial  commitment to free speech
but by the corporate self-interest of its parent company, the
owner of television stations.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> This instinctual opposition to corporations is inherent
in Pertschuk's mind-set.  He searches for the vicious corporate
self-interest in every private sector act while attributing a
noble public interest to every nonprofit sector act.  Indeed,
this is the assumption that underlies Pertschuk's Advocacy Institute.
 Co-chaired by veteran Common Cause lobbyists David Cohen and
Kathleen D. Sheeky _ and supported by the Ford Foundation, the
Joyce Foundation, the MacArthur Foundation, the Nathan Cummings
Foundation, the Kaiser Family Foundation, the New York Community
Trust, the Tides Foundation, the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation
and the Florence and John Schumann Foundation (headed by Bill
Moyers's son, John) _ the Advocacy Institute spends some $2 million
annually running workshops, training sessions, and networking
activities for foundations and &quot;community&quot; organizations.
 Its mission statement declares its political objective, &quot;strengthening
the capacity of social and economic justice advocates to influence
and change public policy.&quot;  Despite decades of misguided
social spending, Pertschuk remains blind to the failures of federal
government programs and foundation support for nonprofits who
promote it.  When asked about the Great Society's ignominious
War On Poverty, he only responds that its initiatives &quot;were
not fully funded.&quot;  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> One might go so far as to say that the Advocacy
Institute's sources of funding suggest a self-interested reason
why Pertschuk won't publicly criticize his patrons and the failure
of their initiatives, to use his own method of analysis.  Pertschuk
knows how the bread of advocacy is buttered.  The Institute's
1995 annual report states &quot;the largest grants to the Institute
come from private foundations.&quot;  If the priority of foundation
giving were direct provision of services rather than advocacy,
the first casualty would be the Advocacy Institute.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Pertschuk's uncritical attitude toward the mandarins
of philanthropy was manifested at the three-day meeting of the
Communications Network in Philanthropy in Detroit on October 9-11.
 He was there to inform public relations staffers from the foundation
sector about the &quot;threats&quot; to their activities and to
recommend how they could be overcome.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>A GATHERING OF  GIANTS<BR>
</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> By words the mind is excited and  the spirit elated,&quot;
read the quote from Aristophanes gracing the cover of the program
packet for the 1996 Communications Network in Philanthropy Fall
Conference.  Hosted by the Charles Stewart Mott Foundation of
Flint, Michigan, the conference was held at the Atheneum Hotel
in Detroit's Greektown.  This was the venue for the annual gathering
of public relations officers who belong to the &quot;affinity
group&quot; of the Council on Foundations, and those in attendance
represented the giants of philanthropy. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Among those present were emissaries of the biggest
of the big foundations: America's largest, the $7.5 billion Ford
Foundation, was represented by vice-president Robert Curvin. 
Karen E. Lake, director of communications, carried the flag for
the $6 billion W.K. Kellogg Foundation.  Victoria D. Weisfeld
was there; she is outgoing president of the Communications Network
in Philanthropy and Senior Communications Officer of the $4 billion
Robert Wood Johnson Foundation.  And so was Raymond C. Boyer,
director of communications for the $3 billion John D. and Catherine
T. MacArthur Foundation.  <I> </I></FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The meeting participants found themselves in a focus
group led by Richard Harwood, whose private consulting company
has been a major beneficiary of so-called &quot;public journalism
grants from the Pew and Kettering foundation. In another event
they heard  from Hedrick Smith, the former <I>New York Times </I>Moscow
correspondent -- who was pinch-hitting for <I>U.S. News and World
Report </I>editor James Fallows, a last minute cancellation. Smith's
anti-Republican PBS election special &quot;The People and  the
Power Game&quot; had received significant support from the funders
represented in Detroit (the event hosts, the Charles Stewart Mott
Foundation, had given his show a quarter of a million dollars).
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>  <I>Foundation Watch</I> was there as well, as an
invited speaker at a closing-day panel called &quot;Foundations
Under Scrutiny.&quot;  This panel allowed the foundation communication
chiefs to hear themselves attacked from Left and Right.  The other
speakers on the panel included the Hudson Institute's Michael
Horowitz, who, as a Reagan Administration official at the Office
of Management and Budget, tried some fifteen years ago to end
federal funding of advocacy groups, and Robert Bothwell, director
of the liberal National Committee for Responsive Philanthropy.
 The conservative criticisms were strong, with Horowitz accusing
foundation officers of being &quot;little better than thieves&quot;
who worsened the plight of the poor by diverting resources from
the needy to themselves.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>  The <I>Foundation Watch</I> presentation, subdued
by comparison, asked those assembled to consider the advantages
of a more even-handed approach to funding controversial public
issues.  Bothwell, who had recently received a $30,000 foundation
grant to study conservative foundation activity, singled out the
Pew Charitable Trusts for special criticism, arguing that they
so micromanaged their grant projects that independent thought
became almost impossible.   <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> It is doubtful, however, whether any of these criticisms
were taken to heart.  <I>Foundation Watch</I> was privileged to
observe two days of networking, seminars, and fellowship.  Perhaps
as befits a convention of public relations spinmeisters, the purpose
of their meetings was not to change foundation behavior but to
change the perception of foundation behavior.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> There was one critical session at which we were
not present.  However, materials concerning the session are available,
and they offer perhaps the most significant evidence of the failure
of the foundation sector to understand that more is at stake than
public relations imagery and perceptions.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>PERTSCHUK'S P.R. MENU </FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>On the first day of the Detroit conference, Wednesday,
October 9, the Communications Network in Philanthropy held its
business meeting and election of officers.  This was followed
by a motor coach excursion to the Detroit Zoological Institute
where the participants enjoyed a cash bar social hour, followed
by dinner and a keynote address by Michael Pertschuk.  A printed
outline of his talk, &quot;A Wake-Up Call: It's Your Turn,&quot;
discloses that he discussed neither tobacco nor children's advertising.
 <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>Foundation Watch </FONT></I><FONT SIZE=2>was not
present for the give-and-take.  But the outline, which is entitled
<I>A Menu of Possible Responses to Meeting the Growing Challenges
to Foundation Legitimacy</I>, invites foundations to confront
their critics aggressively with a battery of opposition research
and public relations initiatives.  Nowhere in the document does
Pertschuk suggest that the giants of philanthropy take criticism
seriously and reform their giving.  Instead, his analysis reassures
foundations that it is the critics who are to blame.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Section one, bearing the title &quot;'Opposition'
Research: define the problem,&quot; defines the problem in a curiously
self-serving way.  It identifies foundations as victims.  Point
&quot;a&quot;: <I> &quot;Keep track: who is thinking about doing
what to foundations, and when?  Organize an on-line, private information
exchange among foundation communications officers.&quot; </I>underscores
a defensiveness toward public discussion that one would not expect
of foundations that want to improve communications.  Rather than
call for increased openness, public scrutiny and accountability,
the promise made by Dorothy Ridings, the new Council on Foundations
president, Pertschuk's first recommendation is for a proprietary
exchange of privileged information.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Pertschuk's point &quot;b&quot; reframes an important
debate over policy into a strategy to capture political rhetoric:
<I> &quot;Do or fund research on 'defunding the left' initiatives
and rhetoric to identify percursory moves for future attacks on
foundation.  Analyze the rhetoric of the Christian Right, the
populist right, Istook, Simpson, et. al.; George Mason University,
the Cato Institute, the Heritage Foundation.&quot; </I> Rather
than answer conservative critics seriously on the merits of their
claims, Pertschuck  instead advocates &quot;deconstructing&quot;
their arguments. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Point &quot;c&quot; reiterates the strategy of out-talking
your critics:  <I>&quot;Develop likely scenarios for future attacks
on foundations, including rhetorical devices that demonize foundations.&quot;
 <BR>
</I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Finally, point &quot;d&quot; formalizes public relations
&quot;spin&quot;:<I>  &quot;Commission polls and focus groups
designed to elicit knowledge, feelings and responsive chords so
as to gauge the success of attacks on foundations and to provide
guidance for affirmative responses.&quot;</I>  With the right
focus groups, nothing needs to change. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Building on the questionable premises of these appetizers,
the Pertschuk menu's second course is &quot;Strategic Planning:
define the goals.&quot;  The goal is to defend against change.
 Point &quot;a&quot; calls upon foundations to<I> &quot;build
broad public recognition and support, through public education,
for the role of foundations in society_free of government controls?&quot;</I>
 Of course, foundations are creatures of government control, specifically
the I.R.S. and the states that charter foundation activities.
 Service to the public interest is what asset-rich foundations
are supposed to provide in exchange for their tax-exemption .
 It is odd that Pertschuk, who would increase government control
over other parts of society, downplays the legal restrictions
currently placed on foundations. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Point &quot;b&quot;: attacks what to this observer
is the reality of the Foundation sector and again urges new strategies
focused on changing perceptions:<I>  &quot;To zero in on changing
public perceptions of national foundations as elitist, unaccountable,
wasteful, illegitimate, too left, too liberal, too big.&quot;
<BR>
</I></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Pertschuk's point &quot;c&quot; flatters his patrons:<I>
&quot;To build support for foundations as an integral part of
the 'independent sector' and, specifically, as public policy watchdogs
identifying private sector failures and government corruption,
inefficiency, overreaching? (The foundation as the latter day
equivalent of the old testament prophets?).&quot;  </I>When a
corporation hires a management consultant, it looks for internal
problems before it blames external conditions.  But Pertschuk's
menu of responses reverses the order.  Public criticism of foundations
is occurring not because the public fails to see the good that
foundations do, but because it disapproves of what it sees. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> The menu's third section, &quot;Smorgasboard of
possible initiatives,&quot; repeats the effort to manage criticism
of the grantmaking activities of foundations with public relations
stunts. One point, however might especially interest readers of
this publication:<I>  &quot;Support an independent, investigative
'Foundation Watch' Watch.&quot;</I>  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> This particular invitation to dig up dirt on foundation
critics -- specifically this periodical -- highlights the cowardice
and disingenuousness of the foundation sector in the face of criticism.
Rather than engage in civil debate over contested issues based
on facts, figures, and the historical record,  the advocates of
&quot;advocacy&quot;  prefer to sling mud at those raising questions.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>  This editor told Pertschuk in an interview that
he could find out all he needs to know about <I>Foundation Watch</I>
by purchasing a subscription and reading the publication.  But
clandestine activity is a constant temptation for those with vested
interests in maintaining the <I>status quo</I>.  When invited
to contribute an article to Capital Research Center on his vision
for philanthropy, Pertschuk replied, &quot;I don't have a particular
vision for philanthropy.&quot;  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Instead, Pertschuk suggests public relations ploys:
 editorial board visits, the production of videos, sponsoring
PBS and NPR programs, funding public relations campaigns through
Independent Sector, and &quot;strategic communications training&quot;
_ not coincidentally a specialty of the Advocacy Institute _ for
foundation leaders, staff, selected grantees, and &quot;'esteemed'
non-foundation leaders as spokespersons.&quot;  All are methods
which are designed to make concrete criticisms of foundations
go away, rather than receive the attention they deserve.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><B><FONT SIZE=2>THE FISHBOWL'S INNER CIRCLE<BR>
</FONT></B></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> One needed only to wait one month to see Michael
Pertschuk's recommendations turned into action items.  The National
Symposium on Foundations and the Public Sector held in Washington
on November 14 and 15 bore all the hallmarks of the Pertschuk
influence.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Participants at the first day's session of the Symposium
seemed to be reading from Pertschuk's script. All the &quot;esteemed&quot;
foundation and non-foundation leaders were gathered together by
the Council on Foundations and by a number of non-profit groups.
 There were dozens of participants at the opening ceremonies.
 But a curious segregation occurred shortly afterwards.  On the
morning of the first day, participants were arranged into an &quot;inner
circle&quot; and an outer circle in what conference organizers
called &quot;the fishbowl.&quot;  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> The fishbowl was the central feature in a two-day
exercise in consensus formation that might remind filmgoers of
a scene in &quot;The Manchurian Candidate.&quot;  It was fascinating
to an outside observer.  For in their rush to confront their critics,
the foundations justified the critics' strongest claims.  The
foundations were engaging in a public demonstration of &quot;group-think&quot;
as shallow and embarrassing as it was doomed to failure.  And
the failures of the group dynamics on display in the fishbowl
reflected the failures of a philanthropy enamoured of faddish
trends in media relations and public opinion formation that were
on display in Detroit and Washington.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> In the &quot;fishbowl&quot; were gathered the &quot;inner
circle&quot; _ one might call them the usual suspects _ who represented
the central committee of the liberal philanthropic establishment.
 <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Notably absent were representatives of any conservative
foundation or organization, although at least two representatives
of the Philanthropy Roundtable -- Whitney Ball and John Walters
-- were in the room.  The conservatives later were permitted to
lead small group sessions.  But the main event was reserved for
liberals.  All others were were relegated to the &quot;outer circle.&quot;
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Moderator Judy K. Chynoweth, executive director
of the Foundation Consortium for School-Linked Services, announced
that she would &quot;play Oprah.&quot;  Her language was thick
with the phrases familiar to foundation types _ she once actually
did say, &quot;Thank you for sharing.&quot;  Chynoweth would call
on individuals from the &quot;outer circle&quot; to sit briefly
in an &quot;inner circle&quot; guest chair to ask a  question
_ a procedure used to insure that the &quot;inner circle&quot;
remained secure.  Not only was she insensible to the elitism of
the enterprise, but in technocratic phrases she charged the participants
 to recognize that the session was &quot;a production meeting,&quot;
and that the participants should see themselves as &quot;assembly
line workers&quot; who were manufacturing a &quot;learning tool&quot;
in a &quot;carefully crafted process&quot; involving the &quot;construction
of small groups.&quot;  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Occupants of the inner circle dutifully nodded,
then launched into tense and peculiar disquisitions on the dangers
foundations faced from a Republican Congress.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> The first speaker, Joel Orosz, read aloud from a
1952 <I>American Legion Magazine</I> article describing foundations
as composed of &quot;outright communists...fellow travellers...</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>one worlders&quot; and what he called &quot; my personal
favorite: well-meaning dupes.&quot; <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>  That comment was greeted by condescending laughter
as Orosz outlined the failure of Congress' 1954 Reece Committee
investigations as well as the 1969 Wright Patman investigations,
which he characterized as &quot;relatively benign&quot; compared
to today's criticisms. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Waving Heather MacDonald's <I>Wall Street Journal</I>
article in the air, Orosz declared that the present situation
was &quot;more dangerous&quot; than ever, and that foundations
faced a political climate unseen since the days of Andrew Jackson.
 Jacksonian democracy, he said, regarded foundations as closed
corporations, and the danger was that foundation opponents like
those of the nineteenth century Anti-Masonic party were mobilizing
against the assembled foundations and eyeing their tax exemptions.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Peter Edelman, whose judicial nomination was left
twisting in the wind by the Clinton Administration, praised conservative
foundations.  He announced that he was &quot;grateful for Scaife,
Mellon, Olin, and Bradley, the people on the conservative side
who are unabashed in their willingness to spend money on advocacy
and public policy.&quot;  The problem, he said, was that the liberal
side was letting conservative efforts go &quot;unanswered.&quot;
 To correct this &quot;imbalance&quot; was the task before philanthropy.
 Ironically, conservative foundations would assist this task because,
he said, they would be able &quot;to resist changes and to protect
the ability to advocate.&quot;  Whether Edelman was pursuing some
private joke or on to something new was unclear to this reporter.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Only Robert Wood Johnson Foundation vice-president
Paul Jellinek  said something of genuine insight during the seemingly
endless round-robin, perhaps because of  his organization's participation
in the Clinton administration's ill-fated health care plan.  He
observed that the nonprofit sector got &quot;so wrapped up in
fighting Istook that we missed the big policy debate&quot; over
welfare.  Jellinek suggested that next time foundations &quot;keep
at least one eye open&quot; for issues other than their own institutional
self-interest. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> The fishbowl session ended.  Much like the family
goldfish, life eventually drained out of the panelists who tired
of the discussion.  They moved on to small group discussions which
were intended to raise &quot;questions&quot; for the larger group.
 (Social science research has determined that small groups are
most conducive to reinforcing shared opinions, which is called
&quot;consensus formation.&quot;) <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> The activities of the small groups were obviously
a pretext for political networking, as was apparent when the &quot;questions&quot;
were posted on the wall in the hotel ballroom.  Written in magic
marker on giant sheets of paper held up by masking tape, each
repeated the banalities of &quot;community&quot; and &quot;public
interest,&quot; &quot;accountability&quot; and &quot;the role
of the press.&quot; <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> What was the meeting really about?  (&quot;Who am
I?  Why am I here?&quot;)  Sara Melendez, president of Independent
Sector, offered some hint in remarks at the first and final public
discussions of the conference.  She warned the assembled group
that Independent Sector would be investigated in the next session
of Congress by Rep. Nancy Johnson's (R-CT) House oversight committee
as &quot;payback&quot; for its advocacy efforts to defeat the
Istook amendment.  Melendez asked for their support in the coming
months. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> After cutting through all the New Age psychobabble,
here was what the National Symposium was about: creating a network
to defend Independent Sector and derail congressional oversight.
 Rally the troops, issue marching orders, and, no doubt, follow
up with memoranda and private communications which will not be
provided to <I>Foundation Watch</I>.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>===</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times">The Big Fish in the &quot;Fishbowl&quot;
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Times">The following persons were members
of the &quot;fishbowl's&quot; inner circle:<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Times"> Alan Abramson of the Aspen Institute's
Nonprofit Sector Research Fund; Peter Edelman, former HHS official
in the Clinton administration and husband of Children's Defense
Fund head Marian Wright Edelman; Chris Gates of the National Civic
League; Jim Hyman of the Annie E. Casey Foundation; Frank Karel
of the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation; White House liaison Doris
Matsui; Ann Mitchell-Sackey, from the National Council of Nonprofit
Associations; the Kellogg Foundation's Joel Orosz; Lisa Parrish,
a New York City deputy budget commissioner ; Michael Seltzer,
from the Ford Foundation; the Center for Policy Alternative's
Linda Tarr-Whelan, Paul Jellinek from the Robert Wood Johnson
Foundation; and Maxine Thomas of the Kettering Foundation. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>===<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<a name="review"></a>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Defending the &quot;The Best and the Brightest&quot;:
<I><B>Narcissism and Philanthropy</B></I></FONT></B>
<P>
by Robert Huberty<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>DEFENDING THE BEST AND THE BRIGHTEST<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Gerald Freund, <I>Narcissism and Philanthropy: Ideas
and Talent Denied</I> (Viking, 1996) 158 pages. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Modern liberals deny that one can know the true
and good.  But this ignorance does not stop them from wanting
to win, nor does it interfere with their desire to reward the
success of those who share their convictions, or lack thereof.
 Washington abounds with such people, who seek to dazzle through
brilliance.  The best and the brightest, as they once were called,
believe they deserve rewards and honors, and it is the thesis
of this book that they are not getting what they deserve.  Gerald
Freund, an administrator and official active in foundation affairs
for over forty years, is the former director of the John D. and
Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation &quot;genius&quot; awards program.
 In <I>Narcissism and Philanthropy</I> he mourns the failure of
other foundations to appreciate the importance of grace and favors
for golden boys.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Writing for foundation insiders, Freund argues that
foundation grants are used most productively when they support
&quot;exceptional&quot; individuals of &quot;extraordinary&quot;
promise.  Increasingly, however, foundations are caught between
the forces of left and right.  Multiculturalists pounce on grants
for individual excellence to find evidence of racism and elitism,
while conservative populists abhor cutting-edge creativity.  Freund
worries that foundation officers are turning inward: they have
become sensitive to appearances and have grown self-assertive
and self-regarding (hence the book's peculiar title).  Freund
contends that the networks of talent scouts to which foundations
once turned for advice are deteriorating.  Foundation program
officers don't consult with outside experts as they once did.
 They don't seek out bright minds to explore ideas and create
programs to reward risk-takers.  Instead, they carefully screen
grant applicants through complex criteria and narrowly define
projects to fulfill specific goals.  Self-conscious of their own
professional standing (and defensive about it), foundations impose
limiting conditions on their dispensations.  The arrogance of
the insecure purseholder is making a comeback.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Freund is a former Rockefeller Foundation program
officer who handled grants to individuals and he has fond memories
of the days when program officers dispensed them freely and easily.
 He extols the example of John D. Rockefeller and his family,
who recruited &quot;the best brains they could attract to investigate
competing claims on their philanthropies.&quot;  He contrasts
Rockefeller to the narcissist Andrew Carnegie who trusted only
his own philanthropic judgment.  Freund has no sympathy for &quot;donor
intent,&quot; the notion that donors should insure that their
intentions are precise and fully observed when they establish
foundations.  He argues instead that foundations misuse their
power, not when they violate donors' intentions, but when they
are unresponsive to grant recipients' needs.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> And who are the needy?  Certainly not the recipients
of charity.  Freund is careful to distinguish philanthropy from
charity, and, one suspects, he would make the latter a handmaiden
to the welfare state.  No: philanthropy's task is to identify
the &quot;imaginative minority&quot; and &quot;superior talents&quot;
who are &quot;our most important resource.&quot; <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Trapped in a New Frontier time-warp, Freund says
foundations once honored that obligation to find and help the
very best.  He commends the Rockefeller Foundation:  During the
dark days of the 1950s Dean Rusk, its president and a future Secretary
of State, supported the recruitment of talent to specialize in
international legal theory, which international legal theorists
warned was in short supply.  Then there was the Ford Foundation
under president McGeorge Bundy, President Kennedy's former National
Security Council advisor:  In 1968 Ford braved controversy by
giving individual grants to Robert Kennedy's presidential campaign
staff after the Senator was assassinated, thereby providing Peter
Edelman and others with much-needed &quot;turn-around time.&quot;
 And the Carnegie Corporation under president John Gardner (HEW
secretary to LBJ) rescued overworked college presidents of exceptional
talent by funding year-long sabbaticals, enabling them to recharge
their batteries.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Most of <I>Narcissism and Philanthropy </I>consists
of foggy tips on ways that foundations can continue to seek out
&quot;excellence&quot; and shepherd &quot;the creative spirit.&quot;
 Worthwhile grants to individuals are possible, says Freund, when
foundations pick grant selection committees whose members &quot;have
sufficient knowledge to make rigorous judgments, but one wants
them also to be generous and imaginative, open-minded, seasoned
and perspicacious.&quot;  Foundations should employ mature and
knowledgeable program officers who can offer their grantees &quot;nurturing
support and an ongoing relationship.&quot;  Foundation professionals
should be tactful, too:  &quot;Helpful when called upon but not
intrusive or prying; they do not make grantees feel they need
to express inordinate or inappropriate gratitude.&quot;   <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> In a book notably lacking in clarity or humor, the
ten pages Freund devotes to the origins of the MacArthur Foundation
&quot;genius&quot; awards provides some relief.  In spring 1979
the Foundation hired Freund, then a Hunter College dean, to assemble
assorted luminaries to brainstorm the purpose of the awards and
consider how to pick their winners.  The deliberations recounted
here reveal how silly bright people can be.  Jonas Salk &quot;urged
MacArthur to create a program that would enable people to train
in a discipline other than one they were in and also to create
an ambience that would encourage people to change fields.&quot;
 Unnamed others worried that interviews and written applications
might give articulate candidates an unfair advantage.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Freund says nothing about the MacArthur awards'
notorious reliance on race, gender and ethnicity, and he is silent
about when and why he left MacArthur's employ as the awards' program
director.  But from other remarks it is clear that he is dismayed
by foundations' use of multicultural criteria and worried that
conservatives will attack them for it.  In an aside, he consoles
himself that a conservative Congress may hesitate to encroach
on foundation autonomy because it will not want to interfere with
the bold work of conservative foundations like Bradley and Olin.
 They, apparently, are the final defense of Camelot.<BR>
</FONT>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
